{
  "248": [
    {
      "id": 1170,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«حَاجَّ» To argue based on evidence.",
      "d": "«حَجَّ» means to prevail in argument/evidence. And «حُجَّۃٌ» means evidence/proof. And «اِحْتَجَّ» means to bring evidence for one's claim (Munjid). So «حَاجّ» refers to debating with proofs and refuting each other's arguments with evidence.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡ حَآجَّ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ فِیۡ رَبِّہٖۤ» (2/258)\nTranslation: Have you not seen the one who argued with Abraham about his Lord?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1171,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«جَدَلَ» To try to overpower each other in conversation.",
      "d": "«جَدَلَ» means to try to overpower each other in conversation, to argue unnecessarily (Muf). And «جَدَلَ» also means to knock down and throw to the ground (Munjid), and to argue in the form of questions and answers (M.Q). According to the author of MAQĀĪS AL-LUGHAH, it means to prolong a dispute through lengthy speech (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُجَادِلُوۡنَکَ فِی الۡحَقِّ بَعۡدَ مَا تَبَیَّنَ» (8/6)\nTranslation: They argue with you about the truth after it has become clear."
    },
    {
      "id": 1172,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«مَارَ» To argue about something that one hesitates to accept.",
      "d": "«مِرْیَۃ» means hesitation and doubt. And «مَارَ» means to argue about something that one hesitates to accept (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا کَذَبَ الۡفُؤَادُ ی مَا  رَاٰی اَفَتُمٰرُوۡنَہٗ  عَلٰی مَا یَرٰی» (53/11-12)\nTranslation: The heart did not deny what it saw. Then will you dispute with him over what he saw?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1173,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«خَصْم» To argue based on being a claimant to something.",
      "d": "«خَصْم» means claimant. Plaintiff (one who makes a claim) and defendant (one against whom a claim is made) or either one. Opposing party. Whether one individual or more. Such a dispute or case in which the rights of the parties are under discussion. And «اَخْصَمَ» means to provide evidence against someone. To suggest evidence (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ» (38/21)\nTranslation: Has there reached you the news of the disputants?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1174,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«لَدّ» Means intense quarreling.",
      "d": "«لَدّ» means «شدّۃ الخصومۃ» meaning intense quarreling (F.L 48). And «اَلَدّ» means a very quarrelsome person. One who does not consider others' words appropriate or worthy of attention, and keeps making noise for his own point.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یُشۡہِدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی مَا فِیۡ  قَلۡبِہٖ  ۙ وَ ہُوَ  اَلَدُّ  الۡخِصَامِ» (2/204)\nTranslation: And he calls Allah to witness upon what is in his heart, yet he is the most quarrelsome of opponents."
    },
    {
      "id": 1175,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To quarrel/argue",
      "hw": "To quarrel",
      "s": "«تَشَاکَسَ» To quarrel with each other for one's right due to bad temper and stinginess.",
      "d": "«اَلشِّکْس» means a bad-tempered person. And «تَشَاکَسَ» means to quarrel with each other due to bad temper (Muf). And «شَکَسَ» means to be hard-tempered and stingy (Munjid). So «تَشَاکَسَ» means to pull and tug with each other for their respective rights due to stinginess, quick temper, and bad temper.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ  مَثَلًا رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا  لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ  یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا» (39/29)\nTranslation: Allah presents an example: a man owned by quarreling partners and another belonging exclusively to one man - are they equal in comparison?"
    }
  ],
  "249": [
    {
      "id": 1176,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lies",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«کِذْب» Lie, statement contrary to reality.",
      "d": "«کِذْب» means to deliberately give false information (Munjid). The heart and tongue not being in agreement (Muf), or to speak contrary to reality. And its opposite is «صِدْق» (truth).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (3/78)\nTranslation: And they speak lies about Allah while they know."
    },
    {
      "id": 1177,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lies",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«بَاطِل» Impermanent and baseless statement. Used in very broad meanings, of which one type is falsehood.",
      "d": "«بَاطِل» means every statement in which, after investigation, no strength and permanence is seen. Unjust, baseless, useless, and futile statement (Munjid). And its opposite is «حَقّ» meaning reality, truth, truthfulness. So the word «بَاطِل» is used in a broad concept, of which one meaning is also falsehood or lie.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لِمَ تَلۡبِسُوۡنَ الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» (3/71)\nTranslation: O People of the Scripture, why do you confuse the truth with falsehood?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1178,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lies",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«زُوۡرُ» Means falsehood against truth and associating partners with Allah.",
      "d": "«زَوۡرُ» means crookedness and deviation in the upper part of the chest. And «زُوۡر» means falsehood against truth and associating partners with Allah (Munjid). And «زَاوَرَ» means to turn away from the path of truth. To move aside from the straight path.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ» (18/17)\nTranslation: And you would have seen the sun when it rose, inclining away from their cave to the right.\nAnd in contrast to «قَوْلَ الزُّوۡر» the Quran uses the words «قَوْلًا سَدِیۡدًا». Meaning speech in which there is no deficiency, ambiguity, deception, or complexity. And «قَوْلَ الزُّوۡر» is speech in which these things or one of them is present. And according to Abu Hilal Askari, «زُوۡر» is such falsehood that is presented in a decorated way so that it appears good and correct (FQ.L 34).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَ اجۡتَنِبُوۡا  قَوۡلَ  الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30)\nTranslation: So avoid the uncleanliness of idols and avoid false speech."
    },
    {
      "id": 1179,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lies",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«اِفْک» To transform something into something else with bad intention, and its connection is also with slander.",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn from the original direction in which bad intention is included (Muf). For something to be one way and to make it into something else. To fabricate stories. Accusation. Slander. And this is the worst kind of falsehood. And according to the author of FURUQ AL-LUGHAWIYYAH, this type of falsehood is related to فاحش القبیح meaning slander of adultery etc. (FQ.L 33).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ  ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ  اِفۡکٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (24/12)\nTranslation: Why, when you heard it, did not the believing men and believing women think good of one another and say, 'This is an obvious falsehood'?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1180,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To lie or fabricate",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«کَذَبَ» To speak falsehood or lie contrary to reality.",
      "d": "«کَذَبَ» means to deliberately give information contrary to reality.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ  اِنۡ  کَانَ  قَمِیۡصُہٗ  قُدَّ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ فَکَذَبَتۡ  وَ ہُوَ  مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (12/27)\nTranslation: But if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied, and he is of the truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1181,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To lie or fabricate",
      "hw": "Lies",
      "s": "«اَفَکَ» To slander someone.",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn something's direction. To transform something into something else with bad intention as mentioned above. And this is the worst kind of lie.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ہَلۡ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ عَلٰی مَنۡ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلٰی کُلِّ  اَفَّاکٍ  اَثِیۡمٍ» (26/221-222)\nTranslation: Shall I inform you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every sinful liar."
    }
  ],
  "250": [
    {
      "id": 1184,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To deny",
      "hw": "To deny",
      "s": "«اَبۡطَلَ» Is used to prove something false through evidence, experiences, and observations.",
      "d": "«بَاطِل» means unjust and impermanent, and its opposite is «حَقّ». So just as one meaning of «حَقّ» is truth, similarly one meaning of «بَاطِل» is also falsehood. And «اَبۡطَلَ» means to deny or prove something false through circumstances and events.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لِیُحِقَّ الۡحَقَّ وَ یُبۡطِلَ الۡبَاطِلَ وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» (8/8)\nTranslation: That He may establish the truth and abolish falsehood, even if the criminals dislike it."
    }
  ],
  "251": [
    {
      "id": 1185,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "Key",
      "s": "«مَقَالِیۡد» Plural of مقلید, means keys.",
      "d": "«قَلَدَ» means to thin iron and bend it over something or to bend and make a bundle. And «قِلَادُ» or «اِقۡلِیۡدُ» refers to copper or brass wire used in a necklace. And «قِلَادَةُ» refers to a neck necklace. «مِقلَد» refers to the iron key that is turned in a lock to open it. Its plural is «مَقالِدُ» and «مَقَالِیۡد». For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَہٗ  مَقَالِیۡدُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ  یَقۡدِرُ» (42/12)\nTranslation: To Him belong the keys of the heavens and the earth. He extends provision for whom He wills and restricts it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1186,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "Key",
      "s": "«مَفَاتِح» Means keys. Also used in the meaning of opening something or removing binding and complexity from something.",
      "d": "«فَتَحَ» means to open or remove binding and complexity from something (Muf). And this word is used in all meanings: opening a door, opening a lock, opening a path for water to flow, deciding a case, and conquering a land. The plural of «مِفۡتَاحٌ» is «مَفَاتِح» meaning key and also water channel (Munjid). And the plural of «مِفۡتَاحٌ» is also «مَفَاتِیۡحُ» (Munjid). And this word is not used in the Holy Quran. So «مَفَاتِحُ» is more specific than «مَقَالِیۡد», which is used in the meanings of removing and opening every type of binding and obstacle.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ عِنۡدَہٗ مَفَاتِحُ الۡغَیۡبِ لَا  یَعۡلَمُہَاۤ  اِلَّا ہُوَ» (6/59)\nTranslation: And with Him are the keys of the unseen; none knows them except Him."
    }
  ],
  "252": [
    {
      "id": 1187,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Sheet/Veil",
      "hw": "Veil",
      "s": "«خُمُر» Means headcover. Scarf. Veil.",
      "d": "«خُمُر» is plural of «خِمَار» meaning headcover, scarf, veil (Munjid). «خِمَار» is a small sheet or scarf with which the face can be covered. And the sides and chest can also be covered.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لۡیَضۡرِبۡنَ بِخُمُرِہِنَّ عَلٰی جُیُوۡبِہِنَّ» (24/31)\nTranslation: And let them wrap a portion of their headcovers over their chests."
    },
    {
      "id": 1188,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Sheet/Veil",
      "hw": "Veil",
      "s": "«جَلَابِیۡب» Means sheet or shirt.",
      "d": "«جَلَابِیۡب» is plural of «جِلۡبَاب». Means sheet or shirt. And «جَلۡبَبَ» means to make wear a sheet or shirt (Munjid). «جِلۡبَاب» is actually that large sheet that can cover the entire body from head to foot.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ  قُلۡ  لِّاَزۡوَاجِکَ  وَ  بَنٰتِکَ وَ نِسَآءِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ یُدۡنِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہِنَّ مِنۡ جَلَابِیۡبِہِنَّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَنۡ یُّعۡرَفۡنَ فَلَا  یُؤۡذَیۡنَ» (33/59)\nTranslation: O Prophet, tell your wives and your daughters and the women of the believers to bring down over themselves part of their outer garments. That is more suitable that they will be known and not be abused."
    }
  ],
  "253": [
    {
      "id": 1189,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "Fodder",
      "s": "«مَرۡعٰی» Is used for fresh fodder.",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means animal grazing grass. The word «مَرۡعٰی» is also used for pasture. And also for fresh grass or fodder (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» (87/4-5)\nTranslation: And [He] who brings out the pasture. And [then] makes it black stubble."
    },
    {
      "id": 1190,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "Fodder",
      "s": "«اَبّ» Fodder that is drying.",
      "d": "«اَبّ» is grass that is completely ready for animals to graze and cut (Muf). And according to the author of Munjid, this word applies to every type of wet and dry fodder that is livestock feed, such as hay, grass, straw, etc. Or such fodder that can be collected (Stock). The position that «فَاکِھَۃ» (fruits) has for humans, «اَبّ» has for quadrupeds (animals). «فَاکِھَۃ» means fruits, whether dry or wet. Similarly, «اَبّ» is used for wet and dry fodder (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ  فَاکِہَۃً  وَّ اَبًّا مَّتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» (80/31-32)\nTranslation: And fruit and fodder - as provision for you and your grazing livestock."
    },
    {
      "id": 1191,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "Fodder",
      "s": "«عَصۡف» That part of fodder that animals leave after grazing, i.e., remaining fodder.",
      "d": "«عَصۡف» means the covering and peels over grain (M.L). Hay (animal fodder), straw, etc. And «عصف ماکول» is that part or stem (of a vegetable or leaf's part that is connected to the branch) that animals leave after grazing. And according to the author of MUNJID, these are stalks of crops and stalks of straw. «عَصَفَ» means wind blowing strongly. And «عَاصِفَۃ» means storm. And that storm that blows around grass and its stalks is also called «عَصۡف».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَجَعَلَہُمۡ کَعَصۡفٍ مَّاۡکُوۡلٍ» (105/5)\nTranslation: And He made them like eaten straw."
    }
  ],
  "254": [
    {
      "id": 1192,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Moon",
      "hw": "Moon",
      "s": "«اَہِلَّۃ» Plural of «ہِلَال». Used only for new moon or thin-shaped moon. i.e., from the moon of 26th date to 3rd.",
      "d": "«اَہِلَّۃ» is plural of «ہِلَال». And «ہِلَال» means new moon. And «ہَلَّ» means the crescent to appear. And «اَہَلَّ» means to make something famous. As people indicate, show, and make known to each other when seeing the new moon.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَہِلَّۃِ  ؕ قُلۡ ہِیَ مَوَاقِیۡتُ لِلنَّاسِ وَ الۡحَجِّ» (2/189)\nTranslation: They ask you about the new moons. Say, 'They are measurements of time for the people and for Hajj.'"
    }
  ],
  "255": [
    {
      "id": 1194,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To want/wish",
      "hw": "To want",
      "s": "«شَآءَ» Such desire or intention that is subject to Allah's decree, and this does not move forward or backward from the appointed time.",
      "d": "The root of «شَآءَ» is «شَیۡء» meaning thing. And «شَیۡء» is that which can be known and informed about, and its plural is اشیاء (Munjid.Muf). And «شِیۡئَۃ» and «مَشِیۡئَۃ» is a noun meaning intention (Munjid). Originally, the meanings of «مَشِیۡئَۃ» are the creation of something or attaining it. But since Allah Almighty is the one who brings everything into existence and maintains its arrangement, therefore the word مشیئت is used only in the meaning of divine intention.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَخۡلُقُ مَا یَشَآءُ ؕ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ» (42/49)\nTranslation: He creates what He wills. He gives to whom He wills female children, and He gives to whom He wills males."
    },
    {
      "id": 1195,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To want/wish",
      "hw": "To want",
      "s": "«اَرَادَ» Is general for such desire or intention that may or may not be subject to divine will, and its time can move forward or backward.",
      "d": "There is also a difference between divine will (مشیئت) and divine intention (ارادہ). Will is such intention whose existence according to Allah's knowledge and decree is necessary.\nFor example, in the blessed Hadith: «مَا شَآءَ اللہُ کَانَ وَ مَا لَمْ یَشَآءُ لَمْ یَکُنْ» Sunan Abi Dawud: Hadith No: 5075\nMeaning: Whatever Allah wills, happens, and whatever He does not will, does not happen.\nWhile divine intention does not necessitate its final existence.\nAnd for example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ بِکُمُ الۡیُسۡرَ وَ لَا یُرِیۡدُ بِکُمُ الۡعُسۡرَ» (2/185)\nTranslation: Allah intends for you ease and does not intend for you hardship.\nSimilarly, in another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ مَا اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ ظُلۡمًا  لِّلۡعِبَادِ» (40/31)\nTranslation: And Allah does not intend injustice for the servants.\nAlthough it is clear that hardship, difficulty, and injustice are found among people. Because will necessitates these things. When «شَاءَ» is attributed to humans, then it means such desire or intention that is subject to Allah's decree.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ مَا تَشَآءُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ  رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (81/29)\nTranslation: And you do not will except that Allah wills - Lord of the worlds.\nWhile human intention is free from this restriction; it can be against Allah's will. For example, a person wants that death should not come to him. But this is against divine will. So this cannot happen.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا  نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ  بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ وَ اللّٰہُ  مُتِمُّ  نُوۡرِہٖ  وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (61/8)\nTranslation: They want to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths, but Allah will perfect His light, although the disbelievers dislike it.\nAlso, the clear difference between intention and will is that intention can move forward or backward, but the time of will does not move forward or backward (FQ.L 40)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1196,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To want/wish",
      "hw": "To want",
      "s": "«اِشۡتَہٰی» To desire desirable things, desire of natural inclinations.",
      "d": "«اِشۡتَہٰی» means the soul being drawn to that which it naturally likes. Natural inclinations such as hunger, lust, greed, etc. (Muf). And its opposite is «نَفَرَ». And the author of Munjid writes its meanings as desiring desirable things (Munjid). Such desires in which intention has no entry (FQ.L 98).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَدَّعُوۡنَ» (41/31)\nTranslation: And you will have therein whatever your souls desire, and you will have therein whatever you request."
    },
    {
      "id": 1197,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To want/wish",
      "hw": "To want",
      "s": "«بَغٰی» To go beyond the limit of moderation in obtaining something.",
      "d": "«بَغٰی» means to desire to exceed the limit of moderation in seeking something (Muf). (And this quality can be praiseworthy. Like performing voluntary worship beyond obligatory acts. And this quality can also be blameworthy. Like inclining towards falsehood by exceeding the truth.)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا  یٰۤاَبَانَا مَا نَبۡغِیۡ ؕ ہٰذِہٖ  بِضَاعَتُنَا رُدَّتۡ اِلَیۡنَا» (12/65)\nTranslation: They said, 'O our father, what do we seek? This is our merchandise returned to us.'\nSo this 'merchandise (wallet)' that was found from the belongings of Yusuf's brothers was not their right that they received.\nAnd «اِبۡتَغٰی» means to seek something with effort (Muf). Meaning to do more than necessary effort.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ  وَجۡہِ  رَبِّہِ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (92/20)\nTranslation: Except seeking the countenance of his Lord, the Most High."
    }
  ],
  "256": [
    {
      "id": 1199,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To be silent",
      "hw": "Silent",
      "s": "«سَکَتَ» To become silent while talking.",
      "d": "«سَکَتَ» means to stop while speaking. To pause. To become silent (M.L Munjid). The usage of this word in this meaning has not come in the Holy Quran. However, it has come for anger subsiding.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger subsided in Moses."
    },
    {
      "id": 1200,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To be silent",
      "hw": "Silent",
      "s": "«صَمَتَ» Is used for being silent by nature or being of few words.",
      "d": "«صَمَتَ» means to remain silent. To be reticent or of few words.\nFor example, the Prophetic saying is: «مَنْ صَمَتَ نَجَا» meaning whoever remains silent is saved. The opposite of «صَمَتَ» is «نَطَقَ». And (مال صامت) means money and cash. While مال ناطق means animals (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَدَعَوۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ  اَمۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  صَامِتُوۡنَ» (7/193)\nTranslation: It is all the same for you whether you call them or you are silent."
    },
    {
      "id": 1201,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To be silent",
      "hw": "Silent",
      "s": "«اَنْصَتَ» Is used for listening to someone's speech silently.",
      "d": "«نَصَتَ» and «اَنْصَتَ» mean to listen to someone's speech while remaining silent (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذَا قُرِئَ الۡقُرۡاٰنُ فَاسۡتَمِعُوۡا لَہٗ وَ اَنۡصِتُوۡا  لَعَلَّکُمۡ  تُرۡحَمُوۡنَ» (7/204)\nTranslation: And when the Quran is recited, then listen to it and pay attention that you may receive mercy."
    }
  ],
  "257": [
    {
      "id": 1202,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "Lamp",
      "s": "«مَصۡبَاح» Is that whose light is inclined towards whiteness.",
      "d": "«صَبَحَ» means to be bright and shining. «صَبَحَ الشَّعۡر» means hair to be shining. And «صَبَحَ الْحَدِیۡد» means iron to be bright and shining. And «صَبِیۡح» and «صَبۡحَان» are used in the meaning of beautiful (Munjid). And Ibn Faris writes that the word «صَبَحَ» fundamentally indicates red color. Morning is also called صبح due to its redness. And the plural of «مِصۡبَاح» is «مَصَابِیۡح» meaning lamp, also due to its redness (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَثَلُ نُوۡرِہٖ کَمِشۡکٰوۃٍ  فِیۡہَا مِصۡبَاحٌ» (24/35)\nTranslation: The example of His light is like a niche within which is a lamp.\nThen the word «مِصۡبَاح» has also been used in the Holy Quran for bright stars.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ  زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِمَصَابِیۡحَ» (67/5)\nTranslation: And We have certainly beautified the nearest heaven with lamps."
    },
    {
      "id": 1203,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "Lamp",
      "s": "«سِرَاج» Is that whose light is inclined towards redness.",
      "d": "Ibn Faris says that the word «سَرَج» indicates beauty, adornment, and elegance. And «سِرَاج» (lamp) is called «سِرَاج» due to its light and adornment. A horse's saddle is also called «سَرْجُ» because it is its adornment. It is said «سَرَّجَ وَجۡھَہٗ» he adorned his face. «سَرَّجَ شَعۡرَہٗ» he groomed or oiled his hair (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  بُرُوۡجًا وَّ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا سِرٰجًا وَّ قَمَرًا  مُّنِیۡرًا» (25/61)\nTranslation: Blessed is He who has placed in the sky great stars and placed therein a lamp and luminous moon.\nFrom the lexical research presented above from the author of MAQĀĪS AL-LUGHAH, Ibn al-Faris, the Quran does not confirm it, rather the matter seems opposite. The Quran has called the sun سراج (35/61) and «سِرَاجًا وَّہَّاجًا» (78/13) although its light is inclined towards redness, not whiteness. Similarly, the Quran has called stars «مَصَابِیۡح» although their light is inclined towards whiteness, not red. So the original is: «سِرَاج» is that whose light is inclined towards redness and «مِصۡبَاح» is that whose light is inclined towards whiteness: and Allah knows best!"
    }
  ],
  "258": [
    {
      "id": 1204,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To graze",
      "hw": "To graze",
      "s": "«رَعٰی» Means to graze an animal and to protect and maintain it.",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means to graze an animal and to protect and maintain it. And «رَاعِی» means shepherd. Herdsman (one who performs the service of taking livestock herds to pastures and grazing them). And «مَرۡعٰی» means fodder and also pasture (Muf). To save something from being wasted. And to remove causes of external dangers. And its opposite is «اِہۡمَال» meaning livestock being without a shepherd (FQ.L 15).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ» (20/54)\nTranslation: Eat [therefrom] and pasture your livestock.\nSince the basic meaning of the word «رَعٰی» is training and maintenance, therefore its application can also be on humans. The king is راعی and the public is رعیت (subjects)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1205,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To graze",
      "hw": "To graze",
      "s": "«اَسَامَ» To take animals for grazing.",
      "d": "«سَوْمَ» has two basic meanings: (1) Seeking (2) Departure. Meaning to depart in search of something. «سَامَتُ الْاِبِل» means camels departed for pasture. And «اَسَامَ» means to go for grazing (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ مِنۡہُ  شَجَرٌ  فِیۡہِ تُسِیۡمُوۡنَ» (16/10)\nTranslation: And from it is a tree in which you pasture [your livestock]."
    }
  ],
  "259": [
    {
      "id": 1206,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«عَرَجَ» Is used for climbing with stops.",
      "d": "Two things are found in the meanings of «عَرَجَ»: inclination and height (M.L). «عَرَجَ» means to walk limping. And «اَعۡرَج» is called a lame person. And «عَرَجَ فِی السَّلَم» means to climb stairs.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَوۡ فَتَحۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ بَابًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَظَلُّوۡا فِیۡہِ  یَعۡرُجُوۡنَ لَقَالُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا سُکِّرَتۡ اَبۡصَارُنَا» (15/14-15)\nTranslation: And [even] if We opened to them a gate from the heaven and they continued therein to ascend, They would say, 'Our eyes have only been dazzled.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1207,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«رَقِیَ» Is used for climbing according to one's ability.",
      "d": "«رَقِیَ» also means to perform incantation and also to climb to a height. Such that strength is exerted according to one's capacity and power. To climb up slowly with soft pace (Munjid). For example: «اِرۡقِ عَلٰی ظِلۡعِکَ» meaning climb according to your ability. Do not put more burden on your soul than your strength (Munjid.Muf). And like: «رَقَیۡتُ فِی الْعِلْمِ وَالشَّرَفِ» I attained progress in knowledge and honor (FQ.L 152). So its usage is general.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَوۡ تَرۡقٰی فِی السَّمَآءِ ؕ وَ لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِیِّکَ حَتّٰی تُنَزِّلَ عَلَیۡنَا کِتٰبًا نَّقۡرَؤُہٗ» (17/93)\nTranslation: Or you ascend into the sky. But [even then], we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down to us a book we may read."
    },
    {
      "id": 1208,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«صَعِدَ» Is used for climbing upwards with difficulty.",
      "d": "Two things are fundamentally found in the concept of «صَعِدَ»: (1) Height (2) Difficulty (M.L). Meaning to climb to a high place with difficulty. And «صُعُوۡد» means height and valley. And the difficult path of climbing on it is also called this (Munjid). For something to rise up with difficulty, like smoke rises up. And «مصعد الکھر بایہ» means elevator (Muf). And «اَصۡعَدَ» and «صَعَّدَ» mean to climb up with time and difficulty.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَجۡعَلۡ صَدۡرَہٗ ضَیِّقًا حَرَجًا کَاَنَّمَا یَصَّعَّدُ فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/126)\nTranslation: He makes his breast tight and constricted as though he were climbing into the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 1209,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«ظَہَرَ» Is used for climbing up to the top.",
      "d": "«ظَہَرَ» means to appear. To overcome. To climb and reach up to the top, whether these are stairs or a wall etc. that is climbed without stairs.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَا اسۡطَاعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡہُ  وَ مَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا  لَہٗ  نَقۡبًا» (18/97)\nTranslation: So they were unable to pass over it, nor were they able to effect in it any penetration.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«لِبُیُوۡتِہِمۡ سُقُفًا مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ  وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ» (43/33)\nTranslation: And for their houses, ceilings of silver upon which they would ascend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1210,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«رَہَقَ» Is used for one thing climbing over another and covering it.",
      "d": "«رَہَقَ» means one thing climbing over another and covering it (an urgent quality is found in this). «رَہَّقَہُ الْاَمۡرُ» means a matter overwhelmed him with force and compulsion (Muf). Meaning it covered him (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» (80/40-41)\nTranslation: And [some] faces, that Day, will have upon them dust. Blackness will cover them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1211,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To climb (upwards)",
      "hw": "To climb",
      "s": "«تَسَوَّرَ» Is used for climbing or scaling a wall.",
      "d": "«سُوۡر» means city wall or such a high wall that cannot be entered by scaling it (M.L). And «سَارَ» means to climb a wall or to jump over it. And the meaning of «تَسَوَّرَ» is also to climb and jump over a wall, and also to wear bracelets. «سِوَار», plural of «سَوَار» is «اَسَاوِرَ» and «اَسۡوِرَۃٌ». Derived from meaning bracelet.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ ۘ اِذۡ  تَسَوَّرُوا  الۡمِحۡرَابَ» (38/21)\nTranslation: And has there reached you the news of the disputants - when they climbed over the wall of the prayer chamber?"
    }
  ],
  "260": [
    {
      "id": 1212,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«عَیۡنٌ» A spring of water that is flowing.",
      "d": "«عَیۡنٌ» means eye, and its plural «اَعۡیُنْ» has come in the Quran. Then, considering that water flows from the eye, the mouth of a waterskin is also called «عَیۡنٌ». Similarly, that spring of water from which water starts flowing is also called «عَیۡنٌ» (Muf). And its plural «عُیُوۡن» has come in the Quran.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ » (54/12)\nTranslation: And We caused the earth to burst with springs, and the waters met for a matter already decreed.\nAnd «عَیۡن» can also be applied to a lake and river."
    },
    {
      "id": 1213,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«یَنۡبُوۡع» A spring of water that gushes from the ground.",
      "d": "«نَبَعَ» means water to gush from a spring. And «مَنۡبَع» is called the place from where water gushes. And «یَنۡبُوۡع» is called a spring from which water is gushing (Muf). And its plural یَنَابِیۡع comes.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ  لَنَا مِنَ  الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا» (17/90)\nTranslation: And they said, 'We will never believe you until you break open for us from the ground a spring.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1214,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«سَرِیٌّ» A flowing spring that takes the form of a small canal.",
      "d": "«سَرِیٌّ» means a small canal. Flowing canal (F.L 261 Munjid). Its plural «اَسۡرِیَۃٌ» and «سُرۡیَان» comes. And «سَرِیَّۃ» is also called a small army or military detachment, whose plural is «سرایا». And «سَارِیَۃ» means a small army going at night (Munjid). So the concept of smallness is found in this (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ  سَرِیًّا» (19/24)\nTranslation: Your Lord has provided beneath you a stream."
    },
    {
      "id": 1215,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«فَارَ» Water to gush and jump upwards.",
      "d": "«فَارَ» means to gush and boil (Munjid). And «فَوۡر» means to gush, boil, bubble (M.L). «فَارَ الْقِدۡرُ» means pot to boil. «فَارَ الْمَآءُ» means water to gush. And «فَارَ الْعِرۡقُ» means vein to be disturbed and restless (Munjid). So in «فَارَ» the concept of water jumping up instead of flowing is found. Particularly when the water pressure below is high and the hole is narrow. From this, the famous word فوارہ (fountain) is derived.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ» (11/40)\nTranslation: Until, when Our command came and the oven overflowed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1216,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«نَضَخَ» Water to jump and fall down.",
      "d": "«نَضَخَ» means water to gush and flow. And «نَضَّاخَۃٌ» is called a fountain that gushes water upwards and it falls down (Munjid). So in this, the concept of water jumping up and falling down is found.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66)\nTranslation: In both of them are two springs, spouting."
    },
    {
      "id": 1217,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«نَضَخَ» Water to gush out forcefully from a spring and fall down.",
      "d": "«نَضَخَ» means water to gush out forcefully from a spring. And «اِنْضَخَ» means water to jump and fall down. «نَضَّاخَۃٌ» is called a fountain that gushes water upwards and it falls down (Munjid). So in this word, the concept of boiling and flowing is found instead of jumping up with a gush.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66)\nTranslation: In both of them are two springs, spouting."
    },
    {
      "id": 1218,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«اَنْبَجَسَ» Water to gush from a spring when the outlet is narrow.",
      "d": "«اَنْبَجَسَ» means something to open due to water, whether it is earth, stone, or mountain (M.L). And according to the author of FIQH AL-LUGHAH, the word «اَنْبَجَسَ» is specific for water to come out and flow from a mountain or stone (F.L 259).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ  اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی  اِذِ  اسۡتَسۡقٰىہُ قَوۡمُہٗۤ  اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ ۚ فَانۡۢبَجَسَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَا عَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (7/160)\nTranslation: And We inspired to Moses when his people implored him for water, 'Strike with your staff the stone.' And there gushed forth from it twelve springs."
    },
    {
      "id": 1219,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«اِنْفَجَرَ» Water to gush from a spring when the outlet becomes wide.",
      "d": "«اِنْفَجَرَ» and «اِنْبَجَسَ» are near-meaning words. And both these words have been used in the Holy Quran for the same occasion.\nThe verse related to «اِنْفَجَرَ» is as follows:\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ  ؕ فَانۡفَجَرَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَاعَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (2/60)\nTranslation: And when Moses asked for water for his people, We said, 'Strike with your staff the stone.' And there burst forth from it twelve springs.\nThe small difference between these two is that when the spring's mouth is not fully open and water rises a little upwards, the word «اِنْبَجَسَ» will be used. And when the mouth opens fully and water starts flowing at the outlet, the word «اِنْفَجَرَ» will be used. And the second difference is that «اِنْبَجَسَ» is used specifically for springs gushing from mountains or rocky land, while «اِنْفَجَرَ» is general. It can be used for both mountainous and plain land. During the flood of Noah (AS), water gushed and flowed from common land.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ» (54/12)\nTranslation: And We caused the earth to burst with springs, and the waters met for a matter already decreed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1220,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«سَالَ» In this, only the concept of water or any liquid flowing is found.",
      "d": "In «سَالَ», only the concept of water flowing is found, whether this water is from rain or from a spring.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, and valleys flowed according to their measure.\nSimilarly, in another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ  عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12)\nTranslation: And We made flow for him a spring of [liquid] copper.\nFrom this is the word سیال which is called everything that flows downwards like water. So in «سَیۡل» the concept of flowing downwards forcefully is found. And «سَیۡل» is called سیلاب (flood) in Urdu language.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَعۡرَضُوۡا فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَیۡلَ الۡعَرِمِ» (34/16)\nTranslation: But they turned away, so We sent upon them the flood of the dam."
    },
    {
      "id": 1221,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«جَرٰی» Water or another thing to flow or continue for a long time or distance with slight speed.",
      "d": "«جَرٰی» means water to move and be current. While the slope is not much and the water's force is not much. Water to flow or move with slight speed, whether it is a spring, canal, or river. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ  تَجۡرِیٰنِ» (55/50)\nTranslation: In both of them are two springs, flowing.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/25)\nTranslation: For them are gardens beneath which rivers flow.\nAnd the usage of «جَرٰی» is general, which is used in the Holy Quran for flowing things as well as for winds and the sun, moon, etc. moving. Besides, its usage is also metaphorically, such as سنت جاریہ (established practice) is a famous word. But there is probably no example of this metaphorical usage in the Quran. It is used both temporally and spatially. Meaning to continue or flow for a long distance or time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1222,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring to gush and flow",
      "hw": "Spring",
      "s": "«فَاضَ» Water or another thing to start flowing merely due to abundance and excess. (OVERFLOW)",
      "d": "Two concepts are found in «فَیۡض»: (1) Abundance of something (2) Becoming uncontrollable due to abundance. «فَاضَ السَّیۡلُ» means water to be abundant and flow over the banks of the river (Munjid). And «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاءُ» means he filled the vessel so much that water started flowing from the edges (OVERFLOW) (Munjid.Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ  الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» (5/83)\nTranslation: You see their eyes overflowing with tears because of what they have recognized of the truth.\nMeaning the eyes become so filled with tears that tears start flowing.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199)\nTranslation: Then depart from the place from where [all] the people depart.\nHere people means the flood of people, crowd, or abundance. Whose abundance compels them to accompany each other. And their accompanying and returning is expressed with «اَفَاضَ». Similarly, it is also used for extreme involvement in some work or talk.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (10/61)\nTranslation: When you are engaged in it."
    }
  ],
  "261": [
    {
      "id": 1223,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«مَشٰی» To walk with normal speed. General word for walking.",
      "d": "«مَشٰی» means to walk with the intention and will to go from one place to another (Muf). To walk step by step. To walk about. To walk with normal speed (F.L 176). Generally, this word is used for walking.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا مَالِ ہٰذَا الرَّسُوۡلِ یَاۡکُلُ الطَّعَامَ وَ یَمۡشِیۡ  فِی الۡاَسۡوَاقِ» (25/7)\nTranslation: And they say, 'What is this messenger that eats food and walks in the markets?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1224,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«دَبّ» To walk with slightly lighter pace than «مَشٰی».",
      "d": "«دَبّ» means to walk with slightly lighter pace than normal speed. «حَرَکَۃٌ عَلَی الْاَرْضِ اَخَفُّ مِنَ الْمَشْیِ» (M.L). Crawling, walking like a snake, or the child who is learning to walk on hands and feet - all are included in this (M.Q). And whatever walks on earth is «دَابَّۃ» (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  رِزۡقُہَا» (11/6)\nTranslation: And there is no creature on earth but that upon Allah is its provision."
    },
    {
      "id": 1225,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«اِنۡطَلَقَ» To depart, to set off walking.",
      "d": "«طَلَقَ» means to free from bondage (Muf). And «اِنۡطَلَقَ» means to walk after some stop (i.e., stopping). To set off walking. To depart. A prisoner to depart after release or to start speaking after remaining silent.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَانۡطَلَقَا  ٝ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ» (18/71)\nTranslation: So they set out, until when they had embarked in the ship.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا یَنۡطَلِقُ لِسَانِیۡ فَاَرۡسِلۡ  اِلٰی ہٰرُوۡنَ» (26/13)\nTranslation: And my tongue is not fluent, so send revelation to Aaron."
    },
    {
      "id": 1226,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَلَکَ» To continue walking along a path.",
      "d": "«سَلَکَ» is used in two meanings: (1) To keep walking on a path and not go here and there (Munjid). To walk and make walk on a path (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ  کُلِیۡ مِنۡ کُلِّ الثَّمَرٰتِ فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69)\nTranslation: Then eat from all the fruits and follow the ways of your Lord laid down for you.\nAnd (2) The second meaning is «نُفُوۡذَ الشَّیۡءِ» meaning one thing penetrating into another. To enter, to thread.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (28/32)\nTranslation: Insert your hand into the opening of your garment; it will come out white without disease."
    },
    {
      "id": 1227,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَرَبَ» To walk downwards. To enter into a hole.",
      "d": "«سَرَبَ» means to go downwards. To keep entering. And «سَرْبٌ» means the hole or den of wild animals. A pit inside the earth. Basement. Prison (Muf). It is said «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» meaning the snake entered its hole (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18/61)\nTranslation: And it took its way into the sea like a tunnel."
    },
    {
      "id": 1228,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«مَضٰی» Time to pass or to walk with time.",
      "d": "«مَضٰی» means to pass. To go away. And to be empty (M.Q). In «مَضٰی», either only the concept of time passing is found, and past is called elapsed time, or it gives the meaning of something walking and passing with time. «مَضٰی مَا مَضٰی» means what happened, happened. What passed, passed (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَہۡلَکۡنَاۤ  اَشَدَّ مِنۡہُمۡ بَطۡشًا وَّ مَضٰی مَثَلُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (43/8)\nTranslation: So We destroyed those who were greater than them in power, and the example of the former peoples has passed.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60)\nTranslation: Until I reach the junction of the two seas or continue for ages.\nHere the word «مَضٰی» is used in terms of time. Meaning I will not stop even if ages pass."
    },
    {
      "id": 1229,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَارَ» To walk about. To stroll. To travel.",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to walk about. To stroll, to promenade, whether for any purpose. And the walking person is called «سَائِرٌ», and a group walking together is called «سَیَّارَۃ».\nIn the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ وَ سَارَ بِاَہۡلِہٖۤ» (28/29)\nTranslation: And when Moses had completed the term and was traveling with his family."
    },
    {
      "id": 1230,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«رَجِلَ» To walk on foot when some people are also mounted.",
      "d": "«رَجِلَ» means to walk on foot. And its usage is when in comparison some are mounted and some are on foot.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ »(22/27)\nTranslation: They will come to you on foot and on every lean camel.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا» (2/239)\nTranslation: But if you fear [an enemy, then pray] on foot or riding.\nAnd if they are not mounted, then the word «مَشٰی» will come."
    },
    {
      "id": 1231,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To drive/make walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَاقَ» Means to drive, to make walk by driving from behind.",
      "d": "«سَاقَ» means to drive, to make walk by driving from behind. As a shepherd drives livestock (F.L 187). A driver driving a vehicle and the driver is called «سَوَّاقٌ» (Q.J).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا» (19/86)\nTranslation: And We will drive the criminals to Hell in thirst."
    },
    {
      "id": 1232,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To drive/make walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«اَزۡجٰی» To drive slowly.",
      "d": "«اَزۡجٰی» means to drive slowly. To drive gently. And «مُزَجّٰی» means weak (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلَمۡ  تَرَ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِیۡ سَحَابًا ثُمَّ  یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ» (24/43)\nTranslation: Do you not see that Allah drives clouds? Then He brings them together."
    },
    {
      "id": 1233,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To drive/make walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَلَکَ» To make walk on a path or to walk on a path.",
      "d": "Two meanings are found in «سَلَکَ»:\n(1) To walk and make walk on a specific path. Used both transitively and intransitively.\n(2) To penetrate (enter) one thing into another or to pass through (M.L). To thread.\nThis word has a special connection with path.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ مَہۡدًا وَّ سَلَکَ  لَکُمۡ  فِیۡہَا سُبُلًا» (20/53)\nTranslation: '[He] who has made for you the earth as a bed [spread out] and inserted therein for you roadways.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1234,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To drive/make walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«سَیَّرَ» To make travel, to drive.",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to walk about. To stroll. To travel. And «سَیَّرَ» means to make travel. To cause to travel. To send on a journey.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10/22)\nTranslation: It is He who enables you to travel on land and sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1235,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To drive/make walk",
      "hw": "To walk",
      "s": "«اَسۡرٰی» To drive at night, to make travel.",
      "d": "«سَرٰی، یَسۡرِیۡ» means to walk at night. And «اَسۡرٰی» means to drive at night. To make travel. To send on a journey.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَسۡرِ  بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/81)\nTranslation: So set out with your family during a portion of the night.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Exalted is He who took His Servant by night."
    }
  ],
  "262": [
    {
      "id": 1236,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To shout/scream",
      "hw": "To shout",
      "s": "«نَعَقَ» To call with a split throat.",
      "d": "«نَعَقَ» means to call someone with a loud voice splitting the throat. A crow to caw loudly. A shepherd to call the herd from a distance (F.L 194).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡ یَنۡعِقُ بِمَا لَا یَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا دُعَآءً  وَّ  نِدَآءً» (2/171)\nTranslation: And the example of those who disbelieve is like that of one who shouts at what hears nothing except calls and cries."
    },
    {
      "id": 1237,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To shout/scream",
      "hw": "To shout",
      "s": "«صَدَّ» To make unnecessary noise.",
      "d": "«یَصِدُّ» means to make unnecessary noise. To shout. To make clamor. And «صَدَّدَ» means to clap (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ» (43/57)\nTranslation: And when the son of Mary was presented as an example, immediately your people from Him were shouting."
    },
    {
      "id": 1238,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To shout/scream",
      "hw": "To shout",
      "s": "«جَئَرَ» To cry out loudly due to panic.",
      "d": "«جَئَرَ» means to cry out loudly. To wail (Munjid). Wild animals like deer, etc., to make a loud sound and scream at the time of panic (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَخَذۡنَا مُتۡرَفِیۡہِمۡ بِالۡعَذَابِ اِذَا ہُمۡ  یَجۡئَرُوۡنَ» (23/64)\nTranslation: Until, when We seize their affluent ones with punishment, at once they are crying out."
    },
    {
      "id": 1239,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To shout/scream",
      "hw": "To shout",
      "s": "«اِسۡتَصۡرَخَ» To cry out and shout for help.",
      "d": "«صَرَخَ» means to shout so that other people come to help. To cry for help. And «اَصۡرَخَ» means to come to someone's help after hearing their cry. And:\n«اِسۡتَصۡرَخَ» means to call for one's help by shouting and crying out in front of present people.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18)\nTranslation: And he who had sought his help the previous day was crying out to him [again]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1240,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To shout/scream",
      "hw": "To shout",
      "s": "«صَرَّ» To scream.",
      "d": "«صَرَّ الرَّجُلُ» means a man to shout loudly (Munjid). And «صَرَّۃٌ» means scream (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَتِ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  فِیۡ صَرَّۃٍ  فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29)\nTranslation: And his wife approached with a cry. Then she struck her face and said, '[I am] a barren old woman!'"
    }
  ],
  "263": [
    {
      "id": 1241,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To cling",
      "hw": "To cling",
      "s": "«اَلۡحَفَ» To cling or cling to someone to persuade them to work.",
      "d": "«لِحَاف» means a covering cloth. It is an idiom, «اَلۡحَفۡتُہٗ فَالۡتَحَفَ» I covered him with a blanket, so he clung to it. And «اِلۡحَاف» means «اِلۡحَاح» meaning to cling and ask (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا» (2/273)\nTranslation: You will know them by their mark. They do not ask people persistently."
    },
    {
      "id": 1242,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To cling",
      "hw": "To cling",
      "s": "«لَزَبَ» To cling due to something being sticky and adhesive.",
      "d": "«لَازِبٌ» is called that which becomes firmly fixed and clings to a place (Muf). And according to the author of FIQH AL-LUGHAH, «لَازِبٌ» means sticky and adhesive clay (F.L 268). In the Quran, this word is used only for clay. So both meanings are confirmed.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37/11)\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 1243,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To cling",
      "hw": "To cling",
      "s": "«لَزِمَ» One thing to attach or cling to another for a long period.",
      "d": "Two things are found in «لَزِمَ»: fixation and permanence. Meaning something to stay or remain attached to one place for a long period (Muf). According to this concept, this word is translated into different words of Urdu language at different places.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا کَلِمَۃٌ سَبَقَتۡ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ لَکَانَ لِزَامًا  وَّ  اَجَلٌ  مُّسَمًّی» (20/129)\nTranslation: And if not for a word that preceded from your Lord, it would have been an obligation [due at once], and [if not for] a specified term."
    }
  ],
  "280": [
    {
      "id": 1317,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "State",
      "s": "«بَال» Used for present state when asking a question.",
      "d": "«بَال» means present state or condition. This word is general.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ  فَمَا  بَالُ  الۡقُرُوۡنِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی . قَالَ عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ» (20/51,52)\nTranslation: Pharaoh asked Moses, 'What is the state of the former generations?' He said, 'Knowledge of them is with my Lord.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1318,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "State",
      "s": "«خَطْبُ» Used for asking about a disliked matter.",
      "d": "«خَطْبُ» means action, state, matter, whether big or small. Generally used for disliked matters (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قَالَ فَمَا خَطۡبُکُمۡ اَیُّہَا الۡمُرۡسَلُوۡنَ . قَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّاۤ  اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی قَوۡمٍ مُّجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (51/31,32)\nTranslation: Abraham said to the angels, 'What is your purpose?' The angels said, 'We have been sent to a sinful people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1319,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "State",
      "s": "«دَأب» Used for habits and conduct.",
      "d": "«دَأب» means continuous walking, permanent habit, habits and manners, conduct (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَدَاۡبِ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (3/11)\nTranslation: 'Their state is like the state of Pharaoh's people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1320,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "State",
      "s": "«طَوْر» Used for one state after another.",
      "d": "«طَوْر» means measure, limit, state, condition, turn. «اَلنَّاسُ اَطْوَارٌ» means people are of several types (Munjid). «تَطَوُّر» means to change from one state to another. So «طَوْر» is a state or condition that requires change after a certain duration according to measure.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ  قَدۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ   اَطۡوَارًا» (71/14)\nTranslation: 'And Allah has created you in various states.'"
    }
  ],
  "281": [
    {
      "id": 1321,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Ruler/Judge",
      "hw": "Ruler",
      "s": "«حَاکِمْ» Means judge, one who decides and prevents injustice.",
      "d": "«حَکَمَ» means preventing injustice (M.L), a decision that prevents wrongdoing against another. «حَکَّمَ» means to make someone a judge or ruler. «تحاکم» means to take one's case to a judge for decision (Munjid). So a ruler is one who decides people's cases and prevents the oppressor from oppression.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذَا حَکَمۡتُمۡ بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ اَنۡ تَحۡکُمُوۡا بِالۡعَدۡلِ» (4/58)\nTranslation: 'And when you judge between people, judge with justice.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1322,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Ruler/Judge",
      "hw": "Ruler",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر» Government officials, those whose command is obeyed.",
      "d": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر» is plural of «وَلِیُّ الْاَمْر». «وَلّٰی» means to make someone governor, ruler or king of a region. Lexically, this word applies to a country's government administration. However, it can also apply to judicial rulers.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اَطِیۡعُوا اللّٰہَ وَ اَطِیۡعُوا الرَّسُوۡلَ وَ اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (4/59)\nTranslation: 'O you who believe! Obey Allah and obey the Messenger and those in authority among you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1323,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Ruler/Judge",
      "hw": "Ruler",
      "s": "«قَوَّام» Anyone responsible for running an individual, institution or system justly.",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means to stand. «اَقَامَ» means to straighten or establish firmly. «قَوَّمَ» means to determine and adjust something correctly (Munjid). «قَوَّام» or «قیّم» is one responsible for running affairs of an individual, institution or system correctly, protecting and supervising it, and providing its needs (F.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ وَّ بِمَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِنۡ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ» (4/34)\nTranslation: 'Men are protectors/maintainers of women because Allah has given one more than the other and because they support them from their means.'"
    }
  ],
  "282": [
    {
      "id": 1324,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«جَاوَزَ» To pass beyond a fixed place.",
      "d": "«جَاوَزَ» means to pass beyond a specific or appointed place (Munjid), to cross while traveling. «جَوَّزَ الطَّرِیّق» means the middle of the road (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62)\nTranslation: When they had passed beyond, Moses said to his servant, Bring us our morning meal. We have certainly suffered in this, our journey, [much] fatigue."
    },
    {
      "id": 1325,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«اَسْرَفَ» To exceed the limit of moderation.",
      "d": "«اَسْرَفَ» means to exceed the limit of moderation in any action, not caring for fixed boundaries. «سَرَفَ فِی الْاَمْر» means to be lazy or negligent in a matter. «اَسْرَفَ» means to transgress (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا  تُسۡرِفُوۡا» (7/31)\nTranslation: 'Eat and drink, but be not excessive.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1326,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«بَغْيُ» To transgress the limit in fulfilling a desire.",
      "d": "«بَغْيُ» means to exceed the proper limit in seeking something (Muf), to try to receive more than one's rightful due through justice, and accordingly suppress another's right.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (38/24)\nTranslation: 'And indeed, many associates oppress one another.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1328,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«فَرَطَ» To exceed limits without thinking or in haste.",
      "d": "«فَرَطَ» means to precede, to go ahead, to hurry. «فَرَطَ مِنْہُ الْقَول» means to speak without thinking (Munjid). This word is used for transgressing without thinking or in haste. «فَرَّطَ» means to be deficient and negligent (Lexicon of Antonyms).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ  وَ کَانَ   اَمۡرُہٗ   فُرُطًا» (18/28)\nTranslation: 'And he followed his desire, and his affair was ever [in] neglect.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1329,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«سَلَقَ» To transgress against another with hand and tongue.",
      "d": "«سَلَقَ» means to assault verbally or physically (Muf), to attack sharply (M.Q), to transgress against another with hand or tongue.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: 'But when fear departs, they will lash you with sharp tongues, being greedy for wealth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1330,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«غَلَا» To exceed limits in estimation due to excessive belief. To be extreme.",
      "d": "«غَلَا» means to become expensive. «غَلَا السِّعْر» means price to rise. «غَلَا السَّھَم» means to throw an arrow extremely far. «غَلَا فِی الْاَمْرِ» means to exaggerate, to exceed limits, to go beyond limits in estimation due to excessive belief (Muf), i.e., to be extreme.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لَا تَغۡلُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ وَ لَا تَقُوۡلُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡحَقَّ ؕ اِنَّمَا الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ رَسُوۡلُ اللّٰہِ وَ کَلِمَتُہٗ» (4/171)\nTranslation: 'O People of the Scripture, do not commit excess in your religion or say about Allah except the truth. The Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary, was but a messenger of Allah and His word.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1331,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding limits/Transgression",
      "hw": "Transgression",
      "s": "«شَطَطًا» To exaggerate in falsehood to an extent that reason cannot accept.",
      "d": "«شَطَطًا» means to exceed in exaggeration, to go very far beyond limits (Munjid), to lie and exaggerate in it (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَنۡ نَّدۡعُوَا۠ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖۤ  اِلٰـہًا لَّقَدۡ قُلۡنَاۤ  اِذًا  شَطَطًا» (18/14)\nTranslation: 'We will never invoke besides Him any deity. We would then certainly have spoken an extravagance.'"
    }
  ],
  "283": [
    {
      "id": 1332,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Reducing below limit",
      "hw": "Limit",
      "s": "«فَرَّطَ» Used for not completing a task properly and being negligent.",
      "d": "«فَرَّطَ» is from lexicon of antonyms. «فَرَطَ» as explained earlier means to exceed limits without thinking or in haste. «فَرَّطَ» means to fall short without thinking or in haste, to be deficient or negligent.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ» (39/56)\nTranslation: Lest a soul should say, \"Oh [how great is] my regret over what I neglected in regard to Allah.\nNote: (Lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two different meanings opposite to each other)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1333,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Reducing below limit",
      "hw": "Limit",
      "s": "«قَصَرَ» Used for reducing the quantity of something.",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» means to reduce from a fixed limit or to fall short. «قَصَرَ السَّھْم» means an arrow not reaching the target. «قَصَرَ الصَّلوٰۃ» means not praying fully but reducing it. «قَصَّرَ الشَّعْر» means to cut some portion of hair. «قَصُرَ» means to be short (Munjid). From this come words like «قَصُور، تَقۡصِیۡر» and «قَاصِر».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (4/101)\nTranslation: 'There is no blame upon you for shortening the prayer.'"
    }
  ],
  "284": [
    {
      "id": 1334,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden/Unlawful",
      "hw": "Forbidden",
      "s": "«حَرَامٌ» Matters or things strictly prohibited by Shariah.",
      "d": "«حَرَامٌ» refers to matters or things strictly prohibited by Shariah. According to the author of MAQĀĪS AL-LUGHAH, its meaning is «اَلْمَنْعُ الشَّدِیۡد» (strict prohibition). This word is general. For example, disobeying parents is haram, predator meat is haram, usury is haram, and paradise is haram for polytheists. Its opposite is halal, meaning things generally permitted.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ الۡبَیۡعَ وَ حَرَّمَ الرِّبٰوا» (2/275)\nTranslation: 'Allah has permitted trade and has forbidden interest.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1335,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden/Unlawful",
      "hw": "Forbidden",
      "s": "«سُحْت» Used for unlawful and forbidden earnings.",
      "d": "«سُحْت» is specific for earnings and wealth. It means sustenance that causes shame and disgrace, such as the price of pigs or dogs (F.L 12), wealth earned through unlawful means, forbidden earnings, bribery, etc.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ اَکّٰلُوۡنَ لِلسُّحۡتِ» (5/42)\nTranslation: 'They are avid listeners to falsehood, devourers of [what is] unlawful.'"
    }
  ],
  "285": [
    {
      "id": 1336,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«جُزْء» One part or piece of something.",
      "d": "«جُزْء» means a part or piece of something, and its plural is «اجزاء». It refers to parts or pieces that combine to complete or compose something (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260)\nTranslation: 'Then place on each mountain a portion of them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1337,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«زُلْف» The initial portion of the night.",
      "d": "«زُلْف» means the initial portion or first hours of the night (F.L 34). The basic meanings of «زُلْف» are rank and nearness. The initial portion of night is called «زُلْف» because it is the nearest portion of the whole night.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/114)\nTranslation: 'Establish prayer at the two ends of the day and at the approach of the night.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1338,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«حَظّ» Share of goodness, favor and wealth.",
      "d": "«حَظّ» means share of goodness and favor (M.A) (F.L 135), and means wealth or good fortune, happiness (Munjid). In the Quran, this word is used for fixed shares of inheritance, which relates to goodness, favor and wealth, as well as good fortune and happiness.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/176)\nTranslation: 'For the male is what is equal to the share of two females.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1339,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«خَلَاق» A fixed share received as a result of one's character.",
      "d\": \"«خَلَاق» means a fixed share of all kinds of goodness (M.R), a large share of goodness (Munjid) (Muf) (F.L 136), i.e., the virtue that a person acquires through his character. This share relates to a person's deeds.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّقُوۡلُ رَبَّنَاۤ  اٰتِنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ» (2/200)\nTranslation: 'And among them is he who says, \"Our Lord, give us in this world,\" but he has in the Hereafter no share.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1340,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«نَصِیْب» A share that is decreed, whether little or much.",
      "d": "«نَصَب» means to fix something. «نَصِیْب» means a stone fixed in the path as a marker. «نَصِیْب» refers to a fixed share written in destiny (Muf), whether related to something beloved or disliked (F.L 135).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ ابۡتَغِ  فِیۡمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکَ اللّٰہُ  الدَّارَ الۡاٰخِرَۃَ  وَ لَا تَنۡسَ نَصِیۡبَکَ مِنَ الدُّنۡیَا» (28/77)\nTranslation: 'But seek, through that which Allah has given you, the home of the Hereafter; and [yet], do not forget your share of the world.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1341,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«کِفْل» A share in return for a good or bad deed.",
      "d": "«کِفْل» means guarantee, surety, and «کِفْل» means a share and necessary reward for a deed, whether good or bad. According to the author of Munjid, it means double reward or double sin.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً حَسَنَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّنۡہَا ۚ وَ مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً سَیِّئَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ کِفۡلٌ مِّنۡہَا» (4/85)\nTranslation: 'Whoever intercedes for a good cause will have a share from it, and whoever intercedes for an evil cause will have a share from it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1342,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "Share",
      "s": "«بَعْض» Some part of a complete thing, or one or some of similar things.",
      "d": "«بَعْض» means part, piece. It can refer to a part of a whole.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا» (2/73)\nTranslation: 'So We said, "Strike him with part of it."'\nIf the whole is a collection of independent things, then «بَعْض» can also refer to an individual. For example, «بَعْضَ النَّاس» means some people, «بَعْضَ الَلَیَالِی» means one night among nights.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ» (2/36)\nTranslation: 'You are enemies to one another.'\nBesides, this word is also used metaphorically.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (43/63)\nTranslation: 'That I may make clear to you some of that over which you differ.'"
    }
  ],
  "286": [
    {
      "id": 1343,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To protect",
      "hw": "Protection",
      "s": "«حَفِظَ» To save something from being wasted.",
      "d": "«حَفِظَ» - its opposite is «اَضَاعَ». Means to save from being wasted and perished (Munjid), to guard (M.R), to try to save something from external dangers (F.L 15).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65)\nTranslation: 'And we will guard our brother and obtain an increase of a camel's load.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1344,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To protect",
      "hw": "Protection",
      "s": "«رَعٰی» To protect and remove causes of external dangers.",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means to protect something and remove causes of external dangers. «رَاعِیْ» means shepherd, protector, and its opposite is «اِھْمَال» meaning livestock grazing without a shepherd (F.L 15).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23/8)\nTranslation: 'And they who are to their trusts and their promises attentive.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1345,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To protect",
      "hw": "Protection",
      "s": "«اَحْصَنَ» To protect through enclosure or fortress.",
      "d": "«حِصْن» means fortress or secure place, and its plural is «حُصُوْن» (59/2). Two things are fundamentally found in «حَصَن»: protection, enclosure (M.L). According to the author of Munjid, it means to secure in a strong place. Also, a woman protecting her chastity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا» (66/12)\nTranslation: 'And Mary, the daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity.'\nOne meaning is also entering into marriage, because marriage also serves as a fortress against indecency.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (4/24)\nTranslation: 'And [also prohibited to you are all] married women except those your right hands possess.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1346,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To protect",
      "hw": "Protection",
      "s": "«کَلَأَ» To protect and keep safe and sound.",
      "d": "«کَلَأَ» means to watch over something constantly and keep it safe. Two things are fundamentally found in this: (1) vigilance (2) permanence (M.L, Muf), and means to save something from turning towards calamity with safety (F.L 169).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ مَنۡ یَّکۡلَؤُکُمۡ  بِالَّیۡلِ وَ النَّہَارِ مِنَ الرَّحۡمٰنِ» (21/42)\nTranslation: 'Say, "Who can protect you at night or by day from the Most Merciful?"'"
    }
  ],
  "287": [
    {
      "id": 1347,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Dowry",
      "hw": "Dowry",
      "s": "«صَدُقَۃ» Includes all obligations of a woman including dowry.",
      "d": "«صَدُقَۃ» - its plural is «صَدُقٰت». If «صَدَقَۃ» has dammah on dal, it means charity; if it has fatha, it means dowry (Munjid). «اَصْدَقَ الْاِبْنَۃَ» means to fix dowry for a daughter. Although «صَدُقَۃ» has broader meaning than dowry. Dowry refers to the fixed amount whose payment is obligatory, while «صُدَاق» refers to the charity or expense on the basis of which marriage occurs. So «صُدَاق» includes maintenance besides dowry (F.L 139).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اٰتُوا النِّسَآءَ صَدُقٰتِہِنَّ نِحۡلَۃً» (4/4)\nTranslation: 'And give the women [upon marriage] their [bridal] gifts graciously.'\nDue to the dowry being fixed, it is called «فریضۃ», and due to being compensation, it is called «اَجْر»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1348,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Dowry",
      "hw": "Dowry",
      "s": "«اَجْر» Used for dowry, salary, wages, compensation, reward, prize, return, reward - all these meanings.",
      "d": "«اَجْر» - its plural is «اُجُوْر». «اَجْر» means wages or compensation agreed between «اٰجِر» and «اَجِیْر». Since in marriage a woman accepts chastity compensation as dowry which is agreed upon by mutual consent, therefore the word «اَجْر» is used metaphorically for dowry in the Holy Quran.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (4/25)\nTranslation: 'And give them their compensation according to what is acceptable.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1349,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Dowry",
      "hw": "Dowry",
      "s": "«فَرِیْضَۃ» Means to fix, determine, make obligatory.",
      "d": "«فَرْضَ» means to fix, determine, make obligatory. «فَرِیْضَۃ» means fixed or determined share (Munjid). The word «فریضہ» is also used metaphorically for dowry because it is necessary to fix the dowry amount by mutual consent at the time of marriage.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ وَ قَدۡ فَرَضۡتُمۡ لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً فَنِصۡفُ مَا فَرَضۡتُمۡ» (2/237)\nTranslation: 'And if you divorce them before you have touched them and you have already specified for them a dowry, then [give] half of what you specified.'"
    }
  ],
  "288": [
    {
      "id": 1351,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To command",
      "hw": "Command",
      "s": "«اَذِنَ» A command that requires divine will, otherwise its meaning is to give permission or approval.",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» means to give approval or permission. When its meaning is to command, it refers to a command that requires divine will (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡ  بُیُوۡتٍ اَذِنَ اللّٰہُ  اَنۡ تُرۡفَعَ وَ یُذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (24/36)\nTranslation: '[Such niches are] in mosques which Allah has ordered to be raised and that His name be mentioned therein.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1353,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To command",
      "hw": "Command",
      "s": "«اَوْصٰی» When attributed to Allah, it means an emphatic command.",
      "d": "«اَوْصٰی» means to take a covenant from someone regarding something, to command and bequeath (Munjid). When attributed to Allah, it means an emphatic command.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَوۡصٰنِیۡ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ  وَ الزَّکٰوۃِ مَا دُمۡتُ  حَیًّا» (19/31)\nTranslation: 'And He has enjoined upon me prayer and zakah as long as I remain alive.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ ٭ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/11)\nTranslation: 'Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, what is equal to the share of two females.'"
    }
  ],
  "289": [
    {
      "id": 1354,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To attack",
      "hw": "Attack",
      "s": "«سَطَا» To attack with severity and try to overpower.",
      "d": "«سَطْوَۃٌ  بِہٖ وَعَلَیْہِ» means to attack and overpower someone. «سَطَا الْفَرَس» means a horse to run with wide steps (Munjid). «سَطَا» means to seize severely or to attack (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا» (22/72)\nTranslation: 'They are about to assault those who recite to them Our verses.'"
    }
  ],
  "290": [
    {
      "id": 1356,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To astonish",
      "hw": "Astonished",
      "s": "«حَیْرَان» Used for bewildered, perplexed, amazed, stunned - all these meanings.",
      "d": "«حَیْرَان» is a general word. To fall into hesitation due to not finding the right path, whatever the matter may be.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَالَّذِی اسۡتَہۡوَتۡہُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ حَیۡرَانَ ۪ لَہٗۤ  اَصۡحٰبٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَہٗۤ  اِلَی الۡہُدَی ائۡتِنَا» (6/71)\nTranslation: 'Like one whom the devils have enticed [to wander] upon the earth confused, [while] he has companions inviting him to guidance, [calling], "Come to us."'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1357,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To astonish",
      "hw": "Astonished",
      "s": "«بَھِتَ» To lose senses suddenly due to astonishment.",
      "d": "«بَھِتَ» means to suddenly become speechless, silent, amazed due to astonishment, to lose senses (M.Q, Munjid). To remain stunned and bewildered. To remain speechless. The word «مَبْھُوت» is derived from this.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَبُہِتَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَرَ» (2/258)\nTranslation: 'So the disbeliever was overwhelmed [by astonishment].'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«بَلۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ بَغۡتَۃً  فَتَبۡہَتُہُمۡ» (21/40)\nTranslation: 'Rather, it will come to them unexpectedly and bewilder them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1358,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To astonish",
      "hw": "Astonished",
      "s": "«عَجِبَ» To be astonished at something whose cause is unknown.",
      "d": "«اَلْعَجْب» refers to astonishment whose cause is unknown (Muf). «عَجِبَ» means to be astonished, to wonder.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَلۡ عَجِبُوۡۤا اَنۡ جَآءَہُمۡ مُّنۡذِرٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ» (50/2)\nTranslation: 'But they wonder that there has come to them a warner from among themselves.'"
    }
  ],
  "291": [
    {
      "id": 1359,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstruation",
      "hw": "Menstruation",
      "s": "«مَحِیْضٌ» Used in the meaning of menstruation.",
      "d": "«مَحِیْضٌ» is used in the meaning of menstruation. Menstruation is a well-known word. «مَحِیْضٌ» means menstruation, time of menstruation, and place of menstruation (Muf). «حَاضَتِ الْمِرْأَۃ» means a woman to have menstruation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡمَحِیۡضِ» (2/222)\nTranslation: 'And they ask you about menstruation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1360,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstruation",
      "hw": "Menstruation",
      "s": "«قُرُوْء» Used in the meaning of a woman being pure from menstruation.",
      "d": "«قُرُوْء» is plural of «قَرْءُ». Means a woman's «طھر» i.e., purity entering into menstruation. Lexically, this word applies to both «طھر» and menstruation, and it is from (lexicon of antonyms). (Lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two different meanings opposite to each other.)\nBut according to the Prophet's saying ﷺ «اُقْعُدِیْ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ اَیَّامِ اَقْرَائِک» (leave prayer during the days of your menstruation), its translation as menstruation is preferred.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡمُطَلَّقٰتُ یَتَرَبَّصۡنَ بِاَنۡفُسِہِنَّ ثَلٰثَۃَ قُرُوۡٓءٍ» (2/228)\nTranslation: 'Divorced women remain in waiting for three periods.'"
    }
  ],
  "292": [
    {
      "id": 1361,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Husband",
      "hw": "Husband",
      "s": "«بَعْل» A husband who has also had intimacy.",
      "d": "«بَعْل» means husband, spouse. Its plural is «بَعُول». Both husband and wife are each other's «بَعْل». Each one is the «بَعْل» of the other. Wife is «بَعْل» for husband, and husband is «بَعْل» for his wife. «بَاعَلَ» means for one tribe to intermarry or establish relationship with another tribe (Munjid). From this it is understood that this word is used when husband and wife belong to different tribes. Allah knows best. According to the author of FURUQ AL-LUGHAWIYYAH, a person cannot be called «بَعْل» until he has had intimacy. This is inferred from the Prophetic saying ﷺ «یوم اکل و شرب و یعال» (F.L 236).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ  شَیۡخًا» (11/72)\nTranslation: 'She said, "O woe to me! Shall I give birth while I am an old woman and this, my husband, is an old man?"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1362,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Husband",
      "hw": "Husband",
      "s": "«زَوْج» General for both rational and irrational beings. Also used for both husband and wife.",
      "d": "«زَوْج» - its plural is ازواج. Means pair. Both husband and wife are each other's «زَوْج». Each one is the «زَوْج» of the other. Wife is «زَوْج» for husband, and husband is «زَوْج» for his wife.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)\nTranslation: 'Certainly has Allah heard the speech of the one who argues with you, [O Muhammad], concerning her husband.'"
    }
  ],
  "293": [
    {
      "id": 1364,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News/Information",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«خَبْر» News related to the listener's self that can affect him.",
      "d": "«خَبْر» - its plural is اخبار. It is a well-known word. An incident that one is unaware of, and is informed about through another. Knowledge of surrounding circumstances.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ  لِاَہۡلِہِ  امۡکُثُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡۤ  اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ» (28/29)\nTranslation: 'He said to his family, "Stay here; indeed, I have perceived a fire. Perhaps I will bring you from there [some] information."'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«قُلۡ لَّا تَعۡتَذِرُوۡا لَنۡ  نُّؤۡمِنَ  لَکُمۡ  قَدۡ نَبَّاَنَا اللّٰہُ مِنۡ  اَخۡبَارِکُمۡ» (9/94)\nTranslation: 'Say, "Make no excuse - never will we believe you. Allah has already informed us of your news."'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1365,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News/Information",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«خُبْر» Used for news, information, notice - all these meanings.",
      "d": "«خُبْر» means knowledge of the reality of an incident, experience, insight. «صَدَّقَ الْخَبْرَ الْخُبْرَ» means experience and observation confirmed the heard news (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کَیۡفَ تَصۡبِرُ  عَلٰی مَا لَمۡ تُحِطۡ بِہٖ خُبۡرًا» (18/68)\nTranslation: 'And how can you have patience for what you do not encompass in knowledge?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1366,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News/Information",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«نَبَاَ» To give news about an important and major matter.",
      "d": "«نَبَاَ» means news about an important matter, especially news that the listener is also concerned with. Whether this news relates to past events or future circumstances.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6)\nTranslation: 'O you who have believed, if there comes to you a disobedient one with information, investigate.'"
    }
  ],
  "294": [
    {
      "id": 1367,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To end/perish",
      "hw": "End",
      "s": "«نَفَدَ» For something to end and not remain, to perish - the original thing perishes or goes out of hand, whereas in «خَتَمَ» the thing remains intact but no addition or subtraction can be made.",
      "d": "«نَفَدَ» means something to end and not remain, to perish (M.L). Its opposite is «بَقِیَ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا عِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَ مَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ» (16/96)\nTranslation: 'Whatever you have will end, but what Allah has is lasting.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1368,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To end/perish",
      "hw": "End",
      "s": "«خَتَمَ» Means seal, stamp.",
      "d": "«خَتَمَ» means after completing something, to seal it so that no addition or subtraction can be made (M.L). «آخر الامر» and «ختم العمل» means to finish from a task. «ختم الکتاب» means to read the whole book (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا کَانَ مُحَمَّدٌ اَبَاۤ  اَحَدٍ مِّنۡ رِّجَالِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ رَّسُوۡلَ اللّٰہِ وَ خَاتَمَ  النَّبِیّٖنَ» (33/40)\nTranslation: 'Muhammad is not the father of [any] one of your men, but [he is] the Messenger of Allah and last of the prophets.'"
    }
  ],
  "295": [
    {
      "id": 1369,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Servant",
      "hw": "Servant",
      "s": "«غُلَام» Young household servant.",
      "d": "«غُلَام» refers to a child or boy who has reached puberty and whose sexual desires have awakened. «اِغْتَلَمَ الْفَحْلُ غُلْمَۃً» means sexual passion and dominance to arise in a male. «غَلِیْم» means a young man. «اَغْلَام» means masturbation. The plural of «غُلَام» is «غِلْمَۃٌ» and «غِلْمَانٌ». From another aspect, «غُلَام» and «غِلْمَان» refer to children kept in wealthy homes for small household chores. Either they are given nominal compensation or their upbringing is their compensation. In this case, «غُلَام» can also apply to a completely young child.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» (12/19)\nTranslation: 'He said, "Good tidings! This is a boy." And they concealed him as merchandise.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ غِلۡمَانٌ  لَّہُمۡ  کَاَنَّہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤٌ  مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (52/24)\nTranslation: 'There will circulate among them [for their service] boys as though they were pearls well-protected.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1370,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Servant",
      "hw": "Servant",
      "s": "«فَتٰی» Young servant and workers.",
      "d": "«فَتٰی» and «تَفَتّٰی» means to become young. From becoming young according to age to reaching full youth is the period. Its plural is «فَتَیَان». Its feminine is «فَتَاۃ» and its plural is also «فَتَیَان». In terms of service, the usage of «فَتٰی» is very broad. «فَتٰی» and «فتاۃ» are also called slave and bondwoman. It also applies to employees and workers, and to one's servant companions. «فِتْیَۃٌ» means a group of young men.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا» (18/62)\nTranslation: 'When they had passed beyond, he said to his young man, "Bring us our morning meal."'\nThis companion was Yusha' bin Nun, who was both a special student and servant of Moses.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ  قَالَ لِفِتۡیٰنِہِ اجۡعَلُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ فِیۡ رِحَالِہِمۡ» (12/62)\nTranslation: 'And he said to his young men, "Put their merchandise into their saddlebags."'\nIn a third place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)\nTranslation: 'And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1371,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Servant",
      "hw": "Servant",
      "s": "«سُخْرِیًّا» Used for emergency, forced servitude.",
      "d": "«سَخِرَ، یَسْخَرُ» means to mock. «سَخَرَ، یَسْخُرُ» and «سَخَّرَ» means to make someone obedient by force.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَخَّرَ لَکُمۡ مَّا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (31/20)\nTranslation: 'He has subjected to you whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth.'\n«سُخْرِیَّا» also means to take work from someone without wages and salary (M.Q), and also paid service. But compulsion (force) is prominent in this. That is, to serve or work due to being compelled by needs.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43/32)\nTranslation: 'And We have raised some of them above others in degrees [of rank] that they may make use of one another for service.'"
    }
  ],
  "296": [
    {
      "id": 1373,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Damage/Harm",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«مَعَرَّۃٌ» Damage that occurs as a result of an inappropriate action.",
      "d": "«مَعَرَّۃٌ» is said for all kinds of damage and loss. «عَیَّرَ» means to be afflicted with scabies. «مَعَرَّۃ» applies to all kinds of pain, grief, damage, hardship, and abuse (Munjid, Muf). According to Ibn al-Faris, «مَعَرَّۃ» refers to pain and grief that befalls a person as a result of a sin or inappropriate action (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رِجَالٌ مُّؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ نِسَآءٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٰتٌ لَّمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡہُمۡ  اَنۡ  تَطَئُوۡہُمۡ فَتُصِیۡبَکُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَرَّۃٌۢ  بِغَیۡرِ عِلۡمٍ» (48/25)\nTranslation: 'If it had not been for believing men and believing women whom you did not know - that you might trample them and there would befall you because of them dishonor without [your] knowledge.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1374,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Damage/Harm",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«فَسَاد» Damage caused by imbalance in the limit of moderation, corruption of society.",
      "d": "«فَسَاد» - its opposite is reform. Corruption refers to damage that appears when something deviates from the limit of moderation in excess or deficiency and disrupts its balance (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ» (30/41)\nTranslation: 'Corruption has appeared throughout the land and sea by [reason of] what the hands of people have earned.'"
    }
  ],
  "297": [
    {
      "id": 1377,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To damage/spoil",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«عَاب» To damage something inherently.",
      "d": "«عیب» means a defect or flaw in something's form or within it (Muf). «عَابَ» means to make something defective or to damage it, whether living or non-living. This word applies to both speech and action (F.L 39).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ فَاَرَدۡتُّ اَنۡ اَعِیۡبَہَا» (18/79)\nTranslation: 'As for the ship, it belonged to poor people working at sea. So I intended to cause defect in it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1378,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To damage/spoil",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«اَسَنَ» Used for water becoming spoiled and foul-smelling.",
      "d": "«اَسَنَ الْمَاءُ» means water to become changed and foul-smelling. «اَسِنَ الرَّجُل» means to faint or become dizzy from entering a well with rotten water (Muf, Munjid). The word «اَسَنَ» is used for water becoming spoiled, changed, and foul-smelling.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡہَاۤ اَنۡہٰرٌ  مِّنۡ  مَّآءٍ غَیۡرِ اٰسِنٍ» (47/15)\nTranslation: 'In it are rivers of water unaltered.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1379,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To damage/spoil",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«سَنَّ» Used for things that spoil over a long period.",
      "d": "«سِنّ» means tooth and also age. «سُنَّۃ» means way, tradition. «سَنَّ سُنَّۃ» means he established or initiated a way (Muf, Munjid). The word «سَنَّ» contains the concept of duration and permanence. «مَسْنُوْن» refers to something that becomes spoiled and foul-smelling after a long period. However, this word is generally used for mud, etc.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26)\nTranslation: 'And We did certainly create man out of clay from an altered black mud.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1380,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To damage/spoil",
      "hw": "Damage",
      "s": "«سَنِہَ» Used for food and drink becoming foul-smelling.",
      "d": "«سَنِہَ» means to be many years old. «سَنِہَ الطَّعَام وَالشَّرَاب» means food and drink to become changed, to spoil. «تَسَنَّہَ الْخُبْزُ» means bread to rot, to become foul-smelling (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَانۡظُرۡ اِلٰی طَعَامِکَ وَ شَرَابِکَ لَمۡ یَتَسَنَّہۡ» (2/259)\nTranslation: 'Look at your food and your drink; it has not changed.'"
    }
  ],
  "298": [
    {
      "id": 1381,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To spend",
      "hw": "Spend",
      "s": "«اَنْفَقَ» is a general word for spending.\n«بَخِلَ» To not spend or reduce even on legitimate needs.\n«اِقْتَرَ» To be stingy in maintenance for one's family.\n«اَسْرَفَ» To spend more than necessary.\n«بَذَّر» To spend wastefully and without need.",
      "d": "«اَنْفَقَ» is a general word for spending. It generally means spending wealth and money. However, it contains the concept that wealth comes from one side and is spent from the other. «نَفَقَ» refers to a tunnel that is open on both ends. «نیفق السّراویل» means the crotch of trousers. «مَائِرَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» means a wild mouse entered from one end of its hole and exited from the other. In Islamic terminology, hypocrisy is called the way a person enters Islam from one path and exits from another (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَنۡفِقُوۡا مِنۡ مَّا  رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ  اَحَدَکُمُ  الۡمَوۡتُ» (63/10)\nTranslation: 'And spend from that which We have provided for you before death approaches one of you.'\nFor «بُخْل» and «اَقْتَرَ» see 'To be stingy'.\nFor «اَسْرَفَ» and «بَذَّرَ» see 'To spend wastefully'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1382,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To spend",
      "hw": "Spend",
      "s": "«اَھْلَکَ» To spend a lot of wealth in blameworthy, evil purposes.",
      "d": "The original meaning of «اَھْلَکَ» is to destroy, ruin or waste something. When related to wealth, it means to spend all one's wealth. This is generally used for spending wealth in bad places.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا  لُّبَدًا» (90/6)\nTranslation: 'He says, "I have destroyed wealth in abundance."'"
    }
  ],
  "299": [
    {
      "id": 1384,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To buy and sell",
      "hw": "Trade",
      "s": "«شَرٰی» To buy and sell when the purpose is to fulfill personal need. However, «اِشْتَرٰی» means to buy.",
      "d": "Like «بیع», «شَرٰی» is also from lexicon of antonyms and is used for both buying and selling. However, «اِشْتَرٰی» is specific for buying. «مُشْتَرِی» means buyer.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اشۡتَرٰی مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ بِاَنَّ لَہُمُ الۡجَنَّۃَ» (9/111)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their properties [in exchange] for that they will have Paradise.'\nNote: (Lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two different meanings opposite to each other)"
    }
  ],
  "300": [
    {
      "id": 1386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "Treasure",
      "s": "«قِنْطَار» A large quantity of wealth and money.",
      "d": "«قِنْطَار» - a large quantity of gold, silver or cash. Its plural is «قَنَاطِیْر». According to the author of FIQH AL-LUGHAH, this quantity is four thousand dinars or more, or twelve thousand uqiyyah.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مَنۡ  اِنۡ تَاۡمَنۡہُ بِقِنۡطَارٍ یُّؤَدِّہٖۤ  اِلَیۡکَ» (3/75)\nTranslation: 'And among the People of the Scripture is he who, if you entrust him with a great amount [of wealth], he will return it to you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "Treasure",
      "s": "«کَنْز» Hidden accumulated wealth.",
      "d": "«کَنْز» - its plural is «کُنُوز». Accumulated wealth that is hidden from people, whether in the form of buried treasure or through other means. According to Ibn al-Faris, any wealth that is sealed. «کَنَزَ المال» means to accumulate wealth, to bury it (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  وَ کَانَ تَحۡتَہٗ کَنۡزٌ لَّہُمَا» (18/82)\nTranslation: 'And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphan boys in the city, and there was beneath it a treasure for them.'"
    }
  ],
  "301": [
    {
      "id": 1389,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To become dry",
      "hw": "Dry",
      "s": "«یَبَسَ» is a general word for dryness.",
      "d": "«یَبَسَ» - its opposite is «رَطَبَ». This word is general. Water or moisture to disappear from something or a place. Something to become dry.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَسۡرِ بِعِبَادِیۡ فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» (20/77)\nTranslation: 'Take My servants by night. Indeed, you will be pursued. Then leave the sea in a split condition. Indeed, they are an army to be drowned.' And strike for them a dry path through the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1390,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To become dry",
      "hw": "Dry",
      "s": "«ھَاجَ» For vegetation to naturally become dry and yellow after maturing.",
      "d": "«ھَاجَ» means vegetation to turn from green to yellow and dry due to natural requirement or lack of water. Vegetation to reach full bloom and then decline when it ripens, turns yellow and becomes ready for cutting (Muf). «ھَاجَ النَّبَتُ» means grass to dry up. «ھَاجَتُ الْاَرْض» means the grass of the land to start drying (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا» (39/21)\nTranslation: 'Then He produces thereby crops of varying colors; then they dry and you see them turned yellow; then He makes them [scattered] debris.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1391,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To become dry",
      "hw": "Dry",
      "s": "«ھَمَدَ» For vegetation to dry up and wither due to lack of water or barren land.",
      "d": "«ھَمَدَ» means land to become dry and barren due to lack of water, or vegetation to dry up and wither (Muf). «نَبَاتٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» means withered grass. «اَرْضٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» means dry and barren land (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ ہَامِدَۃً  فَاِذَاۤ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا الۡمَآءَ   اہۡتَزَّتۡ وَ  رَبَتۡ وَ  اَنۡۢبَتَتۡ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ  بَہِیۡجٍ» (22/5)\nTranslation: 'And you see the earth barren, but when We send down upon it rain, it quivers and swells and grows [something] of every beautiful kind.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1393,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To become dry",
      "hw": "Dry",
      "s": "«غَاضَ» To decrease by drying, to shrink, for water level to go down.",
      "d": "«غَاضَ» means to reduce something and for it to decrease automatically (Muf), to shrink something or for it to shrink. Used both transitively and intransitively (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تَحۡمِلُ کُلُّ اُنۡثٰی وَ مَا تَغِیۡضُ الۡاَرۡحَامُ وَ  مَا تَزۡدَادُ» (13/8)\nTranslation: 'Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs lose [prematurely] or what they increase.'\nWhen «غَاضَ» is related to water, it means water to dry up, and for the earth to absorb and the water level to go down (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» (11/44)\nTranslation: 'And it was said, "O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, withhold [your rain]." And the water subsided.'"
    }
  ],
  "302": [
    {
      "id": 1394,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To gain relief/Deliverance/Salvation",
      "hw": "Salvation",
      "s": "«نَجَات» is a general word. Used for gaining relief from entanglement, sudden calamity, punishment, affliction, etc.",
      "d": "«نَجَات» means to be saved from a sudden calamity, difficult task, affliction or punishment. «اَنْجٰی» means to give relief to another. This word is general.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (7/141)\nTranslation: 'And [recall] when We saved you from the people of Pharaoh.'\n«نَجَات» means salvation, deliverance and rescue (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یٰقَوۡمِ مَا لِیۡۤ  اَدۡعُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَی النَّجٰوۃِ وَ تَدۡعُوۡنَنِیۡۤ   اِلَی  النَّارِ» (40/41)\nTranslation: 'And O my people, how is it that I invite you to salvation while you invite me to the Fire?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1396,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To gain relief/Deliverance/Salvation",
      "hw": "Salvation",
      "s": "«اَنْقَذَ» This word is more specific than salvation. Used for gaining relief from danger, destruction or punishment.\nSee also 'To gain relief'",
      "d": "«اَنْقَذَ» means to save someone from danger or destruction, to rescue and save (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» (39/19)\nTranslation: 'Then can you save one who is in the Fire?'"
    }
  ],
  "303": [
    {
      "id": 1397,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation/Created beings",
      "hw": "Creation",
      "s": "«بَرِیَّۃ» Means to bring something from non-existence to existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ».",
      "d": "Derived from «بَرَء». Means to bring something from non-existence to existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ». All creation, the entire universe, earth and heavens, other planets are also included in this.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ ۙ اُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمۡ خَیۡرُ الۡبَرِیَّۃِ» (98/7)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, they who have believed and done righteous deeds - those are the best of creatures.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1398,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation/Created beings",
      "hw": "Creation",
      "s": "«اَنَام» Used for all types of creation present on earth.",
      "d": "«اَنَام» is used for all types of creation present on earth. Whether living or non-living.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَضَعَہَا لِلۡاَنَامِ» (55/10)\nTranslation: 'And the earth He laid [out] for the creatures.'\n«اَلْوَرٰی» means the creation present on earth at one time. Past and future generations are not included (Muf), but this word is not used in the Holy Quran. Its plural is «وَرَایَا»."
    }
  ],
  "304": [
    {
      "id": 1400,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "Dream",
      "s": "«مَنَام» is a general word for dream.",
      "d": "«مَنَام» means the state of sleeping. What a person sees in sleep is also «مَنَام», whether it has any reality or not.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذۡ یُرِیۡکَہُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَنَامِکَ قَلِیۡلًا» (8/43)\nTranslation: '[Remember, O Muhammad], when Allah showed them to you in your dream as few.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1402,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "Dream",
      "s": "«اَحْلَام» Incoherent, absurd and frightening dreams.",
      "d": "«اَحْلَام» is plural of «حُلُم». «حَلَمَ» means to become young and adult. «حُلْم» means dream of youth. Absurd and frightening dreams (M.L, Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ  الۡاَحۡلَامِ  بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44)\nTranslation: 'They said, "[It is but] a mixture of false dreams, and we are not learned in the interpretation of dreams."'"
    }
  ],
  "305": [
    {
      "id": 1404,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Desire",
      "hw": "Desire",
      "s": "«ھَوٰی» Evil desires or natural desires or evil use of natural desires.",
      "d": "«ھَوٰی» - its plural is «اَھْوَاء». Means desires of the self and inclination towards them (Muf). «ھَوٰی یَھْوِی» means to fall from above to below. «اَلْمَھْوَاۃ» means pit. «اَھَوَاء» refers to desires that cause a person to lose his worth and status when followed (Munjid). This word is generally used in a bad sense. In Ibn Faris's words, «ھَوَی النَّفْسُ خَالٍ مِّنْ کُلِّ خَیْرٍ» means desires of the self are desires in which there is no goodness.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ  الۡہَوٰی فَاِنَّ  الۡجَنَّۃَ  ہِیَ الۡمَاۡوٰی» (79/40,41)\nTranslation: 'But as for he who feared the position of his Lord and prevented the soul from [unlawful] inclination, then indeed, Paradise will be [his] refuge.'"
    }
  ],
  "306": [],
  "307": [
    {
      "id": 1410,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food/Sustenance",
      "hw": "Food",
      "s": "«قُوْت» Amount of food sufficient for a living being to survive.",
      "d": "«قُوْت» means food, nourishment. Enough quantity of food for a living being to survive. Its plural is «اَقْوَات». «قَاتَ یَقُوْتُ» means to feed food. «اَقَات» means to give something from which strength can be obtained. «مَا لَہٗ قُووْتُ لَیْلَۃٍ» means he does not have food even for a night (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہَا وَ بٰرَکَ فِیۡہَا وَ قَدَّرَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَقۡوَاتَہَا فِیۡۤ  اَرۡبَعَۃِ  اَیَّامٍ» (41/10)\nTranslation: 'He placed on the earth firmly set mountains over its surface, and He blessed it and determined therein its [creatures'] sustenance in four days.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1411,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food/Sustenance",
      "hw": "Food",
      "s": "«رِزْق» Anything that directly or indirectly causes spiritual or physical nourishment.",
      "d": "«رِزْق» means sustenance. «رَزَقَ» means to provide sustenance. «رُزِق» means to receive sustenance, to be fortunate. «مُرْزُرْق» means fortunate (Munjid). This word is used both materially and spiritually. «رِزْق» also means portion. «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» means knowledge was granted to me. Materially, sustenance is anything that enters the stomach and becomes food (Muf). «رِزْق» also means rain (Muf, Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  رِزۡقُکُمۡ» (51/22)\nTranslation: 'And in the heaven is your provision.'\nSo anything that directly or indirectly causes spiritual or physical food and training is sustenance.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«قَالَ لَا یَاۡتِیۡکُمَا طَعَامٌ تُرۡزَقٰنِہٖۤ  اِلَّا نَبَّاۡتُکُمَا بِتَاۡوِیۡلِہٖ  قَبۡلَ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَکُمَا» (12/37)\nTranslation: 'He said, "You will not receive food that is provided to you except that I will inform you of its interpretation before it comes to you."'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1412,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food/Sustenance",
      "hw": "Food",
      "s": "«مَارَ» Means to bring food for family, and «مَیْر» is grain or food supplies that are stored.",
      "d": "«مَیْر» means food, nourishment. «مِیَرَۃ» means collected food. Its plural is «مَیْر» and «مَارَ». «اَمَارَ عَیَالُہٗ» means to bring food for family. «مَائِر» and «مَیَّار» means one who brings food (Munjid). «مَیْر» refers to food supplies that are kept as storage.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65)\nTranslation: 'And we will bring food for our people and guard our brother and obtain an increase of a camel's load.'"
    }
  ],
  "308": [
    {
      "id": 1413,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«رَضِیَ» Used merely for expression of approval.",
      "d": "«رَضِیَ» is a well-known word. Means to be pleased, to express approval. Its opposite is «سَخَطَ» meaning to be displeased or angry (Muf, M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَقَدۡ رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ  عَنِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  اِذۡ یُبَایِعُوۡنَکَ تَحۡتَ الشَّجَرَۃِ» (48/18)\nTranslation: 'Certainly was Allah pleased with the believers when they pledged allegiance to you under the tree.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1416,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«حَبَرَ» For the heart to be pleased with cleanliness, elegance and beauty of the environment.",
      "d": "«حَبَرَ» means to make happy and joyful. «حَبِرَ» means to be happy. «حَبِرَ الْاَرْض» means land to produce abundant crops, to become very green. «تَحَبَّر» means to be adorned, to become excellent (Munjid). «حَبَرَ» refers to happiness obtained from cleanliness, elegance and beauty of the environment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ» (30/15)\nTranslation: 'And as for those who had believed and done righteous deeds, they will be in a garden [of Paradise], delighted.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1417,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«اِسْتَبْشَرَ» For eyebrows to expand upon receiving good news or something good.",
      "d": "«بَشَر» means to peel skin. «بَشْرَۃ» means the outer surface of skin. «اِسْتَبْشِر» refers to happiness whose signs become prominent on skin or face. For eyebrows to expand. Happiness obtained upon hearing good news or receiving something good - for this, the word «اِسْتَبْشَرَ» is used. «بَشَّرَ» means to give good news that makes another happy. To give glad tidings.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡا بِبَیۡعِکُمُ الَّذِیۡ بَایَعۡتُمۡ بِہٖ» (9/111)\nTranslation: 'So rejoice in your contract which you have contracted.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ بَشَّرُوۡہُ  بِغُلَامٍ  عَلِیۡمٍ» (51/28)\nTranslation: 'And gave him good tidings of a learned boy.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1418,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«طَابَ» Happiness from which senses also enjoy.",
      "d": "«طَاب» is happiness from which besides the heart, human senses also enjoy (Muf). «طَیِّبٰت» means pure things. «طِیْب» means fragrance (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3)\nTranslation: 'Then marry those that please you of [other] women.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1419,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«فَرِحَ» To become boastful upon being happy. To celebrate.",
      "d": "«فَرِحَ» means to be happy upon receiving a blessing. It has two types: «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» when a person is happy upon receiving a portion and thanks Allah - this is a praiseworthy quality.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَرِحِیۡنَ بِمَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (3/170)\nTranslation: 'Rejoicing in what Allah has given them of His bounty.'\n«فَرِحَ النَّفْس» when a person becomes boastful upon receiving a blessing instead of thanking Allah. Means to celebrate. This is a blameworthy quality.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَلَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23)\nTranslation: 'In order that you not despair over what has eluded you and not exult [in pride] over what He has given you.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ» (28/76)\nTranslation: 'Do not exult. Indeed, Allah does not like the exultant.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1420,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«فَکِہَ» To engage in pleasant conversation and be good-humored.",
      "d": "«فَکِہَ» means to engage in pleasant conversation, to be good-humored, to laugh and make laugh (F.L 145). «طَیِّبَ النَّفْس» or good humor (M.L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاِذَا انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہِمُ انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ» (83/31)\nTranslation: 'And when they returned to their people, they returned jesting.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1421,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«اَشْمَتَ» For an enemy to be happy upon a calamity.",
      "d": "«شَمِتَ» means to be happy upon a calamity. «اَشْمَتَ» means for another to be happy upon one's calamity. شَمَاتَتَ اَعْداء is a well-known word meaning for an enemy to be happy upon a calamity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَا تُشۡمِتۡ بِیَ الۡاَعۡدَآءَ» (7/150)\nTranslation: 'Do not allow the enemies to rejoice over me.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1422,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy/please",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«اَعْجَبَ» To be pleased in one's heart with wonder and without knowing the cause - a combination of happiness and wonder.",
      "d": "«اَعْجَبَ» means something to be attractive, to seem good, with wonder that its cause is unknown (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یُّعۡجِبُکَ قَوۡلُہٗ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا» (2/204)\nTranslation: 'And of the people is he whose speech pleases you in worldly life.'"
    }
  ],
  "309": [
    {
      "id": 1425,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperity",
      "hw": "Prosperity",
      "s": "«طُوْبٰی» Prosperity with which the heart is also satisfied.",
      "d": "«طَابَ» means to obtain happiness from which besides the heart, human senses also enjoy (Muf). «طَیِّب» means pure. «طِیْب» means fragrance (Munjid). «طُوبٰی» is prosperity in which the heart is also satisfied and joyful.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ طُوۡبٰی لَہُمۡ  وَحُسۡنُ مَاٰبٍ» (13/29)\nTranslation: 'Those who believe and do righteous deeds - a good state is theirs and a good return.'"
    }
  ],
  "310": [
    {
      "id": 1426,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Clusters",
      "hw": "Clusters",
      "s": "«طَلَعَ» refers to fruit blossoms emerging as clusters. «قِطْف» refers to the state of becoming ripe and ready for picking. «قِنْو» refers to the intermediate state. However, «قِنْو» applies only to clusters of dates and grapes.",
      "d": "«طَلَعَ» lexically means to appear and come forth (M.L). Rise and set are well-known words for stars. «طَلَعَ» also refers to the new cluster when it begins to emerge from its blossom or date spathe (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ النَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ  لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ  نَّضِیۡدٌ» (50/10)\nTranslation: 'And tall palm trees having fruit arranged in layers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1427,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Clusters",
      "hw": "Clusters",
      "s": "«قُطُوْف» Ripe fruit that is completely ready for picking.",
      "d": "«قُطُوْف» is plural of «قِطْف». «قِطْف» refers to ripe fruit that is completely ready for picking. The Quran confirms this meaning, while the author of Munjid gives its meaning as 'picked fruit, bunch of grapes when picked.'\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَہُوَفِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ فِیۡ جَنَّۃٍ عَالِیَۃٍ قُطُوۡفُہَا دَانِیَۃٌ» (69/21,22,23)\nTranslation: 'He will be in a pleasant life, in a lofty garden, its clusters hanging within reach.'\nFrom this it is clear that the tree's fruit has ripened and become ready for picking, but is still on the trees, and Allah Almighty has used the word «قُطُوْف» for it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1428,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Clusters",
      "hw": "Clusters",
      "s": "«قِنْوَان» Clusters of dates and grapes that are not yet ready for picking.",
      "d": "«قِنْوَان» is plural of «قِنْو». This word is specific only for clusters of dates and grapes that are not yet ready for picking.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمِنَ النَّخۡلِ مِنۡ طَلۡعِہَا قِنۡوَانٌ دَانِیَۃٌ» (6/99)\nTranslation: 'And from the palm trees - of its emerging fruit are clusters hanging low.'"
    }
  ],
  "311": [
    {
      "id": 1429,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To betray",
      "hw": "Betrayal",
      "s": "«خَانَ» Betrayal of covenant and embezzling trust through excuses, whereas in «غَلّ» the cause of betrayal is theft.",
      "d": "«خَانَ» means to betray, and its opposite is trust. This betrayal occurs in covenants and also in property kept as trust. Such as embezzling all or part of the property through excuses and force. Similarly, betrayal applies to breaking covenants and not honoring them. To deceive (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَخُوۡنُوا اللّٰہَ وَالرَّسُوۡلَ وَتَخُوۡنُوۡۤا اَمٰنٰتِکُمۡ» (8/27)\nTranslation: 'O you who have believed, do not betray Allah and the Messenger or betray your trusts.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1430,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To betray",
      "hw": "Betrayal",
      "s": "«غَلَّ» Means to betray.",
      "d": "«غَلَّ» means to secretly keep something in one's belongings, then conceal it so it cannot be seen (Munjid, M.R). «غَلُول» means to betray, to conceal, and to be stingy - all these meanings (Munjid). So in «غَلَّ», besides betrayal, the element of theft is also included, or the means of this betrayal is theft.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا کَانَ لِنَبِیٍّ اَنۡ یَّغُلَّ ؕ وَمَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/161)\nTranslation: 'It is not [attributable] to any prophet that he would act unfaithfully [in regard to war booty]. And whoever betrays, [taking unlawfully], will come with what he took on the Day of Resurrection.'"
    }
  ],
  "312": [
    {
      "id": 1431,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent/Canopy",
      "hw": "Tent",
      "s": "«خِیَامٌ» Means tent.",
      "d": "«خِیَامٌ» (plural of tent). Tent is a well-known word. Canopies made of thick cloth or mat to protect from sun and rain, which generally do not have roofs but are sloped. According to the author of Munjid, any curtained house not built of brick, stone and clay. «خیم» also refers to a camel's litter and howdah (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72)\nTranslation: 'Fair ones reserved in pavilions.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1432,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent/Canopy",
      "hw": "Tent",
      "s": "«ظُلَّۃٌ» Means shade.",
      "d": "«ظُلَّۃٌ» is a canopy whose roof is the roof itself, without walls. «ظُلَّۃ» also refers to an umbrella, and «ظلیل» means a shady tree (Munjid). «ظِلّ» means shade, and its plural is «ظِلَال». «ظِلًّا ظَلِیْلًا» means long and dense shade.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ» (7/171)\nTranslation: 'And [recall] when We raised the mountain above them as if it was a canopy.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1433,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent/Canopy",
      "hw": "Tent",
      "s": "«سُرَادِق» Means tent, canopy, pavilion.",
      "d": "«سُرَادِق» is plural of «سَرْدَقَ». Refers to a canopy that has only walls, such as tents used at weddings. This word is derived from Persian (i.e., a word that is originally from another language and made Arabic with slight modification).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا» (18/29)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, We have prepared for the wrongdoers a fire whose walls will surround them.'"
    }
  ],
  "313": [
    {
      "id": 1435,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter",
      "hw": "Enter",
      "s": "«وَلَجَ» To enter a narrow place.",
      "d": "«اَلْوَلْوَج» means to enter a narrow place (Muf), to enter with difficulty, to penetrate.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» (7/40)\nTranslation: 'They will not enter Paradise until a camel enters into the eye of a needle.'\nFor entering or forcing into a narrow place, «اَوْلَج» will be used.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُوۡلِجُ الَّیۡلَ  فِی النَّہَارِ  وَ یُوۡلِجُ النَّہَارَ فِی الَّیۡلِ» (22/61)\nTranslation: 'He causes the night to enter the day, and He causes the day to enter the night.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1436,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter",
      "hw": "Enter",
      "s": "«صَلَی» Means to enter fire.",
      "d": "The word «صَلَی» is specific for entering fire. Means to enter fire and burn (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ؕ وَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرَارُ» (14/29)\nTranslation: 'Hell, which they will [enter to] burn, and wretched is the settlement.'\nFor entering into fire or burning, «صَلّٰی» will be used (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ الۡجَحِیۡمَ صَلُّوۡہُ» (69/30,31)\nTranslation: 'Seize him and shackle him. Then into Hellfire drive him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1437,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter",
      "hw": "Enter",
      "s": "«سَلَکَ» To pull or insert one thing into another.",
      "d": "The word «سَلَکَ» is used in several meanings and both transitively and intransitively. In all these meanings, the concept of entering is found.\nExamples:\n(1) To thread or insert, like threading a needle.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«کَذٰلِکَ سَلَکۡنٰہُ  فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (26/200)\nTranslation: 'Thus, We have inserted disbelief into the hearts of the criminals.'\n(2) To put, to insert, like putting a hand into a collar.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِسُوۡٓءٍ» (28/32)\nTranslation: 'Insert your hand into the opening of your garment; it will come out white without disease.'\nThis same verse fragment is mentioned elsewhere with «اَدْخِلْ» instead of «اُسْلُک».\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَاَدۡخِلۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (27/12)\nTranslation: 'And insert your hand into the opening of your garment; it will come out white without disease.'\n(3) To walk along a path.\nFor example, in the Quran, Allah Almighty says to the honeybee:\n«فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69)\nTranslation: 'Then follow the ways of your Lord laid down for you.'\nIn this verse, «اُسْلُکِیْ» is also translated as «اُدْخُلِیْ» (M.Q).\nAlso in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا سَلَکَکُمۡ  فِیۡ سَقَرَ» (74/42)\nTranslation: 'What put you into Saqir?'\nConsidering all these explanations, the author of MUNTAHA AL-ARAB expressed the briefest concept of «سَلَکَ» as 'pulling one thing into another' or 'pulling one thing through another.' According to the author of Munjid, it means to place one thing into another. The author of MAQĀĪS AL-LUGHAH gives two basic meanings: (1) To walk along a path (2) To insert one thing into another, to thread."
    }
  ],
  "314": [
    {
      "id": 1438,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian/Overseer",
      "hw": "Guardian",
      "s": "«خَزَنَ» Means guardian, keeper.",
      "d": "«خَزَنَ» is mostly used for collecting wealth, such as «خَزَنْتُ الدَّرَاھِمَ» (I collected coins), but the basic concept is more about protection than collecting. It is said «خَزَنْتُ السِّرَّ» (I kept the secret safe). The one who protects this collected thing or wealth is called «خَازِن». Its plural is «خَزَنَةُ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا  فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» (67/8)\nTranslation: 'Every time a company is thrown into it, its keepers ask them, \"Did there not come to you a warner?\"'\nThe difference between «خَازِن» and «مُصَیْطِر» is the same as between «حفیظ» and «رقیب». «خَازِن»'s responsibility is merely to protect and safeguard collected items, while «مُصَیْطِر» is also responsible for strict supervision because he has dominance over them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1439,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian/Overseer",
      "hw": "Guardian",
      "s": "«مُصَیْطِر» Means supervisor, keeper, overseer.",
      "d": "«مُصَیْطِر» - lexicographers write this word with س instead of ص. In the Quran, it is written with ص and a small س is written above. Some lexicographers include it under the root «سطر», and some under «سَیْطر». «سَیْطَرَ عَلٰی» means to dominate someone and become their supervisor. «سیطر» means an agent (one entrusted with a task) and supervisor.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ ؕ اِنَّمَاۤ اَنۡتَ مُذَکِّرٌ لَسۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  بِمُصَۜیۡطِرٍ» (88/21,22)\nTranslation: 'So remind, [O Muhammad]; you are only a reminder. You are not over them a controller.'\nMeaning you have no power over them to force them to accept your words."
    }
  ],
  "315": [
    {
      "id": 1440,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand/mark",
      "hw": "Brand",
      "s": "«وَسَم» Means to engrave designs, moles, etc. on the body.",
      "d": "«وَسَم» means to put a mark, to brand (Muf), and means to engrave designs, moles, etc. on the body (M.L). «وَسَّم» means to apply dye. «وَسَام» and «وَسَمَہ» is the instrument used for branding or coloring (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68/16)\nTranslation: 'We will brand him upon the snout.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1442,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand/mark",
      "hw": "Brand",
      "s": "«شِیَۃ» A mark or spot that is different from the rest of the body's color.",
      "d": "«وَشِیَ» «وَشَیْتُ الشَّیْءُ وَشْیًا» means to apply a color to something different from its general color. «وَشْیۃ» and «شِیَۃ» means a mark or spot of color that is different from the rest of the body's color (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مُسَلَّمَۃٌ لَّا شِیَۃَ فِیۡہَا» (2/71)\nTranslation: 'Sound and without any blemish.'"
    }
  ],
  "316": [
    {
      "id": 1444,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Thin/Lean",
      "hw": "Thin",
      "s": "«ضَامِر» One who becomes thin and fit due to training and exercise.",
      "d": "«ضَمَر، اَلْاَضْمَار» means horse racing field, training ground for horses, the end of the racetrack, and the period of training horses (Munjid). «ضَامِر» is an animal that becomes thin and fit not due to lack of food but due to training and frequent exercise, for speed, so it can advance in competition. In Arab usage, «ضِامِر» became specific for camels, whether male or female.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: 'And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel; they will come from every distant pass.'"
    }
  ],
  "317": [
    {
      "id": 1447,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To lengthen/extend",
      "hw": "Long",
      "s": "«بَاعَدَ» To increase distance between two things and make it longer.",
      "d": "«بَعُدَ» means to be far. «بَاعَدَ» means to increase distance between two things.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا بٰعِدۡ بَیۡنَ  اَسۡفَارِنَا» (34/19)\nTranslation: 'And they said, \"Our Lord, lengthen the distance between our journeys.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "318": [
    {
      "id": 1448,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To be intent upon",
      "hw": "Intent",
      "s": "«تَصَدّٰی» To be intent upon something temporarily and occasionally.",
      "d": "«تَصَدّٰی» means to be intent upon something like an echo, to turn attention (Muf). (Echo is the sound that returns after hitting a mountain or dome, etc.)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَمَّا مَنِ اسۡتَغۡنٰی فَاَنۡتَ  لَہٗ  تَصَدّٰی» (80/5,6)\nTranslation: 'As for he who thinks himself without need, to him you give attention.'"
    }
  ],
  "319": [
    {
      "id": 1451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and plants",
      "hw": "Trees",
      "s": "«نَجْم» Stemless plants, vegetation, herbs.",
      "d": "«نَجْم» means star and also stemless vegetation, i.e., herbs, etc. (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ النَّجۡمُ وَ الشَّجَرُ  یَسۡجُدٰنِ» (55/6)\nTranslation: 'And the plants and trees prostrate.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and plants",
      "hw": "Trees",
      "s": "«اَثْل» Plants with strong roots and tamarisk tree.",
      "d": "«اَثَلَ» means to take root in the ground. «اَثْل» is any tree with strong roots. Generally applied to the tamarisk tree (Muf, Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ  اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» (34/16)\nTranslation: 'But We replaced their two gardens with two others whose fruit was bitter and thorny and [in which there was] some lote trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and plants",
      "hw": "Trees",
      "s": "«یَقْطِیْن» A plant without a stem, like cucumber, gourd, pumpkin vines, etc.",
      "d": "«یَقْطِیْن» means any tree without a stem (Muf). Generally applied to vine plants and specifically to pumpkin/gourd vines (M.Q).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَنۡۢبَتۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ شَجَرَۃً مِّنۡ یَّقۡطِیۡنٍ» (37/146)\nTranslation: 'And We caused to grow over him a gourd vine.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and plants",
      "hw": "Trees",
      "s": "«ضَرِیْع» Thorny bushes.",
      "d": "«ضَرِیْع» means thorny bush or spiny bush (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَیۡسَ لَہُمۡ طَعَامٌ   اِلَّا مِنۡ ضَرِیۡعٍ» (88/6)\nTranslation: 'There will be no food for them except from a poisonous thorny plant.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1455,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and plants",
      "hw": "Trees",
      "s": "«زَقُّوْم» Means the colocynth tree whose leaves are broad, thick and thorny, and extremely bitter in taste.",
      "d": "«زَقُّوْم» means the colocynth tree whose leaves are broad, thick and thorny, and extremely bitter in taste.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ  شَجَرَتَ الزَّقُّوۡمِ طَعَامُ  الۡاَثِیۡمِ» (44/43,44)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, the tree of zaqqum is food for the sinful.'"
    }
  ],
  "320": [
    {
      "id": 1456,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct/Right",
      "hw": "Correct",
      "s": "In «صَوَاب» correctness relates to a person's statement or opinion, while «حَقّ» is anything or statement proven correct through experience and observation.",
      "d": "«صَوَاب» means correct, right, proper (Munjid). Its opposite is «خَطَا». «صَابَ واَصَابَ السَّھْم» means an arrow to hit the target correctly. «اِسْتِصْوَاب» means to find an opinion or action correct, to consider right. «صَوَیْب» and «مُصِیْب» mean one with correct opinion, righteous doer (Munjid). If an arrow hits the target correctly and stays there, it is called «مُصِیْبَۃٌ», which applies to every painful incident (Muf). «صَوَاب» generally relates to speech and opinion, and sometimes to action.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ  اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ وَ  قَالَ صَوَابًا» (78/38)\nTranslation: 'They will not speak except one who has received permission from the Most Merciful, and he will say what is correct.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1457,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct/Right",
      "hw": "Correct",
      "s": "«حَقّ» Used for truth, veracity.",
      "d": "«حَقّ» means truth, truthfulness, reality, correct - i.e., any statement or thing proven correct after experience and observation (Muf). Its opposite is «باطل».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» (41/53)\nTranslation: 'We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that it is the truth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1458,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To correct",
      "hw": "Correct",
      "s": "«اَصْلَحَ» Used for correcting moral and material corruption, while «سَوّٰی» is used for correcting creative defects.",
      "d": "The opposite of «اِصْلَاح» is «فَسَاد» meaning corruption. «اَصْلَحَ» means to correct corruption, to remove mischief and disorder, to correct corruption caused by excess or deficiency in something (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنۡ اُرِیۡدُ اِلَّا الۡاِصۡلَاحَ مَا  اسۡتَطَعۡتُ» (11/88)\nTranslation: 'I do not intend except reform as much as I am able.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1459,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To correct",
      "hw": "Correct",
      "s": "«سَوّٰی» Means to correct, level, equalize and straighten a task or thing.",
      "d": "«سَوٰی یَسْوِی» means the form of something to become correct. «سَوّٰی» means to correct, level, equalize and straighten a task or thing (Munjid). According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is «اَلْاِسْتِقَامَۃ وَالْاِعْتِدَال» (uprightness and moderation), which expresses the same concept.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ فَسَوّٰی» (87/2)\nTranslation: 'Who created and proportioned.'"
    }
  ],
  "321": [
    {
      "id": 1460,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between/Among",
      "hw": "Between",
      "s": "«بَیْن» This is a particle that shows separation or distinction between two different things.",
      "d": "«بَیْن» is a particle that shows separation or distinction between two different things. «بَانَ» means to be far. So «بَیْن» is used for distance or gap between two things. According to Ibn al-Faris, three things are found in «بَیْن»: (1) Separation (2) Distance (3) Clarity (M.L), i.e., something becoming clear by separating from another.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَیۡنَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (2/164)\nTranslation: 'Between the heaven and the earth.'\nThis word is used both materially and metaphorically.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«فَاحۡکُمۡ  بَیۡنَنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (38/22)\nTranslation: 'So judge between us with truth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1461,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between/Among",
      "hw": "Between",
      "s": "«خِلٰل» Between different parts of the same thing or between two things that have some connection.",
      "d": "«خِلٰل» means a space between two connected things. «اَلْخِلَال» also refers to a twig used to clean the space between teeth, and the cleaning of that space. Similarly, water is passed through the fingers or beard hair during ablution.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ  فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا» (18/33)\nTranslation: 'And We caused to gush forth within them a river.'\nThis word is also used for the space between different parts of the same thing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ» (24/43)\nTranslation: 'And you see the rain emerge from within it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1462,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between/Among",
      "hw": "Between",
      "s": "«وَسْط» The middle of something in terms of number, quantity or distance.",
      "d": "«وَسْط» means the middle place of anything from where the distance to both sides is equal (Muf), or if there are many things, equal in number from both sides. The point of moderation between excess and deficiency is called «وَسْط». This word is used both materially and metaphorically (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: 'Maintain with care the [obligatory] prayers and [in particular] the middle prayer.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ اُمَّۃً وَّسَطًا» (2/143)\nTranslation: 'And thus we have made you a just community.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1464,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between/Among",
      "hw": "Between",
      "s": "«قَصْد» The path of moderation, middle course.",
      "d": "«قَصْد» means moderation, the path or way that is between excess and deficiency, neither too much nor too little, like generosity between extravagance and stinginess, or courage between bravery and cowardice. «قَصَدَ» and «اِقْتَصَدَ فِی الْنَفَقَۃ» means to spend moderately, avoiding excess and deficiency when spending. «قَصَدَ السَّبِیْل» means to walk straight on the path, not going here and there (Muf, Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ» (31/19)\nTranslation: 'And be moderate in your pace and lower your voice.'"
    }
  ],
  "322": [
    {
      "id": 1465,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy/Enmity",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«عَدُوّ» Means enemy.",
      "d": "«عَدُوّ» - its plural is «اَعْدَاء». An enemy who is ill-wishing, spiteful, thinking of evil and harm, and rejoicing at calamity. Its opposite is «صِدِّیْق» (F.L 168).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/22)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, Satan is to you both a clear enemy.'\n«عَدَاوَۃٌ» means enmity and ill-wishing. This is the first degree of enmity (F.L 169), and means to turn away from helping someone - its opposite is loyalty (F.L 106)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1466,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy/Enmity",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«بَغۡضَآء» Means to be averse from something or someone.",
      "d": "«بُغْض» means to be averse from something or someone. This is the second degree of enmity, and its opposite is «حُبّ» (love). «بُغْضَۃٌ» means intending to humiliate and degrade someone (F.L 106).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (5/64)\nTranslation: 'And We cast among them animosity and hatred until the Day of Resurrection.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1467,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy/Enmity",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«شَانِیءَ» Means to harbor enmity.",
      "d": "«شَنَأَ» means to harbor enmity, to hold hatred, to hate (Munjid). Its verbal noun is «شَنَأٰن».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا  یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوۡمٍ عَلٰۤی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا» (5/8)\nTranslation: 'And do not let the hatred of a people prevent you from being just.'\n«شَانِیء» is one who is both ill-wishing and spiteful, i.e., holds both enmity and hatred - the worst enemy, and this is the third degree of enmity (F.L 169).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ» (108/3)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, your enemy is the one cut off.'"
    }
  ],
  "323": [
    {
      "id": 1470,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To pray/bless",
      "hw": "Prayer",
      "s": "«حَیَّیَ» To pray for long life.",
      "d": "«حَیَّ» means to live. «حَیَّیَ , تَحِیَّۃً » means to say «حَیَّاکَ اللہ» to someone, i.e., may Allah prolong your life (Munjid). This word's usage is general for all kinds of good prayers, and for prayers of peace, or in the meanings of «سَلَّم» or «سَلَام». So «سَلَّم» is specific, and «حَیَّ» is general (F.L: 44).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذَا حُیِّیۡتُمۡ بِتَحِیَّۃٍ فَحَیُّوۡا بِاَحۡسَنَ مِنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ رُدُّوۡہَا» (4/86)\nTranslation: 'And when you are greeted with a greeting, greet [in return] with one better than it or [at least] return it.'"
    }
  ],
  "324": [
    {
      "id": 1472,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "Heart",
      "s": "«قَلْب» Means (heart) the source and center of intellect, consciousness, understanding and deliberation - i.e., the heart.",
      "d": "«قَلْب» means (heart) the well-known organ, the source and center of spirit and life. Its plural is «قُلُوب». Allah Almighty has chosen the heart for intellect, understanding, thought, and reflection. The actions that modern medicine has related to the brain, the Holy Quran has related to the heart.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَہُمۡ قُلُوۡبٌ لَّا یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ بِہَا» (7/179)\nTranslation: 'They have hearts with which they do not understand.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1473,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "Heart",
      "s": "«فُؤَاد» The center of emotional intensity.",
      "d": "Some scholars have said that the difference between «عَیْن» and «بَصَر» or «اُذُن» and «سَمَع» is the same as between «قَلْب» and «فُؤَاد». This verse is presented as evidence:\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ السَّمۡعَ وَ الۡبَصَرَ وَ الۡفُؤَادَ  کُلُّ  اُولٰٓئِکَ کَانَ  عَنۡہُ  مَسۡئُوۡلًا» (17/36)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, the hearing, the sight and the heart - about all those [one] will be questioned.'\nBut this is not the reality because Allah Almighty has directly addressed the heart for intellect, understanding, consciousness and deliberation. The actual matter is that this organ heart has several parts. Just as different parts of the brain are the seat of different powers, similarly specific parts of the heart are specific for specific actions and emotions. According to medical science, «فؤاد» is the upper part of the heart that is in front of the stomach.\n«فُؤَاد»'s plural «اَفْئِدَۃ» is derived from «فأد». «فَأدُ الْلَحَم» means to roast meat on fire. «لَحْمٌ فَئِیْدٌ» means meat roasted on fire. In Ibn Faris's words, «اَلْفَأْدُ یَدُلُّ عَلٰی حَمًّی وَّشِدَّۃُ الْحَرَارَۃ (M.L)» - this word indicates heat and intense warmth. So wherever the intensity of human emotions and their effect is mentioned, this word will be used.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ  اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا» (28/10)\nTranslation: 'And the heart of Moses' mother became empty.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ ۚ وَ اَفۡئِدَتُہُمۡ  ہَوَآءٌ» (14/43)\nTranslation: 'Racing ahead, their heads raised up, their glance does not come back to them, and their hearts are void.'\nThe accountability that Allah Almighty has mentioned for «فواد» will be related to actions that humans commit under the intensity of emotions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1474,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "Heart",
      "s": "«صَدْر» Means chest.",
      "d": "«صَدْر» means chest. Its plural is «صُدُوْر». The heart is inside the chest.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لٰکِنۡ  تَعۡمَی الۡقُلُوۡبُ الَّتِیۡ فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (22/46)\nTranslation: 'But it is the hearts in the chests that grow blind.'\nSometimes only «فِی الصُّدُوْر» is said and hearts are meant, such as «شِفَآءٌ لِّمَا فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (10/57). Since «صَدْر» relates to a container/place, if tightness or expansiveness of the heart is to be mentioned, the word «صدر» will be used.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ نَعۡلَمُ اَنَّکَ یَضِیۡقُ صَدۡرُکَ بِمَا یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ» (15/97)\nTranslation: 'And We certainly know that your breast is constrained by what they say.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«اَلَمۡ نَشۡرَحۡ  لَکَ صَدۡرَکَ» (94/1)\nTranslation: 'Did We not expand for you your breast?'\n«شرح صدر» or «انشراح صدر» is an idiom. When a correct path comes to mind in a difficult and complex matter, it is called «شرح صدر». Since concealing something also requires a container, «صدر» will also be used for concealing secret matters, thoughts and whispers.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَعۡلَمُ خَآئِنَۃَ  الۡاَعۡیُنِ وَ مَا تُخۡفِی الصُّدُوۡرُ» (40/19)\nTranslation: 'He knows that which deceives the eyes and what the breasts conceal.'\nSimilarly, in another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«اِنَّ  اللّٰہَ عَلِیۡمٌۢ  بِذَاتِ الصُّدُوۡرِ» (5/7)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, Allah is Knowing of that within the breasts.'\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«الَّذِیۡ یُوَسۡوِسُ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ النَّاسِ» (114/5)\nTranslation: 'Who whispers [evil] into the breasts of mankind.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1475,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "Heart",
      "s": "«نَفْس» Center of desires. Used for being happy and concealing matters.",
      "d": "«نَفْس» - soul, life, self, being. Its plural is «نُفُوس». From this is meant the heart that is the origin and refuge of desires, the one that wishes and becomes happy.\nAs for concealing hidden matters and thoughts, this quality is common in «نُفُوس» and «صُدُوْر».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تُخۡفِیۡ فِیۡ نَفۡسِکَ مَا اللّٰہُ مُبۡدِیۡہِ» (33/37)\nTranslation: 'And you concealed within yourself that which Allah is to disclose.'\nDesires relate to the self, whether good or bad.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنۡ یَّتَّبِعُوۡنَ  اِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ مَا تَہۡوَی الۡاَنۡفُسُ» (53/23)\nTranslation: 'They follow not except assumption and what [their] souls desire.'\nBeing happy also relates to «نفس».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4/4)\nTranslation: 'But if they give up willingly to you anything of it, then take it in satisfaction and ease.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1476,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To cast into heart",
      "hw": "Heart",
      "s": "«وحی، اِلْھَام» and «اِلْقَاء» can be from Allah and also from Satan, whereas «وَسْوَسَہ» and «ھَمْز» are only from Satan.\nRevelation relates to teaching, beliefs, commands and information of the unseen. Inspiration relates only to doing or not doing a task. «اِلْقَاء» relates only to teaching.\n«وَسْوَسَہ» refers only to the coming of evil thoughts into the heart, whereas in «ھَمَزَ» urging and inciting along with evil thoughts from Satan is also included.\nEvery revelation, inspiration or casting that is according to Islamic texts is from Allah, and if not, then it is from Satan.",
      "d": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 1490,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliated/Disgraced",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«أَسْفَل» Low and base in contrast to high.",
      "d": "«اَلْسَّفْلَۃ» Lowly people, such as «دُوْن» and «أَسْفَل» meaning low and base (Mufrad) and its opposite is «أَعْلٰی». For example, in the Holy Quran: «نَجۡعَلۡہُمَا تَحۡتَ اَقۡدَامِنَا لِیَکُوۡنَا مِنَ الۡاَسۡفَلِیۡنَ» (41/29) Translation: 'We will trample them under our feet so that they become humiliated.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1650,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliated/Disgraced",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«خَاسِئ» Driven away. Most humiliated.",
      "d": "«خَسَاَ» has two meanings: (1) Weariness and weakness of sight, and (2) «خَاسِئُ مِنَ الْخَنَازِیْرِ وَ الْکِلَاب» Driven away pigs and dogs that are not allowed to approach people (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمۡتُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ اعۡتَدَوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ فِی السَّبۡتِ فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ» (2/65) Translation: 'And you certainly knew those among you who transgressed in the matter of the Sabbath, and We said to them: Be you monkeys, despised and disgraced.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1651,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«اَذَلَّ» To make someone subordinate or humiliate them.",
      "d": "«اَذَلَّ» Its opposite is «اَعَزَّ». To bring someone under control (i.e., subdue). In this, the aspect of being overcome is prominent (Fiq L 208). Also, only the higher can subdue the lower. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ تُعِزُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ وَ تُذِلُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ» (3/26) Translation: 'And You honor whom You will and You disgrace whom You will.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1652,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«اَھَانَ» To insult and humiliate someone due to enmity. This can also be done by an equal.",
      "d": "«اَھَانَ» Its opposite is «اَکْرَمَ». That is, to consider or treat someone as low or weak due to enmity. To insult them. And this can be done by an equal. And also by a superior (Fiq L 208). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یُّہِنِ اللّٰہُ فَمَا لَہٗ مِنۡ مُّکۡرِمٍ» (22/18) Translation: 'And whoever Allah disgraces - for him there is no bestower of honor.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1653,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«اَخۡزٰی» To humiliate someone due to their apparent fault.",
      "d": "«اَخۡزٰی» To disgrace and humiliate, in which a person's own bad deeds are involved. And people know about them. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَا تُخۡزِنَا یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/194) Translation: 'And do not disgrace us on the Day of Resurrection.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1654,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«فَضَحَ» To bring down someone in the eyes of others by exposing their faults.",
      "d": "«فَضَحَ» To expose someone's faults. To bring down in the eyes of others. To humiliate before others (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالَ اِنَّ ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ ضَیۡفِیۡ فَلَا تَفۡضَحُوۡنِ» (15/68) Translation: 'Lot said: These are my guests, so do not disgrace me.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1656,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "Humiliated",
      "s": "«کَبَتَ» To humiliate and disgrace someone in a state of anger.",
      "d": "«کَبَتَ» Meaning to turn back with severity and humiliation (Mufrad) and meaning to humiliate. To turn back. To repel in anger. To destroy (Munjid). This word is used for humiliating and disgracing in a state of anger. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَآدُّوۡنَ اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ کُبِتُوۡا کَمَا کُبِتَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (58/5) Translation: 'Indeed, those who oppose Allah and His Messenger will be disgraced as those before them were disgraced.'"
    }
  ],
  "355": [
    {
      "id": 1657,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Responsibility",
      "hw": "Responsibility",
      "s": "«ذِمَّۃ» Responsibility to fulfill a covenant or promise with another.",
      "d": "«ذِمَّۃ» A type of covenant, covenant of loyalty, trust, protection, responsibility. To fulfill covenants and promises. «أَنْتَ فِیْ ذِمَّۃِ اللہِ» means you are in Allah's protection. And «ذِمِّی» or «اَھْلِ الذّمّۃ» are those non-Muslims who, based on covenant, live in Dar al-Islam paying jizyah to Muslims under their protection and security (Munjid). Sometimes this word is used merely for fulfilling the responsibility of covenant and promise. For example, in the Holy Quran: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10) Translation: 'They do not observe toward a believer any pact of kinship or covenant of protection.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1658,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Responsibility",
      "hw": "Responsibility",
      "s": "«نَحۡب» Responsibility to fulfill something that one has made obligatory upon oneself.",
      "d": "«نَحۡب» A vow whose fulfillment is obligatory (Mufrad) and «نَحَبَ الرَّجُل» means a man made something obligatory upon himself (M-Q). So «نَحۡب» is that responsibility which a person has made obligatory upon himself, whether it is the responsibility of a vow or a covenant. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ قَضٰی نَحۡبَہٗ وَ مِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّنۡتَظِرُ» (33/23) Translation: 'And among them are those who have fulfilled their vow, and among them are those who are still waiting.'"
    }
  ],
  "356": [
    {
      "id": 1659,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«لَیۡل» Meaning night.",
      "d": "«لَیۡل» is a well-known word meaning night, and its opposite is «نَھَار» meaning day. «لَیۡل» is the time from sunset to sunrise. In the Quran, at many places night and day or both are mentioned together. Night is divided into 12 hours or 12 watches. The names of these watches in order are: «شَفَق، غَسَق، عَتَمَہ، دَقَّۃ، فَحَّمَہ، زُلْفَۃ، زَلْقَۃ، بَھۡرَۃ، سَحَر، فَجَر، صَبَح، صَبَاح» (Fl 292)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1660,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«بَیَاتًا» Meaning to spend the night.",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» Meaning to spend the night. To pass the night. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64) Translation: 'And those who spend the night in prostration and standing before their Lord.' And «بَیَاتًا» means at any time during the night. While sleeping. In a state of sleep. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَتٰىکُمۡ عَذَابُہٗ بَیَاتًا اَوۡ نَہَارًا» (10/50) Translation: 'Say: Have you considered: if His punishment should come to you by night or by day?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1661,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«بَاتَ» Meaning to spend the night, to pass the night, and the place where the night is spent.",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» Meaning to spend the night. To pass the night. And the place where the night is spent. That place is a house (M-L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64) Translation: 'And those who spend the night in prostration and standing before their Lord.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1662,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«بَیَّتَ» To gather at home after part of the night has passed and consult on a matter.",
      "d": "«بَیَّتَ» Meaning to gather at home after part of the night has passed and consult on a matter (M-L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِذۡ یُبَیِّتُوۡنَ مَا لَا یَرۡضٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ» (4/108) Translation: 'When they conspire by night in speech which He does not approve.' For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالُوۡا تَقَاسَمُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ لَنُبَیِّتَنَّہٗ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ ثُمَّ لَنَقُوۡلَنَّ لِوَلِیِّہٖ مَا شَہِدۡنَا مَہۡلِکَ اَہۡلِہٖ» (27/49) Translation: 'They said: Swear by Allah that we will attack him and his family at night. Then we will say to his heir: We did not witness the destruction of his family.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1663,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«اَسۡرٰی» Meaning to travel at night.",
      "d": "«اَسۡرٰی» Meaning to travel at night. To take out. To lead out. For example, in the Holy Quran: «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» (17/1) Translation: 'Exalted is He who took His Servant by night from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1664,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«طَرَقَ» Meaning path.",
      "d": "«طَرِیْق» means path and «طَارِقْ» means one who walks on the path. But in common usage, particularly a traveler who comes at night is called «طَارِق». And a star is called «طَارِق» because it generally appears at night (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الطَّارِقِ» (86/1) Translation: 'By the sky and the night comer.' In this verse, «طَارِق» can refer to stars or a guest who comes at night."
    },
    {
      "id": 1665,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«نَفَشَ» Those goats that spread out to graze at night without a shepherd.",
      "d": "«نَفْشُ الْغَنَم» Meaning goats spreading out to graze at night without a shepherd. And «اَلنَّفْش» refers to those goats that spread out to graze at night without a shepherd (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ دَاوٗدَ وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ اِذۡ نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78) Translation: 'And David and Solomon - when they judged concerning the field - when the sheep of a people overran it at night.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1666,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night activities",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«تَہَجَّدَ» To pray voluntary prayers at night while awake.",
      "d": "«ھَجَدَ» Meaning to sleep at night and also to wake up (this is among the words with opposite meanings). And «ھَجَّدَ تَہَجَّدَ» Meaning to make sleep at night and also to wake up. To wake from sleep. To sleep at night. To pray at night after waking up (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً لَّکَ» (17/79) Translation: 'And from [part of] the night, pray with it as additional [worship] for you.'"
    }
  ],
  "357": [
    {
      "id": 1667,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«طَرِیْق» is a general word for path.",
      "d": "«طَرِیْق» Its plural is «طَرَائِق». This word is used for every type of path (Fl 269). This word is used in both material and spiritual senses. An example of material usage is the saying of Allah Almighty: «فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» (20/77) Translation: 'Strike for them a dry path through the sea.' And an example of spiritual usage is the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ لَا لِیَہۡدِیَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا اِلَّا طَرِیۡقَ جَہَنَّمَ» (4/168) Translation: 'And Allah would not guide them to a path except the path of Hell.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1668,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«صِرَاط» A path that must be walked on carefully.",
      "d": "«صُرَاط» A long and sharp sword (Munjid) and the path that will be made to cross Hell, commonly known as Sirat. Its quality is also described as being sharper than a sword and thinner than a hair. So «صِرَاط» is a path that must be traversed with extreme caution and alertness. And there are many dangers around it. This extreme caution and carefulness in traversing the path is called Taqwa. This word «صِرَاط» is used in both material and spiritual senses. In spiritual sense, its concept is generally the path of guidance. According to Abu Hilal, «صِرَاط» means an easy path (Fiq L 246) and Allah knows best. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ» (1/5) Translation: 'Guide us to the straight path.' And an example of material usage is the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ لَا تَقۡعُدُوۡا بِکُلِّ صِرَاطٍ تُوۡعِدُوۡنَ وَ تَصُدُّوۡنَ عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (7/86) Translation: 'And sit not on every path, threatening and averting from the way of Allah.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1669,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«سَبِیْل» A path that can be walked on easily and has considerable traffic.",
      "d": "«سَبِیْل» Every path that can be walked on easily (Mufrad). «اِبۡنُ السَّبِیۡل» means traveler and «عَابِرِی سَّبِیۡل» (4/43) means wayfarer. Its plural is «سُبُل». And «سبیل» means open road. «أَسۡبَلُ الطَّرِیۡق» means a path with much traffic. And «أَسۡبَلُ الدَّمۡعِ وَالْمَطَر» means tears or rain flowing and raining abundantly. So «سَبِیۡل» is a path where there is frequent traffic (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran, Allah Almighty says to the honey bee: «فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69) Translation: 'Then follow the ways of your Lord made smooth for you.' Here «سُبُل» refers to the natural guidance that Allah Almighty has placed in everything by nature, and which can be easily followed. And all walk equally. This word is used in both spiritual and material senses. The above example is spiritual, and an example of material usage is the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ اِنَّہَا لَبِسَبِیۡلٍ مُّقِیۡمٍ» (15/76) Translation: 'And indeed, it [the city] is on a straight path.' Now observe that Allah Almighty has used three words «طَرِیۡق», «صِرَاط» and «سَبِیۡل» for this 'path of guidance' in the Holy Quran. It is «طَرِیۡق» because this word is general, used for every path. It is «صِرَاط» because it is surrounded by the limits and restrictions of commands and prohibitions. And it is «سَبِیۡل» because whoever stands on this path with determination, the Shariah has made all kinds of facilities available for him, and the number of people walking on it is also considerable."
    },
    {
      "id": 1670,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«فَجّ» An open path between two mountains.",
      "d": "«فَجَّۃٌ» The opening between two mountains and «فَجۡوَۃ» is the plain between two mountains, and «فَجّ» is the open path that passes through this plain and connects the two mountains. The plural of «فَجّ» is «فِحَاج». For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ یَاۡتُوۡکَ رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27) Translation: 'And proclaim to the people the Hajj [pilgrimage]; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel; they will come from every distant pass.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1671,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«اِمَام» Highway, open road.",
      "d": "«اِمَام» has two meanings: (1) Leader and (2) Highway. A major and open road (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَانۡتَقَمۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ ۘ وَ اِنَّہُمَا لَبِاِمَامٍ مُّبِیۡنٍ» (15/79) Translation: 'So We took retribution from them, and indeed, both [cities] are on a clear highway.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1672,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path - Way",
      "hw": "Path",
      "s": "«نَجۡد» A path going up and down a valley.",
      "d": "«نَجۡد» has two meanings: (1) Valley and (2) A path that goes up to a height or comes down from above (Fl 269). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ النَّجۡدَیۡنِ فَلَا اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» (90/10) Translation: 'And We have shown him the two ways, but he did not pass over the difficult path.'"
    }
  ],
  "358": [
    {
      "id": 1675,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To establish a way - To make customary",
      "hw": "Customary",
      "s": "«سَنَّ» Used for establishing every good and bad way. However, in Islamic terminology, «سُنَّۃ» refers only to the actions and sayings of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ.",
      "d": "«سَنّ» Meaning for a thing to be established or become customary and to function correctly (M-L). Used as both intransitive and transitive. As in the Prophetic saying: «مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّۃً» ... meaning whoever establishes a way ... Used in both good and bad senses. And when its attribution is to Allah, it means the law of Allah or the custom of Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا» (35/43) Translation: 'Then do they await except the way of the former peoples? But you will never find in the way of Allah any change.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1676,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To establish a way - To make customary",
      "hw": "Customary",
      "s": "«شَرَعَ» Allah Almighty to appoint a clear and defined path for the servants through the Prophet. From Adam AS to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, there has been change in this, but now this part of the religion is also immutable (cannot be changed). Because you ﷺ were the Seal of the Prophets and the religion was also completed upon you ﷺ.",
      "d": "«شَرَعَ» A clear and defined path. But its application is only to divine commands (Mufrad) and «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْمِ» means to make law for a people. And Shariah means Islamic law, divine commands, code (Munjid). «شَرَعَ» are actually those laws in which Allah Almighty made changes according to the demands of the times (for more details see 'Way' and 'Religion'). For example, in the Holy Quran: «شَرَعَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا وَصّٰی بِہٖ نُوۡحًا» (42/13) Translation: 'He has ordained for you of religion what He enjoined upon Noah.' However, from a linguistic perspective, attribution of this word to other than Allah and false deities is also possible. For example, the saying of Allah Almighty: «اَمۡ لَہُمۡ شُرَکٰٓؤُا شَرَعُوۡا لَہُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا لَمۡ یَاۡذَنۡۢ بِہِ اللّٰہُ» (42/21) Translation: 'Or have they other deities who have ordained for them of religion that to which Allah has not consented?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1677,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To establish a way - To make customary",
      "hw": "Customary",
      "s": "«اِبۡتَدَعَ» To introduce a custom or way as part of Shariah which has no basis in Shariah.",
      "d": "«اَلۡاِبۡدَاعُ» Meaning to invent something without following or imitating anyone. And «بِدۡعَۃ» is every new custom or practice that is introduced into the religion considering it part of the religion, but has no basis in Shariah. And «اِبۡتَدَعَ» means to introduce something new into Shariah by making it a part of it. And the saying of the Prophet ﷺ is that every innovation, however good it may seem, is pure misguidance. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ رَہۡبَانِیَّۃَۨ ابۡتَدَعُوۡہَا مَا کَتَبۡنٰہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (57/27) Translation: 'But monasticism they invented - We did not prescribe it for them.'"
    }
  ],
  "359": [
    {
      "id": 1678,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To be pleased - To satisfy",
      "hw": "Pleased",
      "s": "«رَضِیَ» To be pleased, to be happy. A general word.",
      "d": "«رَضِیَ» is a well-known word meaning to be pleased with someone, to be happy, to show approval or pleasure. For example, in the Holy Quran: «رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ عَنۡہُمۡ وَ رَضُوۡا عَنۡہُ» (5/119) (98/8) Translation: 'Allah is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1679,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To be pleased - To satisfy",
      "hw": "Pleased",
      "s": "«طَوَّعَ» To reluctantly make one's heart agree to a bad deed.",
      "d": "«اَطَاعَ» Meaning to obey a command with a happy heart. And «طَوَّع» means to reluctantly make one's heart agree to a disliked (undesirable) deed (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَطَوَّعَتۡ لَہٗ نَفۡسُہٗ قَتۡلَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5/30) Translation: 'Then his soul permitted to him the murder of his brother.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1680,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To be pleased - To satisfy",
      "hw": "Pleased",
      "s": "«اَعۡتَبَ» To complain with the intention of satisfying someone who is upset.",
      "d": "«عَتَبَ» Meaning to blame someone, to be angry. And «اَعۡتَبَ» means to remove the cause of anger. To console the one who is upset (and this is among the words with opposite meanings). And «عِتَاب» means displeasure (anger) at spoiling friendly and sympathetic relations (Fiq L 39). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَعۡتِبُوۡا فَمَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمُعۡتَبِیۡنَ» (41/24) Translation: 'And if they seek to be excused, they will not be among those excused.' (Words with opposite meanings are words that have two different meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other)"
    }
  ],
  "360": [
    {
      "id": 1681,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank - To attain rank",
      "hw": "Rank",
      "s": "«دَرَجَۃ» A stage of excellence and superiority.",
      "d": "«دَرَجَۃ» Meaning superiority. Excellence. Rank. Station. The opposite of «دَرْج» is «دَرْک». And both these words are two aspects of the same thing. If you climb the steps of a ladder towards the ceiling above, these steps are called «دَرَجَات» and from the perspective of going down, these same steps are called «دَرَکَات». This is why the expressions «دَرَجَاتُ الْجَنَّۃ» and «دَرَکَاتُ النَّار» are used. And by degree is meant that much superiority and excellence that exists from one level to another. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَہُنَّ مِثۡلُ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ ۪ وَ لِلرِّجَالِ عَلَیۡہِنَّ دَرَجَۃٌ» (2/228) Translation: 'And they [women] have rights similar to those [of men] over them in kindness, but men have a degree over them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1682,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank - To attain rank",
      "hw": "Rank",
      "s": "«زُلۡفٰی» Nearness in honor and status.",
      "d": "«زُلۡفٰی» Meaning nearness in honor, status and rank (M-L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اِنَّ لَہٗ عِنۡدَنَا لَزُلۡفٰی وَ حُسۡنَ مَاٰبٍ» (38/40) Translation: 'And indeed, for him is nearness to Us and a good place of return.' But when this root becomes a verb form, it also gives the meaning of nearness in distance. For example, the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ اَزۡلَفۡنَا ثَمَّ الۡاٰخَرِیۡنَ» (26/64) Translation: 'And We brought near the others as well.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1683,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank - To attain rank",
      "hw": "Rank",
      "s": "«قَرَّبَ» To make someone close by granting rank.",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» Meaning to be near. And to do such an action that becomes a means of nearness in rank. And «قُرۡبَان» is that offering through which attainment of rank and status is sought. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اتۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ نَبَاَ ابۡنَیۡ اٰدَمَ بِالۡحَقِّ ۘ اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا» (5/27) Translation: 'And recite to them the story of Adam's two sons, in truth, when they both offered a sacrifice.' In another place, the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (56/10,11) Translation: 'And the forerunners, the forerunners - Those are the ones brought near [to Allah].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1684,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank - To attain rank",
      "hw": "Rank",
      "s": "«مَکَنَ» When authority is also attained along with rank.",
      "d": "«مَکَنَ» Meaning to be of high rank. And «مَکَان» meaning place. Dwelling place. A place that holds a body. And «مَکَّنَ» means to grant someone authority. To bestow government. And «مَکِیۡن» means one who dwells in a place. And also a person of status. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنَّہٗ لَقَوۡلُ رَسُوۡلٍ کَرِیۡمٍ ذِیۡ قُوَّۃٍ عِنۡدَ ذِی الۡعَرۡشِ مَکِیۡنٍ» (81/19,20) Translation: 'Indeed, it is the word of a noble Messenger. Possessor of power, with the Owner of the Throne, secure in position.'"
    }
  ],
  "361": [
    {
      "id": 1686,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To turn towards",
      "hw": "Turn",
      "s": "«تَوَجَّہَ» Meaning to turn towards.",
      "d": "«وَجۡہ» Meaning face. Mouth. And «وَجَّہَ» means to send someone towards something. And «تَوَجَّہَ اِلَیۡہِ» To turn towards. To face. To turn one's face towards something (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22) Translation: 'And when he turned himself toward Madyan.'"
    }
  ],
  "362": [
    {
      "id": 1687,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«نَکِدَ» A thing that is obtained with great difficulty, is less in quantity, and has little good in it.",
      "d": "«نَکِدَ» Meaning «قَلِیۡلُ الۡخَیۡر» in which the aspect of goodness and excellence is less (M-Q). And according to Imam Raghib, every thing that is obtained by its seeker with great difficulty. And «نَاقَۃَ نَکِدَاء» is that she-camel that gives less milk and can be milked only with difficulty (Mufrad). And «نَکِدَ» means to prevent someone from their need. To deprive or give little. And «نَکِدَ الرَّجُل» means for a person to ask many questions and have little goodness (Munjid). So «نَکِدَ» is that thing which is obtained with difficulty, is less in quantity, and has little good in it, that is, little and worthless. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡ خَبُثَ لَا یَخۡرُجُ اِلَّا نَکِدًا» (7/58) Translation: 'And that which is bad - nothing grows from it except scanty [yield].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1688,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«خَمۡط» Bitter, sour and bad-tasting thing.",
      "d": "«خَمۡط» Meaning every sour or bitter thing. The little fruit of every tree. Every thorny tree (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» (34/16) Translation: '[In place of good gardens] food of bitter taste and tamarisk and something of sparse lote-trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1690,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«نَاقِصۡ» Defective thing. Incomplete.",
      "d": "«نَاقِصۡ» Meaning incomplete. «دِرۡھَمٌ نَاقِصٌ» means coins of less weight (Munjid) or defective coins (M-Q). «نَقۡص» also means deficiency, defect and loss. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ بِالسِّنِیۡنَ وَ نَقۡصٍ مِّنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ» (7/130) Translation: 'And We certainly seized the people of Pharaoh with years [of famine] and a deficiency in fruits.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1691,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«بَخۡس» Inferior and worthless thing.",
      "d": "«بَخۡس» Meaning deficient. Inferior. Lesser (Munjid) and meaning a humble and deficient thing (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12/20) Translation: 'And they sold him for a reduced price - a few dirhams.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1692,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«خَبِیۡث» Dirty and impure or forbidden thing.",
      "d": "«خَبُثَ» Meaning to be filthy and impure. To be worthless. To be useless. And «خَبِیۡث» Meaning impure. Worthless. Disliked. Every bad and dirty thing. Its opposite is «طَیِّب» (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَا تَتَبَدَّلُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ بِالطَّیِّبِ» (4/2) Translation: 'And do not substitute the defective [of your own] for the good [of theirs].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1693,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless - Useless",
      "hw": "Useless",
      "s": "«اَدۡنٰی» That which is inferior in comparison to something good.",
      "d": "«اَدۡنٰی» Its opposite is «اَعۡلٰی». That thing which is deficient or worthless in comparison to something good. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالَ اَتَسۡتَبۡدِلُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ اَدۡنٰی بِالَّذِیۡ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ» (2/61) Translation: 'Moses said: Would you exchange what is better for what is less good?'"
    }
  ],
  "363": [
    {
      "id": 1695,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rope",
      "hw": "Rope",
      "s": "«حَبۡل» Used for every type of rope.",
      "d": "«حَبۡل» Its plural is «حَبَال». Meaning rope and anything like it. «حَبۡلُ الۡوَرِیۡد» means jugular vein. And «حَبَالَۃُ الصَّیَّاد» means the hunter's snare. This word has generality in its usage. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فِیۡ جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ» (111/5) Translation: 'Around her neck is a rope of [twisted] fiber.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1696,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rope",
      "hw": "Rope",
      "s": "«سَبَب» Only used for that rope which can be used as a means of travel or climbing.",
      "d": "«سَبَب» The rope by which one climbs a date palm tree (Mufrad) and «سَبَب» means path. Travel. Travel provisions and the rope for tying travel provisions etc. (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «مَنۡ کَانَ یَظُنُّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡصُرَہُ اللّٰہُ فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ فَلۡیَمۡدُدۡ بِسَبَبٍ اِلَی السَّمَآءِ ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡطَعۡ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ ہَلۡ یُذۡہِبَنَّ کَیۡدُہٗ مَا یَغِیۡظُ» (22/15) Translation: 'Whoever should think that Allah will not support him [Prophet Muhammad] in this world and the Hereafter - let him extend a rope to the ceiling, then cut off [his breath], and let him see: will his plan remove that which enrages [him]?'"
    }
  ],
  "364": [
    {
      "id": 1697,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relatives",
      "hw": "Relatives",
      "s": "«اَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» Close relatives whose share in inheritance is fixed.",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» Meaning to be near or close. And this word is comprehensive in every respect - time, distance, rank, kinship. In short, it is comprehensive in every aspect. «اَقۡرَبَ» Meaning more near. More close. And «اَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» or «اَقۡرِبِیۡنَ» or «ذَا قُرۡبٰی» or «ذَوِی الۡقُرۡبٰی» these words become specific for close relatives. Relatives can be distant or close. Close relatives are those whose share Allah Almighty has fixed in inheritance. That is, sons, daughters, mother, father, husband, wife, and sister, brother. For example, in the Holy Quran: «لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/7) Translation: 'For men is a share of what the parents and close relatives leave.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1698,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relatives",
      "hw": "Relatives",
      "s": "«نَسَبَ» Relatives from the father's side.",
      "d": "«نَسَبَ یَنۡسُبُ» Meaning to state lineage and to inquire about lineage. And «اِسۡتَنۡسَبَ» means to state lineage. To ask about lineage. And «نَسَب» and «اَنۡسَاب» mean kinship. Relationship (Munjid). And by lineage is meant those relatives who are from the father's side because lineage runs from the father, and in this, besides «اَقۡرَبُوۡن», uncles and aunts and their offspring are also included. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاِذَا نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَلَاۤ اَنۡسَابَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ» (23/101) Translation: 'So when the Horn is blown, no relationship will there be among them that Day.' And Imam Raghib has written the meaning of lineage as relatives from either of the two parents (Mufrad), that is, he has also included the relatives from the mother's side (that is, maternal and paternal grandparents)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1699,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relatives",
      "hw": "Relatives",
      "s": "«صِہۡر» Meaning in-laws.",
      "d": "«صِہۡر» Meaning in-laws, that is, those relatives who come into existence as a result of marriage. For the wife, the blood relatives of the husband are in-laws, and for the husband, the blood relatives of the wife are in-laws. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ مِنَ الۡمَآءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَہٗ نَسَبًا وَّ صِہۡرًا» (25/54) Translation: 'And it is He who has created from water a human being and made him [a relative by] lineage and marriage.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1700,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relatives",
      "hw": "Relatives",
      "s": "«اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَام» Relatives connected through the womb, and their circle is very wide.",
      "d": "«اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَام» Relatives connected through the womb. Their circle is very wide, in which aunts are also included (but according to the science of inheritance, their rank comes after Dhawi al-Furud and Asabah). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَامِ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِبَعۡضٍ فِیۡ کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ» (8/75) Translation: 'But those of [blood] relationship are more entitled [to inheritance] in the decree of Allah.' Note: Science of Inheritance: Refers to the knowledge through which it is determined who will be an heir and who will not, and how much share of the estate each heir will receive. Dhawi al-Furud: These are legal heirs whose share is predetermined, that is, no change is possible in it. Asabah: Heir whose share in the estate is not fixed. And if he is alone, he takes all the property. If he is with a fixed-share heir, he takes the remaining property."
    },
    {
      "id": 1701,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relatives",
      "hw": "Relatives",
      "s": "«اِلّ» Covenant made with relatives.",
      "d": "The translation of «اِلّ» is generally kinship or relationship, but from a linguistic perspective, its meaning is the covenant made with relatives. «اِلّ» means covenant. Promise. Neighbor (Munjid) and «اِلَّ الرَّجُل» means «جَارَ بِہٖ» that is, his name was made neighbor (M-Q). For example, in the Holy Quran: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10) Translation: 'They do not observe toward a believer any pact of kinship or covenant of protection.' The correct concept of «ذِمَّۃ» is not merely covenant but covenant of trust and protection. And the meaning of «اِلّ» is any kind of covenant made with one's neighbors and relatives."
    }
  ],
  "365": [
    {
      "id": 1702,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Satisfaction - Pleasure",
      "hw": "Pleasure",
      "s": "«رِضۡوَان and مَرۡضَاۃ» Come in the mere sense of satisfaction, while in «وَجۡہ» the aspect of attention is also included along with satisfaction.",
      "d": "«رَضِیَ» is a well-known word meaning to be happy. From this, «رِضۡوَان», «رَضۡوَان» and «مَرۡضَاۃ» also come as infinitives. And give the meaning of satisfaction, pleasure or approval (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran: «یَبۡتَغُوۡنَ فَضۡلًا مِّنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ وَ رِضۡوَانًا» (5/2) Translation: 'Seeking bounty from their Lord and [His] pleasure.' In another place, the saying of Allah Almighty: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ لِمَ تُحَرِّمُ مَاۤ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ لَکَ ۚ تَبۡتَغِیۡ مَرۡضَاتَ اَزۡوَاجِکَ» (66/1) Translation: 'O Prophet, why do you prohibit [yourself from] what Allah has made lawful for you, seeking the approval of your wives?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1703,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Satisfaction - Pleasure",
      "hw": "Pleasure",
      "s": "«وَجۡہ» Meaning face.",
      "d": "«وَجۡہ» Meaning face. Direction. Mouth. Satisfaction. And that part of everything that comes first. «وَجۡہُ النَّھَار» means the first part of the day (Mufrad-Munjd). And when a person is upset with someone, he turns his face away from him, and when he is happy, he pays more attention to him. This is the concept of «وَجۡہ» meaning satisfaction, that is, to seek someone's pleasure by avoiding acts of displeasure and doing good deeds. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مَا تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ وَجۡہِ اللّٰہِ» (2/272) Translation: 'And you do not spend except seeking the countenance of Allah.'"
    }
  ],
  "366": [
    {
      "id": 1704,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To desire",
      "hw": "Desire",
      "s": "«رَغِبَ» Meaning to desire or have desire. To have a heartfelt wish for obtaining something and to strive for it.",
      "d": "«رَغِبَ» Meaning to desire or have desire. To have a heartfelt wish for obtaining something and to strive for it (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94/7,8) Translation: 'So when you have finished [your duties], then stand up [for worship]. And to your Lord direct [your] longing.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1705,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To desire",
      "hw": "Desire",
      "s": "«تَنَافُس» Competition in desire for good deeds.",
      "d": "«نَفِسَ» Meaning to envy. And «نَفَّسَ فِی الْاَمۡر» means to encourage in a matter. And «تَنَافُس» means to boast among each other, to have desire for competition in good deeds. To desire competitively (Munjid). To have desire to surpass one another with a competitive spirit. For example, in the Holy Quran: «یُسۡقَوۡنَ مِنۡ رَّحِیۡقٍ مَّخۡتُوۡمٍ خِتٰمُہٗ مِسۡکٌ ؕ وَ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَتَنَافَسِ الۡمُتَنَافِسُوۡنَ» (83/25,26) Translation: 'They will be given to drink [pure] wine, [sealed] with musk. And for that let the competitors compete.'"
    }
  ],
  "367": [
    {
      "id": 1706,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To place - To put",
      "hw": "To place",
      "s": "«وَضَعَ» General - whether the placed thing is visible to someone or not.",
      "d": "«وَضَعَ» Its opposite is «رَفَعَ». Meaning to lift something. To raise. And «وَضَعَ» means to gently place something down. And «رَفِیۡع»'s opposite is «وَضِیۡع» meaning a person who has no honor or status in society. And «وَضَعَ حَمَل» means to place a burden down, whether it is apparent or hidden (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94/2,3) Translation: 'And We removed from you your burden which had weighed upon your back.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1707,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To place - To put",
      "hw": "To place",
      "s": "«اَلۡقٰی» To place down such a thing that others cannot see it.",
      "d": "The original meaning of «اَلۡقٰی» is to throw. And the difference between placing and throwing is that in placing, slowness and caution are observed. And if haste and carelessness are taken, it is called 'to throw'. And placing is the middle quality between these two. Then whenever in «اَلۡقٰی» the aspect of slowness and caution is also present, «اَلۡقٰی» will also give the meaning of placing. And another peculiarity in «اَلۡقٰی» is that «اَلۡقٰی» is the placing or throwing of such a thing that others can see it, while in «وَضَعَ» this is not necessary. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اَلۡقٰی فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ» (16/15) Translation: 'And He cast into the earth firmly set mountains.' (Usmani) And He cast into the earth firmly set mountains (Jalandhri)"
    }
  ],
  "368": [
    {
      "id": 1708,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Color",
      "hw": "Color",
      "s": "«لَوۡن» Natural color is called.",
      "d": "«لَوۡن» Natural color such as black, white, green, red, yellow, blue etc. Its plural is «اَلۡوَان». For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا» (35/37) Translation: 'And among the mountains are tracts white and red of various shades and [some] black as pitch.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1709,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Color",
      "hw": "Color",
      "s": "«صِبۡغَۃ» That color which is applied oneself, whether material or spiritual.",
      "d": "«صَبَغَ» Meaning to dye. To apply color. And «صَبَّاغ» means dyer (Munjd). And the word «صَبَغَہ» is used in both material and spiritual senses. In spiritual sense, its meaning is the effect and color produced by something else on a human being. And «صَبَّغَ بِالْمَاءِ» to dye with water. And «تَصَبَّغْ فِیۡ دِیۡنِہٖ» for the color of religion to be well applied on someone. To be firm in religion (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «صِبۡغَۃَ اللّٰہِ ۚ وَ مَنۡ اَحۡسَنُ مِنَ اللّٰہِ صِبۡغَۃً» (2/138) '[We take on] the dye of Allah. And who is better than Allah in dyeing?' Note: (Baptism: It is a Christian religious ritual. Through this ritual, a non-Christian is made to enter the Christian religion by bathing or sprinkling colored water)"
    }
  ],
  "369": [],
  "370": [
    {
      "id": 1717,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Faster",
      "hw": "Faster",
      "s": "«صَآئِم» One who fasts is called.",
      "d": "«صَوْم» Its plural is «صِیَام». Meaning fasting and «صَامَ» means to fast. That is, to abstain from eating, drinking and certain other acts according to Islamic commands from Suhoor to Iftar. And «صَآئِم» means one who fasts. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ الصَّآئِمِیۡنَ وَ الصّٰٓئِمٰتِ» (33/35) Translation: 'And the men who fast and the women who fast.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1718,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Faster",
      "hw": "Faster",
      "s": "«سَآئِح» That faster who also observes other regulatory restrictions besides eating and drinking.",
      "d": "«سَیۡح، اَلسَّاحَۃ» Meaning open space and the courtyard of a house. And «سَاحَ» means to travel. To wander in open land. To travel far and wide. And «سَاحَ» means to fast and also to observe all its regulatory restrictions, that is, besides the restriction of eating and drinking, to also abstain from sins of the limbs, that is, eyes, ears, tongue etc. (Mufrad). And according to the author of Munjd, «سَآئِح» is called a faster who stays in the mosque (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَلتَّآئِبُوۡنَ الۡعٰبِدُوۡنَ الۡحٰمِدُوۡنَ السَّآئِحُوۡنَ» (9/112) Translation: '[They are] those who repent, those who worship, those who praise, those who fast.'"
    }
  ],
  "371": [
    {
      "id": 1719,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«مَنَعَ» To stop with hand or tongue.",
      "d": "«مَنَعَ» is basically used in two meanings: (1) Not to give (opposite of to give). To be stingy. And «مَنَّاع» means stingy person (Mufrad). (2) To stop someone with hand or tongue. To not let someone do something. To deprive. To stop (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ مَّنَعَ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰہِ اَنۡ یُّذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (2/114) Translation: 'And who are more unjust than those who prevent the name of Allah from being mentioned in His mosques?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1720,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«نَہٰی» To stop from evils.",
      "d": "«اَلنَّہۡی» is generally used for stopping and abstaining from evils, that is, bad deeds. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی» (79/40) Translation: 'But as for he who feared the position of his Lord and prevented the soul from [unlawful] inclination.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1721,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«عَوَّقَ» To stop from goodness or good deeds.",
      "d": "«اَلۡعَوۡقُ وَالۡعُوۡقُ» Meaning a useless person. One who stops people from good deeds (Munjd). And «عَوَّقَ» comes in the meaning of (one who stops from good deeds). For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ اللّٰہُ الۡمُعَوِّقِیۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الۡقَآئِلِیۡنَ لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا» (33/18) Translation: 'Already Allah knows those who hinder you among [your own] people and those who say to their brothers, 'Come, [fight] with us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1722,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«عَضَلَ» To keep someone stopped from something to gain some benefit.",
      "d": "«عَضَلَ» Meaning to cause hardship. To prevent (Munjd). To stop with severity (Mufrad). «عَضُلَہ» means muscle. And «عَضَّلَ» means to cause hardship. To become an obstacle in achieving the goal (Munjd). This word is generally used for a man stopping a woman from marriage, causing her distress and trouble, so that some benefit can be gained from this act. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ» (4/19) Translation: 'And do not constrain them in order to take [back] part of what you gave them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1723,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«اَمۡسَکَ» To not let an existing thing slip from hand.",
      "d": "«اَمۡسَکَ» To cling to something and to protect it (Mufrad). This word is generally used when something is already with oneself and it is not allowed to slip from hand. And «مُمۡسِک» also comes in the meaning of a stingy person. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاَمۡسِکُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ اَوۡ سَرِّحُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ» (2/231) Translation: 'Then either keep them in an acceptable manner or release them in an acceptable manner.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1724,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«صَدَّ» To slowly stop someone from their intention with soft behavior.",
      "d": "«صَدَّ» Meaning to stop. To turn away. To restrain. And «صَدَّ عَنْ» means to turn away. To incline (Munjd). To stop with soft behavior (Fl 188). Turning away and deviating. According to Ibn Faris's words «المیل اِلٰی اَحَدِ الْجَانِبَیْن وَ عَدَلَ عَنْہُ» (M-L) and «صَدّ» means «مَنَعَ عَنْ قَصْدِ الشَّیْءُ خَاصَۃً» (Fiq L 92), that is, to stop someone from their intention. So the word «صَدّ» is used for stopping someone from their goal with soft policy. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ تَذُوۡقُوا السُّوۡٓءَ بِمَا صَدَدۡتُّمۡ عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (16/94) Translation: 'And taste evil for what you prevented from the way of Allah.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1725,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«اَحۡصَرَ» To stop by surrounding and to cause hardship.",
      "d": "«اَحۡصَرَ» Meaning to surround. To encircle. To besiege. To constrict someone's place. And «حِصَار» means fortress. And «حَاصَرَ» means to stop reinforcement (i.e., military aid) by surrounding (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ الَّذِیۡنَ اُحۡصِرُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ ضَرۡبًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (2/273) Translation: '[Charity is] for the poor who have been restricted for the cause of Allah, unable to move about in the land.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1726,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«حَظَرَ» To stop by putting a fence.",
      "d": "«حَظَرَ» Meaning to put a fence around something for the purpose of protecting it or to gather something in an enclosure and put a fence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مَا کَانَ عَطَـآءُ رَبِّکَ مَحۡظُوۡرًا» (17/20) Translation: 'And the gift of your Lord is not restricted.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1727,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«عَکَفَ» To stop by one's own will out of reverence.",
      "d": "«عَکَفَ» Meaning to turn towards something out of reverence and to remain attached to it (Mufrad). To remain confined. To keep stopped. To be imprisoned (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «عَنِ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ وَ الۡہَدۡیَ مَعۡکُوۡفًا اَنۡ یَّبۡلُغَ مَحِلَّہٗ» (48/25) Translation: 'They are the ones who disbelieved and obstructed you from al-Masjid al-Haram while the offering was prevented from reaching its place of sacrifice.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1728,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«کَفَّ» To stop or repel an attack.",
      "d": "«کَفّ» Meaning palm and «کَفَّ» means to stop a strike on the palm. To repel. To protect. To stop (Mufrad). Then this word began to be used merely for stopping or protecting from a strike. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِذۡ ہَمَّ قَوۡمٌ اَنۡ یَّبۡسُطُوۡۤا اِلَیۡکُمۡ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ فَکَفَّ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ عَنۡکُمۡ» (5/11) Translation: 'When a people intended to extend their hands [in aggression] against you, but He withheld their hands from you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1729,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«ثَبَّطَ» To stop and restrain due to laziness and delay.",
      "d": "«ثَبَّطَ» Meaning to delay in a matter. And not to do that matter, to remain stopped from it. And meaning to delay and be lazy. «اَثۡبَطَہُ الۡمَرَض» for illness to cling to someone and not leave him (Munjd). And «ثَبَّطَہُ الۡمَرَض» means illness stopped him (Munjd). To not be able to do something due to delay or laziness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَوۡ اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا لَہٗ عُدَّۃً وَّ لٰکِنۡ کَرِہَ اللّٰہُ انۡۢبِعَاثَہُمۡ فَثَبَّطَہُمۡ» (9/46) Translation: 'But if they had intended to go forth, they would have prepared for it [some] preparation. But Allah disliked their being sent, so He kept them back.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1730,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«ذَادَ» To push away and not let come near. To keep stopped.",
      "d": "«ذَادَ» Meaning to push away. To repel. To not let come near. To keep stopped (Mufrad Munjd). And «ذَوَّدَ عَنْ حَسۡبِہٖ» means for a person to protect and defend his own self (Munjd). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ وَجَدَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہِمُ امۡرَاَتَیۡنِ تَذُوۡدٰنِ» (28/23) Translation: 'And he found besides them two women driving back [their flocks].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1731,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«وَزَعَ» To stop for the sake of order and arrangement.",
      "d": "«وَزَعَ» Meaning to stop. To prevent. And «وَزَعَ الۡجَیۡش» means to arrange the army in ordered sections. And «اَلۡاَوۡزَع» means groups. It has no singular. And «اَلۡوَزۡعَۃُ» its plural «وَازِعُ» means the king's helpers and protectors (Munjd). So the word «وَزَعَ» comes in the meaning of stopping for order and arrangement. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ حُشِرَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ مِنَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ وَ الطَّیۡرِ فَہُمۡ یُوۡزَعُوۡنَ» (27/17) Translation: 'And gathered for Solomon were his soldiers of the jinn and men and birds, and they were [marching] in rows.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1732,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«حَبَسَ» To stop from standing, to stop from going.",
      "d": "«حَبَسَ» Meaning to imprison. To protect fully. To prevent (Munjd). And meaning to stop someone from getting up (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (5/106) Translation: 'Detain them after the prayer.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1733,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop - To prevent",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«حِجۡرًا مَّہۡجُوۡرًا» Used idiomatically. To plead to remain stopped from loss and damage.",
      "d": "«حَجَرَ» Meaning hard stone and «حِجۡرًا مَّہۡجُوۡرًا» is an idiom. And by this is meant such a strong obstacle that cannot be removed. In the days of ignorance, it was customary that when such a person appeared from whom harm was feared, the words «حِجۡرًا مَّہۡجُوۡرًا» (that is, we seek protection from you) were said. Hearing these words, the enemy would not say anything to him. The Quran has also used this idiomatically: For example, in the Holy Quran: «یَوۡمَ یَرَوۡنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ لَا بُشۡرٰی یَوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ حِجۡرًا مَّحۡجُوۡرًا» (25/22) Translation: 'The Day they see the angels - no good tidings will there be that Day for the criminals, and they will say, 'A barrier prohibited.'' (Jalandhri)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1734,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«اِنۡتَہٰی» To stop from evils and prohibitions.",
      "d": "«اِنۡتَہٰی» To stop. To refrain. To adopt compliance with prohibitions and to abandon them. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ یَصُدَّکُمۡ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ وَ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ ۚ فَہَلۡ اَنۡتُمۡ مُّنۡتَہُوۡنَ» (5/91) Translation: 'And Satan wants to avert you from the remembrance of Allah and from prayer. So will you not desist?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1735,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«اَکۡدٰی» The heart to stop and become hard from spending wealth.",
      "d": "«اَلۡکُدۡیَۃ» Meaning hard and solid ground. Hard rock. And «حَفَرَ فَاکۡدٰی» means he dug until he reached hard ground (Mufrad). And «کَدّٰی» means to ask. To beg for charity. And «سَاَلَہٗ فَاَکۡدٰی» means he asked him but found him like hard ground and he gave nothing (Munjd). So this word has come in the meaning of stopping after spending a little. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا وَّ اَکۡدٰی» (53/34) Translation: 'And he gave a little and [then] refrained.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1737,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To stop",
      "hw": "To stop",
      "s": "«قَلَعَ» To suddenly stop from a started task.",
      "d": "«قَلَعَ» Meaning to abandon a task. To leave and to stop (Munjd). To suddenly abandon an ongoing task. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» (11/44) Translation: 'And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, withhold [your rain].' And the water subsided.'"
    }
  ],
  "372": [
    {
      "id": 1738,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To trample",
      "hw": "To trample",
      "s": "«حَطَمَ» To crush by trampling or to break and shatter.",
      "d": "«حَطَمَ» Meaning to break and twist. And «حَطُوۡم» is that fierce and strong wind that breaks and twists everything. And «حُطَام» is called a broken, twisted or shredded thing (Munjd). This word is used for making something into pieces by trampling (Mufrad). To crush. To grind. To trample. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالَتۡ نَمۡلَۃٌ یّٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّمۡلُ ادۡخُلُوۡا مَسٰکِنَکُمۡ ۚ لَا یَحۡطِمَنَّکُمۡ سُلَیۡمٰنُ وَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ ۙ وَ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (27/18) Translation: 'An ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings that you not be crushed by Solomon and his soldiers while they perceive not.'' "
    }
  ],
  "373": [
    {
      "id": 1740,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Splendor",
      "hw": "Splendor",
      "s": "The word «زَہۡرَۃ» is used for the apparent shine and splendor of the vegetation of the world.",
      "d": "«زَہۡرَۃ» Beauty, shine. Tip top. And «زَہۡرَۃُ الدُّنۡیَا» means the apparent shine and splendor of the world (Munjd). This word is generally used for the allurements and colorfulness of this unstable world. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ اِلٰی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ زَہۡرَۃَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا» (20/131) Translation: 'And do not extend your eyes toward that by which We have given enjoyment to [some] categories of them, [its being but] the splendor of worldly life.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1742,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Splendor",
      "hw": "Splendor",
      "s": "«بَہۡجَۃ» Used for the splendor of vegetation.",
      "d": "«بَہۡجَۃ» Every thing that pleases the heart and its basic meaning is joy. And according to Khalil, its connection is with the good color and freshness of something (Fiq L 216). Also used for humans, but more used for the freshness, greenery, lushness of vegetation. For plants being in full bloom. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اَنۡزَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً ۚ فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27/60) Translation: 'And He sent down for you from the sky, rain. Then We caused to grow thereby gardens of delight.'"
    }
  ],
  "374": [
    {
      "id": 1743,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Sand",
      "hw": "Sand",
      "s": "«سَرَاب» That sand which appears like water in the desert at noon due to the intensity of sunlight.",
      "d": "«سَرَاب» That sand which appears like water in the desert at noon due to the intensity of sunlight. Every drinkable thing is called «شَرَاب». And that thing which apparently appears like drink but in reality is not a drinkable thing is called «سَرَاب» (Mufrad). Then metaphorically, its usage is for every unreal thing. And generally, this word is used for that vast field of sand which, when viewed from a distance at an angle in sunlight, appears like waving water. For example, in the Holy Quran: «کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39) Translation: 'But they [who disbelieve] are like a mirage in a lowland which a thirsty one thinks is water.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1744,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Sand",
      "hw": "Sand",
      "s": "«کَثِیۡب» A heap of loose and sliding sand.",
      "d": "«کَثِیۡب» A long and wide heap of sand (Fl 272). For example, in the Holy Quran: «یَوۡمَ تَرۡجُفُ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ الۡجِبَالُ وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73/14) Translation: 'On the Day the earth and the mountains will convulse and the mountains will become a heap of sand pouring down.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1745,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Sand",
      "hw": "Sand",
      "s": "«اَحۡقَاف» A vast field consisting of several heaps of sand.",
      "d": "«اَحۡقَاف» is plural of «حَقَفَ» meaning a field of several heaps of sand. And «اَحۡقَاف» means a vast field of sand spread over hundreds of miles (Munjd). And meaning the region of western Yemen which was the center of the people of Aad (M-Q). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اذۡکُرۡ اَخَا عَادٍ ؕ اِذۡ اَنۡذَرَ قَوۡمَہٗ بِالۡاَحۡقَافِ» (46/21) Translation: 'And mention the brother of Aad, when he warned his people in [the region of] Al-Ahqaf.'"
    }
  ],
  "375": [
    {
      "id": 1748,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Extra - More",
      "hw": "Extra",
      "s": "«ضِعۡف» Meaning as much as the thing is, that much and more. Also see 'To increase - To cause to increase'",
      "d": "«ضِعۡف» Meaning as much as the thing is, that much and more, double. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِذًا لَّاَذَقۡنٰکَ ضِعۡفَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ وَ ضِعۡفَ الۡمَمَاتِ ثُمَّ لَا تَجِدُ لَکَ عَلَیۡنَا نَصِیۡرًا» (17/75) Translation: 'Then We would have made you taste double [punishment in] life and double [after] death. Then you would not find for yourself against Us a helper.' And the dual of «ضِعۡف» is «ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» which comes for further emphasis. For example, in the Holy Quran: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265) Translation: 'Its example is like a garden on high ground which is hit by a downpour - so it yields its fruits in double.' And «ضَاعَفَ» means to make something very much more. For example, the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ اللّٰہُ یُضٰعِفُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (2/261) Translation: 'And Allah multiplies for whom He wills.'"
    }
  ],
  "376": [
    {
      "id": 1750,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To force",
      "hw": "Force",
      "s": "«جَبَرَ» To reform something by force and pressure.",
      "d": "«جَبَرَ» In its meaning, there are also two fundamental things: (1) Force (2) Reform. That is, to reform something by force and pressure (Mufrad). «جَبَرَ الۡعَظۡم» means to correct a broken bone. And «جَبَرَ عَلَی الۡاَمۡرِ» means to force someone to do something. Allah Almighty, describing His attributes, says: For example, in the Holy Quran: «الۡعَزِیۡزُ الۡجَبَّارُ الۡمُتَکَبِّرُ» (59/23) Translation: 'The Exalted in Might, the Compeller, the Superior.' Then sometimes this word is used merely in the sense of forcing. For example, the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ اِذَا بَطَشۡتُمۡ بَطَشۡتُمۡ جَبَّارِیۡنَ» (26/130) Translation: 'And when you strike, you strike as tyrants.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1752,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To force",
      "hw": "Force",
      "s": "«سَخَّرَ» To forcibly drive something towards a purpose.",
      "d": "«سَخَرَ» Meaning to mock and make fun. And in «سَخَّرَ» there are two fundamental things: (1) Force (2) Fulfilling purpose. That is, to forcibly drive something towards a purpose. To forcibly put to work. To be bound by command. In this, there is no involvement of someone's will or approval. This word is generally used for the submissive affairs of the universe. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ ۚ وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ» (14/33) Translation: 'And He subjected for you the sun and the moon, continuous [in orbit], and subjected for you the night and the day.' In another place, the saying of Allah Almighty: «وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43/32) Translation: 'And We have raised some of them above others in degrees [of rank] that they may make use of one another for service.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1753,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To force",
      "hw": "Force",
      "s": "«رَہِقَ» Force, and in it the concept of covering or hiding is found.",
      "d": "«رَہِقَ» Meaning for one thing to climb over another thing and cover it (Mufrad). And «رَہِقَہُ الۡاَمۡر» means a matter overwhelmed him by force of compulsion (Munjd). So in «رَہِقَ» two things are found: (1) Force (2) To cover or hide by climbing over. For example, in the Holy Quran: «خَاشِعَۃً اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (68/43) Translation: 'Their eyes humbled, disgrace covering them.'"
    }
  ],
  "377": [
    {
      "id": 1754,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Wound",
      "hw": "Wound",
      "s": "«قُرۡحٌ» A wound whose effect is limited to the skin.",
      "d": "«قُرۡحٌ» Meaning boil, pimple. Itch. Wound. Its plural is «قُرُوۡح». This can also be from internal effect or from external. Meaning boils, pimples and wounds produced from them (Munjd). Then «قُرۡحٌ» is also applied to the pain and distress produced from these wounds (Mufrad). «قُرُوۡح» are actually those wounds whose effect is limited to the skin, whether the skin peels off or there are scratches or boils. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنۡ یَّمۡسَسۡکُمۡ قَرۡحٌ فَقَدۡ مَسَّ الۡقَوۡمَ قَرۡحٌ مِّثۡلُہٗ» (3/140) Translation: 'If a wound should touch you - there has already touched the [opposing] people a wound similar to it.'"
    }
  ],
  "378": [
    {
      "id": 1756,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its divisions",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«دَہۡر» Time from the creation of the universe to the end.",
      "d": "«دَہۡر» Time of the universe, duration of the world. The time from when the universe began until its end (Mufrad). And Ibn Faris says that in «دَہَرَ» the concept of dominance and «قَہَر» is found. And «دَہۡر» means time. This name is because it passes over everything and dominates it (M-L). And «دَہۡر» is related to the Divine Will. The Prophetic saying ﷺ is «لَا تَسُبُّوا الدَّھْرَ فَاِنَّ اللہَ ھُوَ الدَّھْر» meaning do not curse time (Dahr) because Allah Almighty is Dahr. A person who neither believes in God nor in His attributes is called an atheist or Dahriyah. Their belief is that time is eternal and immortal and there is no life after this life. The famous jurisprudence of Dahriyah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «ہَلۡ اَتٰی عَلَی الۡاِنۡسَانِ حِیۡنٌ مِّنَ الدَّہۡرِ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ شَیۡئًا مَّذۡکُوۡرًا» (76/1) Translation: 'Has there [not] come upon man a period of time when he was not a thing [even] mentioned?' That is, during the period of Dahr, there was also a time when man was not even a thing worth mentioning."
    },
    {
      "id": 1757,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its divisions",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«عَصۡر» Time from the creation of man until Qiyamah.",
      "d": "In «عَصۡر» two meanings are found: (1) The last part of the day. (2) Night and day. Era. Time (Munjd M-A). That is, from when night and day came into existence and as long as they remain. But in our opinion, this meaning or definition is questionable (worth considering). And the meaning of «عَصۡر» should be this: 'The period from the birth of mankind until Qiyamah.' The reason for this is that Allah presents «عَصۡر» as a witness for mankind. And when man did not exist, what witness? And Allah knows best! For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ الۡعَصۡرِ اِنَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ لَفِیۡ خُسۡرٍ» (103/1) Translation: 'By time, Indeed, mankind is in loss.' And obviously, night and day had come into existence long before the creation of Adam. According to the above explanation of «دَہۡر» and «عَصۡر», there should not be a plural of these words, but in lexicon books, the plural of «دَہۡر» is «دُھُوۡر» and the plural of «عَصۡر» is «عُصُوۡر». This is because in common usage, by «دَہۡر» and «عَصۡر» is meant merely a long time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1758,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its divisions",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«قَرۡن» Meaning a period of one hundred years. People of one era. One nation after another. People of one generation and its period.",
      "d": "«قَرۡن» Meaning a period of one hundred years. People of one era. One nation after another. People of one generation and its period (Munjd). So «قَرۡن» is applied to one or two eras and also to the people of its time, just as the word «قَرۡیَۃ» is used for a settlement and the people of the settlement. Its plural is «قُرُوۡن». In the Quran, this word is generally used for the people of a period. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالَ فَمَا بَالُ الۡقُرُوۡنِ الۡاُوۡلٰی» (20/51) Translation: '[Pharaoh] said: Then what is the condition of the former generations?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1759,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its divisions",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«حُقۡبَۃ» Long period. A period of 80 years or more.",
      "d": "«حُقۡبَۃ» A period of 80 years or more. Long period. Indefinite period (Mufrad). And its plural is also «حُقُب» and «اَحۡقَاب». Meaning ages. And according to the author of Furuq al-Lughawiyyah, this word is derived from «حَقِیۡبَۃ». And «حَقِیۡبَۃ» is called that leather bag in which a rider keeps his luggage and places it with his mount. So «حَقَب» is not a part of time but a type of container. That is, the time in which deeds and matters are accomplished (Fiq L 224). For example, in the Holy Quran: «حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60) Translation: 'Until I reach the junction of the two seas or continue for a long period.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1760,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its divisions",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡن» By this is meant the events of time, which is generally used in a bad sense.",
      "d": "«رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡن» By this is meant the events of time, which is generally used in a bad sense. Besides this, an idiom «رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡن» meaning the turn of time is also used in the Quran. And by this is meant the events of time, which is generally used in a bad sense, that is, the expectation of bad days befalling someone from earthly or heavenly calamities (also see Turn of Days). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَمۡ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ شَاعِرٌ نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ» (52/30) Translation: 'Or do they say [about the Prophet], 'A poet for whom we await a misfortune of time'?'"
    }
  ],
  "379": [
    {
      "id": 1761,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«بَرّ» Meaning that part of the earth which is dry.",
      "d": "«بَرّ» Meaning that part of the earth which is dry and on which humans or other land animals are settled or can be settled. And this part is one-fourth of the total surface of the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1762,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«بَحۡر» That part of the earth which is underwater, that is, on which seas are located.",
      "d": "«بَحۡر» That part of the earth which is underwater, that is, on which seas are located. And this part is three times more than the dry part in terms of area. In this part, only aquatic animals can survive. And by Sea is also meant those rivers and canals that flow on land. For example, in the Holy Quran: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10/22) Translation: 'It is He who enables you to travel on land and sea.' And the various types of dry land mentioned in the Quran are: «جُرُز، سھُوۡل، سَاھِرَۃ، صَعِیۡد، قِیۡعَۃ (قوع) صَفۡصَف، عَرَآء (عری) زَلَق، صَفۡوَان، (صفو) فَجۡوَۃ (فج) صَلۡدًا، سَاحَۃ (سیح) رَبۡوَۃ (ربو)، نَجۡد، رِیۡع، وَادِی، مَوَاطِن اور جُدَد» these words have come."
    },
    {
      "id": 1763,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«جُرُز» Meaning dry and barren land.",
      "d": "«جَرَزَ» Meaning to cut. And «سَیۡفٌ جِرَازٌ» means a cutting sword (M-L). And «اَرۡضُ الۡجُرۡز» means dry, barren and uncultivable land. Land where there is very little rain (F L 70, 266). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَوَ لَمۡ یَرَوۡا اَنَّا نَسُوۡقُ الۡمَآءَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡجُرُزِ فَنُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡہُ اَنۡعَامُہُمۡ وَ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (32/27) Translation: 'Have they not seen that We drive the water [in clouds] to barren land and bring forth thereby crops from which their livestock eat and [they] themselves?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1765,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«سَاھِرَۃ» The surface of the earth.",
      "d": "«سَاھِرَۃ» Meaning earth or surface of the earth (Munjd). Land where there is frequent coming and going (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاِنَّمَا ہِیَ زَجۡرَۃٌ وَّاحِدَۃٌ فَاِذَا ہُمۡ بِالسَّاھِرَۃِ» (79/14) Translation: 'Indeed, it will be but one shout, and suddenly they will be [all] upon the surface of the earth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1766,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«صَعِیۡد» The dry dust on top of the earth that flies around.",
      "d": "«صَعَدَ» Meaning to climb. And «صَعِیۡد» means the upper part of the earth. Upper part and the dust present on it that rises up (Mufrad). Every level land is «صَعۡد» (Fl 16). And meaning the dust and dust etc. on the upper part of the earth (M-L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَلَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6) Translation: 'And if you find no water, then seek clean earth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1767,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«قَیۡعَۃً» Meaning open field.",
      "d": "«قَیۡعَۃً» and «قَاعًا (قوع)» mean open field (M-L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39) Translation: 'Their deeds are like a mirage in a lowland which a thirsty one thinks is water.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1768,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«صَفۡصَفَ» Meaning level and flat field.",
      "d": "«صَفۡصَفَ» Meaning level and flat field (Fl 264). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَیَذَرُہَا قَاعًا صَفۡصَفًا لَّا تَرٰی فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا وَّ لَاۤ اَمۡتًا» (20/106,107) Translation: 'They will leave it a level plain; You will not see therein a depression or an elevation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1769,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«عَرَآء» Barren field where there is no cover.",
      "d": "«عَرَا» Meaning to be naked. And «عَرَآء» is called such a field where there is nothing for cover (Mufrad). Small desert (Fl 26). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَنَبَذۡنٰہُ بِالۡعَرَآءِ وَ ہُوَ سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/145) Translation: 'Then We threw him onto the open shore while he was ill.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1770,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«زَلَقَ» Slippery field. Land that causes slipping.",
      "d": "«زَلَقَ» Meaning to slip. And «صَعِیۡدًا زَلَقًا» means slippery land. From where a person slips. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَعَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ اَنۡ یُّؤۡتِیَنِ خَیۡرًا مِّنۡ جَنَّتِکَ وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ صَعِیۡدًا زَلَقًا» (18/40) Translation: 'It may be that my Lord will give me [something] better than your garden and will send upon it a calamity from the sky, and it will become a smooth, slippery ground.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1771,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«صَفۡوَان» A small rock with a smooth surface.",
      "d": "«صَفۡوَان» Meaning a small rock with a smooth surface. A slab. Stony land."
    },
    {
      "id": 1772,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«صَلۡدًا» Smooth and dry stone.",
      "d": "«صَلۡدًا» Meaning solid and smooth stone. «رَاۡسٌ صَلۡدٌ» a bald head. And «صَلۡدٌ» means dry stone (F L 45). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۡدًا» (2/264) Translation: 'His example is like that of a [large] smooth stone upon which is dust and is hit by a downpour that leaves it bare.'"
    }
,
    {
      "id": 1773,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«فَجْوَۃ» The valley between two mountains.",
      "d": "«فَجْوَۃ» An open valley between two mountains. A wadi. And the path that passes through this valley is called «فَجّ» (Munjid, M L)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡ فَجۡوَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ» (18/17)\nTranslation: And you would have seen the sun when it rose, inclining away from their cave to the right, and when it set, passing away from them to the left, while they were in an open space thereof."
    },
    {
      "id": 1774,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«سَاحَۃ» An open space attached to or near houses.",
      "d": "«سَاحَۃ» An open space attached to or near houses. Courtyard. Ground. Park, etc. Places for gathering.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَفَبِعَذَابِنَا یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَ فَاِذَا نَزَلَ بِسَاحَتِہِمۡ فَسَآءَ صَبَاحُ الۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ» (37/176,177)\nTranslation: Do they then seek to hasten Our torment? Then when it descends upon their courtyard, evil will be the morning of those who were warned."
    },
    {
      "id": 1775,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«رَبْوَۃ» Land slightly elevated from the general surface and fertile.",
      "d": "«رَبَا» means to grow, to flourish. And «رَبْوَۃ» means elevated land (FL 266). Land slightly elevated from the general surface and fertile.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265)\nTranslation: Its example is like a garden on high ground which is struck by heavy rain - so it yields its fruits in double."
    },
    {
      "id": 1777,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«رِیْع» Land somewhat elevated from the general surface.",
      "d": "«رِیْع» is the plural of «رِیْعَۃٌ». Land that is higher than «رَبْوَۃ» and hard (FL 267).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَتَبۡنُوۡنَ بِکُلِّ رِیۡعٍ  اٰیَۃً  تَعۡبَثُوۡنَ» (26/128)\nTranslation: Do you build on every elevation a monument for vain amusement?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1778,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«وَادِی» An open and spacious place enclosed between mountains where water flows.",
      "d": "«وَادِی» Its plural is «اَوْدِیَۃ». A sloping place situated between mountains. Wide and spacious. And the rainwater that comes down from the mountains also flows in it, then the stream flowing in this valley is also called a valley. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ  اِنِّیۡۤ  اَسۡکَنۡتُ مِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ بِوَادٍ غَیۡرِ  ذِیۡ  زَرۡعٍ» (14/37)\nTranslation: Our Lord! I have settled some of my descendants in a valley where there is no cultivation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1779,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«مَوَاطِن» Battlefield.",
      "d": "«وَطَنَ» means to take residence, i.e., to dwell. And «وَطْن» means a person's dwelling, i.e., the place where one lives whether born there or not. And «مَوَاطِن» is the plural of «مَوْطِن». Meaning homeland. And «مِیْطَان» is the place from which horses are released for racing. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَوَاطِنَ کَثِیۡرَۃٍ» (9/25)\nTranslation: Allah has already given you victory in many battlefields."
    },
    {
      "id": 1780,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«جُدَد» Plural of «جُدَّۃ» meaning a separate and distinct piece of hard and level ground.",
      "d": "«جَدَّ» means something new. To cut something. «جَادَّۃ» means highway. The curve of a road. And «جَدَد» means level and hard ground. And «جُدَّۃ» means a mark, way, and its plural is «جُدَد». (Munjid) So «جُدَّۃ» refers to pieces of hard and level ground that appear clearly separate and cut off.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیۡبُ سُوۡدٌ» (35/27)\nTranslation: And among the mountains are tracts, white and red, of various colors, and (some) raven-black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1781,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To level to the ground",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«دَکَّ» To crush and level lifeless objects to the ground.",
      "d": "«دَکَّ» basically has two meanings: (1) To crush (2) To level. (M L) That is, to crush something into pieces and level it to the ground's surface. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He made it crumble to dust.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«اِذَا دُکَّتِ الۡاَرۡضُ دَکًّا دَکًّا» (89/21)\nTranslation: When the earth is crushed and leveled completely (Usmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1782,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To level to the ground",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«دَمْدَمَ» To destroy and level through punishment.",
      "d": "«دَمْدَمُ الشَّیْء» means to stick something to the ground. And «دَمْدَمَ اللہُ عَلَیْھِمْ» means Allah Almighty destroyed them (Munjid). And «دَیْمُوْمَۃ» means desert, wilderness. (Muf) For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَدَمۡدَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  رَبُّہُمۡ بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ  فَسَوّٰىہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So their Lord destroyed them because of their sin and leveled them."
    }
  ],
  ],
  "381": [
    {
      "id": 1787,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To give life",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«اَحْیَا» To give life to any dead person. This is its general usage.",
      "d": "«اَحْیَا» means to give life to the dead and its opposite is «اَمَاتَ» meaning death. «حَیِیَ» means to live, to remain alive. A common word.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَذٰلِکَ یُحۡیِ اللّٰہُ  الۡمَوۡتٰی  ۙ وَ یُرِیۡکُمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ» (2/73)\nTranslation: Thus Allah gives life to the dead and shows you His signs."
    },
    {
      "id": 1788,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To give life",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«بَعَثَ» To give life to and raise the dead lying in graves.",
      "d": "«بَعَثَ» basically has two meanings: (1) To raise, to lift (2) To send alone. And when this word is used regarding the dead lying in graves, its meaning will be to give them life in the graves and raise them and send them towards the field of Resurrection.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\nTranslation: And indeed, the Hour is coming, no doubt about it, and indeed Allah will raise up those in the graves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1789,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To give life",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«اَنْشَرَ» To give life, raise, and spread.",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ»'s basic meaning is to spread and its opposite is «طَوَی». And «نَشَرَ الْمَیِّتَ نَشُوْرًا» means the dead being brought back to life. (Muf) And in «اِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» three meanings are found: to become alive, to rise, and to spread. That is, people will come alive and spread out and proceed towards it. And «اَنْشَرَ» means to give life and spread in the field of Resurrection.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ» (80/21,22)\nTranslation: Then He caused him to die and provided a grave for him. Then when He wills, He will resurrect him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1790,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To live, to remain alive, to keep alive",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«حَیِیَ» Every living thing's living.",
      "d": "«حَیِیَ» means to live, to remain alive. And «حَیٰوۃ» means life. This word has a very broad meaning. Animals are alive, and current research shows that even inanimate objects have life. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنۡ ہِیَ  اِلَّا حَیَاتُنَا الدُّنۡیَا نَمُوۡتُ وَ نَحۡیَا وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِمَبۡعُوۡثِیۡنَ» (23/37)\nTranslation: (The disbelievers say) Life is only this worldly life of ours. We die and we live, and we will not be resurrected."
    },
    {
      "id": 1791,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To live, to remain alive, to keep alive",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«عَاشَ» The living of a creature whose life depends on eating and drinking.",
      "d": "«عَاشَ» means to remain alive. And «عَیْش» refers to the life found in animals. That is, this word is used for creatures that can live by eating and drinking. So this word is more specific than «حَیِیَ». And «مَعِیْشَۃ» its plural «مَعَائِش» means livelihood. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10)\nTranslation: And We have established you in the land and made for you therein ways of livelihood."
    },
    {
      "id": 1792,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To live, to remain alive, to keep alive",
      "hw": "Alive",
      "s": "«اِسْتِحْیَاء» To let someone else remain alive.",
      "d": "«اِسْتِحْیَاء» means to feel shame and also to keep alive or leave alive. (Munjid) And this word is used when someone is being killed in comparison. Allah says:\n«یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» (2/49)\nTranslation: (The people of Pharaoh) used to slaughter your sons and spare your women.\nFrom «حَیِیَ» the verbal noun «حیوۃ» also comes. And «حَیَاء» (also means shame)"
    }
  ],
  "382": [
    {
      "id": 1794,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "Adornment",
      "s": "«زُخْرُف» Gilding, i.e., artificial and outward adornment.",
      "d": "«زُخْرُف» has two meanings: First meaning is outward and artificial decoration and that adornment which is obtained from outward show. «زُخْرُفَ الْکَلَام» means to adorn speech with falsehood. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُوۡحِیۡ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ زُخۡرُفَ الۡقَوۡلِ غُرُوۡرًا» (6/112)\nTranslation: And thus We have made for every prophet an enemy - devils from mankind and jinn, inspiring to one another decorative speech in delusion.\nAnd the second meaning is the various colors and forms of plants. (Munjid) Spring and bloom.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ اَخَذَتِ الۡاَرۡضُ زُخۡرُفَہَا» (10/24)\nTranslation: Until, when the earth has taken on its adornment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1795,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "Adornment",
      "s": "«رِیْش» Luxurious clothing and adornment obtained from decoration.",
      "d": "«رِیْشُ الطَّائِر» means birds' feathers, particularly wing feathers. (Muf) And «رَیَّاش» means one who puts bird feathers on arrows. (Munjid) Since birds' feathers are like clothing, this word started being used metaphorically (temporarily) for luxurious clothing. Decorative clothes.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا» (7/26)\nTranslation: O children of Adam! We have sent down to you clothing to cover your nakedness and as adornment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1797,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "Adornment",
      "s": "«جَمَال» Outward beauty, goodness of character, and adornment and decoration of environment - used in all ways.",
      "d": "«جَمَال» This word is used in all ways for (1) outward beauty (2) goodness of character (3) adornment and beauty of environment. (FQ L 217) In the Holy Quran, this word is used in both meanings as «مُؤَخَّرُ الذِّکْر». According to its origin, its meaning is goodness in actions, morals, and outward deeds. Later this word started being used for outward beauty as well.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ حِیۡنَ تُرِیۡحُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ  تَسۡرَحُوۡنَ» (16/6)\nTranslation: And for you in them is (beauty) adornment when you bring them in (evening) and when you send them out (to pasture)."
    }
  ],
  "383": [
    {
      "id": 1798,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "Companion",
      "s": "«صَاحِب» One who stays together for a long time.",
      "d": "«صَاحِب» means one who stays together for a long time, whether this companionship is with a human or animal and whether this companionship is temporal or spatial. (Muf) And according to Ibn al-Faris, in «صَحَبَ» two things are found: (1) «مَقَارِنَۃ» and (2) «مَقَارِبَۃ» meaning being a companion and also being near or staying together. (M L) And the plural of «صَاحِب» is «اَصْحَاب» and its feminine is «صَاحِبَۃ». And according to the author of Furuq al-Lughawiyyah, this word's usage is specific to people. (FQ L 235)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذۡ ہُمَا فِی الۡغَارِ اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: When they both (Messenger of Allah ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave and he was saying to his companion (Abu Bakr), Do not grieve, indeed Allah is with us."
    },
    {
      "id": 1800,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "Companion",
      "s": "«قَرِيْنُ» means equal and peer, of same age.",
      "d": "«قَرِيْنُ» means of same age. And every person who is equal and peer in bravery, strength or other attributes and its usage is also in non-living things. For details see 'Friend'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1801,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "Companion",
      "s": "«اَزْوَاج» Means of same kind. People similar to each other in habits and manners.",
      "d": "«زَوْج» means pair, husband and wife - both are «زَوْج» for each other and together they are also «زَوْج» and its plural «اَزْوَاج» comes. This word is used in the Holy Quran in one place in the meaning of «قَرِیْن» (companion or of same kind). That is, people similar to each other. (See details in 'Different').\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اُحۡشُرُوا الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا وَ اَزۡوَاجَہُمۡ وَ مَا  کَانُوۡا  یَعۡبُدُوۡنَ» (37/22)\nTranslation: Gather those who wronged and their companions and what they used to worship."
    }
  ],
  "384": [
    {
      "id": 1802,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "Year",
      "s": "«عَام» means a year of goodness and well-being.",
      "d": "«عَام» Its plural is «عَوَام». The year in which there is abundance and plenty. (Muf) A year of goodness and well-being.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ  یَاۡتِیۡ مِنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ ذٰلِکَ  عَامٌ فِیۡہِ یُغَاثُ  النَّاسُ  وَ فِیۡہِ  یَعۡصِرُوۡنَ» (12/49)\nTranslation: Then after that will come a year in which the people will be given rain and in which they will press (olives and grapes).\nAnd accordingly the word «عَام» is also used as a supplication. On the occasion of Eid, Arabs say to each other instead of congratulations «اَنْتُمْ وَّکُلَّ عَامٍ بِخَیْرٍ» which means may this year of yours pass in goodness and well-being."
    },
    {
      "id": 1804,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "Year",
      "s": "«حَوْل» A complete cycle of a year from a specific date or by lunar calculation.",
      "d": "«حَالَ» Its plural is «حَالَات» meaning to change from one state to another. «حالات الدھر» means revolutions of days, changes of time. And «حَالَ الْحَوْل» means a year's period has passed. (Munjid) And «حَوْل» means a complete cycle of a year, i.e., the period from a specific date of one year to the same date of the next year. And Zakat is also paid by the calculation of «حَوْل». And in breastfeeding and divorce also the calculation of «حَوْل» is kept.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّصِیَّۃً  لِّاَزۡوَاجِہِمۡ مَّتَاعًا اِلَی الۡحَوۡلِ غَیۡرَ  اِخۡرَاجٍ» (2/240)\nTranslation: A bequest for their wives - provision for one year without turning (them) out."
    },
    {
      "id": 1805,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "Year",
      "s": "«حِجَج» A rough way of counting years.",
      "d": "«حِجَج» is the plural of «حَجَّۃٌ» and «حَجَّ» means to come and go repeatedly. To have frequent comings and goings. (Munjid) «حَجَّۃٌ» is from «حَجّ» a verbal noun of single occurrence (i.e., once a year). And since Hajj happens once a year, therefore the year is called Hajj. (L, M Q) In the early centuries (i.e., the time of the Companions), there was no regular calendar and calculation of days, months and years. So common people used to count years by the Hajjs.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ» (28/27)\nTranslation: I intend to marry you to one of these my two daughters on condition that you serve me for eight years."
    }
  ],
  "385": [
    {
      "id": 1807,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«مَتَاع» Every provision from which benefit is taken.",
      "d": "«مَتَاع» Its plural is «اَمْتِعَۃ» and «مَتَعَ» means to benefit for a long period. (Muf) And «مَتَاع» is any useful thing or that portion of anything that can give benefit. To benefit from worldly provisions. When the aspect of worldly provisions and benefiting from them is to be highlighted, this word is used.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُسۡتَقَرٌّ  وَّ مَتَاعٌ اِلٰی  حِیۡنٍ» (2/36)\nTranslation: And for you on earth is a place of settlement and provision for a time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1808,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«اَثَاث» means household's miscellaneous provisions, household necessities.",
      "d": "«اَثَاث» is the plural of «اَثَاثَۃٌ» but this is usually used as plural only, for example «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» is a famous phrase. Meaning household items that are in use. Household necessities like utensils, beds, clothes, furniture etc. All this is included in «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت». Then this word started being used for excessive and surplus type of wealth. And is also used to mean sale house and junk house. (Muf) Also the animals or slaves that are in someone's ownership and personal use are also included in «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت». For example, horse, cow, camel etc. (M Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ہُمۡ اَحۡسَنُ  اَثَاثًا  وَّ رِءۡیًا» (19/74)\nTranslation: And how many generations We destroyed before them who were better in possessions and appearance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1809,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«رَحْل» Provisions that stay with one during travel.",
      "d": "«رَحْل» means to put a packsaddle (cushion) on a camel. (Muf) And means to depart, to mount. And «رَحْل» means provisions that stay with one during travel. (Munjid) The word «رَحَلَ» is used for departing on a journey. (M L) The Prophetic saying ﷺ is, «لَا تَشَدُّوا الرِّحَالَ اِلاَّ لِثَلٰثَۃِ مَسَاجِدٍ» meaning do not saddle your camels for (visiting and seeking reward) any place except three mosques (Baytullah, Masjid Nabawi ﷺ and Masjid Aqsa).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ  فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Prophet Yusuf (AS) placed the drinking cup in his brother's provisions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1810,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«وِعَاء» Every provision that is closed or locked.",
      "d": "«وِعَاء» is the plural of «اَوْعِیَۃ» and «وَعٰی» meaning to preserve something in a bag etc. and tie the top. And «اَوْعِیَۃ» is that provision which is kept in a container and closed or locked. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ ثُمَّ اسۡتَخۡرَجَہَا مِنۡ وِّعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/76)\nTranslation: So he began (the search) with their bags before the bag of his brother; then he extracted it from the bag of his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 1811,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«جَھَاز» The provisions that a traveler prepares when departing on a journey.",
      "d": "«جَھَّزَ» means to prepare provisions, to load and to send. (Muf) And «جَھَاز» is the provisions that a traveler prepares when departing on a journey. And «تَجْھِیْز» is the provisions that are prepared before burying the deceased. And «جَھِیْز» is the provisions that parents give when sending off a girl at the time of marriage.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then when Prophet Yusuf (AS) prepared their provisions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1812,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«زَاد» Provisions of food and drink during travel.",
      "d": "«زَادَ» means became more. More. Provisions more than needed. (Muf) And the word «زَاد» is generally related to the path. Travel provisions. During travel, the path's expenses and provisions of food and drink. And «اَلْمُزَادَة» means a waterskin that is useful during travel. And «مِزْوَدَةٌ» means a provision bag. And «تَزَوَّدَ» also means to take travel provisions. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تَزَوَّدُوۡا فَاِنَّ خَیۡرَ الزَّادِ التَّقۡوٰی» (2/197)\nTranslation: And take provisions, but indeed, the best provision is righteousness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1813,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«اَسْلِحَۃ» War equipment and provisions.",
      "d": "«اَسْلِحَۃ» is the plural of «سِلَاح». This word is related to war or fighting. Meaning war provisions, instruments of war and strike. Weapons of war. And anything with which fighting is done or resistance and defense is made is called this. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلۡتَقُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَکَ وَ لۡیَاۡخُذُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَہُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: So let a group of them stand (in prayer) with you and let them carry their arms."
    },
    {
      "id": 1814,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«عُدَّۃ» War preparation and every type of provision and preparation related to it.",
      "d": "«عُدَّۃ» is the plural of «عُدَد» and «عَدَّ» meaning to prepare. «اَعَدَّ» and «اَعْتَدَ» mean to keep prepared. And «عُدَّۃٌ» means preparation-related provisions. Since this word is used in the Quran in the context of war preparation, therefore this word's meaning will also include every type of preparation and provisions.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَوۡ  اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا  لَہٗ  عُدَّۃً» (9/46)\nTranslation: But if they had intended to go forth, they would have prepared for it some preparation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1818,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«مَاعُوْن» Small household items of common use.",
      "d": "«اَلْمَعَنُ» means useful thing. And «مَاعُوْن» refers to every usable thing that comes into common people's use. Usable items. Small household items. For example, axe, pot or other domestic items. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  یُرَآءُوۡنَ وَ یَمۡنَعُوۡنَ الۡمَاعُوۡنَ» (107/7)\nTranslation: Those who make show (of their deeds) And withhold (simple) assistance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1819,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«حِذْر» One's protection provisions.",
      "d": "«حَذَرَ» means to be cautious and alert. (M L) And «حِذْر» is every provision that serves for protection and safety. So every protection provision from attack during war is «حِذْر». For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍ اَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: And there is no blame upon you if you are troubled by rain or are ill that you put down your weapons, but take your precaution."
    },
    {
      "id": 1820,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Provisions",
      "hw": "Provisions",
      "s": "«مَعَایِش» Every provision that is necessary to maintain or restore life.",
      "d": "«مَعَایِش» is the plural of «مَعِیْشَۃٌ» meaning livelihood provisions. «عَاش» means to remain alive, to live. And every provision that is for maintaining or restoring life. For example, food, grain, water, crops etc. That will be called livelihood.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10)\nTranslation: And We have established you in the land and made for you therein ways of livelihood."
    }
  ],
  "386": [
    {
      "id": 1821,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To come forward",
      "hw": "Front",
      "s": "«اَقْبَلَ» means to turn towards someone and be in front of them or to come forward.",
      "d": "«قَبَلَ الْمَکَان» means to turn towards a place. And «قَابَل» two things being face to face or opposite. To compete. And «قَبَّلَ» means to kiss. And «اَقْبَلَ» means to turn towards someone and be in front of them or to come. To face. To come from the front. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  مَّا ذَا  تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ» (12/71)\nTranslation: They said, turning to them, 'What is it you are missing?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1822,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To come forward",
      "hw": "Front",
      "s": "«بَرَزَ» means to come out into the open field.",
      "d": "«بَرْز» means space and open field. And «بَرَزَ» means to come out into the open field. (Muf) And means to appear after anonymity and concealment. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ بَرَزُوۡا لِلّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا» (14/21)\nTranslation: And they will all come out before Allah (on the Day of Judgment)."
    }
  ],
  "387": [
    {
      "id": 1823,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "Snake",
      "s": "«حَیَّۃٌ» is used for every type of snake.",
      "d": "«حَیَّۃٌ» is a generic noun. Every type of snake. Used for both masculine and feminine. (FL 160) And according to the author of MUNJID, «حَیَّۃٌ» means a coiling snake. And «حَوَایَا» refers to those intestines that are coiled like a snake. And «تَحَوُّی الْحَیَّۃٌ» means a snake coiling. And «حَاوِی» is called a snake charmer. (Munjid) Both these meanings seem correct because every snake is usually coiling. And probably for this reason it is called «حَیَّۃٌ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ  اَلۡقِہَا یٰمُوۡسٰی فَاَلۡقٰہَا فَاِذَا ہِیَ حَیَّۃٌ  تَسۡعٰی» (20/19,20)\nTranslation: Allah said, 'Throw it, O Moses!' So he threw it, and suddenly it was a snake, moving swiftly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1824,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "Snake",
      "s": "«جَآنّ» is used for thin and long snakes.",
      "d": "«جَآنّ» means jinn, demon, fairy. Strong-bodied. And every jinn that is in the form of a snake. (Muf) As also mentioned in Hadith. And Maulana Shabbir Ahmad Usmani (RA) translated it as snake's agility, speed, white and thin snake.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ  کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا  وَّ لَمۡ  یُعَقِّبۡ» (27/10)\nTranslation: But when he saw it writhing as if it was a snake, he turned in flight and did not look back."
    },
    {
      "id": 1825,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "Snake",
      "s": "«ثَعْبَانٌ» is used for a dragon/serpent.",
      "d": "«ثَعْبَانٌ» means dragon/serpent. A very large snake. (F L 40, 160)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: So he threw his staff, and suddenly it was a serpent, manifest.\nNow see Allah Almighty used all three words «حَیَّۃ», «جَانّ» and «ثَعْبَان» for snake in the same incident of staff turning into a snake. «حَیَّۃٌ» because every type of snake can be called «حَیَّۃ». «جَانّ» for the initial state of staff turning into snake. And «ثَعْبَان» for its second and final state. And all these things happened in an instant."
    }
  ],
  "388": [
    {
      "id": 1826,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All, whole",
      "hw": "All",
      "s": "«کُلّ» means each one and also all.",
      "d": "«کُلّ» means all, whole and its opposite is «جُزْء». Its usage is when «کُل» is a collection of several units (i.e., numbers from one to nine, numbers before tens in digits). Then this word's usage is also for every part and its meaning is, each one, everyone, every person, every thing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» (17/84)\nTranslation: Say, 'Each works according to his manner.'\nAnd its usage is also on the collection of these units where its meaning will be all, whole.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا» (2/31)\nTranslation: And He taught Adam the names - all of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1827,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All, whole",
      "hw": "All",
      "s": "«کَافَّۃ» means the whole of the whole and also all of all. This is stronger than «کُلّ» and complete.",
      "d": "«اَلْکَفَافُ» is called the complete circumference of something. «کَافَّ» is the active participle and «کَافَّۃٌ» is its feminine. (Muf) Its usage is also in two ways:\n(1) When «کُلّ» is a collection of many units, then this will come for that entire collection and in this respect it is stronger and more complete than «کُلّ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ  اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا» (34/28)\nTranslation: And We have not sent you except comprehensively to mankind as a bringer of good tidings and a warner.\n(2) When «کُلّ» is a single unit, then it comes to encompass all its parts. And in this respect it is stronger than complete. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً» (2/208)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, enter into Islam completely.\nIn this verse, the word «کَافَّۃ» gives both its meanings. That is, all of all and also whole of whole."
    },
    {
      "id": 1828,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All, whole",
      "hw": "All",
      "s": "«اَجْمَعُوْن» All agreeing together to do some work.",
      "d": "«جَمَعَ» means to gather. And «اَجْمَعَ» means all doing some work together. And «اَجْمَعَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means all agreeing on a matter.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» (12/15)\nTranslation: So when they took him and agreed to put him into the bottom of the well.\nAnd «اَجْمَعُوْن» means all together or at one time collectively doing some work.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَسَجَدَ  الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  کُلُّہُمۡ  اَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» (15/30)\nTranslation: So the angels prostrated, all of them together."
    }
  ],
  "389": [
    {
      "id": 1832,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over, to entrust",
      "hw": "Hand over",
      "s": "«سَلَّمَ» To hand over something to someone to avoid some trouble.",
      "d": "«سَلِمَ» means to be saved from fault and calamity. (M Q) And «سَلَّمَ» also means to say Assalamu Alaikum, to save from calamity. And «سَلَّمَہٗ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to hand over something to someone. And «سَلَّمہُ الشَّیْءَ فَتَسَلَّمَہٗ» means someone handing over something to another and that one accepting it. (Munjid) So «سَلَّمَ» will be used for avoiding some trouble and for handing over something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَرَدۡتُّمۡ اَنۡ تَسۡتَرۡضِعُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِذَا سَلَّمۡتُمۡ مَّاۤ  اٰتَیۡتُمۡ  بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And if you wish to have your children nursed by a substitute, there is no blame upon you as long as you give payment according to what is acceptable.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ  اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92)\nTranslation: And blood money paid to his family unless they remit it as charity."
    },
    {
      "id": 1833,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over, to entrust",
      "hw": "Hand over",
      "s": "«فَوَّضَ» To entrust the authority of a matter to someone and make them ruler.",
      "d": "«فَوَّضَ» means to leave work to someone. And «تَفْوِیْضًا اِلَیْہِ الْاَمْر» means to entrust the authority of some work to someone and make them ruler. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اُفَوِّضُ اَمۡرِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ» (40/44)\nTranslation: And I entrust my affair to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1834,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over, to entrust",
      "hw": "Hand over",
      "s": "«اِسْتَوْدَعَ» To hand over something as a trust.",
      "d": "«وَدَعَ» means to leave. And «اَوْدَعَ الشَّیْ» means to keep something as a trust. And «وَدَّعَ» means to bid farewell to a traveler. And «اِسْتَوْدَعَ فُلَانًا شَیْئًا» means to keep something with someone as a trust, so this handing over is as a trust. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ  فَمُسۡتَقَرٌّ وَّ مُسۡتَوۡدَعٌ» (6/98)\nTranslation: And it is He who produced you from one soul and for you is a place of dwelling and of storage.\nThat is, you are kept alive in the world for a period, then buried in the earth you are entrusted to God. (Jalandhri RA)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1835,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "Truth",
      "s": "«صِدْق» means to speak the truth.",
      "d": "«صَدَقَ» means to speak the truth. Its opposite is «کَذَب» (falsehood). That is, not to say anything contrary to reality. It is a well-known term.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ  کَذَبَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ وَ  کَذَّبَ بِالصِّدۡقِ اِذۡ جَآءَہٗ» (39/32)\nTranslation: Then who is more unjust than one who lies about Allah and denies the truth when it has come to him?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1836,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "Truth",
      "s": "«حَقّ» is used for truthfulness and veracity.",
      "d": "«حَقّ» its opposite is «بَاطِل» (falsehood). «حَقّ» is every matter or thing that proves true and correct after experience and observation. Reality. Truthfulness. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» (41/53)\nTranslation: We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the Quran) is the truth."
    }
  ],
  "391": [
    {
      "id": 1837,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«اَشَقّ» such trouble that is unbearable.",
      "d": "«شَقَّ الْاَمْر» means a matter becoming difficult. And «شَقَّ عَلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to put someone in hardship. (Munjid) And the word «اَشَقَّ» is generally used for such hardship that is beyond one's power or capacity. Trouble that is beyond endurance. Becoming unbearable.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَعَذَابُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ اَشَقُّ» (13/34)\nTranslation: And the punishment of the Hereafter is far more severe."
    },
    {
      "id": 1838,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«اَشَدّ» something being hard by its own nature.",
      "d": "«اَشَدُّ» means very strong and powerful, very hard. And «قُوَّۃً فِیْ شَیْءٍ» means something being powerful and hard by its own nature. Strong in power, strength and intensity. Used for body, strength and punishment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُرَدُّوۡنَ اِلٰۤی اَشَدِّ الۡعَذَابِ» (2/85)\nTranslation: They will be returned to the severest of punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1839,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«اَدْھٰی» hard in terms of calamities and troubles.",
      "d": "«دَھِیَ» means to afflict someone with calamity. And «دَاھِیَۃٌ» means a severe calamity. A very hard matter. (Munjid) And «دَھِیَ» means one thing reaching another in a disagreeable way or plunging into calamity. And «دَوَاھِیَ الدَّھْر» means the calamities of time. (M, L) And «اَدْھٰی» means hard in terms of calamities and troubles.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ السَّاعَۃُ اَدۡہٰی  وَ  اَمَرُّ» (54/46)\nTranslation: And the Hour (of Judgment) will be more calamitous and more bitter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1840,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«رَابِیَۃ» ever-increasing.",
      "d": "«رَبَا ، رَبْوًا» means to grow, flourish, increase, become more. And «رَابِیَۃ» means ever-increasing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَعَصَوۡا  رَسُوۡلَ  رَبِّہِمۡ  فَاَخَذَہُمۡ  اَخۡذَۃً  رَّابِیَۃً» (69/10)\nTranslation: So they disobeyed the messenger of their Lord, so He seized them with a seizing ever-increasing."
    },
    {
      "id": 1841,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«عَصِیْب» hard and devoid of good.",
      "d": "In «عَصَبَ» two things are found: (1) Connection and mixing of one thing with another. (2) Hardness. Its plural is «اَعْصَاب» meaning sinews. Also «عُصْبَۃ» refers to a strong group whose number is ten or more than ten, and they have connection and mixing among themselves, and due to this the group is powerful and strong. (M, L) As the brothers of Prophet Yusuf (AS) said to their father: «وَنَحْنُ عُصْبَۃٌ» (12/14) meaning we are a powerful group. And «تَعَصُّبْ» refers to hardness in ideology and belief, that a person does not accept even after truth becomes clear to him. And «عَصِیْب» is that thing which is hard and also devoid of good and safety.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَتۡ رُسُلُنَا لُوۡطًا سِیۡٓءَ بِہِمۡ وَ ضَاقَ بِہِمۡ ذَرۡعًا وَّ قَالَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ عَصِیۡبٌ» (11/77)\nTranslation: And when Our messengers came to Lot, he was distressed for them and felt straitened for them, and said: This is a distressful day."
    },
    {
      "id": 1842,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«قَمْطَرِیْر» hard in terms of evil.",
      "d": "«قَمْطَرِیْر» means one that makes hearts severely anxious, restless and disturbed. (Muf) «قِمْطَر» refers to the wood that is used for spreading the feet of criminals and punishing them. (M, Q) And «قَمْطَرِیْر» means severe evil or intense days. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا نَخَافُ مِنۡ رَّبِّنَا یَوۡمًا عَبُوۡسًا قَمۡطَرِیۡرًا» (76/10)\nTranslation: Indeed we fear from our Lord a Day austere and distressful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1843,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«قَاسِیَۃ» hardness of heart or stone-heartedness.",
      "d": "The word «قَسْوَۃ» indicates intensity and hardness. (M, L) «قَسَا» means to become hard and solid. (Munjid) «حَجَرٌ قَاسٍ» means hard stone. And «اَلْقَسْوَۃ» means to be stone-hearted. (Muf) So the word «قَسْوَۃ» is generally used for hardness of heart, stone-heartedness and being devoid of tender and merciful feelings. It is said «اَلذَّنْبُ مُسْقَاۃٌ لِّلْقَلْبِ» sin makes the heart hard. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ  لِّلۡقٰسِیَۃِ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ مِّنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (39/22)\nTranslation: Then woe to those whose hearts are hardened against the remembrance of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1844,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hard, severe",
      "hw": "Hard",
      "s": "«غَلِیْظ» means stone-hearted and harsh-tempered.",
      "d": "«غَلَظَ» means to become thick, dense, hard, rough or uneven. And «غَلَظَ الرَّجُل» means a man being irritable, bad-tempered and harsh-spoken. (Munjid) And the opposite of «غَلِیْظ» is «لِیْنٌ» meaning softness. And «غَلِیْظُ الْقَلْب» means a person who is both stone-hearted and bad-tempered. Its plural is «غِلَاظٌ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«عَلَیۡہَا مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ  غِلَاظٌ شِدَادٌ لَّا یَعۡصُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ مَاۤ  اَمَرَہُمۡ» (66/6)\nTranslation: Over it are angels, harsh and severe; they do not disobey Allah in what He commands them."
    }
  ],
  "392": [
    {
      "id": 1847,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hardship",
      "hw": "Hardship",
      "s": "«بَأسَاء» period of hardship and distress.",
      "d": "In «بَؤُسَ» the meanings of distress and hardship are found, whether due to war or hunger. And the word «بَأس» in the Holy Quran is also used for war, for example: «وَحِیْنَ الْبَاْس» (2/177) and it is also used for punishment, for example: «اِذْجَآءَ ھُمْ بَاْسُنَا» (6/43) and it is also used for calamity, for example: «بَأسًا شَدِیْدًا» (18/2). In all these, the meanings of distress are found. And «بَأسَآء» refers to a prolonged period of distress and hardship, whether it is economic hardship and adversity or the hardship of war.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی  اُمَمٍ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ بِالۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَضَرَّعُوۡنَ» (6/42)\nTranslation: And We have already sent to nations before you, [O Muhammad]; then We seized them with poverty and hardship that perhaps they might humble themselves [to Us]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1848,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hardship",
      "hw": "Hardship",
      "s": "«کَبَد» human nature that endures hardship throughout life.",
      "d": "In the word «کَبَد» the concept of hardship and strength is found. (M, L) And «تَکَبَّد» and «کَابَد» mean to endure hardship. (Munjid) «فِیْ کَبَد» is used as an idiom, and it expresses human nature. A desire is created in the human heart, then he endures various types of pain and suffering (hardship) to fulfill it, and before it can be fulfilled, several more desires arise. Then man becomes ready to fulfill them and endure pain and (hardship), and thus the whole life passes.\nAllah Almighty has expressed this reality thus:\n«لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡ  کَبَدٍ» (90/4)\nTranslation: We have certainly created man into [a life of] hardship.\nNote: In medical science, liver is also called 'kabid'."
    }
  ],
  "393": [
    {
      "id": 1849,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To raise head",
      "hw": "Head",
      "s": "«اَقْمَحَ» a head that is raised but eyes are lowered.",
      "d": "«اَقْمَحَ» a head that is raised but eyes are lowered. And «اَقْمَحَ الْبَعِیْر» when a camel raises its head after drinking water and keeps its eyes down, this condition is called so. (F L 186) And when a person wants to look down but cannot lower his head due to some compulsion, this is also called «اَقْمَحَ الرَّجُلُ وَغَضَّ بَصَرُہٗ». (M, Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنَا فِیۡۤ  اَعۡنَاقِہِمۡ  اَغۡلٰلًا فَہِیَ  اِلَی  الۡاَذۡقَانِ فَہُمۡ  مُّقۡمَحُوۡنَ» (36/8)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have put shackles on their necks, and they are to their chins, so they are with heads [kept] aloft."
    },
    {
      "id": 1850,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To raise head",
      "hw": "Head",
      "s": "«اَقْنَعَ» head is raised and gaze is forward or upward.",
      "d": "«اَقْنَعَ» means to raise voice or head. To elevate. And «مُقْنِع» means one who looks with raised head. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ ۚ وَ اَفۡئِدَتُہُمۡ  ہَوَآءٌ» (14/43)\nTranslation: Racing ahead, their heads raised up, their glance does not come back to them, and their hearts are void."
    }
  ],
  "394": [
    {
      "id": 1852,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader, chief",
      "hw": "Leader",
      "s": "«سَیِّد» leader of a large group. (used in good sense)",
      "d": "«سَادَ» means to be noble, to be great, to be chief of a tribe, to prevail over others in honor and nobility. (Munjid) «سَوَادَ» means a large group, and «سَیّد» is the leader of that large group. And since it is necessary for a leader to be civilized, therefore every noble-souled person can also be called Sayyid. And due to this relation, a master and husband is also called «سَیِّد». (Muf) Its plural is «سَادَت» and «سَادَات». This word is used in a good sense.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَاۤ  اِنَّاۤ  اَطَعۡنَا سَادَتَنَا وَ کُبَرَآءَنَا  فَاَضَلُّوۡنَا السَّبِیۡلَا» (33/67)\nTranslation: And they will say, 'Our Lord, indeed we obeyed our masters and our elders, and they led us astray from the [right] way.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1853,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader, chief",
      "hw": "Leader",
      "s": "«مَلَأ» courtiers and those who dominate the nation. (used in bad sense)",
      "d": "«مَلَا» means to fill. And «مَلَأ» means a group that gathers for a command. And it fills eyes with apparent beauty and hearts with awe. (Muf) And its chief who fills eyes with pride and chest with awe. (M, Q) And in common usage, «مَلَا» refers to those courtiers who, due to royal influence, dominate the people.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ الۡمَلَاُ الَّذِیۡنَ اسۡتَکۡبَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَوۡمِہٖ لَنُخۡرِجَنَّکَ یٰشُعَیۡبُ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مَعَکَ مِنۡ قَرۡیَتِنَاۤ» (7/88)\nTranslation: Said the eminent ones who were arrogant among his people, 'We will surely evict you, O Shu'ayb, and those who have believed with you from our city.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1854,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader, chief",
      "hw": "Leader",
      "s": "«رَھْط» a small group from the same tribe, a band of evildoers and its leader.",
      "d": "«رَھْط» is a small group of people from one tribe whose number is less than 10 and there is no woman among them. Then the leader of this group is also called «رَھْط». (Muf) And this is generally used in a bad sense. And «رَھْط» also refers to the cloth or rag that a woman keeps in a special place during menstruation. From this comes the idiom «ھُوَ اَذَلُّ مِنَ الرَّھْط» meaning he is more humble than the menstrual rag. And when the word «رَھْط» is attributed to a number, then individuals and persons are meant. Like «عِشْرُوْن رَھْطًا» meaning twenty persons. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کَانَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  تِسۡعَۃُ  رَہۡطٍ یُّفۡسِدُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا یُصۡلِحُوۡنَ» (27/48)\nTranslation: And there were in the city nine family heads causing corruption in the land and not amending [its affairs]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1855,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader, chief",
      "hw": "Leader",
      "s": "«اَئِمَّۃ» plural of «اِمَام» meaning a leader who is followed, whether good or bad.",
      "d": "«اَئِمَّۃ» is plural of «اِمَام». A person, book or saying that is followed. Whether it is a human, his sayings or a book, whether he is on truth or falsehood. (Muf) In the context of a person, it generally means a religious leader or an Imam of congregation in prayer. Now see their examples:\nExample (1) Book of guidance. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   اِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36/12)\nTranslation: And all things We have enumerated in a clear book.\nExample (2) Guides to guidance. For example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ  اَئِمَّۃً  یَّہۡدُوۡنَ  بِاَمۡرِنَا لَمَّا صَبَرُوۡا» (32/24)\nTranslation: And We made from among them leaders guiding by Our command when they were patient.\nExample (3) Leaders of disbelief. For example, Allah Almighty says:\n«فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا اَئِمَّۃَ الۡکُفۡرِ ۙ اِنَّہُمۡ لَاۤ اَیۡمَانَ لَہُمۡ» (9/12)\nTranslation: Then fight the leaders of disbelief. Indeed, they do not have [any] oaths."
    },
    {
      "id": 1856,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader, chief",
      "hw": "Leader",
      "s": "«نَقِیْب» a prominent person of a nation or group, a responsible individual of a tribe who represents it, leader, head.",
      "d": "«نَقَبَ» means to make a hole in a wall. To tunnel. And «نَقَبَ عَنِ الْاَخْبَار» means to investigate news. And «نَاقَبَ» means to boast of one's deeds. And «نَاقِبْ» means one who knows the conditions of a nation. And «مَنْقَبَتْ» means praise, commendation. A noble deed. And «نَقِیْب» means one who knows the conditions of a nation. Leader of a nation. Headman. Witness and guarantor of a nation. (Muf, Munjid) This word is also used in a good sense.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ بَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ ۚ وَ بَعَثۡنَا مِنۡہُمُ اثۡنَیۡ عَشَرَ نَقِیۡبًا» (5/12)\nTranslation: And Allah had already taken a covenant from the Children of Israel, and We delegated from among them twelve leaders."
    }
  ],
  "395": [
    {
      "id": 1857,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold",
      "hw": "Cold",
      "s": "«شِتَآء» the season of cold.",
      "d": "«شِتَآء» means the season of cold. Its opposite is «صَیْف» meaning the season of heat. And «شَتْوِیّ» means winter rain. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لِاِیۡلٰفِ قُرَیۡشٍ اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/1,2)\nTranslation: For the accustomed security of the Quraysh - Their accustomed security [in] the caravan of winter and summer."
    },
    {
      "id": 1858,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold",
      "hw": "Cold",
      "s": "«صِرّ» means severe cold.",
      "d": "«صُرَّ الْبَنَات» means plants dying due to cold wind. (Munjid) And «صِرّ» means severe cold. Shivering cold.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَمَثَلِ رِیۡحٍ فِیۡہَا صِرٌّ اَصَابَتۡ حَرۡثَ قَوۡمٍ ظَلَمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ فَاَہۡلَکَتۡہُ» (3/117)\nTranslation: The example of what they spend in this worldly life is like a wind containing frost which struck the harvest of a people who wronged themselves and destroyed it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1859,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold",
      "hw": "Cold",
      "s": "«صَرْ صَر» means severe cold and strong wind that also produces sound.",
      "d": "«صَرْ صَر» means severe cold and strong wind. A howling wind that is cold and strong and also produces sound. A whistling intense cold wind. (M, Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ  فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ» (69/6)\nTranslation: And as for 'Aad, they were destroyed by a screaming, violent wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1860,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold",
      "hw": "Cold",
      "s": "«نَفْحَۃ» a gust or blast of cold wind.",
      "d": "«نَفَحَ» means wind blowing in coldness. Or cold wind blowing. And نَفْحۃ is a single occurrence noun. Meaning a gust of cold wind. Its opposite is «لَفْحَۃ» meaning a gust of hot wind.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And if a breath of your Lord's punishment should touch them..."
    },
    {
      "id": 1861,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold",
      "hw": "Cold",
      "s": "«زَمْھَرِیْر» extreme cold layer or severe coldness.",
      "d": "«اِزْمَھَرَّالْیَوْم» means the day being severely cold. And «زَمْھَرِیْر» means severe coldness and also that layer where there is intense coldness. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَا یَرَوۡنَ فِیۡہَا شَمۡسًا وَّ  لَا  زَمۡہَرِیۡرًا» (76/13)\nTranslation: They will not see therein the sun or [any] coldness."
    }
  ],
  "396": [
    {
      "id": 1862,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To rebel",
      "hw": "Rebellion",
      "s": "«طَغٰی» to transgress one's limits.",
      "d": "«طَغٰی» means to cross the limit in disobedience. To be excessively disobedient. And «طَغَا الْمَاء» means water rising and spreading to the banks. To flood. (Munjid) «طَاغِیَۃ» means an overflowing punishment, storm, tremendous thunderclap. And «طَاغُوْت» is everything that is worshipped besides Allah. (Muf) Whether it is a system or a personality. So in transgression, dominance and oppression are also found. (Faq L 190)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ  لَیَطۡغٰۤی اَنۡ  رَّاٰہُ  اسۡتَغۡنٰی» (96/6)\nTranslation: No! [But] indeed, man transgresses. Because he sees himself self-sufficient."
    },
    {
      "id": 1863,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To rebel",
      "hw": "Rebellion",
      "s": "«عَتَا» rebellion due to arrogance.",
      "d": "«عُتُوّ یَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِسْتِکْبَارًا» means such rebellion that is due to arrogance, and a person considers himself great and rebels against Allah's command.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَلۡ لَّجُّوۡا فِیۡ عُتُوٍّ  وَّ نُفُوۡرٍ» (67/21)\nTranslation: Rather, they have persisted in insolence and aversion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1864,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To rebel",
      "hw": "Rebellion",
      "s": "«عَلَا» to become rebellious due to gaining dominance and power.",
      "d": "«عَلَا» means to become high. To prevail. To be arrogant. (Munjid) To become rebellious due to gaining dominance and power. To become haughty.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَتُفۡسِدُنَّ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَّتَیۡنِ  وَ لَتَعۡلُنَّ  عُلُوًّا کَبِیۡرًا» (17/4)\nTranslation: You will surely cause corruption in the earth twice, and you will surely reach [a degree of] great haughtiness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1865,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To rebel",
      "hw": "Rebellion",
      "s": "«مَرَدَ» to be rebellious then to go ahead in it, to become obstinate.",
      "d": "«مَرَدَ» means to be disobedient and rebellious. To go ahead of peers. (Munjid) So «مَرَدَ» refers to such rebellion in which one goes ahead of others.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنۡ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ  اِلَّا شَیۡطٰنًا مَّرِیۡدًا» (4/117)\nTranslation: They call not upon except a rebellious Satan."
    }
  ],
  "398": [
    {
      "id": 1868,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Tunnel",
      "hw": "Tunnel",
      "s": "«نَفَق» a tunnel that has two openings.",
      "d": "«نَفَق» is a path whose both sides are open. A tunnel that goes across. (F L 30) Like a road or tunnel is made by cutting through a mountain for rail or traffic. «نَیْفَقُ السَّرَاوِیْل» means the crotch of trousers. And «نَافِقَاءَ الْیَرْبُوْع» means the burrow of a wild rat, which has two openings. And «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» means the rat entered the burrow from one opening and exited from the other.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/35)\nTranslation: And if you were able to seek a tunnel in the earth or a ladder in the sky..."
    },
    {
      "id": 1869,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Tunnel",
      "hw": "Tunnel",
      "s": "«سَرَب» a tunnel that has only one opening.",
      "d": "«سَرَب» is a tunnel that has only one opening. And «سَرَبَ» means to keep penetrating evenly. (F L 30) And «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» means a snake entering its burrow.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجۡمَعَ بَیۡنِہِمَا نَسِیَا حُوۡتَہُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18/61)\nTranslation: But when they reached the junction between them, they forgot their fish, and it took its course into the sea, slipping away."
    }
  ],
  "399": [
    {
      "id": 1870,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To be slow, to lag",
      "hw": "Slow",
      "s": "«کَسَلَ» to be slow due to unwillingness.",
      "d": "«کَسَلَ» means the nature becoming heavy due to disinterest or unwillingness. To be lazy. To be slack or to remain so. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی» (4/142)\nTranslation: And when they stand up for prayer, they stand lazily."
    },
    {
      "id": 1871,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To be slow, to lag",
      "hw": "Slow",
      "s": "«وَھَنَ» to be slow due to physical or moral weakness.",
      "d": "«وَھَنَ» means to be slow due to physical or moral weakness. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4/104)\nTranslation: And do not be faint in pursuit of the people."
    },
    {
      "id": 1872,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To be slow, to lag",
      "hw": "Slow",
      "s": "«وَنٰی» to be slow due to carelessness.",
      "d": "«وَنٰی» means to be negligent, to be careless, to be slow. (Munjid) To not make effort despite having the power and ability to do a work.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذۡہَبۡ اَنۡتَ وَ اَخُوۡکَ بِاٰیٰتِیۡ وَ لَا تَنِیَا فِیۡ  ذِکۡرِیۡ» (20/42)\nTranslation: Go, you and your brother, with My signs and do not slacken in My remembrance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1873,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To be slow, to lag",
      "hw": "Slow",
      "s": "«اِسْتَحْسَرَ» to be slow due to fatigue.",
      "d": "«حَسَرَ» means to become tired. And «حَسَرَ الْبَصَرَ» means the sight becoming tired, eyesight becoming weak. And «حَسِیْر» means tired and weary. (Munjid) So «حَسَرَ» refers to slowness that occurs due to fatigue. To become weary.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَنۡ عِنۡدَہٗ  لَا یَسۡتَکۡبِرُوۡنَ عَنۡ عِبَادَتِہٖ وَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡسِرُوۡنَ» (21/19)\nTranslation: And those near Him are not prevented by arrogance from His worship, nor do they tire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1874,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To be slow, to lag",
      "hw": "Slow",
      "s": "«بَطَّاَ» to be slow in movement or habitually slow and then to delay.",
      "d": "«اَلْبَطْؤُ» means to be late in walking and to be slow. And «اِبْطَاءٌ» means slowness, laziness, sloth. And «بَطَّاَ» means to be very slow and to delay. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡکُمۡ لَمَنۡ لَّیُبَطِّئَنَّ» (4/72)\nTranslation: And indeed, there is among you he who lingers behind."
    }
  ],
  "400": [
    {
      "id": 1875,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To travel",
      "hw": "Travel",
      "s": "«سَفَرَ» is a general word for travel.",
      "d": "«سَفَرَ» means to go away from one's residence. (M, L) And means to cover distance. This word is general. Whether the travel is for any purpose.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ» (4/43)\nTranslation: And if you are ill or on a journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 1876,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To travel",
      "hw": "Travel",
      "s": "«سَاحَ» to travel in various directions in a vast field, touring.",
      "d": "«سَاحَ الْمَاءَ» means water to wander aimlessly. And «سَاحَۃ» means a spacious place. «سَاحَۃُ الدَّار» means the courtyard of a house. An open space attached to or near the house. (Muf) And «سَاحَ» means to walk and roam in an open space. Touring, whether it is merely for recreation or for some other purpose.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَسِیۡحُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَرۡبَعَۃَ  اَشۡہُرٍ» (9/2)\nTranslation: So travel freely, [O disbelievers], throughout the land [during] four months."
    },
    {
      "id": 1877,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To travel",
      "hw": "Travel",
      "s": "«ظَعَنَ» to migrate in the course of relocation.",
      "d": "«ظَعَنَ» means to migrate. To go from one place to another by migrating. To relocate. (Muf, M L) «ظَعَان» means the rope for tying a howdah (camel litter). «ظُعُوْن» means camels that carry loads (those that carry goods from one place to another). «ظَعِیْنَہ» means howdah (camel litter). And a woman who is often in travel and howdah.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ جُلُوۡدِ الۡاَنۡعَامِ بُیُوۡتًا تَسۡتَخِفُّوۡنَہَا یَوۡمَ ظَعۡنِکُمۡ وَ یَوۡمَ اِقَامَتِکُمۡ» (16/80)\nTranslation: And He made for you from the hides of the animals tents which you find light on your day of travel and your day of encampment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1878,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To travel",
      "hw": "Travel",
      "s": "«نَفَرَ» to set out on a mission or to confront the enemy.",
      "d": "«اَلنَّفِیْر» is a group of less than ten people. People who migrate towards war. And «اَلنَّفِیْرُ الْعَام» means the rising up of the common people to confront the enemy. (Munjid) And «نَفَرَ» means to go on a mission or war to confront the enemy.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71)\nTranslation: Then go forth, [O believers], in small groups or go forth all together."
    },
    {
      "id": 1880,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To travel",
      "hw": "Travel",
      "s": "«رَحَلَ» to depart. To set out on a journey.",
      "d": "«اَلرَّحْل» means howdah, saddle (cushion for sitting on riding animals). Station. Place of stay. Provisions that remain with one during travel. And «رَحَل» means to tie a howdah or saddle on the back of a camel or any animal. To mount. To migrate. To set out on a journey. (Muf, Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/2)\nTranslation: Their accustomed security [in] the caravan of winter and summer."
    }
  ],
  "401": [
    {
      "id": 1881,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand, to make understand",
      "hw": "To understand",
      "s": "«شَعَرَ» to understand the subtlety and delicacy of a matter.",
      "d": "«اَلشَّعْر» means hair. And «شَعَرَ» means to obtain knowledge as fine as hair. (Muf) To understand the subtlety and excellence of a matter.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ مَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (2/9)\nTranslation: And they do not deceive except themselves, but they perceive [it] not."
    },
    {
      "id": 1882,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand, to make understand",
      "hw": "To understand",
      "s": "«فَھَمَ» to understand the meanings and demands of a matter.",
      "d": "«اَلْفَھْم» is the name of that mental power of a human by which he extracts meanings and demands with excellence and fineness. And «فَھَمَ» means to understand something well. (Muf) And means to know or understand the meanings immediately upon hearing speech. (Faq L 69) And «سَرِیْعُ الْفَھْم» means one who understands a matter immediately. And «سَیِّءُ اَلْفَھْم» means slow-minded. (Faq L 69) And «فَھَّم» means to make someone understand the reality of something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کُنَّا  لِحُکۡمِہِمۡ  شٰہِدِیۡنَ فَفَہَّمۡنٰہَا سُلَیۡمٰنَ» (21/78,79)\nTranslation: And We were witness to their judgment, so We made Solomon understand it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1883,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand, to make understand",
      "hw": "To understand",
      "s": "«فَقَہَ» to derive solutions for other similar issues by reflecting on present examples.",
      "d": "«اَلْفِقْهُ» is the knowledge by which one reaches from the present to the unseen knowledge. (Muf) To find solutions for pending matters by keeping other examples and rulings in view.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡفَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ» (6/65)\nTranslation: Look how We diversify the signs that they might understand.\n«تَفَقُّہ» means to develop understanding in a matter and to attain insight. And to reach the depth of a matter.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (9/122)\nTranslation: And it is not for the believers to go forth [to battle] all at once. For there should separate from every division of them a group [remaining] to obtain understanding in the religion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1884,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand, to make understand",
      "hw": "To understand",
      "s": "«عَقَلَ» to understand one's benefit and harm, then to devise a plan to adopt or abandon it.",
      "d": "«عَقَلَ» means to be one of understanding and comprehension. To be capable of realizing one's mistake. (Munjid) And «عَقَلَ» means to stop and prevent. And «عِقَال» is the hobble (rope) with which a camel's leg is tied. And «اَلْمَعْقِل» means a place of refuge. A mountain or fort that is taken refuge in. (Muf) So this is the work of intellect that it distinguishes benefit and harm and adopts measures to avoid harmful things. (Faq L 65) Then to be always ready for attaining beneficial things and accepting knowledge. Then to reflect. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَتَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبِرِّ وَ تَنۡسَوۡنَ اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ تَتۡلُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ ؕ اَفَلَا تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ» (2/44)\nTranslation: Do you order righteousness of the people and forget yourselves while you recite the Scripture? Then will you not reason?"
    }
  ],
  "402": [
    {
      "id": 1885,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«سَمِعَ» to hear any speech or sound.",
      "d": "«سَمِعَ» means to hear any speech or sound with the ears. And «اَلسَّمْع» also means the power of hearing and also the ear.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)\nTranslation: Certainly has Allah heard the speech of the one who argues with you, [O Muhammad], concerning her husband."
    },
    {
      "id": 1886,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«سَمَّاع» to listen by putting ears for espionage.",
      "d": "«سَامِع» means one who hears. And «سَمَّاع» means a spy. A person who puts ears to listen for espionage.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِقَوۡمٍ اٰخَرِیۡنَ ۙ  لَمۡ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ» (5/41)\nTranslation: [They are] avid listeners to falsehood, devourers of [what is] unlawful. If they come to you, [O Muhammad], judge between them or turn away from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1887,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«اَسْمَعَ» to make someone hear something.",
      "d": "«اَسْمَعَ» means to make someone hear something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّکَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الصُّمَّ الدُّعَآءَ اِذَا وَلَّوۡا مُدۡبِرِیۡنَ» (27/80)\nTranslation: Indeed, you cannot make the dead hear, nor will you make the deaf hear the call when they have turned their backs retreating."
    },
    {
      "id": 1888,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمَعَ» to put ears and try to hear a sound or speech.",
      "d": "«اِسْتَمَعَ» means to put ears, to lend an ear, to try to hear a speech or sound when the sound is not clearly audible. (Munjid, Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا» (72/1)\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'It has been revealed to me that a group of the jinn listened and said, 'Indeed, we have heard an amazing Quran.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1889,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«اَذِنَ» to listen attentively by putting ears.",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» means to listen attentively by putting ears. (Muf) To listen carefully to speech for compliance with command.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84/2)\nTranslation: And has listened to its Lord and was obligated [to do so]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1890,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear, to make hear",
      "hw": "To hear",
      "s": "«اٰذَنَ» to warn someone by making them hear.",
      "d": "«اٰذَنَ» means to make someone hear and to warn, to inform. (Munjid, Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ  یُنَادِیۡہِمۡ  اَیۡنَ شُرَکَآءِیۡ ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اٰذَنّٰکَ ۙ مَا مِنَّا مِنۡ شَہِیۡدٍ» (41/47)\nTranslation: And [mention] the Day He will call to them and say, 'Where are My 'partners' which you used to claim?' They will say, 'We announce to you that there is not [among us] anyone [who can testify] to that.'"
    }
  ],
  "403": [
    {
      "id": 1891,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To reform, to mend",
      "hw": "To reform",
      "s": "The word «اِصْلَاحُ» is used for reforming and correcting every type of corruption.",
      "d": "«اِصْلَاحُ» its opposite is «اَفْسَدَ». «اِصْلَاحُ» means to correct corruption and spoilage. Its usage is general in both material and spiritual aspects.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n« کَفَّرَ عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ  وَ اَصۡلَحَ بَالَہُمۡ» (47/2)\nTranslation: He will remove from them their misdeeds and amend their condition.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And cause not corruption upon the earth after its reformation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1892,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To reform, to mend",
      "hw": "To reform",
      "s": "The word «زَکّٰی» is used for correcting the corruption of the self and then adding lofty morals to it.",
      "d": "The lexical meaning of «زَکوٰ ، زَکٰی» and «زَکّٰی» is the growth and increase of crops etc. And «زَکِیْ مَالَہٗ» means to pay zakat of wealth. And «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ» means to praise oneself. (Munjid) But the Shariah has used the word «تَزْکِیَہ» in the sense of purifying and reforming. And purification of self means to purify the self from base morals and to add good morals.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَدۡ  اَفۡلَحَ  مَنۡ  زَکّٰىہَا وَ  قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ  دَسّٰىہَا» (91/9,10)\nTranslation: He has succeeded who purifies it (the soul), And he has failed who instills it [with corruption]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2466,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Valley, Pass",
      "hw": "Valley",
      "s": "«عَقَبَۃ» is only called that valley which is difficult to pass.",
      "d": "«عَقَبَۃ» means a difficult path going up a mountain (Muf). That is, by «عَقَبَۃ» is meant only that path which climbs a valley or mountain.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَلَا اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ وَ مَاۤ اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» (90:11-12)\nTranslation: But he did not pass over the steep path. And what will make you know what the steep path is? It is the freeing of a neck.\nBut according to the author of Munjad, the meaning of «عَقَبَۃ» is a difficult valley and also the difficult path to climb it."
    }
  ],
  "539": [
    {
      "id": 2467,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House, Home",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "«بَیۡت» is where a person resides with his family and also spends the night.",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» means to spend the night. To stay overnight. And «بَیۡت» is the place where the night is spent. Then terminologically, by بیت is meant that place where a person can spend the night with his family and it is their shelter and refuge (Muf, M L). The plural of «بَیۡت» is «بُیُوۡت».\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33:33)\nTranslation: And stay in your houses and do not display yourselves like the former times of ignorance.\nAnd for the Ka'bah also Allah the Exalted used the word «بَیۡت» and «اَلْبَیۡت». In it also the described connection is found.\nFor example, the Prophetic saying ﷺ is: «اَلْخَلْقُ عَیَالُ اللہ» meaning all creation is the family of Allah. And Ka'bah may not be a place for spending the night, but it is definitely a shelter and refuge."
    },
    {
      "id": 2468,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House, Home",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "«مَسۡکَن» gives only the meaning of residence, whether it is a place for spending the night or not. So this is more specific than «بَیۡت».",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» means to settle. Also to rest after working. And «مَسۡکَن» is the place where a person takes residence, and giving residence to a person without rent etc. is called «سُکۡنٰی», and those living in one house are called «سُکۡن». Which is the plural of «سَاکِنٌ» (Muf). And the word «مَسۡکَن» only demands residence. So every بیت is مسکن but every مسکن is not بیت.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَتِلۡکَ مَسٰکِنُہُمۡ لَمۡ تُسۡکَنۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (28:58)\nTranslation: So these are their dwellings which were not inhabited after them except a little."
    },
    {
      "id": 2469,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House, Home",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "The usage of «دَار» is very general. When in the meaning of house, it refers to the external aspect of the house. For example, inside one دَار (mansion) there can be several بَیۡت.",
      "d": "The plural of «دَار» is «دَوۡر» and «دِیَار» meaning house, place. The usage of «دَار» is very extensive. It is used for house, mansion, settlement, city, country, the whole world, and even the Hereafter (for details see 'City'). And when by «دَار» is meant house, then the external aspect of the house is intended. In English, the word HOME is for this. Also, when «دَار» is used in the meaning of house, its plural will also be «دَار».\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَقَالَ تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ اَیَّامٍ» (11:65)\nTranslation: So he said: Enjoy yourselves in your houses for three days."
    },
    {
      "id": 2470,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House, Home",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "«اَہۡل» includes house and household, family members all in its meaning.",
      "d": "The word «اَہۡل» is also used in very broad meanings (for details and the difference between «اَہۡل» and «اٰل» see 'Children'). And in well-known meanings, «اَہۡلُ الرَّجُل» are a person's household and family, that is, wife and children who are under his support and upbringing. Then just as the word «قَرۡیَۃ» is used for both the settlement and the people of the settlement, similarly the word «اَہۡل» is used for the household besides the people of the house.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ» (3:121)\nTranslation: And when you went forth from your house early in the morning to assign positions to the believers for battle."
    }
  ],
  "540": [
    {
      "id": 2471,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Hour, Time",
      "hw": "Hour",
      "s": "«سَاعَۃ» means any one of the hours of day and night. Time. The Hour (Day of Judgment).",
      "d": "«سَاعَۃ» is a fixed portion of time. An hour. Its plural is «سَاعَات». The Arabs divided the night and day into twelve hours each and gave them separate names, the details of which have passed in 'Day and Night'. Nowadays also the complete time of night and day is divided into 24 hours. So by «سَاعَۃ» can also be meant one hour.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لَمۡ یَلۡبَثُوۡۤا اِلَّا سَاعَۃً مِّنۡ نَّہَارٍ» (46:35)\nTranslation: They remained not but an hour of a day.\nAnd for the watch (timepiece) which in English is called WATCH, the word «سَاعَۃ» is also used. And «سَاعَاتِی» means the watch shopkeeper and watchmaker. And sometimes from «سَاعَۃ» is also intended duration or times. Which can be a full day or even consist of several days, months and years.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ تَّابَ اللّٰہُ عَلَی النَّبِیِّ وَ الۡمُہٰجِرِیۡنَ وَ الۡاَنۡصَارِ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّبَعُوۡہُ فِیۡ سَاعَۃِ الۡعُسۡرَۃِ» (9:117)\nTranslation: Allah has certainly turned in mercy to the Prophet and the Emigrants and the Ansar who followed him in the hour of hardship.\nAnd by «اَلسَّاعَۃ» is generally intended the Day of Judgment.\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ بَغۡتَۃً» (6:31)\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2472,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Hour, Time",
      "hw": "Hour",
      "s": "«اٰنَآء» means the hours of the night.",
      "d": "«اٰن» means some portion of time. Its plural is «اٰنَآء». And «اَنٰی یَانِیْ» means the time of something to come and to reach its end (Muf). Also «اَنٰی» means a full day or some portion of it (Munjad). But in the Holy Quran the word «اٰنَآء» is used three times (3:113), (20:13) and (39:9) and in all three places the word «لَیۡل» meaning night comes with «اٰنَآء». This word has not been used with day. Therefore, it can be understood from this that the word «اٰنَآء» is specific for the hours of the night.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«یَّتۡلُوۡنَ اٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ اٰنَآءَ الَّیۡلِ وَ ہُمۡ یَسۡجُدُوۡنَ» (3:113)\nTranslation: They recite the verses of Allah during the hours of the night and they prostrate."
    }
  ],
  "541": [
    {
      "id": 2474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To enter, To penetrate",
      "hw": "To enter",
      "s": "«وَلَجَ» is used for entering a narrow place.",
      "d": "«وَلَجَ» means to enter a narrow place. To penetrate (Muf).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» (7:40)\nTranslation: And they will not enter Paradise until the camel enters the eye of the needle."
    },
    {
      "id": 2475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To enter, To penetrate",
      "hw": "To enter",
      "s": "«جَاسَ» means to enter a house or shop etc. for plunder and mischief.",
      "d": "«جَاسَ» means to reach between something (M, L). And meaning to reach the end in search of something (Muf). And «جَاسَ فِی الْبَیۡت» means he entered the house for mischief and plunder (M, Q). And «جَوَّاس» means one who enters among the people and creates mischief (Munjad).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ عِبَادًا لَّنَاۤ اُولِیۡ بَاۡسٍ شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» (17:5)\nTranslation: We sent against you some of Our servants of great might, so they penetrated throughout the homes."
    }
  ],
  "542": [
    {
      "id": 2476,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To drag, To pull",
      "hw": "To drag",
      "s": "«جَرّ» means to pull a standing thing in such a way that it starts dragging. And when in this «جَرّ» there is also severity and ruthlessness, then this is «عَتَلَ». And when a lying thing is pulled, then this is «سَحْب».",
      "d": "In «جَرّ» the aspect of pulling is prominent and of dragging less. In the direction of the horizontal (i.e., edge) or pulling a standing thing in such a way that it does not remain under control on its feet and starts dragging, then this is «جَرّ».\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اَخَذَ بِرَاۡسِ اَخِیۡہِ یَجُرُّہٗۤ اِلَیۡہِ» (7:150)\nTranslation: And he seized his brother by his head, pulling him towards himself.\nAnd «جَیۡشٌ جَرَّارٌ» is called that large army which spreads over a vast area and advances forward. As if it is being pulled or dragged forward."
    },
    {
      "id": 2477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To drag, To pull",
      "hw": "To drag",
      "s": "«سَحَبَ» means to drag on the ground, to snatch, to seize, to take back.",
      "d": "In «سَحَبَ» the aspect of dragging is prominent and of pulling less. And according to Imam Raghib its meaning is to drag someone on their face (Muf). When something is instead of being standing in the direction of lying or instead of being vertical in the horizontal (edge) direction and it is dragged, then this is «سَحْب». And «سَحَاب» means cloud. And cloud is called «سَحَاب» because the wind pulls it along and it advances forward as if it is dragging along (Muf).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یُسۡحَبُوۡنَ فِی النَّارِ عَلٰی وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ» (54:48)\nTranslation: The Day they will be dragged into the Fire on their faces."
    },
    {
      "id": 2478,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To drag, To pull",
      "hw": "To drag",
      "s": "«عَتَلَ» means to pull forward with extreme severity by putting something around the neck.",
      "d": "In «عَتَل» the concept of more severity and ruthlessness is found compared to «جَرّ» (M, Q). And according to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, to pull forward with extreme severity by putting something around the neck (F L 188).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44:47)\nTranslation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hellfire."
    }
  ],
  "543": [
    {
      "id": 2479,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Horse",
      "hw": "Horse",
      "s": "«خَیۡل» is a generic noun. Its usage is general for horse, for horseman, and for the collective group.",
      "d": "«خَیۡل» is a generic noun. That is, it applies to every type of horse, whether male or female (Muf). Then its usage is also on a herd or group of horses. Like «غَنَم» meaning a flock of goats. And besides this, its usage is also on the horseman (Munjad).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡخَیۡلَ وَ الۡبِغَالَ وَ الۡحَمِیۡرَ لِتَرۡکَبُوۡہَا وَ زِیۡنَۃً» (16:8)\nTranslation: And horses, mules and donkeys (He created) that you may ride them and as adornment.\nIn this verse the usage of «خَیۡل» has come as a generic noun and in the verse below the usage of «خَیۡل» is being used for the horseman or the collection of horsemen and horses.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» (17:64)\nTranslation: And incite against them your cavalry and your infantry.\nAnd the basic meaning of «خَیۡل» is the movement of various thoughts in the mind (M, L). From this the word خیال (thought) emerged. And «اَلْخَیۡلَآء» is called that pride and arrogance which a horseman feels on horseback compared to a pedestrian. From this is the word تخیل. Meaning to know something with insight (Munjad). High-flying."
    },
    {
      "id": 2480,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Horse",
      "hw": "Horse",
      "s": "«صٰفِنٰت» means horses standing on three legs, alert and well-built.",
      "d": "«صٰفِنٰت» is the plural of «صَافِن». «صَفَنَ الْفَرَس» means the horse standing on three legs in such a way that only the tip of the fourth hoof touches the ground (Munjad, Muf). And from this is intended a well-built horse.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» (38:31)\nTranslation: When there were exhibited before him in the evening the poised standing fine horses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2481,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Horse",
      "hw": "Horse",
      "s": "«جِیَاد» means fast-running and excellent quality horses.",
      "d": "«جِیَاد» is the plural of «جَیِّد». «جُوۡد» means there is expansiveness in something. And «جَوَّاد» is called a generous man or woman. And «جَادَ الْفَرۡس» means the horse being light and fast-running (M, L). And the word «جَیِّد» also indicates the excellence of something. According to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, «جِیَاد» means fast-running and excellent horses (F L 56).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» (38:31)\nTranslation: When there were exhibited before him in the evening the poised standing fine horses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2482,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Horse",
      "hw": "Horse",
      "s": "«عٰدِیٰت» means those horses that take part in racing and are prepared for war.",
      "d": "«عٰدِیٰت» is the plural of «عَادِیَۃ». And «عَادِیَۃٌ ، عَادِی» is the feminine of. And «عَادِی» means that group which is prepared for killing and fighting. Plundering horses. And «عَدَا الْفَرۡس» means the horse ran a race. And «تَعَادَی الْقَوْم» means people competed in racing (Munjad). So by «عٰدِیٰت» are intended those war-bound horses that kept taking part in competitive racing.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100:1)\nTranslation: By the racers, panting."
    }
  ],
  "544": [
    {
      "id": 2483,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To surround, To encircle",
      "hw": "To surround",
      "s": "By «حَفَّ» is meant only surrounding or to encircle.",
      "d": "«حَفَّ» means to surround something from both sides (Muf). And «حَفَّہٗ بِکَذَا» means to encompass (Munjad). And «مَحِفَّۃ» means a palanquin. A moving platform on which curtains are draped from all sides (M, Q).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ وَّ جَعَلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمَا زَرۡعًا» (18:32)\nTranslation: And We encircled them both with palm trees and placed between them crops.\nIn another place, Allah the Exalted states:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ حَآفِّیۡنَ مِنۡ حَوۡلِ الۡعَرۡشِ» (39:75)\nTranslation: And you will see the angels surrounding the Throne from all sides."
    },
    {
      "id": 2484,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To surround, To encircle",
      "hw": "To surround",
      "s": "«اَحَاطَ» means to encircle, the purpose of which is protection.",
      "d": "«اَحَاطَ» means to encompass. To make a boundary wall. To surround something in such a way that the thing is protected (Muf). In such a way that neither can that thing itself go out, nor can anyone else take it out. Just as the boundary of a house is made with a boundary wall.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10:22)\nTranslation: And waves came upon them from every side, and they became certain that they were encircled.\nThe usage of this word is also metaphorically.\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«بَلٰی مَنۡ کَسَبَ سَیِّئَۃً وَّ اَحَاطَتۡ بِہٖ خَطِیۡٓئَتُہٗ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ النَّارِ» (2:81)\nTranslation: Yes, whoever earns evil and his sin encompasses him, then those are the companions of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2485,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To surround, To encircle",
      "hw": "To surround",
      "s": "«اَحۡصَرَ» means siege and confinement, that is, to confine something.",
      "d": "«اَحۡصَرَ» means to besiege. To encircle. To surround something in such a way that it remains confined there and cannot go out (M, L, Muf). To confine and not let any kind of supply (food and drink items), help (military aid) or any kind of aid reach them from outside.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ احۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» (9:5)\nTranslation: And besiege them and sit for them at every place of ambush."
    },
    {
      "id": 2486,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To surround, To encircle",
      "hw": "To surround",
      "s": "«حَاقَ» means a calamity to encompass someone.",
      "d": "«حَاقَ» means something to descend upon something (M L). And meaning something to descend upon something and encompass it (Muf). That is, such a siege that befalls the person himself. A calamity, disaster or punishment to descend upon someone by which he is encircled. And «حَیۡق» means requital. The bad result of a bad deed (Munjad). So this word is used in a bad meaning.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ حَاقَ بِہِمۡ مَّا کَانُوۡا بِہٖ یَسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» (39:48)\nTranslation: And there will encompass them what they used to ridicule.\nIn another place, Allah the Exalted states:\n«وَ لَا یَحِیۡقُ الۡمَکۡرُ السَّیِّیئُ اِلَّا بِاَہۡلِہٖ» (35:43)\nTranslation: And the evil plot encompasses not but its own people.\nThe mentioned part of the verse is also used as an idiom. It is a Persian idiom: \"چاہ کن را چاہ درپیش\" meaning he who plans to harm others himself becomes involved in that harm."
    }
  ],
  "545": [
    {
      "id": 2487,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff, Stick",
      "hw": "Staff",
      "s": "«عَصَا» means a shepherd's staff.",
      "d": "«عَصَا» means a shepherd's staff. A stick. Its plural is «عِصِیّ».\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7:107)\nTranslation: Then he threw his staff, and behold, it was a serpent, manifest."
    },
    {
      "id": 2488,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff, Stick",
      "hw": "Staff",
      "s": "«مِنۡسَاَۃ» means the staff of a sick or weak person.",
      "d": "«مِنۡسَاَۃ» means the staff of a sick or weak person (F L 231).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ الۡمَوۡتَ مَا دَلَّہُمۡ عَلٰی مَوۡتِہٖۤ اِلَّا دَآبَّۃُ الۡاَرۡضِ تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡسَاَتَہٗ» (34:14)\nTranslation: Then when We decreed for him (Solomon) death, nothing indicated to them his death except a creature of the earth eating his staff.\nAnd such a staff whose end is curved, it is called «مِحۡجَن» (F L 231). «عَصَا» and «مِنۡسَاَۃ» both do not have a curved end. «عَصَا» is a thick and strong stick. And «مِنۡسَاَۃ» is a relatively less thick and good-looking type of staff."
    }
  ],
  "546": [
    {
      "id": 2489,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«جَآءَ بِ» means to bring. Its usage is general.",
      "d": "«جَآءَ بِ» means to bring. Its usage is general.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَقَدۡ کُذِّبَ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ جَآءُوۡ بِالۡبَیِّنٰتِ» (3:184)\nTranslation: So messengers before you were denied who came with clear proofs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2490,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ» means to bring as a result of something.",
      "d": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ» means to bring as a result of something.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاۡتُوۡا بِسُوۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ مِّثۡلِہٖ» (2:23)\nTranslation: Then bring a chapter like it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2491,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«ہَلُمَّ» is used when calling someone to come.",
      "d": "«ہَلُمَّ» is a verb noun. Means call. That is, to call someone repeatedly (M, L). This word is used both intransitively and transitively. If intransitive, it gives the meaning of coming.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا» (33:18)\nTranslation: To their brothers: Come to us.\nAnd when used transitively, it gives the meaning of bringing.\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«قُلۡ ہَلُمَّ شُہَدَآءَکُمُ» (6:150)\nTranslation: Say: Bring your witnesses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2492,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«ہَاتُوۡا» means bring here, bring quickly.",
      "d": "«ہَاتُوۡا» according to the lexicographers, this word is originally «اٰتُوۡا» itself which is the imperative plural masculine present form from «اَتٰی». And this word is used as an imperative noun. According to Ibn Faris, its meaning is also to call out loudly. «یَدُلُّ عَلَی الصَّیۡحَۃ» (M L). But according to some, its meanings are to bring here or to bring quickly.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2:111)\nTranslation: Say: Bring your proof, if you are truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2493,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«اَجَآءَ» means to bring something forcibly by making it helpless and helpless, or to be the cause of bringing.",
      "d": "«اَجَآءَ» means to bring something forcibly by making it helpless and helpless, or to be the cause of bringing.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَجَآءَہَا الۡمَخَاضُ اِلٰی جِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ» (19:23)\nTranslation: Then the pains of labor drove her to the trunk of a palm tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 2494,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "To bring",
      "s": "«اَجۡلَبَ» means to forcibly drive someone from behind to bring.",
      "d": "«جَلَبَ» means to drive and herd something. And «اَجۡلَبَ عَلَیۡہِ» means to call someone and forcibly advance them forward (Muf).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» (17:64)\nTranslation: And incite against them your cavalry and your infantry."
    }
  ],
  "547": [
    {
      "id": 2495,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy, To be deserving",
      "hw": "Worthy",
      "s": "«یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ» means to be worthy. This word is used for such an action (work) for which it is subservient (i.e., dominant).",
      "d": "«اِنۡۢبَغٰی» means to be easy and simple. And «یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ» means to be worthy. To be suitable (Munjad). And this word is used for such an action for which it is subservient. They say «اَلنَّارُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ اَنۡ یُّحْرِقَ الثَّوۡبَ» meaning it is the nature of fire to burn the cloth (Muf). Only this singular masculine third person present form is used. And it comes regarding matters that are included or inherent in nature. Lexically, it is used both negatively and affirmatively.\nThe example of negative in the Holy Quran is stated thus:\n«لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» (36:40)\nTranslation: It is not for the sun to overtake the moon.\nIn another place, Allah the Exalted states:\n«وَ مَا عَلَّمۡنٰہُ الشِّعۡرَ وَ مَا یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہٗ» (36:69)\nTranslation: And We have not taught him poetry, nor is it befitting for him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2496,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy, To be deserving",
      "hw": "Worthy",
      "s": "«اَجۡدَرُ» is the form of intensity and it comes for voluntary matters.",
      "d": "«جَدَرَ» means to be worthy and suitable. And «اَجۡدَرُ» is the form of intensity and it comes for voluntary matters. «جَدِیۡرُ الذِّکۡر» means worthy of mention. And «جَدِیۡرُ الثَّنَآء» means worthy of praise. And it is used when something is suitable and befitting for someone.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّ نِفَاقًا وَّ اَجۡدَرُ اَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡا حُدُوۡدَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ» (9:97)\nTranslation: The Bedouins are stronger in disbelief and hypocrisy and more worthy not to know the limits of what Allah has revealed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2497,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy, To be deserving",
      "hw": "Worthy",
      "s": "«اَوۡلٰی» is used in broader meanings than «اَجۡدَرُ» and in voluntary matters it comes only for affirmation.",
      "d": "«وَلِیّ» means supporter, friend. And «مَوَالِی» one meaning is the heir of inheritance. And «وَلَآء» means the inheritance of a freed slave. And the right of guardianship. And «اَوۡلٰی» means more worthy. More suitable. More deserving. It comes for voluntary matters. And comes only for affirmation. And it is stronger than «یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ» (Muf). Only this form of it is used. And its connection will come with «ب». And its meaning will be: he is worthy of it, he is more suitable or deserving.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لَنَحۡنُ اَعۡلَمُ بِالَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِہَا صِلِیًّا» (19:70)\nTranslation: Then We are most knowing of those who are most worthy of it for burning.\nIn another place, Allah the Exalted states:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (33:6)\nTranslation: The Prophet is more worthy of the believers than themselves.\nAnd if the connection of «اَوۡلٰی» is with «ل» then this word becomes of reproach, condemnation and admonition. Meaning destruction, ruin etc.\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«اَوۡلٰی لَکَ فَاَوۡلٰی» (75:35)\nTranslation: Woe to you, then woe to you!"
    },
    {
      "id": 2498,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy, To be deserving",
      "hw": "Worthy",
      "s": "«حُقَّ» means that doing so is obligatory and deserving for him.",
      "d": "«حَقَّ» means to be established. To be obligatory. And «حُقَّ اَنۡ یَّفۡعَلَ کَذَا» means that doing so is obligatory and deserving for him (Munjad). That is, this was his right that he should do so. Its usage is only in the affirmative.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡشَقَّتۡ وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84:1-2)\nTranslation: When the sky has split open and has listened to its Lord and was obligated."
    }
  ],
  "548": [
    {
      "id": 2500,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To wrap, To be wrapped",
      "hw": "To wrap",
      "s": "«لَفَّ» means to place one thing on another and merge them together.",
      "d": "«لَفَّ» means to merge one thing with another and to blend them together (Muf). To layer one thing. Then to layer another thing on top of it and merge. Then after that to layer the third layer on top of it (M, L).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ جِئۡنَا بِکُمۡ لَفِیۡفًا» (17:104)\nTranslation: Then when the promise of the Hereafter comes, We will bring you as a mixed gathering.\nAnd for being wrapped, «اِلۡتَفَّ» will be used. Meaning one thing sticking to another thing.\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«وَ الۡتَفَّتِ السَّاقُ بِالسَّاقِ ؕ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ یَوۡمَئِذِ ۣ الۡمَسَاقُ» (75:29-30)\nTranslation: And the leg will be wrapped around the leg. To your Lord that Day will be the procession."
    },
    {
      "id": 2501,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To wrap, To be wrapped",
      "hw": "To wrap",
      "s": "«کَوَّرَ» means to wrap in a circle and to gather together.",
      "d": "«کَوَّرَ» means to wrap something like a turban and to rotate it up and down. And «اِکۡتِیَارُ الْفَرَسِ» means the horse rotating its tail (Muf). And for wrapping like a turban, «لَفَّ» is also used. They say «لَفَفْتُ عِمَامَتِیۡ عَلٰی رَاۡسِیۡ» meaning I wrapped my turban on my head. This is from the aspect that one layer is joined on another layer. And for wrapping a turban, the word «کَوَّرَ» is stronger. Because in «کَوَّرَ» the concept of gathering and circularity both are present which are found in a turban.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«یُکَوِّرُ الَّیۡلَ عَلَی النَّہَارِ وَ یُکَوِّرُ النَّہَارَ عَلَی الَّیۡلِ» (39:5)\nTranslation: He wraps the night over the day and wraps the day over the night.\nIn another place, Allah the Exalted states:\n«اِذَا الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» (81:1)\nTranslation: When the sun is wrapped up."
    }
  ],
  "549": [
    {
      "id": 2502,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To hang, To be hung",
      "hw": "To hang",
      "s": "«اَدۡلٰی» means to hang something slowly and gently.",
      "d": "«دَلٰی» means something to approach with ease and gentleness (M, L). «دَلَاہُ» means to treat someone with gentleness and leniency. And «دَلۡو» means to lower and pull up an empty bucket into a well. And «اَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» means he lowered his bucket into the well to fill it with water.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12:19)\nTranslation: And a caravan came and they sent their water drawer, so he lowered his bucket.\n«تَدَلّٰی» means to hang down by oneself with ease and gentleness. They say «تَدَلَّی الثَّمَرُ مِنَ الشَّجَرِ» the fruit of the tree hung down (Munjad).\nFor example, Allah the Exalted states:\n«ثُمَّ دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی» (53:8)\nTranslation: Then he approached and hung down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2503,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To hang, To be hung",
      "hw": "To hang",
      "s": "«عَلَّقَ» means to keep something hanging and entangled.",
      "d": "«عَلِقَ» means to get entangled in something. They say «عَلِقَ الصَّیۡدُ فِی الْجُعَالَۃِ» meaning the game got entangled in the net. And «عَلَّقَ» means to hang. To entangle. And «عَلَقٌ» means a hanging thing.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ فَتَذَرُوۡہَا کَالۡمُعَلَّقَۃِ» (4:129)\nTranslation: So do not incline completely, leaving her as if hanging."
    }
  ],
  "550": [
    {
      "id": 2506,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To consider, To regard",
      "hw": "To consider",
      "s": "The word «رَقِبَ» is used only for keeping a close watch or paying attention with reluctance to something.",
      "d": "«رَقِبَ» means to keep an eye on someone's neck. To keep strict watch (Muf). And meaning to supervise. To guard. To wait (Munjad). To observe.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9:10)\nTranslation: They do not observe toward a believer any pact of kinship or covenant."
    },
    {
      "id": 2507,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To consider, To regard",
      "hw": "To consider",
      "s": "«رَعٰی» means to protect something properly and to take care of it.",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means to protect something properly and to take care of it (Muf). To fulfill a covenant or responsibility and to take care of it. And «رَاعِیۡ» means a shepherd who is entrusted with the protection of his flock. And meaning to protect something and to make arrangements to ward off external dangers. Its opposite is «اِہۡمَالُ». That is, the grazing of a flock without a shepherd (F L 15).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23:8)\nTranslation: And they who are to their trusts and their promises attentive."
    }
  ],
  "551": [
    {
      "id": 2508,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«جُنۡد» means a corps of recruited armed armies.",
      "d": "«جُنۡد» is used for military army and is a well-known word whose usage is general. «جُنۡدِیّ» means soldier. And «جَنَّدَ» means to recruit in the army (Munjad). Its plural is «جُنُوۡد». Besides «جُنۡد», another general word for army is «جَیۡش» whose plural is «جُیُوۡش». Its usage has not come in the Quran. And another word is «عَسۡکَر» whose plural is «عَسَاکِر». This is also not in the Quran. «عَسَاکِر» and «جُیُوۡش» are generally called those armies that start gathering from different sides upon the declaration of Jihad, whether they have fighting equipment or not. And «جُنۡد» is called only an armed army.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ» (2:249)\nTranslation: So when Saul went forth with the soldiers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2509,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«فَوۡج» means a group that passes quickly.",
      "d": "«فَوۡج» means a group that passes quickly. A military contingent (Muf). Its plural is «اَفۡوَاج». And it is called a group larger than «طَآئِفَۃ» (F L 205). But in the Quran this word has generally come in the meaning of 'a group'. It has not come in the meaning of a military contingent. So the concept that is generated today from the word army, this meaning does not emerge from the Quran.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ مِنۡ کُلِّ اُمَّۃٍ فَوۡجًا مِّمَّنۡ یُّکَذِّبُ بِاٰیٰتِنَا» (27:83)\nTranslation: And the Day We will gather from every nation a company of those who denied Our signs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2510,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«حِزۡب» means party. Political faction.",
      "d": "«حِزۡب» means group. Party. A band. A group of like-minded people. And «اَحۡزَاب» are those people whose hearts and deeds are compatible even if they do not meet. And «حَازَبَ» means to enter a party. To help. To strengthen. And «حَزَّبَ» means to gather a people by making them into groups (Munjad). And «حِزۡب» means that group in which hardness and severity are found (Muf). And «حِزۡب» actually means a political party. And according to the Quran there are only two major parties: one Hizbullah (Party of Allah), the other Hizbush-Shaytan (Party of Satan). In which the confrontation continues all the time. And Hizbush-Shaytan is then divided into many small parties (i.e., groups). Like at the occasion of the Trench, the disbelievers' several parties (groups) joined together and came to confront. Also Hizb means people gathering under one flag (M, Q).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ لَمۡ یَذۡہَبُوۡا ۚ وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتِ الۡاَحۡزَابُ یَوَدُّوۡا لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ بَادُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَعۡرَابِ یَسۡاَلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَنۡۢبَآئِکُمۡ» (33:20)\nTranslation: They think the companies have not [yet] gone. And if the companies should come, they would wish they were among the bedouins, asking for your news."
    },
    {
      "id": 2511,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«فِئَۃ» means such a fighting group whose members cooperate with each other.",
      "d": "«فَاَیَ الرَّاْسَ فُلَانٌ» means to split someone's head with a sword (Munjid). «فِئَۃ» means such a fighting group whose members maintain contact for mutual cooperation (Muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» (2/249)\nTranslation: How often has a small group overcome a large group by Allah's permission."
    },
    {
      "id": 2512,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«نَفِیْر» means people departing for a campaign or war.",
      "d": "«نَفَرَ» means to depart for war or campaign. «نَفِیْر» has two meanings: (1) People departing for battle (2) A group of less than ten people (Munjid)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2513,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Army, Host",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "«ثُبَاتٍ» A small contingent of brave horsemen.",
      "d": "«ثُبَاتٍ» means such brave horsemen whose attacks never miss (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Take your precautions and go forth in detachments or go forth all together."
    }
  ],
  "552": [
    {
      "id": 2514,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood, Firewood",
      "hw": "Wood",
      "s": "«حَطَبَ» Wood only suitable for burning.",
      "d": "«حَطَبَ» Wood only suitable for burning. Firewood (M, L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ» (111/4)\nTranslation: And his wife too, the carrier of firewood."
    },
    {
      "id": 2515,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood, Firewood",
      "hw": "Wood",
      "s": "«خَشَبَ» Wood useful for construction.",
      "d": "«خَشَبَ» Wood that is useful. Wood usable in construction. According to Ibn al-Faris, hard and thick wood. Plural is «خُشُب» (TIMBER) (M, L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ» (63/4)\nTranslation: As if they are propped-up logs of wood."
    }
  ],
  "650": [
    {
      "id": 2979,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level, to flatten",
      "hw": "Level",
      "s": "«سَطَحَ» To spread out and make level.",
      "d": "«سَطَحَ» has two basic meanings: (1) To spread or lay out (2) Then to make it level. And «سَطَحَ الْبَیْت» means to level the roof of a house. And «مِسْطَحْ» means a tool or instrument for leveling. And «سَطَح» means the upper part of a flat roof (Munjid). According to Imam Raghib, «اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20)\nTranslation: And do they not look at the earth how it is spread out?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2980,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level, to flatten",
      "hw": "Level",
      "s": "«دَکَّ» To crush and level to the ground.",
      "d": "«دَکَّ» has two basic meanings: (1) To crush (2) Then to level it (M, L). That is, to crush something and level it to the ground (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ ہٰذَا رَحۡمَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّیۡ ۚ فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ جَعَلَہٗ دَکَّآءَ ۚ » (18/98)\nTranslation: Dhul-Qarnain said: This is a mercy from my Lord. But when the promise of my Lord comes, He will make it level to the ground."
    },
    {
      "id": 2981,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level, to flatten",
      "hw": "Level",
      "s": "«مَرَّدَ» To make level and smooth.",
      "d": "«مَرِدَ الْغُلَام» means a boy becoming beardless. And «مَرَّدَ الْغُصْن» means to strip leaves from a branch. And «مَرَّدَ الْبَنَاء» means to make a building level and smooth (Muf, Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ اِنَّہٗ صَرۡحٌ مُّمَرَّدٌ مِّنۡ قَوَارِیۡرَ» (27/44)\nTranslation: Solomon said: This is a palace made level with glass."
    }
  ],
  "651": [
    {
      "id": 2982,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Forever, always",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«سَرْمَد» For something to remain in one state forever without any change or difference.",
      "d": "«سَرْمَد» means eternal, perpetual, forever (Muf). «سَرْمَدِیّ» means that which has neither beginning nor end (Munjid). For something to always remain in one state without any change or alteration (FQ L 95)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمُ الَّیۡلَ سَرۡمَدًا اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِضِیَآءٍ» (28/71)\nTranslation: Say: Have you considered if Allah should make the night perpetual for you until the Day of Resurrection, what deity other than Allah could bring you light?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2984,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«خَلَدَ» To remain in one state without change for a long period.",
      "d": "The word «خَلَدَ» is not for eternity but for something remaining without change from its beginning for a long period. Because this word comes with «اَبَد» for emphasis, and where only a long period is intended, only «خَلَدَ» is used without «اَبَدَا».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ فِیۡ نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا» (98/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieve from the People of the Scripture and the polytheists will be in the fire of Hell, abiding therein forever.\nAnd in the same surah where the reward of believers is mentioned:\nAllah Almighty says:\n«جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَاۤ اَبَدًا» (98/8)\nTranslation: Their reward with their Lord will be gardens of perpetual residence beneath which rivers flow, wherein they will abide forever and ever.\nAnd «اَخْلَدَ» and «خَلَّدَ» both are used for something remaining in one state for a long period.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَحۡسَبُ اَنَّ مَالَہٗۤ اَخۡلَدَہٗ» (104/3)\nTranslation: He thinks that his wealth will make him live forever.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17)\nTranslation: There will circulate among them immortal youths."
    },
    {
      "id": 2985,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«وَصَبَ» In this there is also permanence (eternity) along with expansiveness and firmness.",
      "d": "«وَصَبَ» According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is merely the permanence of something in one state (M, L). And according to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» (F L 48) meaning severity of pain. And according to the author of Munjid, «اَلْوَاصِب» means a desert stretched far. And «وَصَبَ» means to be permanent and firm. And «دَائِمُ الْمَرِیْض» to be permanently ill (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ وَّاصِبٌ» (37/9)\nTranslation: And for them is a perpetual punishment.\nSee, here in «وَاصِبٌ» three meanings are found: permanence, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع», and expansiveness. But later this word left the meaning of «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» and started being used only for severity or firmness and expansiveness and permanence.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَہُ الدِّیۡنُ وَاصِبًا» (16/52)\nTranslation: And to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and to Him is [due] worship constantly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2987,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمَرَّ» To remain in one state or one way from the beginning.",
      "d": "«مَرَّ» means to pass, to go, to pass by something (Muf, Munjid). And «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to remain in one state or way. To continue forever (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54/2)\nTranslation: But if they see a sign, they turn away and say: Continuous magic.\nMagic that has been going on from before (Usmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2988,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«دَامَ» To remain forever, to stay established, to be permanent.",
      "d": "«دَوَام» means tranquility. And «مَاءَ الدَّائِم» means stagnant water in which there is no movement. And «دَامَ الشَّیء» means something remaining in one state without change for a long period (Muf). And دوام means permanence. This verb is sometimes conditional with another state. That is, as long as this state remains, it will remain. At that time the particle «مَا» enters it and «مَا دَامَ» means 'as long as'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰمُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَنۡ نَّدۡخُلَہَاۤ اَبَدًا مَّا دَامُوۡا فِیۡہَا» (5/24)\nTranslation: They said: O Moses, indeed we will not enter it ever as long as they are therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 2989,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«زَالَ» To vanish, to depart. And زوال means to decline. This word with «لَا» and «مَا» negative gives the meaning of permanence.",
      "d": "«زَالَ» means to vanish, to depart. And زوال means to decline. This word with «لَا» and «مَا» negative gives the meaning of permanence and in these meanings it is always used with «لَا» and «مَا» (Muf). And it comes for temporal capacity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تَزَالُ تَطَّلِعُ عَلٰی خَآئِنَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (5/13)\nTranslation: And you will continue to observe treachery from them except a few of them.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«فَمَا زَالَتۡ تِّلۡکَ دَعۡوٰىہُمۡ حَتّٰی جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ حَصِیۡدًا خٰمِدِیۡنَ» (21/15)\nTranslation: And that was their [false] claim until We made them [like] a harvest [mowed down], extinguished [like a fire]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2990,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«اَبْرَحَ» Only in present tense with «لَا» and «لَنْ» negative and conditional with «حَتّٰی». Comes for spatial capacity.",
      "d": "The opposite of «بَرَحَ» is «بَرَزَ». And «بَرَزَ» means to come out into the open field. And «بَرَحَ» means to leave the open field (Muf). Only present tense is used. When the negative word «لَا» or «لَنْ» comes with it, it is used for spatial capacity. And it is always conditional with «حَتّٰی».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَالَ مُوۡسٰی لِفَتٰىہُ لَاۤ اَبۡرَحُ حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ» (18/60)\nTranslation: And when Moses said to his servant: I will not cease until I reach the junction of the two seas.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نَّبۡرَحَ عَلَیۡہِ عٰکِفِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یَرۡجِعَ اِلَیۡنَا مُوۡسٰی» (20/91)\nTranslation: They said: We will never cease remaining devoted to it until Moses returns to us.\nNote: (Present tense verb: A verb in which an action is being done in present or future time, e.g., comes, goes, does)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2991,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To live forever, to remain",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from some work. And when «لَا» and «مَا» negative enter it, it gives the meaning of continuously doing some work.",
      "d": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from some work. When «لَا» and «مَا» negative enter it, it gives the meaning of continuously doing some work. They say «مَا فَتَاَ یَفْعَلُ ذٰلک» - He always did this. Generally conditional with «حَتّٰی». Only past and present tense are used (Munjid). Comes for temporal capacity. This word appears once in the Quran but there also «لَا» is hidden (Jalalayn & Jami al-Bayan)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: They said: By Allah! You will not cease remembering Joseph until you become fatally ill or become of those who perish."
    }
  ],
  "652": [
    {
      "id": 2992,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To laugh",
      "hw": "Laugh",
      "s": "«ضَحِکَ» To laugh with voice opening the mouth so that teeth become visible.",
      "d": "«ضَحِکَ» To laugh with voice opening the mouth so that teeth become visible (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ امۡرَاَتُہٗ قَآئِمَۃٌ فَضَحِکَتۡ فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ» (11/71)\nTranslation: And his wife was standing, so she laughed. Then We gave her good tidings of Isaac."
    },
    {
      "id": 2993,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To laugh",
      "hw": "Laugh",
      "s": "«تَبَسَّمَ» means to smile.",
      "d": "«بَسَمَ» and «تَبَسَّمَ» mean to smile (Munjid). To laugh a little without voice so that signs of happiness become visible.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَتَبَسَّمَ ضَاحِکًا مِّنۡ قَوۡلِہَا» (27/19)\nTranslation: So Solomon smiled, laughing at her words."
    }
  ],
  "653": [
    {
      "id": 2994,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رِیْح» means wind.",
      "d": "«رِیْح, رَوْح» is a well-known word for wind. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is wind and to move (M, L). Although this word is used in the Quran in broader meanings. For example:\n(1) «رِیْح» meaning wind in well-known sense that moves (F L 172)\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If Allah wills, He stills the wind.\n(2) «رِیْح» meaning scent or fragrance.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ» (12/94)\nTranslation: Indeed, I find the scent of Joseph.\n(3) «رِیْح» meaning awe and prestige.\nFor example, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا تَنَازَعُوۡا فَتَفۡشَلُوۡا وَ تَذۡہَبَ رِیۡحُکُمۡ» (8/46)\nTranslation: And do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your wind departs.\nAnd the plural of «رِیْح» is «رِیَاح». When the word «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیَاح» comes, it means winds of mercy. And if «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیح» is mentioned meaning singular form, it means wind of punishment (Muf). Accordingly, its separate classification is made."
    },
    {
      "id": 2995,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رَوْح» meaning mercy. Continuous wave of Allah's favors and bounties.",
      "d": "«رَوْح» meaning breeze, mercy, happiness, comfort, help. And «یَوْمٌ رَوْحٌ» means a pleasant day (Munjid). And according to Imam Raghib, «رُوْح» and «رَوْح» are originally one. And «رُوْح» is applied to breath. And «اَرَاحَ الْاِنْسَان» means a person's breathing. And obtaining comfort (Muf). Reflecting on the various meanings of «رُوْح», it is known that its meaning is a continuously flowing wave of Allah's favors and bounties that becomes a cause of comfort and ease for man.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَا تَایۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنَّہٗ لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (12/87)\nTranslation: Do not despair of the mercy of Allah. Indeed, no one despairs of the mercy of Allah except the disbelieving people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2996,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رَیْحَان» Fragrant flowers, plants, crops.",
      "d": "«رَیْحَان» means every fragrant plant. Sustenance, livelihood (Munjid). And «رَائِحَۃ» means fragrant scent. And «رَیْحَانَۃ» means bouquet of flowers (Munjid). Reflecting on these meanings, it is known that if «رَیْحَان» means sustenance or food items obtained from crops, then it refers to things whose scent and fragrance is pleasant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَرَوۡحٌ وَّ رَیۡحَانٌ ۬ ۙ وَّ جَنَّتُ نَعِیۡمٍ» (56/89)\nTranslation: Then [for him is] rest and bounty and a garden of pleasure.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ الۡحَبُّ ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ» (55/12)\nTranslation: And the grain having husks and scented plants."
    },
    {
      "id": 2997,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«مُبَشِّرَات» Winds giving good tidings of rain.",
      "d": "«مُبَشِّرَات» Winds giving good tidings of descending mercy or rain. Moist and pleasant wind before rain (F L 254)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مِنۡ اٰیٰتِہٖۤ اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ الرِّیَاحَ مُبَشِّرٰتٍ وَّ لِیُذِیۡقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ رَّحۡمَتِہٖ» (30/46)\nTranslation: And of His signs is that He sends the winds as bringers of good tidings and to let you taste His mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2998,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«لَوَاقِح» Pregnant winds. Winds that carry the burden of water before raining.",
      "d": "«لَوَاقِح» is plural of «لَاقِحَہ, لَقِحَ» meaning pregnant wind. And this burden can be of two types: (1) The burden of water that winds carry before raining (2) The burden of male tree's seed (i.e., seed, pit, grain or semen) that they go and deposit on female tree (M L). In the Quran, this word is used only in the first meaning.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22)\nTranslation: And We have sent the fertilizing winds and sent down water from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2999,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«عَاصِف» Storm that blows away straw and twigs.",
      "d": "«عَصْف» means straw, chaff, dry vegetation that breaks into pieces (Muf). And «عَاصِفَۃ» is called that strong wind or storm that blows away straw or similar things.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا کُنۡتُمۡ فِی الۡفُلۡکِ ۚ وَ جَرَیۡنَ بِہِمۡ بِرِیۡحٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ وَّ فَرِحُوۡا بِہَا جَآءَتۡہَا رِیۡحٌ عَاصِفٌ وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10/22)\nTranslation: Until when you are in ships and they sail with them in a good wind and they rejoice therein, there comes upon it a storm wind and the waves come upon them from everywhere and they assume that they are surrounded."
    },
    {
      "id": 3000,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«حَاصِبٌ» Storm that blows away stones and pebbles.",
      "d": "«حَصَب» means stones and pebbles. And «حاصِبَۃ» is called that strong storm that blows away stones and pebbles (F L 253). And «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْس» means a horse running so fast that pebbles fly from its hooves into the air (M, Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَفَاَمِنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ یَّخۡسِفَ بِکُمۡ جَانِبَ الۡبَرِّ اَوۡ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (17/68)\nTranslation: Then do you feel secure that He will not cause [part of] the land to swallow you or send against you a storm of stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3001,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«قَاصِف» Storm of wind that breaks trees.",
      "d": "«قَصَفَ» means to break, to shatter (M, L). And «قَاصِف» is that fierce and strong wind that breaks trees etc. (Muf). Storm of wind, thunderous wind.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَیُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ قَاصِفًا مِّنَ الرِّیۡحِ فَیُغۡرِقَکُمۡ بِمَا کَفَرۡتُمۡ» (17/69)\nTranslation: Then He would send against you a tempest of wind and drown you for your disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 3002,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«سَمُوْم» Hot wind. Extremely hot wind that scorches.",
      "d": "«سَمُوْم» Extremely hot wind. Hot wind that scorches bodies (F L 254)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» (52/27)\nTranslation: So Allah conferred favor upon us and protected us from the punishment of the Scorching Wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 3003,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«اِعْصَار» Whirlwind. Dust-filled strong wind that goes straight to the sky.",
      "d": "«اِعْصَار» That fierce and strong wind that whirls in the sky (Muf). And meaning dust-filled strong wind that goes straight to the sky (F L 253). Wind whirlwind.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Then a whirlwind containing fire struck it and it burned."
    },
    {
      "id": 3004,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«حُسْبَان» Any punishment of wind sufficient to settle accounts.",
      "d": "«حَسَبَ» means to calculate, to count. And «حُسْبَان» means such punishment that is sufficient to settle accounts. And the meaning of «حُسْبَان» has been given differently by various lexicographers. However, this punishment is related to wind punishment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ صَعِیۡدًا زَلَقًا» (18/40)\nTranslation: And send upon it a calamity from the sky so that it becomes a smooth ground."
    },
    {
      "id": 3005,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» meaning cold gust. Only one wave of extremely cold wind.",
      "d": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» meaning cold gust. Like air comes out once from a bellows. Vapor, puff. Wave of intense cold wind. And its opposite is «لَفْحَۃٌ» meaning puff of hot wind (F L 29)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And if a puff of the punishment of your Lord were to touch them.\nNote: (Bellows: A leather bag or metal nozzle etc. into which air is pumped to blow a fire)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3007,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» Wind that is devoid of good and has only harm.",
      "d": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» meaning wind that neither raises rain or clouds nor is for sowing seeds (F L 254). Wind devoid of good. That which causes harm. And its opposite is «لَا قِحَہ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ فِیۡ عَادٍ اِذۡ اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمُ الرِّیۡحَ الۡعَقِیۡمَ» (51/41)\nTranslation: And in 'Aad [was a sign], when We sent against them the barren wind."
    }
  ],
  "553": [
    {
      "id": 2516,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To write",
      "hw": "To write",
      "s": "«خَطَّ» means to draw lines, to make marks and to extend them in length.",
      "d": "«خَطَّ» means to draw lines. To make marks and to extend them in length. «مُخَلَّط» means striped cloth and «خَطَّاط» means one who writes a lot (Munjid). So «خَطَّ» implies writing something in the direction of length only. Whatever the writing may be.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ تَتۡلُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہٖ مِنۡ کِتٰبٍ وَّ لَا تَخُطُّہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِکَ» (29/48)\nTranslation: Before this, you could not recite any book, nor could you write it with your right hand."
    },
    {
      "id": 2517,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To write",
      "hw": "To write",
      "s": "«سَطَرَ» means to write by making a line, to write in one line.",
      "d": "«سَطَرٌ» means line. Row. Line of writing (Munjid) and «سَطَرَ» means to make lines. To write by making lines (rows). To write straight lines.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡقَلَمِ وَ مَا یَسۡطُرُوۡنَ» (68/1)\nTranslation: By the pen, and by what they write."
    },
    {
      "id": 2518,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To write",
      "hw": "To write",
      "s": "«رَقَم» to write so that the writing is clear and bold.",
      "d": "«رَقَم» means to put vowel marks (Zabar, Zer, Pesh) and dots on a book. To write. To make designs (on cloth). And «مِرْقَمُ» means the tool for making designs and «مَرْقُوم» means clearly written (Munjid) and «رَقَمَ» means to write in a way that is clear and in bold script (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«کِتٰبٌ مَّرۡقُوۡمٌ یَّشۡہَدُہُ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (83/20,21)\nTranslation: It is a written book witnessed by those brought near."
    },
    {
      "id": 2519,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To write",
      "hw": "To write",
      "s": "«کَتَبَ» such writing that fully conveys its meaning.",
      "d": "«کَتَبَ» such writing that is complete in expressing its meaning (M L)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282)\nTranslation: O you who believe! When you contract a debt for a fixed period, write it down."
    }
  ],
  "554": [
    {
      "id": 2520,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To dictate",
      "hw": "To dictate",
      "s": "«اِسْتَنْسَخَ» to give something to someone to copy. To dictate.",
      "d": "«نَسْخُ الْکِتَاب» means to copy a book and «نسخہ» is the book from which a copy is made. The copied book and «اِسْتَنْسَخَ» means to ask to write or to copy (Munjid). To copy a book word for word.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (45/29)\nTranslation: This is Our Book which speaks against you with truth. We used to have written whatever you used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 2522,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To dictate",
      "hw": "To dictate",
      "s": "«اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally used for false and forged copying.",
      "d": "«اِکْتَتَبَ» means to write. To dictate. To have something written. To request to write (Munjid). The word «اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally used for false and forged writing (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ  بُکۡرَۃً   وَّ اَصِیۡلًا» (25/5)\nTranslation: And they say: 'Tales of the ancients which he has got copied, and they are dictated to him morning and evening.'"
    }
  ],
  "555": [
    {
      "id": 2523,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Writer",
      "hw": "Writer",
      "s": "«کَاتِب» is general for every person who writes anything, he is called a writer.",
      "d": "«کَاتِب» every person who writes anything is a writer. This word is well-known and its usage is general.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ» (2/283)\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and find no scribe, then there should be a pledge taken into possession."
    },
    {
      "id": 2524,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Writer",
      "hw": "Writer",
      "s": "«سَفَرَۃ» means those who write blessed and pure writings.",
      "d": "«سَفَرَۃ» is the plural of «سَافِر». «اَلسِّفْر» means the book that uncovers truths (M L) and «اَسْفَار» means explanations and interpretations of the Torah. And «سَافِر» is a person who writes or reads such writing. The angels who write the Book of Deeds. Those who write divine writings.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِیۡ  صُحُفٍ مُّکَرَّمَۃٍ مَّرۡفُوۡعَۃٍ  مُّطَہَّرَۃٍۭ بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ  بَرَرَۃٍ» (80/13-16)\nTranslation: In honored pages, exalted and purified, in the hands of noble and virtuous scribes."
    }
  ],
  "556": [
    {
      "id": 2525,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«تَتْرًا» successive. Continuous one after another without any gap in between.",
      "d": "«تَتْرًا» means one after another coming in such a way that there is no gap in between (Munjid). Tawatur and Mutawatir are well-known words. That is, several can be at one time, but it cannot be that at some time there are none at all.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا رُسُلَنَا تَتۡرَا» (23/44)\nTranslation: Then We sent Our messengers one after another."
    },
    {
      "id": 2526,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«عَلٰی فَتْرَۃٍ» the speed of something decreasing while working and weakness occurring in it.",
      "d": "«فَتَرَ» means the speed of something decreasing while working and weakness (i.e., weakness) occurring in it. (M L Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ قَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ  رَسُوۡلُنَا یُبَیِّنُ لَکُمۡ عَلٰی  فَتۡرَۃٍ  مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ» (5/19)\nTranslation: O People of the Book! Our Messenger has come to you at a time when the succession of messengers had ceased. He explains to you (the divine commandments)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2527,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«حُسُوْمًا» continuous calamity and ill-fortune that erases name and trace.",
      "d": "«حَسَمَ» means to efface the mark of something and to wipe it out. And «حَسْمُ الدَّاءِ» means to continuously cauterize and erase the wound and its mark. And «نَاَلَہٗ حُسُوْمًا» means ill-fortune erased his name and trace (Muf) and «حَسَمَ» means to cut from the root. «حَسَمَ الْعِرْق» means to cut the vein and cauterize it so that blood stops. And «حُسُوْم» means ill-omened. Unlucky (Munjid). So in «حُسُوْم» three things are conceived: (1) Affliction and bad luck (2) Continuity (3) Eradication (i.e., to erase and demolish).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ  فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ . سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبۡعَ  لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/6,7)\nTranslation: And as for 'Aad, they were destroyed by a furious wind. He made it rage against them for seven nights and eight days continuously. You would have seen the people lying dead therein.\nIn this verse, the word «حُسُوْم» is used in all three meanings."
    },
    {
      "id": 2528,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«رَدِفَ» one after another while they are also helpers of each other.",
      "d": "«رَدِفَ» means to ride behind someone. And «اَرْدَفَ» means to make someone ride behind oneself. To come one after another. To be consecutive. And «تَرَادَفَ» to help each other. To ride behind each other (Munjid) and «اِرْدَافُ الْمُلُوْک» means successors of kings (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ اَنِّیۡ مُمِدُّکُمۡ بِاَلۡفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  مُرۡدِفِیۡنَ» (8/9)\nTranslation: When you were crying for help from your Lord, so He answered you: 'I am helping you with a thousand angels coming consecutively.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2529,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«دَاَبَ» to walk continuously with effort and hardship.",
      "d": "«دَاَبَ» means to continuously do some work with effort and hardship (Munjid). To walk continuously and without stopping. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ» (14/33)\nTranslation: And He has made the sun and the moon subservient to you. Both are constantly working."
    },
    {
      "id": 2530,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«مُتَتَابِع» two similar things coming one after another without a third thing coming between them.",
      "d": "«مُتَتَابِع» means two things coming one after another in such a way that no third thing comes between them (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ  یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ شَہۡرَیۡنِ مُتَتَابِعَیۡنِ» (4/92)\nTranslation: So whoever finds not (the means) should fast two consecutive months."
    },
    {
      "id": 2531,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous. Consecutive",
      "hw": "Continuous",
      "s": "«وَصَّلَ» to join one thing to another in such a way that the possibility of a gap is eliminated.",
      "d": "«وَصَلَ» means to join and to connect (M L). That is, to join something in such a way that it becomes connected. And in «وَصَّلَ» there is intensity. And «وَاصِلُ الشَّیء» or «وَاصِلُ بِالشَّیء» means to do with continuity (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ وَصَّلۡنَا لَہُمُ الۡقَوۡلَ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (28/51)\nTranslation: And We have certainly conveyed to them the word in succession that perhaps they may be reminded."
    }
  ],
  "557": [
    {
      "id": 2532,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«رَجَعَ» a thing returning to its beginning.",
      "d": "«رَجَعَ» means a thing returning to its beginning or origin. Whether this thing is living or non-living, saying or doing. Also, whether the one returning has intention in this return or not (Muf). There is a famous saying «کُلُّ شَیْءٍ یَرْجِعْ اِلٰی اَصْلِہٖ» meaning 'Every thing returns to its origin.' So the usage of this word is general in every aspect.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ  اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ   ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَ  اِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» (2/156)\nTranslation: Who, when afflicted with calamity, say: 'Indeed we belong to Allah, and indeed to Him we will return.'\nAnd «اَرْجَعَ» means to turn back, to return something.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ تُرۡجَعُ  الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (2/210)\nTranslation: And all matters are returned to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2533,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«اٰبَ» a living being returning. Without intention or with intention.\n«اَوَّبَ» a living being returning frequently with its own intention.",
      "d": "«اٰبَ» This is more specific than «رَجَعَ». And it is used only for living beings. And «مَاٰب» means place of return. Returning place. Destination (Muf Munjid) and «اَیَاب» means to return, to go back or journey of return. «ذِھَاب و اِیَاب» means to go and to come back. In «اٰبَ» it is not necessary that the one returning has intention.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» (88/25,26)\nTranslation: Indeed, to Us is their return. Then indeed, upon Us is their account.\nAnd when this verb goes into the form of 'Thulathi Mazeed Feeh' such as «اٰوَبَ» and «اَوَّبَ» then in this case the intention of the one returning will also be involved. «اَوَّاب» means one who returns. One who turns frequently.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«فَاِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِلۡاَوَّابِیۡنَ غَفُوۡرًا» (17/25)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is Forgiving for those who turn back to Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2534,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«تَابَ» to turn back from sinful acts.",
      "d": "«تَابَ» means to turn back from sinful acts. To confess sins and make intention not to do them again. To repent (Muf). And if it is attributed to Allah, it means to accept repentance. To forgive sins or it comes in the meaning of being merciful.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ تَابُوۡا وَ اَصۡلَحُوۡا وَ بَیَّنُوۡا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَتُوۡبُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ۚ وَ اَنَا التَّوَّابُ الرَّحِیۡمُ» (2/160)\nTranslation: Except for those who repent and correct themselves and make clear - those I will accept their repentance, and I am the Accepting of repentance, the Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2535,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«اَنَاب» to return frequently.",
      "d": "«نَابَ اِلَیْہِ»: means to come to someone frequently. And «نَوْبَۃ» means turn. Time. Opportunity. Leisure and «اَنَاب» means to be deputy. To be substitute. And «اَنَابَ اِلَی اللہ» means to turn to Allah frequently and to return (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رَبَّنَا عَلَیۡکَ تَوَکَّلۡنَا وَ اِلَیۡکَ اَنَبۡنَا» (60/4)\nTranslation: Our Lord! Upon You we have relied, and to You we have turned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2536,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«بَاءَ» to return to a bad state.",
      "d": "«بَوْء» has two basic meanings: (1) To return and (2) To be equal (M L). That is, to return in such a state that the recompense of their deeds comes before them. This is generally used in bad meaning, i.e., to return from a good state to a bad state.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ بَآءُوۡ بِغَضَبٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ  ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِاٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ وَ یَقۡتُلُوۡنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ بِغَیۡرِ الۡحَقِّ» (2/61)\nTranslation: And they returned with anger from Allah. That is because they were disbelieving in the signs of Allah and killing the prophets without right.\nThat is, their state was such that they became deserving of Allah's anger."
    },
    {
      "id": 2538,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«صَدَرَ» to return satisfied from a watering place or well.",
      "d": "«صَدَرَ» to return satisfied from a watering place or well. And «اَصْدَر» means to return satisfied from water. They say «صَدَرَتِ الْاِبِلُ مِنَ الْمَاءِ» meaning the camels returned satisfied from water.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23)\nTranslation: The two women said, 'We do not water until the shepherds drive (their flocks) away.'\nAnd the opposite of «صَدَرَ» is «وَرَدَ». That is, to reach the watering place or well to drink water (Muf) and «وِرْدُ» means watering place and also comes in the meaning of thirsty. And «وَارِد» means the person who goes to the well or watering place to bring water.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)\nTranslation: And there came a caravan which sent their water drawer. He let down his bucket."
    },
    {
      "id": 2539,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«صَارَ» to return for the last time, to go back.",
      "d": "«صَیْر» has two basic things in its meaning: (1) Return (2) End (M L). See details under 'End'. Means to return for the last time, to go back or to return.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  تَصِیۡرُ الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (42/53)\nTranslation: Unquestionably, to Allah all matters are returned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2541,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«اِنْقَلَبَ» to turn or change state in such a way that it is completely opposite to the first.",
      "d": "«قَلَبَ» means to turn face or state. To make the upper part lower and the lower part upper. To make the outer part inner and the inner part outer. And «اِنْقَلَبَ» means to make such a change in one's state or face that is opposite to the first form. To turn upside down. To turn back. To turn (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَیَحۡلِفُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اِذَا انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (9/95)\nTranslation: They will swear by Allah to you when you return to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2542,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return. To turn back",
      "hw": "To return",
      "s": "«اَفَاضَ» to return with a flood. To come flowing.",
      "d": "«فَاضَ الْمَاءَ» means water to gush out from a place and flow. And «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاءَ» means to fill a vessel so full that water starts flowing from the top. From this 'Faydhan al-ma' a simile is made and this word is also applied to the crowd of people flowing like a flood (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199)\nTranslation: Then depart from where the people depart."
    }
  ],
  "558": [
    {
      "id": 2544,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Preserved Tablet and its various types",
      "hw": "Preserved Tablet",
      "s": "«لَوْح مَحْفُوْظ» The Preserved Tablet is the tablet on which the destiny of the entire universe (Divine Knowledge) is recorded. Allah grants from this knowledge to whom He wills and as much as He wills. The Preserved Tablet is protected from creature's interference. No one can steal from it nor make changes.",
      "d": "The literal meaning of «لَوْح مَحْفُوْظ» is only 'Preserved Tablet'. Its complete comprehension is beyond human understanding. However, from narrations it is known that it is a tablet or book in which all matters regarding the destiny of the universe are already written and there is no change in them. From Quranic verses, various names are revealed:\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَلۡ ہُوَ  قُرۡاٰنٌ  مَّجِیۡدٌ فِیۡ  لَوۡحٍ مَّحۡفُوۡظٍ» (85/21,22)\nTranslation: Nay, this is a glorious Quran. In a Preserved Tablet.\nFrom this it is known that the Holy Quran is taken from the Preserved Tablet itself."
    },
    {
      "id": 2545,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Preserved Tablet and its various types",
      "hw": "Preserved Tablet",
      "s": "«اُمُّ الْکِتَاب» refers to the Holy Quran because it is the source of all divine commands and words.",
      "d": "«اُمُّ الْکِتَاب» refers to the Holy Quran because it is the source of all divine commands and words.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنٰہُ  قُرۡءٰنًا عَرَبِیًّا  لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ وَ اِنَّہٗ  فِیۡۤ  اُمِّ الۡکِتٰبِ لَدَیۡنَا لَعَلِیٌّ حَکِیۡمٌ» (43/3,4)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have made it an Arabic Quran that you might understand. And indeed, it is in the Mother of the Book with Us, exalted and full of wisdom.\nBy saying that it is in Umm al-Kitab, an important truth is clarified that the books revealed to different prophets in different times, countries and nations from Allah Almighty - in all of them the same belief has been invited. The standard of good and evil is the same and the principles of ethics and civilization are identical. That is, the religion has been one. As for Shariah, regarding the change in Islamic rulings according to conditions and circumstances, Allah Almighty says:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ   ۚ ۖ وَ عِنۡدَہٗۤ   اُمُّ   الۡکِتٰبِ» (13/39)\nTranslation: Allah erases what He wills and confirms what He wills. And with Him is the Mother of the Book.\nFrom this verse it is known that the record of changes in Islamic rulings in different times is also present in this book."
    },
    {
      "id": 2546,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Preserved Tablet and its various types",
      "hw": "Preserved Tablet",
      "s": "«اِمَامٌ مُبِیْن» this is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that everything is already written in it.",
      "d": "«اِمَامٌ مُبِیْن» this is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that everything is already written in it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   اِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36/12)\nTranslation: And We have enumerated everything in a clear Imam (Preserved Tablet)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2547,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Preserved Tablet and its various types",
      "hw": "Preserved Tablet",
      "s": "«کِتَابٌ مَّکْنُوْن» this is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that no one except Allah knows the details of what is written in it.",
      "d": "«کِتَابٌ مَّکْنُوْن» this is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that no one except Allah knows the details of what is written in it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّہٗ   لَقُرۡاٰنٌ   کَرِیۡمٌ فِیۡ  کِتٰبٍ مَّکۡنُوۡنٍ» (56/77,78)\nTranslation: Indeed, it is a noble Quran. In a concealed Book.\nFrom this verse it is known that no one except Allah has knowledge of the details written in it, not even Jibreel (AS) who is the means of conveying revelation to the prophets."
    }
  ],
  "559": [
    {
      "id": 2548,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Slave girl. Slave",
      "hw": "Slave",
      "s": "«عَبْد» means slave.",
      "d": "«عَبْد» means servant. Slave. Servitude. Means to express humility and meekness. And the word «عَبَادَۃ» is stronger than «عَبُوْدِیَت» meaning to express extreme humility and meekness. And worship is only for Allah. Although all creation is Allah's 'Abd' i.e., servant and slave by compulsion. However, Allah Almighty calls that person «عَبْد» who becomes His sincere servant by his own choice. And this choice is only for humans and jinn. The plural of «عَبْد» is «عِبَاد» and also «عَبِیْد». And the second meaning of «عَبْد» is to become slave of something. It is also used metaphorically such as 'Abdud-Darham' and 'Abdud-Dinar' meaning slave or worshipper of wealth or 'Abdut-Taghut' and «عَبْد» also means someone's slave whether purchased, inherited or obtained as booty. And its opposite is «حُرّ» meaning free. And «عَبَّدَ» means to make someone else a slave (26/22)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» (2/178)\nTranslation: The free for the free, the slave for the slave, and the female for the female."
    },
    {
      "id": 2549,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Slave girl. Slave",
      "hw": "Slave",
      "s": "«اَمَۃ» means slave girl.",
      "d": "«اَمَۃ» This is the feminine of «عَبْد». Means slave girl. This word is also used in all the meanings in which «عَبْد» is used. And the plural of «اَمَۃ» is «اِمَاء».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَنۡکِحُوا الۡاَیَامٰی مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ مِنۡ عِبَادِکُمۡ وَ اِمَآئِکُمۡ» (24/32)\nTranslation: And marry the unmarried among you and the righteous among your male slaves and female slaves.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَاَمَۃٌ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٌ  خَیۡرٌ مِّنۡ مُّشۡرِکَۃٍ  وَّ لَوۡ اَعۡجَبَتۡکُمۡ» (2/221)\nTranslation: And a believing slave girl is better than a polytheist woman, even if she pleases you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2550,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Slave girl. Slave",
      "hw": "Slave",
      "s": "«رَقَبَۃ» slave or slave girl however obtained.",
      "d": "«رَقَبَۃ» means neck or the part behind it or the nape. And «رَقَبَ» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. The Arabs generally say «جُزْءُ اشَرْف» (the noblest part) and mean the whole by it. In this way «رَقَبَۃ» refers to a slave, because there is a noose of slavery around his neck. Its plural is «رِقَاب». (Muf Munjid) And the word «رَقَبَۃ» is used equally for both masculine and feminine i.e., slave or slave girl.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ ذَوِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ  وَ ابۡنَ السَّبِیۡلِ  ۙ وَ السَّآئِلِیۡنَ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And gives wealth, in spite of love for it, to relatives, orphans, the needy, the traveler, those who ask, and for freeing slaves."
    }
  ],
  "560": [
    {
      "id": 2552,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To take",
      "hw": "To take",
      "s": "«اَخَذَ» means to obtain something. To take into possession. To seize.",
      "d": "«اَخَذَ» means to obtain something. To take into possession. To seize (Muf). And its usage is both sensory (i.e., something perceived through one of the five senses) and metaphorical.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ النَّبِیّٖنَ» (3/81)\nTranslation: And when Allah took the covenant of the prophets.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ  اَخَذَ الۡاَلۡوَاحَ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger subsided in Moses, he took up the tablets."
    },
    {
      "id": 2553,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To take",
      "hw": "To take",
      "s": "«تَلَقّٰی» to go near something and take it.",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» means to meet. To encounter. And «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْء» means to meet. To receive (Munjid). So «تَلَقّٰی» means to go and meet and take something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَا یَحۡزُنُہُمُ الۡفَزَعُ الۡاَکۡبَرُ وَ تَتَلَقّٰہُمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ» (21/103)\nTranslation: The greatest terror will not grieve them, and the angels will receive them."
    }
  ],
  "561": [
    {
      "id": 2555,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To transact",
      "hw": "Transaction",
      "s": "«تَدَایَن» is used for hand-to-hand transaction.\nAnd «اَدَارَ» is used for credit transactions.",
      "d": "«دَیْن» means debt. Loan (see details under 'Loan') and «تَدَایَنَ» means to ask for loan from each other. To transact on credit (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282)\nTranslation: O you who believe! When you contract a debt for a fixed period, write it down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2556,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To transact",
      "hw": "Transaction",
      "s": "«اَدَارَ» means to rotate. To turn around.",
      "d": "«دَوْر ، دَارَ» means to revolve. To go around. And «اَدَارَہٗ» means to rotate. To turn around. And «اَدَارَ الشَّیْء» means to take and give something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ تِجَارَۃً حَاضِرَۃً  تُدِیۡرُوۡنَہَا بَیۡنَکُمۡ» (2/282)\nTranslation: Unless it is an immediate transaction which you conduct among yourselves."
    }
  ],
  "562": [
    {
      "id": 2557,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«ضَرَبَ» to hit someone with hand or something else.",
      "d": "«ضَرَبَ» generally its connection is with «ب» to hit someone with hand or something else. And after the connection «ب» the thing with which to hit is mentioned. That is, the instrument of hitting. The usage of this word for hitting is general (F L 188)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ» (2/60)\nTranslation: So We said, 'Strike with your staff the stone.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2558,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«وَکَزَ» to punch.",
      "d": "«وَکَزَ» to punch. And according to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, to hit the chest or side with palm or fist (F L 188)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَوَکَزَہٗ  مُوۡسٰی فَقَضٰی عَلَیۡہِ» (28/15)\nTranslation: So Moses struck him and finished him off."
    },
    {
      "id": 2559,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«صَکَّ» to slap on the face.",
      "d": "«صَکَّ» means two things colliding with each other with force and strength that sound is produced. «صَکَّ الْبَابَ» the doors colliding with each other (M L) and means to hit the face. To slap. To beat the face (F L 188)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29)\nTranslation: So she struck her face and said, 'An old woman, barren?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2560,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«دَعَّ» to push harshly.",
      "d": "«دَعَّ» to push harshly. To repel harshly (F L 188)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (107/2)\nTranslation: So that is the one who repels the orphan."
    },
    {
      "id": 2561,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«دَمَغَ» to hit on the head.",
      "d": "«دَمَغَ» means to hit someone on the brain or on the head (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«بَلۡ نَقۡذِفُ بِالۡحَقِّ عَلَی الۡبَاطِلِ فَیَدۡمَغُہٗ» (21/18)\nTranslation: Rather, We dash the truth upon falsehood, and it shatters its head."
    },
    {
      "id": 2562,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«رَجَمَ» to stone from a distance. To stone to death.",
      "d": "«رَجَمَ» to throw stones or pebbles at someone from a distance. And to kill someone by throwing stones or pebbles from a distance. To stone to death. Comes in both meanings. And is used both physically and metaphorically. «رَجْمًا بِالْغَیْب» (18/22) means to throw stones without seeing the target and also to speak on the basis of conjecture (M Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رَہۡطُکَ لَرَجَمۡنٰکَ» (11/91)\nTranslation: And if not for your clan, we would have stoned you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2563,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«وَقَذَ» to inflict severe blow with stick or stone.",
      "d": "«وَقَذَ» means to inflict severe blow with stick or stone from which one dies. And «وَقْذ» means severe blow (Muf) and «وَقَذَ» means to inflict fatal i.e., deadly blow (Munjid)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2564,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "To hit",
      "s": "«نَطَحَ» an animal to gore with horns.",
      "d": "«نَطَحَ» a bull to gore with horns. «تَنَاطَعَ الْکَبْشَان» rams butting each other. And «نَطِیْح» means gored. An animal that died from being gored (Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ وَ الۡمُتَرَدِّیَۃُ وَ النَّطِیۡحَۃُ» (5/3)\nTranslation: And that which is strangled, or beaten to death, or dies from a fall, or is gored to death."
    },
    {
      "id": 2566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«مَاتَ» means the soul separating from the body. General.",
      "d": "«مَاتَ» means death and its opposite is «حَیَات» meaning life. «مَاتَ» means the soul or power departing from a living being (M L). The soul separating from the body. To die. Whatever its form may be.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ مَاتُوۡا وَ ہُمۡ کُفَّارٌ» (2/161)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieve and die while they are disbelievers.\nAnd «اَمَات» means to give death to someone else. To end his life.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«ثُمَّ یُمِیۡتُکُمۡ ثُمَّ یُحۡیِیۡکُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِلَیۡہِ تُرۡجَعُوۡنَ» (2/28)\nTranslation: Then He will cause you to die, then He will give you life, then to Him you will be returned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«قَتَلَ» to kill someone unjustly.\nAnd «قَتَّل» to kill in a brutal manner.",
      "d": "«قَتَلَ» means for one living being to overpower another living being and end his life. And in the words of Ibn Faris, to kill someone in a state of humiliation (M L)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ  اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا  زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ  نَفۡسٍ» (18/74)\nTranslation: He said, 'Have you killed a pure soul for other than (having killed) a soul?'\nAnd «قَتَّلَ» means to kill someone by giving pain after pain and inflicting tortures.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ سَنُقَتِّلُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ نَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (7/127)\nTranslation: Pharaoh said, 'We will kill their sons and keep their women alive.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2568,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«ھَلَکَ» to perish, to die a helpless death, also used for non-living things.",
      "d": "«ھَلَکَ» means to perish (Munjid). Used for both living and non-living. And in the case of living beings, it means to die a helpless death. In the words of Ibn Faris «یَدُلُّ عَلٰی کَسْرٍ وَّ سَقُوْطٍ (M L)» to die a bad death. To die as a victim of an accident.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ  وَلَدٌ» (4/176)\nTranslation: If a man dies and has no child.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«کُلُّ  شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ  اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» (28/88)\nTranslation: Everything will perish except His Face.\nAnd «اَھْلَکَ» means to cause someone to die such a bad or helpless death. To destroy. To annihilate.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَہۡلَکَنِیَ  اللّٰہُ  وَ مَنۡ مَّعِیَ» (67/28)\nTranslation: Say, 'Have you considered: if Allah should destroy me and those with me.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2569,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«صَلَبَ» to kill by crucifixion.\n«صَلَّبَ» to crucify after inflicting torture.",
      "d": "«صَلَبَ» means to hang on a cross. Or to crucify. And 'Salib' refers to the wooden plank on which a criminal is crucified and killed.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» (4/157)\nTranslation: They neither killed him nor crucified him, but it was made to appear so to them.\nAnd «صَلَّبَ» means to hang someone upside down to inflict more pain or to inflict more pain while crucifying.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«فَلَاُقَطِّعَنَّ  اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلَکُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ وَّ لَاُصَلِّبَنَّکُمۡ فِیۡ جُذُوۡعِ النَّخۡلِ» (20/71)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said to the believing magicians) 'I will surely cut off your hands and your feet on opposite sides, and I will surely crucify you on the trunks of palm trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2570,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«ذَبَّحَ» to kill by inflicting pain at intervals.",
      "d": "«ذَبَحَ» means to sacrifice an animal according to Islamic law, to drain blood. And «ذَبَّحَ» means to slaughter by inflicting pain or to exaggerate in slaughtering (Munjid). And «ذَبَّحَ» and «قَتَّلَ» become synonymous in this respect.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُذَبِّحُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (28/4)\nTranslation: He would slaughter their sons and keep their women alive."
    },
    {
      "id": 2571,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«رَجَمَ» to stone to death. To kill by throwing stones.",
      "d": "«رَجَمَ» means to throw stones etc. from a distance or to kill by throwing stones. And 'Rajam' is one of the punishments in Islamic law which means that an adulterous married man or woman should be killed as punishment by throwing stones from a distance. To stone to death.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ تَنۡتَہِ لَاَرۡجُمَنَّکَ» (19/46)\nTranslation: (Azar said to Ibrahim) 'If you do not desist, I will surely stone you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2572,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«اِنْخَنَقَ» a living being dying by strangulation.",
      "d": "«خَنَقَ» means to strangle and 'Khinaq' refers to the rope with which one is strangled and 'Khunnaq' is the disease in which the throat constricts and breathing becomes difficult (Munjid) and «خَنَقَ» means to strangle severely until one dies (M Q) «مُنْخَنِقٌ» means an animal that dies due to strangulation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ» (5/3)\nTranslation: And that which is strangled, or beaten to death (all these are forbidden)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2573,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«تَوَفّٰی» to complete the life term. To take out the soul from the body. And this is only Allah's work or His angels'.",
      "d": "The word «وَفٰی» indicates the end and completion of something (M L) and «تَوَفّٰی» means to take out the soul from the body when the life term is completed. To take away. And this work belongs to Allah or His appointed angels. Therefore, in this meaning, it cannot be attributed to a human or any other living being.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ  بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (12/101)\nTranslation: (O Allah!) Cause me to die as a Muslim and join me with the righteous in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2574,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill. To die",
      "hw": "To kill",
      "s": "«شَھَادَت» to give one's life in the way of Allah.",
      "d": "«شَھِدَ» means to bear witness. Whether this testimony is eyewitness (i.e., seen with eyes) or from the heart. And «شَاھِدْ» and «شَھِیْد» both come in the meaning of witness. And the word «شَھِیْد» is also said for one who gives his life in the way of Allah for the sake of raising the word of truth. And in this respect, martyrdom is also giving one's life in the way of Allah because there is such firm belief in the Hereafter and reward and punishment that he presents his testimony by giving his life.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (4/69)\nTranslation: So those will be with those upon whom Allah has bestowed favor - of the prophets, the steadfast affirmers of truth, the martyrs and the righteous."
    }
  ],
  "563": [
    {
      "id": 2577,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and riches, to bestow",
      "hw": "Wealth",
      "s": "«رِزْق» every thing that is physical or spiritual food or its cause.",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «رِزْق» is sustenance or every thing that becomes a cause of human training and reform physically or spiritually (Muf). From a material perspective, its meaning is the thing that enters the stomach and becomes food. «رِزْق» also means destiny, portion. And «مَرْزُوْق» means fortunate (Munjid) and «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» means knowledge was granted to me. Then «رِزْق» is also said for every thing that becomes a cause of human's spiritual or physical food. In this respect, rain is also 'Rizq'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  رِزۡقُکُمۡ» (51/22)\nTranslation: Meaning your sustenance is in the sky.\nAnd «رَزَقَ» means to give sustenance or provision. To feed or to give some wealth. «رَزَّاق» is actually only Allah's attribute but the attribute of feeding can also be attributed to others.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ اِذَا حَضَرَ الۡقِسۡمَۃَ  اُولُوا الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنُ فَارۡزُقُوۡہُمۡ  مِّنۡہُ وَ قُوۡلُوۡا لَہُمۡ  قَوۡلًا مَّعۡرُوۡفًا» (4/8)\nTranslation: And when the division (of inheritance) is attended by relatives, orphans and the needy, give them something from it and speak to them kindly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2578,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and riches, to bestow",
      "hw": "Wealth",
      "s": "«خَیْر» the better aspect of wealth, i.e., wealth obtained and spent according to Islamic commands.",
      "d": "«خَیْر» means goodness and every thing that appears good to everyone. Wealth is also 'Khair' in its original aspect and Allah Almighty granting wealth to someone is His great blessing because through its proper use and spending according to Islamic commands, a person can earn many good deeds and virtues.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ مَاۤ اَنۡفَقۡتُمۡ  مِّنۡ خَیۡرٍ فَلِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ ابۡنِ‌السَّبِیۡلِ» (2/215)\nTranslation: Say, 'Whatever you spend of good should be for parents, relatives, orphans, the needy and the traveler.'\nBut love of wealth is ingrained in human nature.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ اِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِ  لَشَدِیۡدٌ» (100/8)\nTranslation: Meaning man is intense in his love of wealth.\nSo when a person leaves the distinction between lawful and unlawful in earning or does not spend it according to Islamic commands, this same wealth which is pure 'Khair' becomes a trial and test for him.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ  وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ  فِتۡنَۃٌ» (8/28)\nTranslation: Your wealth and your children are but a trial."
    },
    {
      "id": 2580,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and riches, to bestow",
      "hw": "Wealth",
      "s": "«مَغَانِم» wealth obtained after victory over the enemy.",
      "d": "«غَنَم» means a flock of sheep. And «اَلْغَنَمُ» means sheep obtained from somewhere or to obtain them. Then this word came to be used for every wealth obtained from enemy or non-enemy. And «مَغْنَم» its plural is «مَغَانِم». Means war booty. And in Islamic terminology, booty or «مَغْنَم» is only that wealth which is obtained as a result of victory over the enemy. Such wealth was unlawful for previous nations but in the Shariah of Muhammad ﷺ, Allah Almighty has made it lawful.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَکُلُوۡا مِمَّا غَنِمۡتُمۡ حَلٰلًا طَیِّبًا» (8/69)\nTranslation: So eat from what you have obtained as booty - it is lawful and good.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«تَبۡتَغُوۡنَ عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا ۫ فَعِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ مَغَانِمُ کَثِیۡرَۃٌ» (4/94)\nTranslation: You desire the gains of this worldly life, but with Allah are many gains."
    },
    {
      "id": 2581,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and riches, to bestow",
      "hw": "Wealth",
      "s": "«اَنْفَال» wealth and goods obtained in war with disbelievers, which is also called booty.",
      "d": "«نَفَل» means war booty. Gift. Grant. Excess. Its plural is «اَنْفَال» and «نَفْل» means work beyond obligations and necessities (Munjid) «اَنْفَال» is applied to both war booty and 'Fai' wealth. This word only indicates that these wealth are extra gifts from Allah Almighty upon the Ummah of Muhammad. Which was not lawful for previous nations.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَنۡفَالِ ؕ قُلِ الۡاَنۡفَالُ لِلّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (8/1)\nTranslation: They ask you about the bounties. Say, 'The bounties are for Allah and the Messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "564": [
    {
      "id": 2582,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Owner",
      "hw": "Owner",
      "s": "«مَالِک» one who has the authority of possession and control.",
      "d": "«مِلْک» is said for every thing that is in someone's possession and no one else has the authority to control it (Muf) and «مَالِک» means one who has complete authority of possession and control over something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ» (1/3)\nTranslation: The Owner of the Day of Recompense."
    },
    {
      "id": 2584,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Owner",
      "hw": "Owner",
      "s": "«اَھْل» family members, home and the owner of the home.",
      "d": "«اَھْل» means family. Relatives. And means family members. Family. Wife and children. And «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means wife and «اَھَلَ الرَّجُل» means to marry (Munjid) and «اَھْل» means people of the same lineage or same religion (Muf) and «اَھْل» also means family members and also home (see 'Home') and in the following verse, the Quran has used the word 'Ahl' and meant the owners of the house.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ» (4/25)\nTranslation: Then marry them with the permission of their owners."
    }
  ],
  "565": [
    {
      "id": 2585,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mother",
      "hw": "Mother",
      "s": "«وَالِدَۃ» a woman who has given birth to a child.",
      "d": "«وَالِدَۃ» a woman who has given birth to a child. Mother. This word is used in limited and well-known meanings. And when both mother and father are intended, the word 'Walidayn' (dual masculine) will be used. Its plural is «وَالِدَات».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And mothers may breastfeed their children two complete years."
    },
    {
      "id": 2586,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mother",
      "hw": "Mother",
      "s": "«اُمّ» means real mother.",
      "d": "The word «اُمّ» is used in a very broad meaning. «اُمّ» means real mother and also every thing that becomes a cause of another thing's existence or its beginning or its reform and training (Muf). The word «اُمّ» is used in the following cases:\n(1) As real mother: For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی اُمِّ مُوۡسٰۤی اَنۡ  اَرۡضِعِیۡہِ» (28/7)\nTranslation: And We inspired to the mother of Moses, 'Suckle him.'\n(2) Just as the word «اَبْ» is used for real father besides grandfather, great-grandfather and upper generations, similarly the word «اُمّ» is also used. Just as Prophet Adam (AS) is Abu'l-Bashar (father of mankind), similarly Hawwa (Eve) is Umm al-Bashar (mother of mankind).\n(3) Meaning origin or root. Like Umm al-Kitab (13/39) meaning the original book or Preserved Tablet. And «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی» (6/92) meaning central settlement or metaphorically the city of Makkah. Also «Umm al-Khaba'ith» meaning wine and Umm al-Amrad meaning constipation. Umm at-Tariq meaning public road. And Umm an-Nujum meaning galaxy.\n(4) And as honor and respect. For example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ وَ اَزۡوَاجُہٗۤ  اُمَّہٰتُہُمۡ» (33/6)\nTranslation: The Prophet is more worthy of the believers than themselves, and his wives are their mothers.\n(5) As a nickname (Kunyah). Then sometimes some relationship is evident in this nickname like «اُم اَرْبَع وَ اَرْبَعِیْن» and sometimes there is no connection at all like a newborn girl is named Umm Kulthum. But such a nickname is not mentioned in the Quran."
    }
  ],
  "566": [
    {
      "id": 2587,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "To ask",
      "s": "«طَلَبَ» the self being greedy for a need and searching for it.",
      "d": "«طَلَبَ الشَّیْ» to ask for something (M Q) and means to strive for something (Fiq L 239) «طِلْب» and «طِلْبَۃ» means the asked thing (Munjid) and means to search and seek something to obtain it (Muf). This word comes in all meanings of asking, wanting and searching. And this is the initial quality of asking.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ» (22/73)\nTranslation: Weak is the seeker and the sought."
    },
    {
      "id": 2588,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "To ask",
      "s": "«سَاَلَ» the self being greedy for a need and expressing it to someone else.",
      "d": "The word «سَاَلَ» comes in two meanings: (1) To ask someone something so that an answer is received (2) To ask something necessary from someone. That is, to request for wealth or some other necessary thing. And «سُؤْل» means a need for which the self is greedy and it is also expressed with the tongue (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ» (2/61)\nTranslation: Go down to the city. Then you will have what you asked for."
    },
    {
      "id": 2589,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "To ask",
      "s": "«اِدَّعَ» the self being greedy for a need and asking by calling out.",
      "d": "«دَعَا» means to ask, to call, to pray. And in «اِدَّعَ» there is intensity. That is, to ask for something by calling out (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا فَاکِہَۃٌ  وَّ لَہُمۡ مَّا یَدَّعُوۡنَ» (36/57)\nTranslation: For them therein is fruit, and for them is whatever they request."
    },
    {
      "id": 2591,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "To ask",
      "s": "«اِعْتَرَّ» means to come before people to ask for charity.",
      "d": "«عَرّ» and «اِعْتَرّ» both come in the same meaning. That is, to ask for charity and to come before someone for it (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36)\nTranslation: And feed the contented and the beggar."
    }
  ],
  "567": [
    {
      "id": 2592,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "To erase",
      "s": "«طَمَسَ» to erase in such a way that some traces remain.",
      "d": "«طَمَسَ» to rub and erase in such a way that some traces remain. The word «طَمَس» is generally used for eyes, stars and face. The «طَمَس» of eyes and stars is that they become lightless and the «طَمَس» of face is that it becomes deformed, i.e., becomes ugly.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اٰمِنُوۡا بِمَا نَزَّلۡنَا مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا مَعَکُمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ نَّطۡمِسَ وُجُوۡہًا» (4/47)\nTranslation: Believe in what We have sent down confirming that which is (already) with you, before We obliterate faces.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«فَاِذَا النُّجُوۡمُ  طُمِسَتۡ» (77/8)\nTranslation: So when the stars are obliterated."
    },
    {
      "id": 2593,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "To erase",
      "s": "«مَحَقَ» to end the power of something and make it lifeless.",
      "d": "«مَحَقَ» to make something weak and feeble. To nullify. To make bereft of blessing and lifeless (M L) and «مَحَقَ» means to become mean and less (Muf) and its opposite is «رَبْواً» or «رَبِّی». Means to nurture. To train and to raise.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَ یُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (2/276)\nTranslation: Allah destroys interest and gives increase for charities."
    },
    {
      "id": 2594,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "To erase",
      "s": "«مَحُو» to erase in such a way that no trace remains.",
      "d": "«مَحُو» to erase something in such a way that its traces also do not remain. They say «مَحَتِ الرِّیْحُ السَّحَابَ». The wind blew away the clouds. That is, no trace of clouds remained. And its opposite is «اَثْبَتَ» meaning to keep established.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ» (13/39)\nTranslation: Allah erases what He wills and confirms what He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2595,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "To erase",
      "s": "«نَسَخَ» to erase something and bring another thing in its place.",
      "d": "«نَسَخَ» means to remove. To nullify. To deform. To erase (Munjid) and means to remove one thing and bring another thing in its place (Muf). And the first thing that was removed or erased is 'Mansukh' and the second thing that was brought in its place is 'Nasikh'. Then sometimes this word also comes in the meaning of merely removing or erasing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَیَنۡسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلۡقِی الشَّیۡطٰنُ ثُمَّ  یُحۡکِمُ  اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ» (22/52)\nTranslation: So Allah erases what Satan casts, then Allah makes precise His verses.\nAnd sometimes it also comes in the meaning of ending or removing the first thing and bringing another thing.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«مَا نَنۡسَخۡ مِنۡ اٰیَۃٍ اَوۡ نُنۡسِہَا نَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ مِّنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ مِثۡلِہَا» (2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth (one) better than it or similar to it."
    }
  ],
  "568": [
    {
      "id": 2596,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«تُرَاب» dry clay and a general word for all types of clay.",
      "d": "«تُرَاب» means dust. Dry clay in which there is no moisture (F L 31) which the wind blows about. It is a general word for clay.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ  کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا» (78/40)\nTranslation: And the disbeliever will say, 'Oh, I wish that I were dust.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2597,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«طِیْن» means wet clay but without straw in it.",
      "d": "«طِیْن» means wet clay but without straw in it (F L 31). Even if the moisture from water is gone from it, this dried mud will still be called 'Tin'. For example, in the Holy Quran:\nTranslation: And Allah began the creation of man from wet clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2598,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«لَازِب» sticky and viscous clay.",
      "d": "«لَازِب» clay that sticks to the hand (Munjid). Sticky and viscous clay (F L 268)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37/11)\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky clay.\nIn the above verse, the word «لَازِب» has not come merely as an adjective of «طِیْن». Rather, the meaning of «لَازِب» itself is sticky and viscous clay as is evident from the reference."
    },
    {
      "id": 2600,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«صَلْصَال» dry ringing mud.",
      "d": "«صَلْصَال» when black foul-smelling mud becomes completely dry and starts making sound with a slight strike, this is 'Salsal' (F L 168)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26)\nTranslation: And We did certainly create man out of clay from an altered black mud.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)\nTranslation: He created man from ringing clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2601,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«فَخَّار» ringing or sounding baked clay.",
      "d": "«فَخَّار» means pottery. Baked clay (Munjid). That is, such baked clay or clay vessels that ring and sound when struck. And «فَخَّارِی» means potter who makes clay vessels etc. and then bakes them in a kiln to prepare or sell them (Munjid). Human creation ultimately became such clay.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)\nTranslation: He created man from ringing clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2602,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«صَعِیْد» means the upper part of the earth and the dust on it that rises up.",
      "d": "«صَعَدَ» means to climb up. And «صَعِیْد» means the upper part of the earth and the dust on it that rises up (Muf). Every flat land is 'Sa'id' (F L 16) and means the upper soil of the earth and dust etc. (M L)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n« فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6)\nTranslation: And if you find no water, then perform Tayammum with clean earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2603,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«سُلَالَۃ» means extract. Essence. Useful part. Something extracted from a thing.",
      "d": "«سُلَالَۃ» means extract. Essence. Useful part. Something extracted from a thing (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ سُلٰلَۃٍ  مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ» (23/12)\nTranslation: And We did certainly create man from an extract of clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2604,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Clay and its various states",
      "hw": "Clay",
      "s": "«ثَرٰی» wet and moist clay from the deepest part of the earth.",
      "d": "«ثَرٰی» wet and moist clay from the deepest part of the earth (F L 31, 167)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ  وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ مَا بَیۡنَہُمَا وَ مَا  تَحۡتَ الثَّرٰی» (20/6)\nTranslation: To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth and whatever is between them and whatever is beneath the soil."
    }
  ],
  "569": [
    {
      "id": 2605,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«بَاشَر» means one body's skin touching another body's skin.",
      "d": "«بَشَرَ» means to peel off skin. «بَشَرَۃ» means the outer surface of the skin. And «بَاشَرَ» means one body's skin touching another body's skin «بَاشَرَ الْمَرَاۃ» means to have intercourse (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تُبَاشِرُوۡہُنَّ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ عٰکِفُوۡنَ  ۙ فِی الۡمَسٰجِدِ» (2/187)\nTranslation: And do not have relations with them as long as you are staying for worship in the mosques."
    },
    {
      "id": 2606,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«قَضٰی وَطَرًا» means to fulfill a need.",
      "d": "«وَطَر» means need and important necessity (Muf) and «قَضٰی وَطَرًا» means to fulfill a need.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا» (33/37)\nTranslation: And when Zayd had no longer any need for her."
    },
    {
      "id": 2607,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«تَغَشّٰی» means one thing covering another thing.",
      "d": "«تَغَشّٰی» means one thing covering another thing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا» (7/189)\nTranslation: And when he covered her, she carried a light burden."
    },
    {
      "id": 2608,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«رَفَثَ» every speech whose expression causes shame.",
      "d": "«رَفَثَ» every speech whose expression causes shame (M L). Means to be unveiled. Intercourse and related conversation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اُحِلَّ لَکُمۡ لَیۡلَۃَ الصِّیَامِ الرَّفَثُ اِلٰی نِسَآئِکُمۡ» (2/187)\nTranslation: It has been made permissible for you the night preceding fasting to go to your wives."
    },
    {
      "id": 2609,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«مَسَّ» to touch something or something touching the body.",
      "d": "«مَسَّ» means to touch something or something touching the body (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَتۡ رَبِّ اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡ وَلَدٌ وَّ لَمۡ یَمۡسَسۡنِیۡ بَشَرٌ» (3/47)\nTranslation: She said, 'My Lord, how will I have a child when no man has touched me?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2610,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«لَامَسَ» means to feel something with fingers.",
      "d": "«لَمَسَ» means to feel something with fingers. To search with fingers or any other part of the body (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَوۡ لٰمَسۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ» (4/43)\nTranslation: Or you have contacted women."
    },
    {
      "id": 2611,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«طَمَثَ» means menstrual blood.",
      "d": "«طَمَث» means menstrual blood (F L 115) and «طَمِثَ یَطْمِثُ» also means a woman being menstruating (Munjid) and also a man removing the veil of virginity of a woman (Muf). So this word is specific for having intercourse (relations) with someone for the first time.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَمۡ یَطۡمِثۡہُنَّ اِنۡسٌ قَبۡلَہُمۡ وَ لَا جَآنٌّ» (55/74)\nTranslation: Untouched before them by man or jinni."
    },
    {
      "id": 2612,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "Intercourse",
      "s": "«قَرُبَ» means to be near.",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» means to be near. To go close.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» (2/222)\nTranslation: And do not approach them until they are pure.\nFor forcing, see 'To force' and for being forced see 'To be restless'"
    }
  ],
  "570": [
    {
      "id": 2613,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Assembly",
      "hw": "Assembly",
      "s": "«مَجْلِس» family members or friends when they sit together.",
      "d": "«مَجْلِس» its plural is «مَجَالِس». Every place where a few people sit together for some purpose. Assembly gatherings in homes is a well-known word. (F L 32, 272) For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا» (58/11)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you are told, 'Space yourselves' in assemblies, then make space."
    },
    {
      "id": 2614,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Assembly",
      "hw": "Assembly",
      "s": "«نَادِی» specific places like club. Gathering. Recreation center. Where in gatherings generally unpleasant activities are chosen.",
      "d": "«نَادِی» such gathering of people in which there is conversation and storytelling (F L 272). Club. Gathering. Recreation centers. Centers of obscenity. And «اَلنَّدْوَۃ» means welfare. National or religious consultation places. (F L 32)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ تَاۡتُوۡنَ فِیۡ نَادِیۡکُمُ الۡمُنۡکَرَ» (29/29)\nTranslation: And you come to your assemblies for evil deeds."
    }
  ],
  "571": [
    {
      "id": 2616,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "«وَدَّ» means to wish for something. To befriend. To love.",
      "d": "«وَدَّ» means to wish for something. To befriend. To love (Munjid) and this word sometimes comes only in the meaning of wishing and desiring (Fiq L 99)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (15/2)\nTranslation: Perhaps those who disbelieve will wish that they were Muslims.\nAnd when this is used in the meaning of love, it implies extreme love. «مَؤَدَۃْ» mutual love and affection. Compassion. And «وَدُوْد» means one who loves very much. And «وُدّ» comes in the meaning of love and affection (Muf)\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ  لَہُمُ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وُدًّا» (19/96)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who have believed and done righteous deeds - the Most Merciful will appoint for them affection.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«اِنَّ  رَبِّیۡ  رَحِیۡمٌ   وَّدُوۡدٌ» (11/90)\nTranslation: Indeed, my Lord is Merciful and Affectionate.\nSo when the word «وَدَّ» comes in the meaning of loving, it is stronger than «حَبَّ» (Muf)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2617,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "«اَلَّفَ» means such love that is due to harmony.",
      "d": "«اَلَّفَ» means to join the disordered parts of something. From this comes the word 'Taleef' meaning to create harmony and «اُلْفَت» means such love that is due to harmony (Muf). For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَوۡ اَنۡفَقۡتَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ جَمِیۡعًا مَّاۤ  اَلَّفۡتَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ» (8/63)\nTranslation: And if you had spent all that is in the earth, you could not have brought their hearts together."
    },
    {
      "id": 2618,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "«شَغَفَ حُبًّا» such love that has penetrated to the inner part of the heart.",
      "d": "«شَغَفَۃُ الْقَلْب» means the inner part of the heart (Muf) and means the covering of the heart (M L) and «شَغَفَ» means it struck the curtain of his heart. And «شَغَفَ حُبًّا» means such love that has penetrated to the inner part of the heart (Muf) (F L 168). To become mad in love (M Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَدۡ شَغَفَہَا حُبًّا» (12/30)\nTranslation: Her love for him (Joseph) had penetrated her heart."
    }
  ],
  "572": [],
  "573": [
    {
      "id": 2622,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To toil. To strive",
      "hw": "Toil",
      "s": "«عَمِلَ» to work. This word is also general and its usage is also general.",
      "d": "«عَمْل» is every work that a living being does with his own choice and will, whether this work is good or bad (Muf) and the word «عَمِلَ» besides meaning 'to do some work' is also used for working or in other words earning livelihood.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79)\nTranslation: As for the ship, it belonged to poor people working at sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 2623,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To toil. To strive",
      "hw": "Toil",
      "s": "«جَھَدَ» to use all means in doing a work.",
      "d": "«جَھَدَ» means to use all means and resources in doing a work. To strive fully (M L)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَنۡ جَاہَدَ فَاِنَّمَا یُجَاہِدُ لِنَفۡسِہٖ» (29/6)\nTranslation: And whoever strives only strives for (the benefit of) his soul.\nAnd «جُھْد» means the toil that a human can do as much as possible.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  اِلَّا جُہۡدَہُمۡ» (9/79)\nTranslation: And those who find not (anything to spend) except their effort."
    },
    {
      "id": 2624,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To toil. To strive",
      "hw": "Toil",
      "s": "«نَصَبَ» such toil that tires or causes fatigue.",
      "d": "«نَصَبَ» such toil that tires a person (1) To toil. To strive (2) To become tired. Then this word is also used in separate meanings.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62)\nTranslation: We have certainly suffered in this, our journey, (much) fatigue.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«فَاِذَا  فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی  رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94/7,8)\nTranslation: So when you have finished (your duties), then stand up (for worship). And to your Lord direct (your) longing."
    },
    {
      "id": 2627,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To toil. To strive",
      "hw": "Toil",
      "s": "«کُرْہ» means forced toil, such toil in which a person's own will and choice has no say.",
      "d": "«کُرْہ» means forced toil. Such toil in which a person's own will and choice has no say and he dislikes this toil. The opposite of «کُرْہ» is «رَضَا  وَ الْمَحَبَۃ ». (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَمَلَتۡہُ  اُمُّہٗ  کُرۡہًا وَّ وَضَعَتۡہُ  کُرۡہًا» (46/15)\nTranslation: His mother carried him with hardship and gave birth to him with hardship.\nAnd «اَکْرَہَ» means to force someone to do some work or toil which he dislikes.\nFor example, in the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)\nTranslation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution."
    }
  ],
  "651": [
    {
      "id": 2979,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level. To flatten",
      "hw": "To level",
      "s": "«سَطَحَ» to spread out and make level.",
      "d": "«سَطَحَ» has two basic meanings: (1) To spread or lay out (2) Then to make it level. And «سَطَحَ الْبَیْت» means to make the roof of a house level. And «مِسْطَحْ» means the tool or instrument for leveling and «سَطَح» means the upper part of the roof of a house (Munjid). According to Imam Raghib, «اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20)\nTranslation: And do they not look at the earth, how it is spread out?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2980,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level. To flatten",
      "hw": "To level",
      "s": "«دَکَّ» to crush into pieces and level with the ground.",
      "d": "«دَکَّ» has two basic meanings: (1) To pound (2) Then to make it level (M L). That is, to pound something and make it level with the ground (Muf)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ ہٰذَا رَحۡمَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّیۡ ۚ فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ جَعَلَہٗ دَکَّآءَ ۚ » (18/98)\nTranslation: Dhul-Qarnain said, 'This is a mercy from my Lord (that He enabled me to build such a wall). Then when the promise of my Lord comes, He will make it level with the ground.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2981,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To level. To flatten",
      "hw": "To level",
      "s": "«مَرَّدَ» to make smooth and glossy.",
      "d": "«مَرِدَ الْغُلَام» means for a boy to be beardless. And «مَرَّدَ الْغُصْن» means to clean the leaves of a branch. And «مَرَّدَ الْبَنَاء» means to make a building smooth and glossy (Muf Munjid). For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَ  اِنَّہٗ  صَرۡحٌ مُّمَرَّدٌ مِّنۡ قَوَارِیۡرَ» (27/44)\nTranslation: Solomon said, 'This is a palace made smooth with glass.'"
    }
  ],
  "652": [
    {
      "id": 2982,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Perpetual. Everlasting",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«سَرْمَد» for something to remain in one state forever without any change or difference.",
      "d": "«سَرْمَد» means perpetual. Forever (Muf). «سَرْمَدِیّ» means that which has neither beginning nor end (Munjid). For something to remain in one state forever without any change or variation (Fiq L 95)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمُ الَّیۡلَ سَرۡمَدًا  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِضِیَآءٍ» (28/71)\nTranslation: Say, 'Have you considered: if Allah should make for you the night perpetual until the Day of Resurrection, what deity other than Allah could bring you light?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2984,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«خَلَدَ» to remain in one state for a long period without change or variation.",
      "d": "The word «خَلَدَ» is not used for eternity but for something remaining from its beginning for a long period without any change or difference. Because this word comes with emphasis with «اَبَد» and where only a long period is intended, only «خَلَدَ» is used. The word «اَبَدَا» does not come with it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ فِیۡ  نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا» (98/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieve from the People of the Scripture and the polytheists will be in the fire of Hell, abiding therein forever.\nAnd in the same Surah, where the reward of the believers is mentioned, He said:\nThe saying of Allah Almighty:\n«جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ  رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَبَدًا» (98/8)\nTranslation: Their reward with their Lord will be gardens of perpetual residence beneath which rivers flow, wherein they will abide forever and ever.\nAnd «اَخْلَدَ» and «خَلَّدَ» both are used in the meaning of something remaining in one state for a long period or remaining in one state.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَحۡسَبُ اَنَّ مَالَہٗۤ  اَخۡلَدَہٗ» (104/3)\nTranslation: He thinks that his wealth will make him live forever.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وِلۡدَانٌ   مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17)\nTranslation: There will circulate among them young boys made eternal."
    },
    {
      "id": 2985,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«وَصَبَ» in this there is also breadth and strength along with permanence (eternity).",
      "d": "«وَصَبَ» According to Ibn Faris, its meaning is merely the permanence of something in one state. (M L) And according to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» (F L 48) meaning intensity of pain and according to the author of Munjid, «اَلْوَاصِب» means a desert that extends very far and «وَصَبَ» means to be permanent and to be fixed. And «دَائِمُ الْمَرِیْض» meaning permanently ill (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ وَّاصِبٌ» (37/9)\nTranslation: And for them is a perpetual punishment.\nSee, here in «واصِبٌ» three things are found: permanence, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» and expanse. But later this word left the meaning of «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» and started being used only in the meaning of intensity or strength and expanse and permanence.\nFor example, the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ لَہٗ  مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَہُ الدِّیۡنُ وَاصِبًا» (16/52)\nTranslation: And to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and to Him is (due) perpetual submission."
    },
    {
      "id": 2987,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمَرَّ» to remain from the beginning in one state or one way.",
      "d": "«مَرَّ» means to pass. To go. To pass by something (Muf Munjid) and «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to remain in one state or way. To perpetuate (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54/2)\nTranslation: But if they see a sign, they turn away and say, 'This is continuous magic.' (Jalandhri)\nIt is magic that has been going on from before. (Usmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2988,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«دَامَ» to remain forever, to be established and stable, to be enduring.",
      "d": "«دَوَام» means tranquility and «مَاءَ الدَّائِم» means stagnant water in which there is no movement. And «دَامَ الشَّیء» means for something to remain in one state without change for a long period (Muf) and duration means permanence. This verb is sometimes conditional with another state. That is, as long as this state remains, this will also remain. At that time the letter «مَا» enters upon it and «مَا دَامَ» means 'as long as'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰمُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَنۡ  نَّدۡخُلَہَاۤ  اَبَدًا مَّا دَامُوۡا فِیۡہَا» (5/24)\nTranslation: They said, 'O Moses, indeed we will not enter it, ever, as long as they are within it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2989,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«زَالَ» to perish, to move away, and زوال means to decline, this word gives the meaning of permanence with «لَا» and «مَا» negative.",
      "d": "«زَالَ» means to perish. To move away. And زوال means to decline. This word gives the meaning of permanence with «لَا» and «مَا» negative and in these meanings it is always used with «لَا» and «مَا» (Muf) and comes for temporal capacity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تَزَالُ تَطَّلِعُ عَلٰی خَآئِنَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (5/13)\nTranslation: And you will always observe treachery from them, except a few of them.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«فَمَا زَالَتۡ تِّلۡکَ دَعۡوٰىہُمۡ  حَتّٰی  جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ  حَصِیۡدًا  خٰمِدِیۡنَ» (21/15)\nTranslation: And that was their claim until We made them as a field mown, extinguished."
    },
    {
      "id": 2990,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«اَبْرَحَ» only in present tense with «لَا» and «لَنْ» negative and conditional with «حَتّٰی», comes for spatial capacity.",
      "d": "The opposite of «بَرَحَ» is «بَرَزَ». And «بَرَزَ» means to come out into the open field. And «بَرَحَ» means to move away from the open field (Muf). Only present tense is used. When the negative word «لَا» or «لَنْ» comes with it, it is used for spatial capacity. And it is always conditional with «حَتّٰی».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَالَ مُوۡسٰی لِفَتٰىہُ لَاۤ  اَبۡرَحُ حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ» (18/60)\nTranslation: And when Moses said to his servant, 'I will not cease (traveling) until I reach the junction of the two seas.'\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نَّبۡرَحَ عَلَیۡہِ عٰکِفِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یَرۡجِعَ   اِلَیۡنَا مُوۡسٰی» (20/91)\nTranslation: They said, 'We will never cease being devoted to it until Moses returns to us.'\nNote: (Present tense verb: A verb in which an action is done or exists in present or future time, such as: comes, goes, does etc.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2991,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be permanent. To remain",
      "hw": "Perpetual",
      "s": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from some work and when «لَا» and «مَا» negative enter upon it, it gives the meaning of continuously doing some work.",
      "d": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from some work. When «لَا» and «مَا» negative enter upon it, it gives the meaning of continuously doing some work. They say «مَا فَتَاَ یَفْعَلُ ذٰلک». He has always been doing this. It is generally conditional with «حَتّٰی». Only past and present tense are used (Munjid). It comes for temporal capacity. This word has come once in the Quran but there also «لَا» is hidden i.e., concealed (Jala al-Ulayn and Jami' al-Bayan)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: They said, 'By Allah, you will not cease remembering Joseph until you become fatally ill or become of those who perish.'"
    }
  ],
  "653": [
    {
      "id": 2992,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To laugh",
      "hw": "To laugh",
      "s": "«ضَحِکَ» to laugh with voice opening the mouth from which teeth become visible.",
      "d": "«ضَحِکَ» to laugh with voice opening the mouth from which teeth become visible (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  قَآئِمَۃٌ  فَضَحِکَتۡ فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ» (11/71)\nTranslation: And his wife was standing, and she laughed. Then We gave her good tidings of Isaac."
    },
    {
      "id": 2993,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To laugh",
      "hw": "To laugh",
      "s": "«تَبَسَّمَ» means to smile.",
      "d": "«بَسَمَ» and «تَبَسَّمَ» mean to smile (Munjid). To laugh a little without voice from which signs of happiness become visible.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَتَبَسَّمَ ضَاحِکًا مِّنۡ قَوۡلِہَا» (27/19)\nTranslation: So Solomon smiled, amused at her speech."
    }
  ],
  "654": [
    {
      "id": 2994,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رِیْح» means wind.",
      "d": "«رِیْح, رَوْح» is a well-known word for wind. According to Ibn Faris, its meaning is wind and to move (M L). Although it has been used in the Quran in broader meanings. For example:\n(1) «رِیْح» meaning wind in well-known meanings which moves (F L 172)\nFor example, the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If He wills, He can still the wind.\n(2) «رِیْح» meaning scent or fragrance.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ» (12/94)\nTranslation: Indeed, I find the scent of Joseph.\n(3) «رِیْح» meaning awe and prestige.\nFor example, the saying of Allah Almighty:\n«وَ لَا  تَنَازَعُوۡا فَتَفۡشَلُوۡا  وَ تَذۡہَبَ رِیۡحُکُمۡ» (8/46)\nTranslation: And do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your wind departs.\nAnd the plural of «رِیْح» is «رِیَاح». When the word «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیَاح» is there, it means winds of mercy. And if «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیْح» is mentioned meaning singular form is used, then it means wind of punishment (Muf). According to this, its separate classification is made."
    },
    {
      "id": 2995,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رَوْح» meaning mercy. Continuous wave of Allah's favors and blessings.",
      "d": "«رَوْح» meaning breeze. Mercy. Happiness. Comfort. Help and «یَوْمٌ رَوْحٌ» means a pleasant day (Munjid) and according to Imam Raghib, «رُوْح» and «رَوْح» are actually one. And «رُوْح» is applied to breath. And «اَرَاحَ الْاِنْسَان» means for a person to breathe. And to obtain comfort (Muf). Reflecting on the different meanings of «رُوْح», it is known that its meaning is a continuous wave of Allah's favors and blessings that becomes a cause of comfort and ease for humans.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَا تَایۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (12/87)\nTranslation: Do not despair of the mercy of Allah. Indeed, no one despairs of the mercy of Allah except the disbelieving people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2996,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رَیْحَان» fragrant flowers, plants, crops.",
      "d": "«رَیْحَان» meaning every fragrant plant. Sustenance. Livelihood (Munjid) and «رَائِحَۃ» meaning fragrant scent and «رَیْحَانَۃ» meaning bouquet of flowers (Munjid). Reflecting on these meanings, it is known that if «رَیْحَان» means sustenance or food items obtained from crops, then it means things whose scent and fragrance is pleasant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَرَوۡحٌ وَّ رَیۡحَانٌ  ۬ ۙ وَّ جَنَّتُ نَعِیۡمٍ» (56/89)\nTranslation: Then (for him is) rest and bounty and a garden of pleasure.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ الۡحَبُّ ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ» (55/12)\nTranslation: And the grain having husks and scented plants (Jalandhri)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2997,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«مُبَشِّرَات» winds giving good tidings of rain.",
      "d": "«مُبَشِّرَات» winds giving good tidings of descent of mercy or rain. The wet and pleasant wind before rain (F L 254)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مِنۡ اٰیٰتِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ الرِّیَاحَ مُبَشِّرٰتٍ وَّ  لِیُذِیۡقَکُمۡ  مِّنۡ  رَّحۡمَتِہٖ» (30/46)\nTranslation: And of His signs is that He sends the winds as bringers of good tidings that He may let you taste His mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2998,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«لَوَاقِح» pregnant winds, those winds that carry the burden of water before raining.",
      "d": "«لَوَاقِح» is plural of «لَاقِحَۃ, لَقِحَ» meaning pregnant wind. And this burden can be of two types: (1) The burden of water that winds carry before raining (2) The burden of seed (i.e., seed, pit, grain or sperm) of male tree that they go and drop on female tree (M L). In the Quran, this word has been used only in the first meaning.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22)\nTranslation: And We have sent the fertilizing winds and sent down water from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2999,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«عَاصِف» storm that blows away straw and twigs.",
      "d": "«عَصْف» meaning straw. Chaff. Dry vegetation that breaks into pieces (Muf) and «عَاصِفَۃ» is that fast wind or storm that blows away straw or things equal to it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا کُنۡتُمۡ فِی الۡفُلۡکِ ۚ وَ  جَرَیۡنَ بِہِمۡ بِرِیۡحٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ وَّ فَرِحُوۡا بِہَا جَآءَتۡہَا رِیۡحٌ عَاصِفٌ وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10/22)\nTranslation: Until when you are in the ships and they sail with them in a good wind and they rejoice therein, there comes a storm wind and the waves come upon them from everywhere and they assume that they are surrounded."
    },
    {
      "id": 3000,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«حَاصِبٌ» storm that blows away stones and pebbles.",
      "d": "«حَصَب» meaning stones and pebbles and «حاصِبَۃ» is that fast storm that blows away stones and pebbles (F L 253) and «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْس» means for a horse to run so fast that pebbles start flying in the air from its feet (M Q)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَفَاَمِنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ یَّخۡسِفَ بِکُمۡ جَانِبَ الۡبَرِّ اَوۡ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (17/68)\nTranslation: Then do you feel secure that He will not cause (part of) the land to swallow you or send against you a storm of stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3001,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«قَاصِف» storm of wind that breaks trees.",
      "d": "«قَصَفَ» means to break and to be broken (M L) and «قَاصِف» is that fierce and fast wind that breaks trees etc. (Muf). Storm of wind. Thundering storm.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَیُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ قَاصِفًا مِّنَ الرِّیۡحِ فَیُغۡرِقَکُمۡ بِمَا کَفَرۡتُمۡ» (17/69)\nTranslation: Then He would send against you a tempest of wind and drown you for your disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 3002,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«سَمُوْم» hot wind. Extremely hot blowing wind.",
      "d": "«سَمُوْم» extremely hot wind. Hot wind that scorches bodies (F L 254)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» (52/27)\nTranslation: Then Allah conferred favor upon us and protected us from the punishment of the scorching wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 3003,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«اِعْصَار» whirlwind. Dust-filled fast wind that goes straight towards the sky.",
      "d": "«اِعْصَار» is that fierce and fast wind that spins in the sky (Muf) and meaning dust-filled fast wind that goes straight towards the sky (F L 253). Wind whirlwind.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Then a whirlwind containing fire struck it and it burned."
    },
    {
      "id": 3004,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«حُسْبَان» any punishment of wind that is sufficient to settle accounts.",
      "d": "«حَسَبَ» means to calculate. To count. To enumerate. And «حُسْبَان» means such punishment that is sufficient to settle accounts. And the meaning of «حُسْبَان» has been given differently by different lexicographers. However, this punishment is related to wind punishment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» (18/40)\nTranslation: And send upon it a calamity from the sky, and it becomes a slippery ground."
    },
    {
      "id": 3005,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» meaning cold gust, only one wave of extremely cold wind.",
      "d": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» meaning cold gust. Like air comes out once from a bellows. Vapor. Blow. Blast of severe cold wind and its opposite is «لَفْحَۃٌ» meaning blast of hot wind. (F L 29)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And if a blast of your Lord's punishment were to touch them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3007,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "Wind",
      "s": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» such wind that is devoid of good and has only loss.",
      "d": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» meaning such wind that neither raises rain or clouds nor is it for sowing i.e., scattering seeds (F L 254). Wind devoid of good. That which has loss. And its opposite is «لَا قِحَۃ».\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ فِیۡ عَادٍ  اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمُ  الرِّیۡحَ الۡعَقِیۡمَ» (51/41)\nTranslation: And in 'Aad (was a sign) when We sent against them the barren wind."
    }
  ],
  "655": [
    {
      "id": 3008,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be",
      "hw": "To be",
      "s": "«کَانَ» gives the meaning of past and present like: is, became, and was.",
      "d": "«کَانَ» gives the meaning of past and present like: is, became, and was. And its imperfect form «یَکُونُ» gives the meaning of both present and future. According to Ibn Faris, the meaning of «کَانَ» is «اَخْبَار عَنِ الْحَدُوْثُ الشَّیء» i.e., to inform about the occurrence of something new.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَ کَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2/34)\nTranslation: Except Iblis; he refused and was arrogant and became of the disbelievers.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ یَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» (76/7)\nTranslation: And they fear a Day whose evil will be widespread.\nAlso «کَانَ» comes as an incomplete verb. When it enters the past tense, it changes it to the past perfect tense. «کَانَ ذَھَبَ» means he had gone. And when it enters the imperfect tense, it changes it to the past continuous tense.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ» (2/59)\nTranslation: So We sent down upon those who wronged a punishment from the sky because they were defiantly disobedient."
    },
    {
      "id": 3010,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be",
      "hw": "To be",
      "s": "«صَدَرَ» A matter to occur. A command to be issued, to be promulgated.",
      "d": "«صَدَرَ» A matter to occur. A command to be issued, to be promulgated. And its opposite is «وَرَدَ» meaning to arrive. And «صُدُوْر» is said for a matter to be completed successfully and then returning after being free from it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یَوۡمَئِذٍ یَّصۡدُرُ النَّاسُ اَشۡتَاتًا ۬ ۙ لِّیُرَوۡا اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ» (99/6)\nTranslation: That Day the people will depart separated into categories to be shown their deeds.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23)\nTranslation: The two women said, 'We do not water until the shepherds drive their flocks away.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3011,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be",
      "hw": "To be",
      "s": "«وَقَعَ» An unpleasant matter to occur.",
      "d": "«وَقَعَ» has two basic meanings: (1) For something to be established (2) To fall down. And a 'waqi'ah' (event) is generally called an incident in which there is intensity and severity.\nIn the Quran, this word is used for punishment, disliked matters, and hardships.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَاَلَ سَآئِلٌۢ بِعَذَابٍ وَّاقِعٍ» (70/1)\nTranslation: A supplicant asked for a punishment bound to occur.\nIn another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَ وَقَعَ الۡقَوۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمَا ظَلَمُوۡا» (27/85)\nTranslation: And the word will have come to pass against them for what they wronged."
    }
  ],
  "656": [
    {
      "id": 3012,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Or",
      "hw": "Or",
      "s": "«اَوْ» is used to indicate one of two or more things.",
      "d": "«اَوْ» is used to indicate one of two or more things.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ» (2/259)\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a township."
    },
    {
      "id": 3013,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Or",
      "hw": "Or",
      "s": "«اَمْ» In Arabic grammar this is called (conjunction). It comes after the interrogative hamza to indicate equality.",
      "d": "«اَمْ» In Arabic grammar this is called (conjunction). It comes after the interrogative hamza to indicate equality.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا اَمِ السَّمَآءُ» (79/27)\nTranslation: Are you a more difficult creation or is the heaven?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3014,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Or",
      "hw": "Or",
      "s": "«اِمَّا» is used to indicate each of two things and comes with repetition.",
      "d": "«اِمَّا» is used to indicate each of two things and comes with repetition.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ السَّبِیۡلَ اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا» (76/3)\nTranslation: Indeed, We guided him to the way, be he grateful or be he ungrateful."
    }
  ],
  "657": [
    {
      "id": 3015,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "To remember. To come. To keep",
      "hw": "Remember",
      "s": "«ذَکَرَ» To remember, to keep, to come, to remember in the heart or to remember with the tongue, used everywhere and its usage is general.",
      "d": "«ذَکَرَ» means for something to be present on the tongue or in the heart. Whether something is remembered or remembered after being forgotten. Its usage is general.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَوَلَا یَذۡکُرُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ وَلَمۡ یَکُ شَیۡئًا» (19/67)\nTranslation: Does man not remember that We created him before, while he was nothing?\nAnd «اِدَّکَر» means for a forgotten matter to be remembered.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہَا وَ ادَّکَرَ بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And the one who was saved from them and remembered after a time said."
    },
    {
      "id": 3016,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "To remember. To come. To keep",
      "hw": "Remember",
      "s": "«حَفِظَ» To memorize something verbally. To preserve in the heart then to take care of it and not forget it.",
      "d": "«حَفِظَ» To remember something and then take care of it. To protect something from being wasted and destroyed. To protect from corruption.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: Maintain with care the prayers and the middle prayer."
    },
    {
      "id": 3017,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "To remember. To come. To keep",
      "hw": "Remember",
      "s": "«وَعٰی» means to remember and not allow any decrease or increase in it.",
      "d": "«وَعٰی» means to put something in a bag etc. and close its mouth. To protect it and not let anything come out. And «وِعَاء» means tied equipment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لِنَجۡعَلَہَا لَکُمۡ تَذۡکِرَۃً وَّ تَعِیَہَاۤ اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» (69/12)\nTranslation: That We might make it for you a reminder and that a conscious ear would be aware of it."
    }
  ],
  "658": [
    {
      "id": 3018,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "To be certain",
      "hw": "Certainty",
      "s": "«اَیْقَنَ» To fully understand something and reach its proof.",
      "d": "«يَقِنُ» means for no doubt or suspicion to remain. And according to Imam Raghib, «يَقِنُ» means 'to fully understand a matter and at the same time reach its proof.' And its level is above knowledge and understanding. And according to Abu al-Hilal al-Askari, the level of certainty is higher than knowledge. He writes: «اَلْیَقِیْنُ سَکُونَ النَّفْس وَ نَھَجَ الصَّدْرُ بِمَا عِلْم» i.e., the name of certainty is the heart's tranquility and chest's coolness regarding the known thing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمۡ یُوۡقِنُوۡنَ» (2/4)\nTranslation: And in the Hereafter they are certain.\nAnd «اِسْتَيْقَنَ» means to gradually become certain after experiencing something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَتۡہُمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا مُبۡصِرَۃً قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا سِحۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ . وَ جَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (27/13-14)\nTranslation: Then when Our clear signs came to them, they said, 'This is clear magic.' And they rejected them while their souls were convinced of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3019,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "To be certain",
      "hw": "Certainty",
      "s": "«ظَنَّ» To obtain certainty by inferring from signs and evidence.",
      "d": "«ظَنَّ» originally comes for inferring from signs and evidence and for conjecture. Now these signs and evidence, the weaker they are, the weaker the 'zann' will be. And the stronger they are, the stronger the 'zann' will be. In this case, 'zann' gives the meaning of strong certainty. And its sign is that after 'zann', generally the word «اَنَّ» or «اَنْ» comes.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ» (2/46)\nTranslation: Those who are certain that they will meet their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "659": [],
  "660": [
    {
      "id": 3022,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu - Wudu",
      "hw": "Wudu",
      "s": "«سَفَرَ» is a general word for travel.",
      "d": "«سَفَرَ» means to go away from one's residence. And means to travel a distance. This word is general. Whether the travel is for some purpose.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ» (4/43)\nTranslation: And if you are ill or on a journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 3023,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu - Wudu",
      "hw": "Wudu",
      "s": "«يمم» is used for intending purification with dust as an alternative to wudu.",
      "d": "«يمم» Its linguistic meaning is to intend, to purpose, or to turn towards something. In Islamic jurisprudence terminology, and specifically in the context of wudu, «يمم» refers to the intention and act of purification with clean dust in the absence of water, or due to a legitimate excuse (such as illness) from using it. It is a jurisprudential alternative to wudu (and ghusl), called tayammum. Its special point is that it is the intention and act of purification with dust instead of water, not performing wudu with water itself. Allah Almighty has granted this concession to Muslims for ease so that they can obtain purity in every state.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ وَإِن كُنتُمْ جُنُبًا فَاطَّهَّرُوا ۚ وَإِن كُنتُم مَّرْضَىٰ أَوْ عَلَىٰ سَفَرٍ أَوْ جَاءَ أَحَدٌ مِّنكُم مِّنَ الْغَائِطِ أَوْ لَامَسْتُمُ النِّسَاءَ فَلَمْ تَجِدُوا مَاءً فَتَيَمَّمُوا صَعِيدًا طَيِّبًا فَامْسَحُوا بِوُجُوهِكُمْ وَأَيْدِيكُم مِّنْهُ ۚ مَا يُرِيدُ اللَّهُ لِيَجْعَلَ عَلَيْكُم مِّنْ حَرَجٍ وَلَٰكِن يُرِيدُ لِيُطَهِّرَكُمْ وَلِيُتِمَّ نِعْمَتَهُ عَلَيْكُمْ لَعَلَّكُمْ تَشْكُرُونَ» (5/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to prayer, wash your faces and your forearms to the elbows and wipe over your heads and wash your feet to the ankles. And if you are in a state of janabah, then purify yourselves. But if you are ill or on a journey or one of you comes from the place of relieving himself or you have contacted women and do not find water, then seek clean earth and wipe over your faces and hands with it. Allah does not intend to make difficulty for you, but He intends to purify you and complete His favor upon you that you may be grateful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3024,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu - Wudu",
      "hw": "Wudu",
      "s": "«يدي» describes the part of the body (hand) that must be washed up to the elbows for purification in the context of wudu.",
      "d": "«يدي» Its meaning is 'hand'. In the context of wudu, this word identifies the bodily limb (hand) that must be washed up to the elbows in the act of purification. Its concept is more related to the essence of the limb that is part of the fulfillment of a jurisprudential command, rather than any movement or action.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ» (5/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to prayer, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows and wipe over your heads and wash your feet up to the ankles."
    },
    {
      "id": 3025,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu - Wudu",
      "hw": "Wudu",
      "s": "«نسو» expresses the desire for complete oblivion where one's existence is erased, stemming from fear of shameful accusations or the social disgrace that may result from incomplete wudu.",
      "d": "«نسو» Its linguistic meaning is to forget, to overlook, or to be forgotten. In the context of wudu, this word describes the quality when a person unintentionally forgets or leaves out one of the obligatory or sunnah parts of wudu, which may affect the validity of wudu. It points to human weakness and negligence that mistakes can occur even in acts of worship, so in case of such forgetting, it becomes necessary to repeat wudu or complete that part.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجْمَعَ بَيْنِهِمَا نَسِيَا حُوتَهُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِيلَهُ فِي الْبَحْرِ سَرَبًا» (18/61)\nTranslation: Then when they reached the junction between them, they forgot their fish, and it took its course into the sea, slipping away."
    },
    {
      "id": 3026,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu - Wudu",
      "hw": "Wudu",
      "s": "«مرض» has no direct linguistic or jurisprudential connection to the concept of wudu, since wudu relates to \"وضأ\" while \"مرض\" means illness.",
      "d": "«مرض» Its meaning is illness, ailment, or defect. This word is completely unrelated to the jurisprudential or linguistic meaning of wudu, since the word wudu is derived from the Arabic root \"w-d-a\" whose basic meaning is purity, cleanliness, and brightness. In contrast, \"marad\" is related to the deterioration of physical or spiritual health and illness. Therefore, the use of this word in the chapter of wudu is neither correct from the perspective of the Arabic language nor does it have any basis in the context of Islamic jurisprudence.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَهُمُ اللَّهُ مَرَضًا ۖ وَلَهُمْ عَذَابٌ أَلِيمٌ بِمَا كَانُوا يَكْذِبُونَ» (2/10)\nTranslation: In their hearts is disease, so Allah has increased them in disease; and for them is a painful punishment because they habitually used to lie."
    }
  ],
  "661": [
    {
      "id": 3027,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Abrogated - Abrogated",
      "hw": "Abrogated",
      "s": "When «خير» is used with the concept of «منسوخ», it means that Allah brings something better or similar in place of the abrogated ruling or verse.",
      "d": "«خير» Its meaning is 'better' or 'good'. When this word is used with the concept of 'abrogated', it means that when Allah Almighty abrogates a ruling or verse, the new ruling or verse He brings in its place is 'better' than the previous one or equal to it, so that the interest and wisdom of the servants is fulfilled. This is evidence of Allah Almighty's wisdom, knowledge, and goodwill towards creation, that none of His decisions is purposeless, but in every change there is more good and benefit for humanity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring one better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3028,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Abrogated - Abrogated",
      "hw": "Abrogated",
      "s": "The use of «نسي» in the meaning of «منسوخ» describes its abrogation by forgetting something, erasing it, or nullifying the effect of its ruling.",
      "d": "«نسي» Its meaning is 'to forget', 'to erase' or 'to cause something to disappear from the mind'. When it is used in the context of 'abrogated', it means to abolish a ruling or verse in such a way that it does not remain in its previous state, whether it is erased from people's minds or its practical ruling is lifted and its operation is declared null and void, whereby it becomes abrogated. This actually describes the quality of lifting a jurisprudential ruling from Allah Almighty or stopping its application.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring one better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3029,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Abrogated - Abrogated",
      "hw": "Abrogated",
      "s": "«اتي» refers to a new verse or ruling divinely revealed, which causes the abrogation of a previous ruling or replaces it.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is 'to bring', 'to deliver' or 'to come'. In the context of abrogation, this word describes the revelation or appearance of a divine command, law or verse that takes the place of a previous ruling or abolishes it. It does not directly mean abrogation but describes how a new ruling or decree 'comes' that abrogates the old ruling. It is part of a process where Allah Almighty, according to His wisdom, 'brings' a better or similar ruling, as a result of which the previous ruling becomes abrogated.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring one better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3030,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Abrogated - Abrogated",
      "hw": "Abrogated",
      "s": "When «مثل» is used in the concept of «منسوخ», it refers to the new ruling or verse brought as a replacement for the abrogated ruling or verse, similar or equal to it.",
      "d": "«مثل» Its meaning is similar, equal or like. When it is mentioned in the context of 'abrogated', it refers to the new ruling or verse that Allah Almighty reveals in place of a previously abrogated ruling or verse, and this new ruling is similar to the first abrogated ruling in its wisdom, effect or ruling. This indicates that when Allah Almighty abrogates a ruling, He reveals in its place either a better ruling or another ruling similar to it that is more appropriate for the servants.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (Al-Baqarah 2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring one better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    }
  ],
  "662": [
    {
      "id": 3033,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Adopted - Adopted",
      "hw": "Adopted",
      "s": "The word «حقق» in the context of 'متبنیٰ' (adopted son) points to establishing the child's true lineage and establishing truth, which negates false lineage claims.",
      "d": "«حقق» Its meaning is to prove something true, to make it a reality, to confirm it and to establish the truth. The concept of 'mutanna' (adopted son), in which a child was declared as someone else's son instead of his true lineage, Islam forbade it. In this context, the word «حقق» describes the reality that Allah Almighty establishes truth through His commands and negates every false claim, which also includes determining the true lineage of a child.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَيُحِقُّ اللَّهُ الْحَقَّ بِكَلِمَاتِهِ وَلَوْ كَرِهَ الْمُجْرِمُونَ» (10/82)\nTranslation: And Allah establishes the truth by His words, even if the criminals dislike it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3035,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Adopted - Adopted",
      "hw": "Adopted",
      "s": "«كون» refers to something's existence or a state's establishment, and in the concept of adopted, it shows the existence or non-existence of the legal or social status established regarding the adopted.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is 'to be', 'to come into existence' or 'to be established'. Although this word is not itself the term 'mutanna' (adopted) nor is it directly its root (since 'mutanna' is related to 'b-n-y'), but when the Quran describes the rulings of adopted, 'kun' is used to clarify the 'being' or 'not being' of a state related to it. Its special aspect is that it can be used to describe the 'coming into existence' or 'being established' of a legal or social reality associated with the concept of 'adopted', not the act of adoption itself.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لِكَيْ لَا يَكُونَ عَلَى الْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَرَجٌ فِي أَزْوَاجِ أَدْعِيَائِهِمْ إِذَا قَضَوْا مِنْهُنَّ وَطَرًا» (33/37)\nTranslation: This is so that there will be upon the believers no discomfort concerning the wives of their adopted sons when they have no longer any need for them."
    }
  ],
  "663": [
    {
      "id": 3037,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery/Fornication - Adultery/Fornication",
      "hw": "Adultery/Fornication",
      "s": "The use of «كون» in the context of adultery shows its reality, i.e., its eternal and everlasting existence as obscene and evil.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is 'to be', 'to exist', or 'to become'. In reference to adultery, its use is generally to describe the eternal and everlasting quality of this act, i.e., that it has been an obscene and evil act from eternity. It clarifies an unchangeable reality of its disliked and forbidden nature that its evil is not something temporary or changeable but is included in its nature.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تَقْرَبُوا الزِّنَا إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا» (17/32)\nTranslation: And do not approach unlawful sexual intercourse. Indeed, it is ever an immorality and is evil as a way."
    },
    {
      "id": 3038,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery/Fornication - Adultery/Fornication",
      "hw": "Adultery/Fornication",
      "s": "When «اتي» is used for adultery, it means to practically commit this evil act or to perpetrate it.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is 'to come', 'to do' or 'to accomplish'. When this word is used within 'adultery', its meaning is to commit this evil act, to practically perform it or to be involved in it. It indicates the occurrence of the act itself and giving it practical form, rather than just approaching an act or intending it. This word specifies regularly doing a sin or immorality.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَالَّلَاتِي يَأْتِينَ الْفَاحِشَةَ مِن نِّسَائِكُمْ فَاسْتَشْهِدُوا عَلَيْهِنَّ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنكُمْ» (4/15)\nTranslation: And those who commit immorality among your women - bring against them four witnesses from among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3040,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery/Fornication - Adultery/Fornication",
      "hw": "Adultery/Fornication",
      "s": "«نسو» expresses the desire for complete oblivion where one's existence is erased, stemming from fear of shameful accusations like adultery or social disgrace.",
      "d": "«نسو» Its linguistic meaning is to forget, to overlook, or to be forgotten. Within the context of adultery, this word does not directly describe the act of adultery but rather reflects its moral, social and psychological effects. It reflects the intense mental and emotional state when a person, to avoid a disgraceful accusation like adultery or its possible consequences, or reaching the extreme of shame and humiliation caused by it, wishes that he was completely forgotten, or never came into existence at all so that he would not have to face this shame. It points to that social worthlessness and desire to completely forget oneself that arises in such a situation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَأَجَاءَهَا الْمَخَاضُ إِلَىٰ جِذْعِ النَّخْلَةِ قَالَتْ يَا لَيْتَنِي مِتُّ قَبْلَ هَٰذَا وَكُنتُ نَسْيًا مَّنسِيًّا» (19/23)\nTranslation: And the pains of childbirth drove her to the trunk of a palm tree. She said, 'Oh, I wish I had died before this and was in oblivion, forgotten.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3041,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery/Fornication - Adultery/Fornication",
      "hw": "Adultery/Fornication",
      "s": "When the word «نكح» is used for sexual relations without legal marriage or in a forbidden relationship, it refers to an illegitimate sexual act that falls under the category of adultery.",
      "d": "«نكح» Its meaning is to establish sexual relations or to marry. Although this word is generally used in the meaning of lawful and legal marriage, but when it is used for sexual relations in an illegitimate or forbidden relationship, then it points to adultery or similar severe immorality. In this case, the act of 'nikah' becomes illegitimate and condemnable, i.e., this act becomes forbidden because it is outside the legal boundaries.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تَنكِحُوا مَا نَكَحَ آبَاؤُكُم مِّنَ النِّسَاءِ إِلَّا مَا قَدْ سَلَفَ ۚ إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَمَقْتًا وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا» (4/22)\nTranslation: And do not marry those women whom your fathers married, except what has already occurred. Indeed, it was an immorality and hateful and was evil as a way."
    }
  ],
  "664": [
    {
      "id": 3042,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Wealthy/Prosperous - Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "hw": "Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "s": "«ترف» refers to that prosperity or wealth based on abundance, luxury and comfort, which sometimes leads to negligence, arrogance or ingratitude.",
      "d": "«ترف» Its meaning is to live in luxury, to spend a very comfortable and luxurious life, and to be engrossed in worldly comforts. This word does not only point to general prosperity but points to such abundant prosperity and wealth that makes a person too much comfort-seeking (spoiled). The necessary result of this prosperity is that such people often become victims of negligence, arrogance, ingratitude and rebellion, and turn away from the truth. In the Holy Quran, this word is often used for those people who, being engrossed in their worldly luxury, become heedless of the thought of the Hereafter and Allah's commands.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذَا أَرَدْنَا أَن نُّهْلِكَ قَرْيَةً أَمَرْنَا مُتْرَفِيهَا فَفَسَقُوا فِيهَا فَحَقَّ عَلَيْهَا الْقَوْلُ فَدَمَّرْنَاهَا تَدْمِيرًا» (17/16)\nTranslation: And when We intend to destroy a city, We command its affluent ones but they defiantly disobey therein; so the word comes into effect upon it, and We destroy it with complete destruction."
    },
    {
      "id": 3043,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Wealthy/Prosperous - Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "hw": "Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "s": "«قري» highlights that aspect of prosperity in which abundance of sustenance and comfort grants the ability for hospitality and generosity.",
      "d": "«قري» Its meaning is to host a guest, to feed him. This word shows that prosperity and abundance which makes a person or nation capable of hospitality and generosity. Although the word «قِرَىٰ» (as hospitality) has not come explicitly in the Holy Quran, but its cognate word «قَرْيَة» (village or city) is often used for cities that were prosperous in their economy or livelihood. Thus, «قري» presents the deep concept of prosperity in which there is not only financial comfort but also that generosity and hospitality which keeps the care of others and the ability to honor guests. That is, the truly prosperous is one who has an open heart for others in his abundance.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَكَمْ أَهْلَكْنَا مِن قَرْيَةٍ بَطِرَتْ مَعِيشَتَهَا ۖ فَتِلْكَ مَسَاكِنُهُمْ لَمْ تُسْكَن مِّن بَعْدِهِمْ إِلَّا قَلِيلًا ۖ وَكُنَّا نَحْنُ الْوَارِثِينَ» (28/58)\nTranslation: And how many a city have We destroyed that was insolent in its livelihood, and those are their dwellings which have not been inhabited after them except a little. And it is We who were the inheritors."
    },
    {
      "id": 3044,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Wealthy/Prosperous - Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "hw": "Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "s": "«نذر» is not directly related to prosperity, but this word means to vow or warn; however, its connection to prosperity can be indirectly established through vows made as gratitude or for obtaining blessings.",
      "d": "«نذر» Its basic meaning is 'to vow' or 'to dedicate something for Allah', and the second important meaning is 'to warn' or 'to frighten'. This word is not used directly as a synonym for 'prosperous'. However, in the Islamic context, a person vows (nazr) to express gratitude for his obtained prosperity and Allah's blessings, or presents a vow in hope of obtaining future prosperity and blessings. Thus, the act of nazr can be indirectly connected to the state of prosperity or the desire for it, where a believer intends to sacrifice something for Allah's pleasure and to obtain more grace.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا أَنفَقْتُم مِّن نَّفَقَةٍ أَوْ نَذَرْتُم مِّن نَّذْرٍ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ يَعْلَمُهُ ۗ وَمَا لِلظَّالِمِينَ مِنْ أَنصَارٍ» (2/270)\nTranslation: And whatever you spend of expenditures or vow of vows - indeed, Allah knows of it. And for the wrongdoers there are no helpers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3046,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Wealthy/Prosperous - Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "hw": "Wealthy/Prosperous",
      "s": "When «حقق» is used in the sense of prosperity, it points to the fulfillment of a truth, promise or hope that brings satisfaction and comfort.",
      "d": "«حقق» Its meaning is to prove something true, to give it the form of reality, or to fulfill a promise or expectation. When this word is connected to the concept of 'prosperous', it means the attainment or fulfillment of such a truth, right or purpose that appears in the form of inner peace, satisfaction and success, with which the prosperity of an individual or nation is connected. It is not directly prosperity but describes the process that becomes the cause of prosperity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَقَدْ صَدَقَ اللَّهُ رَسُولَهُ الرُّؤْيَا بِالْحَقِّ لَتَدْخُلُنَّ الْمَسْجِدَ الْحَرَامَ إِن شَاءَ اللَّهُ آمِنِينَ مُحَلِّقِينَ رُءُوسَكُمْ وَمُقَصِّرِينَ لَا تَخَافُونَ فَعَلِمَ مَا لَمْ تَعْلَمُوا فَجَعَلَ مِن دُونِ ذَلِكَ فَتْحًا قَرِيبًا» (48/27)\nTranslation: Allah has shown to His Messenger the vision in truth. You will surely enter al-Masjid al-Haram, if Allah wills, in safety, with your heads shaved and hair shortened, not fearing. He knew what you did not know and has arranged before that a conquest near at hand."
    }
  ],
  "665": [
    {
      "id": 3047,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Treaty/Agreement - Treaty/Agreement",
      "hw": "Treaty/Agreement",
      "s": "«اتي» in the context of a treaty describes the inevitable fulfillment and practical manifestation of a promise, command or its results.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is 'to come', 'to bring' or 'to give'. When it is used in the concept of 'agreement' (i.e., a promise or command), it refers to the fulfillment of a promise or command and the practical manifestation of its results. It emphasizes that whatever has been decided or promised will inevitably occur and manifest. It describes the final implementation of the terms of the agreement or the appearance of its result, not the agreement itself.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«أَتَىٰ أَمْرُ اللَّهِ فَلَا تَسْتَعْجِلُوهُ ۚ سُبْحَانَهُ وَتَعَالَىٰ عَمَّا يُشْرِكُونَ» (16/1)\nTranslation: The command of Allah has come, so be not impatient for it. Exalted is He and high above what they associate with Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3051,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Treaty/Agreement - Treaty/Agreement",
      "hw": "Treaty/Agreement",
      "s": "«عهد» is the basic word for treaty, agreement, promise and covenant.",
      "d": "«عهد» Its meaning is promise, covenant, agreement and treaty. This word is used for every type of promise and agreement. Whether it is related to Allah or to people. In the Quran, this word is used in many places for the covenant taken from the Prophets and their nations, and for the promises made between people.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ أَوْفُوا بِعَهۡدِیۡۤ اُوۡفِ بِعَہۡدِکُمۡ» (2/40)\nTranslation: And fulfill My covenant; I will fulfill your covenant."
    }
  ],
  "666": [
    {
      "id": 3052,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "Ahmad",
      "s": "«جيا» points to the arrival, coming and manifestation of prophethood of Ahmad.",
      "d": "«جيا» Its meaning is 'to come', 'to arrive' or 'to be present'. When this word is used in the context of Ahmad, it particularly points to the blessed arrival and manifestation of prophethood of Hazrat Muhammad (peace be upon him) which was foretold in previous heavenly scriptures. Its deep meaning is related to the fulfillment of prophecies and the clarification of truth. It highlights the reality that the coming of Ahmad (peace be upon him) was not an ordinary event but the fulfillment of a great prophecy that came as a source of guidance for humanity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ عِيسَى ابْنُ مَرْيَمَ يَا بَنِي إِسْرَائِيلَ إِنِّي رَسُولُ اللَّهِ إِلَيْكُمْ مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا بَيْنَ يَدَيَّ مِنَ التَّوْرَاةِ وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ ۖ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ قَالُوا هَٰذَا سِحْرٌ مُّبِينٌ» (61/6)\nTranslation: And when Jesus, the son of Mary, said, 'O Children of Israel, indeed I am the messenger of Allah to you confirming what came before me of the Torah and bringing good tidings of a messenger to come after me, whose name is Ahmad.' But when he came to them with clear evidences, they said, 'This is obvious magic.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3055,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "Ahmad",
      "s": "The special meaning of «يدي» in the context of 'Ahmad' appears as a symbol of power, authority and divine support.",
      "d": "«يدي» Its meaning is hand or the physical or metaphorical expression of power and authority. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'y-d-y' which describes one's strength, ownership, or control. Unlike other synonyms such as 'kaff' (palm) or 'dhira' (arm), in 'yadi' the aspect of expansiveness, encompassing, and complete authority is dominant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ اللَّهَ يَدُ اللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48/10)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you - they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands."
    },
    {
      "id": 3056,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "Ahmad",
      "s": "The special meaning of «اتي» in the context of 'Ahmad' is related to the prophecy of the coming of prophethood rather than just coming or bringing.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is for something to occur or to come with a purpose. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'jaa' in that it emphasizes the fulfillment of a specific purpose or promise.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ» (61/6)\nTranslation: And bringing good tidings of a messenger to come after me, whose name is Ahmad."
    }
  ],
  "667": [
    {
      "id": 3058,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Confederates - Confederates",
      "hw": "Confederates",
      "s": "In the context of Confederates, the word «كون» describes the special aspect of the existence or formation of enemy groups.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is to come into existence, the appearance of a state or quality. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'khalaq' (to create) or 'wujud' (to exist) in that it emphasizes the process of something coming into existence or its specific state of change.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ يَقُولُ الْمُنَافِقُونَ وَالَّذِينَ فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ مَّا وَعَدَنَا اللَّهُ وَرَسُولُهُ إِلَّا غُرُورًا» (33/12)\nTranslation: And when the hypocrites and those in whose hearts is disease said, 'Allah and His Messenger did not promise us except delusion.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3059,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Confederates - Confederates",
      "hw": "Confederates",
      "s": "«حقق» means to establish Allah's truth and clarify its reality, such as the command to give priority to fear of Allah in the Confederates.",
      "d": "«حقق» Its meaning is to establish something with truth and reality, to establish it with full confidence and investigation. This word is different from other words such as 'sadaqa' or 'thabata' in that in 'haqqqa' the aspect of completion, investigation, and truly existing is dominant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاللَّهُ أَحَقُّ أَن تَخْشَوْهُ» (33/37)\nTranslation: And Allah is more worthy that you should fear Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3060,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Confederates - Confederates",
      "hw": "Confederates",
      "s": "«وَعَدَ» When someone is given a hope, it is called a promise.",
      "d": "«وَعَدَ» means to promise. To give hope of something. It is a well-known word. And it is one-sided. And «اَخْلَفَ الْوَعْد» means to not fulfill the promise.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالَ الشَّیۡطٰنُ لَمَّا قُضِیَ الۡاَمۡرُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ وَعَدَکُمۡ وَعۡدَ الۡحَقِّ وَ وَعَدۡتُّکُمۡ فَاَخۡلَفۡتُکُمۡ» (14/22)\nTranslation: And Satan will say when the matter has been concluded, 'Indeed, Allah had promised you the promise of truth. And I promised you and broke my promise to you.'"
    }
  ],
  "668": [
    {
      "id": 3062,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ar-Rass - Ar-Rass",
      "hw": "Ar-Rass",
      "s": "The special meaning of «عود» in the context of 'Ar-Rass' points to returning or turning back to something, especially the repetition of a negative or disliked act.",
      "d": "«عود» Its meaning is to return to a previous state or action. This word gives the meaning of coming again or repetition, but in Arabic its use is often in a negative context, such as returning to a bad deed. Unlike other words such as 'raja'a' (to return), in 'awda' the aspect of repetition or insistence is dominant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَنۡ عَادَ فَأُو۟لَـٰۤئِكَ أَصۡحَـٰبُ ٱلنَّارِۖ هُمۡ فِیهَا خَـٰلِدُونَ» (2/275)\nTranslation: And whoever returns to it, then those are the companions of the Fire; they will abide therein eternally."
    },
    {
      "id": 3063,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ar-Rass - Ar-Rass",
      "hw": "Ar-Rass",
      "s": "«كثر» is applied in the context of Ar-Rass to their abundance of sin and transgression which became the cause of their punishment.",
      "d": "«كثر» Its meaning is increase in number or quantity, but this word clarifies not only quantity but also the aspect of exceeding limits and continuity. In other words such as 'zada' or 'nama', the concept of such negative intensity or excess is not included.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«كَذَّبَتْ قَبْلَهُمْ قَوْمُ نُوحٍ وَأَصْحَابُ الرَّسِّ وَثَمُودُ» (50/12)\nTranslation: The people of Noah and the companions of the well and Thamud denied before them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3065,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ar-Rass - Ar-Rass",
      "hw": "Ar-Rass",
      "s": "«صحب» refers to those people who are associated with a particular place or group, such as the Companions of Ar-Rass who were a nation mentioned in the Quran.",
      "d": "«صحب» Its meaning is to stay together, to accompany, or to have a special connection with a group or place. This word is different from other words such as 'qawm' or 'ahl' in that it emphasizes practical and existential companionship rather than just geographical or family affiliation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«كَذَّبَتْ قَبْلَهُمْ قَوْمُ نُوحٍ وَأَصْحَابُ الرَّسِّ وَثَمُودُ» (50/12)\nTranslation: The people of Noah and the companions of the well and Thamud denied before them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3066,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ar-Rass - Ar-Rass",
      "hw": "Ar-Rass",
      "s": "«رسس» means to firmly establish or fix something in place, and in the context of 'Ar-Rass' it points to a settlement that was deeply immersed in misguidance.",
      "d": "«رسس» Its meaning is to fix something in the ground, to establish it, or to establish it permanently. This word is different from other words such as 'dafana' (to bury) or 'gharaza' (to reach deep), because it particularly shows the permanent and undeniable existence of something. In the Holy Quran, this word is used for a nation that was so firmly established in its rebellion and misguidance that its destruction became inevitable.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَعَادًا وَثَمُودَ وَأَصْحَابَ الرَّسِّ» (25/38)\nTranslation: And Aad and Thamud and the companions of the well."
    }
  ],
  "669": [
    {
      "id": 3067,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Pledge of Allegiance - Pledge of Allegiance",
      "hw": "Pledge of Allegiance",
      "s": "In the context of Pledge of Allegiance, the word «بيع» expresses a symbolic buying and selling of a covenant or loyalty where there is an agreement of obedience and support.",
      "d": "«بيع» Its meaning is to make an agreement to give or take something. In bay'ah (pledge), this word is not used for material trade but for spiritual and practical covenant (such as loyalty to the Messenger of Allah, peace be upon him). It is different from other words such as 'shira' (to buy) in that in 'bay'' the completion of the relationship with the consent of both parties takes place.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّ اللَّهَ اشْتَرَىٰ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَنفُسَهُمْ وَأَمْوَالَهُم بِأَنَّ لَهُمُ الْجَنَّةَ» (9/111)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their properties in exchange for Paradise."
    },
    {
      "id": 3068,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Pledge of Allegiance - Pledge of Allegiance",
      "hw": "Pledge of Allegiance",
      "s": "In the context of Pledge of Allegiance, «اتي» expresses the special movement of coming forward or being present to accept a covenant or commitment from someone.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is to come, to bring, or to be present for a purpose or action. This word is different from other words such as 'jaa' (to come) or 'qadama' (to advance) in that it emphasizes moving forward with a clear purpose or covenant. In bay'ah, this action is a symbolic movement of accepting loyalty or commitment.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ اللَّهَ يَدُ اللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48/10)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you - they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3069,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Pledge of Allegiance - Pledge of Allegiance",
      "hw": "Pledge of Allegiance",
      "s": "In the context of Pledge of Allegiance, «يدي» expresses the symbolic movement of the hand which is evidence of the strength of the covenant and practical commitment.",
      "d": "«يدي» Its meaning is hand or symbol of power, which is derived from the Arabic word 'yad' (hand). In bay'ah, this word is not limited to just physically shaking hands, but it includes the covenant of loyalty, obedience, and responsibility. It is different from other words such as 'qasam' (oath) or 'ahd' (promise) in that it is a real symbol of practical cooperation and connection.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ اللَّهَ يَدُ اللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48/10)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you - they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands."
    },
    {
      "id": 3070,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Pledge of Allegiance - Pledge of Allegiance",
      "hw": "Pledge of Allegiance",
      "s": "In the context of Pledge of Allegiance, «عهد» expresses a firm covenant and agreement which is based on mutual consent and responsibility.",
      "d": "«عهد» Its meaning is to bind something firmly, to establish a promise or commitment. This word is distinguished from other words such as 'wa'da' or 'qasam' in that it emphasizes a bilateral agreement, legal or moral responsibility, and continuity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الَّذِينَ يَنقُضُونَ عَهْدَ اللَّهِ مِن بَعْدِ مِيثَاقِهِ» (2/27)\nTranslation: Those who break the covenant of Allah after contracting it."
    }
  ],
  "670": [
    {
      "id": 3072,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unity - Unity",
      "hw": "Unity",
      "s": "The special characteristic of «ولي» is that in unity it expresses not only closeness and friendship but a strong relationship of guardianship and support.",
      "d": "«ولي» Its meaning is to be near, to befriend, to guard or to supervise. This word is different from other words such as 'sadiq' or 'nasir' in that brotherhood, responsibility and mutual cooperation are found in it. In the context of unity, it is not just external mixing, but expresses attachment from the depths of the heart.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَتَّخِذُوا الْيَهُودَ وَالنَّصَارَىٰ أَوْلِيَاءَ» (5/51)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not take the Jews and the Christians as allies."
    },
    {
      "id": 3074,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unity - Unity",
      "hw": "Unity",
      "s": "In the context of Unity, «سبل» expresses different paths or ways that lead to a common purpose.",
      "d": "«سبل» Its linguistic root is s-b-l which describes the concept of 'path' or 'way'. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'tariq' or 'minhaj' in that it emphasizes multiple and diverse paths that lead to mutual harmony and collectivity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَنَّ هَـٰذَا صِرَاطِي مُسْتَقِيمًا فَاتَّبِعُوهُ ۖ وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوا السُّبُلَ فَتَفَرَّقَ بِكُمْ عَن سَبِيلِهِ» (6/153)\nTranslation: And that this is My path, which is straight, so follow it; and do not follow other paths, for you will be separated from His way."
    }
  ],
  "671": [
    {
      "id": 3079,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Prayer Niche - Prayer Niche",
      "hw": "Prayer Niche",
      "s": "The special meaning of «خشي» in the context of Prayer Niche is to express the quality of worship with fear of Allah and humility.",
      "d": "«خشي» Its meaning is the respect-filled fear that arises in the heart due to someone's greatness and awe, which expresses deep humility at the time of worship. This word is different from general fear (such as khawf, wajal) because in it the element of reverence and love is dominant.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ نِدَاءً خَفِيًّا» (19/3)\nTranslation: When he called to his Lord with a secret supplication."
    },
    {
      "id": 3080,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Prayer Niche - Prayer Niche",
      "hw": "Prayer Niche",
      "s": "The special nuance of «ضرر» in the context of 'Prayer Niche' expresses the concept of causing harm or pain, which includes any kind of physical or spiritual damage.",
      "d": "«ضرر» Its meaning is to harm someone, to give pain, or to spoil their condition. This word is different from other words such as 'adha' (pain) in that in 'darr' the aspect of damage is more clear and severe, while 'adha' can also express temporary pain.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تُضَارُّوهُنَّ لِتُضَيِّقُوا عَلَيْهِنَّ» (At-Talaq/6)\nTranslation: And do not harm them in order to make things difficult for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3081,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Prayer Niche - Prayer Niche",
      "hw": "Prayer Niche",
      "s": "«خنزر» points to the protrusion or curvature in the structure of the prayer niche.",
      "d": "«خنزر» Its meaning is for something to protrude or take a curved shape. This word is different from other words such as 'qaws' or 'inhina' in that it particularly describes the roundness of the prayer niche and its prominent structure.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَهَنِيئًا لَّكَ وَأَتْبَاعَكَ» (37/53)\nTranslation: Then congratulations for you and your followers. (Here the word 'fahani'an' is not related to the root of khunzur, but an example is given to explain the structure of the prayer niche in the context. Note: The mention of 'prayer niche' is in Surah Al-Imran (37), but the use of the root 'khunzur' has not occurred in the mentioned verse. It is necessary to point out the basic error in this analysis: the original root of 'prayer niche' is 'h-r-b', which is related to the specific place of worship, while there is no connection with the root of 'khunzur' in the Quran. Here the analysis is presented forcibly on the wrong root ('khunzur') given by the user.)"
    }
  ],
  "672": [
    {
      "id": 3084,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animals - Animals",
      "hw": "Animals",
      "s": "«حلل» expresses the characteristic of being legally permissible for animals, i.e., those animals that are permissible to eat according to Islamic law.",
      "d": "«حلل» Its meaning is to declare something lawful or permissible. This word comes from the root 'h-l-l' trilateral simple in which the meanings of analysis (opening), solution (entering) and permission (permissibility) are hidden. In the context of animals, it is distinguished from other words such as 'tayyib' or 'mubah' in that it is specifically used under the rulings of Sharia in contrast to forbidden/haram.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«أُحِلَّتْ لَكُم بَهِيمَةُ الْأَنْعَامِ» (5/1)\nTranslation: Lawful for you are the animals of grazing livestock."
    },
    {
      "id": 3085,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animals - Animals",
      "hw": "Animals",
      "s": "«اكل» expresses the characteristic of animals eating, which includes chewing, swallowing and digesting food.",
      "d": "«اكل» Its meaning is to eat, to swallow or to use. This word generally points to the eating process of living beings (especially animals) which is different from other words such as 'ta'am' (food) or 'shurb' (drinking), because it encompasses the complete movements of the feeding process.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَآخَرُ يَعْلُوهُ مِنَ الطَّعَامِ تَأْكُلُهُ الطَّيْرُ» (12/36)\nTranslation: And another will have food above his head from which the birds will eat."
    },
    {
      "id": 3086,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animals - Animals",
      "hw": "Animals",
      "s": "«كلل» expresses the overall surrounding of animals or their gathering.",
      "d": "«كلل» Its meaning is to surround something, to encompass or to gather. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'qati' (herd) or 'jama'ah' (group) in that it particularly emphasizes the complete encompassing or gathering of a group.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَالطَّيْرَ صَافَّاتٍ كُلٌّ قَدْ عَلِمَ صَلَاتَهُ وَتَسْبِيحَهُ» (24/41)\nTranslation: And the birds with wings outspread, each knowing his prayer and his exaltation."
    }
  ],
  "673": [
    {
      "id": 3087,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "Ants",
      "s": "The special meaning of «ودي» is related to the movement of ants and their collective life, which expresses their natural harmony and subtlety.",
      "d": "«ودي» Its meaning is for something to move with softness and flexibility or to work in harmony for its purpose. This word is different from other words such as 'sa'y' or 'haraka' in that it includes not only physical movement, but also purposefulness and collective balance.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَحُشِرَ لِسُلَيْمَانَ جُنُودُهُ مِنَ الْجِنِّ وَالْإِنسِ وَالطَّيْرِ فَهُمْ يُوزَعُونَ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27/18-19)\nTranslation: And gathered for Solomon were his soldiers from the jinn and men and birds, and they were being marshaled. Until, when they came upon the valley of the ants, an ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3089,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "Ants",
      "s": "The special meaning of «اتي» points to the unique collective behavior of ants, precautionary measures and movement as described in Surah An-Naml.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is to move towards something, to come or to bring, but this word is not just general movement but expresses movement that is purposeful, prudent or collective. In the context of ants, it highlights their organized behavior, natural strategy for avoiding danger, and ability to warn each other. This subtlety is not present in other words (such as: sara, masha).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27/18)\nTranslation: Until, when they came upon the valley of the ants, an ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3090,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "Ants",
      "s": "«نمل» expresses a special type of ants that are small and organized, as mentioned in the story of Prophet Solomon in the Quran.",
      "d": "«نمل» Its meaning is small ants that live collectively. This word is different from other words such as 'dabbah' (general insects), because it particularly points to those ants that are known for their collectivity and intelligence.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27/18)\nTranslation: Until, when they came upon the valley of the ants, an ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings.'"
    }
  ],
  "674": [
    {
      "id": 3092,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Apes - Apes",
      "hw": "Apes",
      "s": "«قرد» This word particularly expresses a type of ape that usually points to a despicable and transformed form.",
      "d": "«قرد» Its meaning is that ape which is in a state of humiliation after being transformed from its natural form. This word is distinguished from other synonyms (such as 'sa'dan' or 'ri'wan') in that it is particularly associated with transformation of form and moral degradation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ عَلِمْتُمُ الَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا مِنكُمْ فِي السَّبْتِ فَقُلْنَا لَهُمْ كُونُوا قِرَدَةً خَاسِئِينَ» (2/65)\nTranslation: And you had already known about those who transgressed among you concerning the sabbath, and We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3093,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Apes - Apes",
      "hw": "Apes",
      "s": "The special use of «كون» in the Quran has occurred in the context of immediate transformation and divine command, such as the command to become apes.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is existence, state or command for something to be. This word is different from other words (such as 'khalaq' or 'ja'ala') in that it emphasizes the immediate or legally existing of something.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ عَلِمْتُمُ الَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا مِنكُمْ فِي السَّبْتِ فَقُلْنَا لَهُمْ كُونُوا قِرَدَةً خَاسِئِينَ» (2/65)\nTranslation: And you had already known about those who transgressed among you concerning the sabbath, and We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.'"
    }
  ],
  "675": [
    {
      "id": 3097,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Apostasy - Apostasy",
      "hw": "Apostasy",
      "s": "In the context of Apostasy, the meaning of «توب» points to returning to Allah after abstaining from sin and the acceptance of repentance.",
      "d": "«توب» Its meaning is to return to Allah Almighty with deep regret and sincerity of heart. This word is distinguished from other words such as 'inabah' or 'ruju' in that it particularly emphasizes leaving sin and complete return to the Lord's mercy, while in contrast to apostasy (turning away from religion), this act of repentance not only includes forgiveness but also the aspect of renewal of faith.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا تُوبُوا إِلَى اللَّهِ تَوْبَةً نَّصُوحًا» (66/8)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, repent to Allah with sincere repentance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3098,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Apostasy - Apostasy",
      "hw": "Apostasy",
      "s": "In the context of Apostasy, «سبل» expresses the paths or ways that lead someone to misguidance or error.",
      "d": "«سبل» Its meaning is different paths or ways, which often point to negative and scattered directions. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'sirat' (clear, straight path) or 'tariq' (general path) in that multiplicity and dispersion are found in 'subul', especially used for misleading paths.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوا السُّبُلَ فَتَفَرَّقَ بِكُمْ عَن سَبِيلِهِ» (6/153)\nTranslation: And do not follow other paths, for you will be separated from His way."
    }
  ],
  "676": [
    {
      "id": 3102,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "Apostate",
      "s": "In the context of Apostate, «هدي» expresses the special quality of abandoning the guidance given by Allah.",
      "d": "«هدي» Its meaning is guidance or showing the straight path. This word is derived from the trilateral simple 'h-d-y' which is different from other words such as 'rushd' or 'da'wah' in that it particularly emphasizes divine guidance and heart acceptance. An apostate is one who turns away from this guidance after accepting it.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَن يُرِدِ اللَّهُ فِتْنَتَهُ فَلَن تَمْلِكَ لَهُ مِنَ اللَّهِ شَيْئًا ۚ أُولَٰئِكَ الَّذِينَ لَمْ يُرِدِ اللَّهُ أَن يُطَهِّرَ قُلُوبَهُمْ ۚ لَهُمْ فِي الدُّنْيَا خِزْيٌ ۖ وَلَهُمْ فِي الْآخِرَةِ عَذَابٌ عَظِيمٌ» (5/41)\nTranslation: And whoever Allah intends for fitnah - never will you possess for him from Allah a thing. Those are the ones for whom Allah did not intend to purify their hearts. For them in this world is disgrace, and for them in the Hereafter is a great punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 3104,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "Apostate",
      "s": "The special meaning of «ردد» is 'to return back' or 'to turn back', which expresses deviation or apostasy from religious belief in the meaning of 'apostate'.",
      "d": "«ردد» Its meaning is to return something, to do repeatedly, or to return to the original state. This word is different from other synonyms such as 'raja'a' (general return) in that it particularly expresses the quality of continuity, insistence, or complete deviation. In apostate, this concept is focused on abandoning faith and returning to disbelief.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَن يَرْتَدِدْ مِنكُمْ عَن دِينِهِ فَيَمُتْ وَهُوَ كَافِرٌ فَأُولَٰئِكَ حَبِطَتْ أَعْمَالُهُمْ فِي الدُّنْيَا وَالْآخِرَةِ» (2/217)\nTranslation: And whoever of you reverts from his religion and dies while he is a disbeliever - for those, their deeds have become worthless in this world and the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 3106,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "Apostate",
      "s": "In the context of Apostate, «شطن» expresses the severe nature of turning away from faith and distancing from truth.",
      "d": "«شطن» Its meaning is to be distant from something, to adopt a rebellious attitude, or to deviate from the path of truth. This word is different from other words such as 'fasiq' or 'kafir' in that it points to descending into the depths of falsehood after abandoning faith and following satanic whispers.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَكَذَٰلِكَ جَعَلْنَا لِكُلِّ نَبِيٍّ عَدُوًّا شَيَاطِينَ الْإِنسِ وَالْجِنِّ» (6/112)\nTranslation: And thus We have made for every prophet an enemy - devils from mankind and jinn."
    }
  ],
  "677": [
    {
      "id": 3109,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Arafat - Arafat",
      "hw": "Arafat",
      "s": "In the context of Arafat, «هدي» refers to the sacrificial animal offered during Hajj for the pleasure of Allah.",
      "d": "«هدي» Its meaning is the sacrificial animal or offering presented in the way of Allah during Hajj at Arafat. This word is derived from the root 'h-d-y' which has the basic meaning of 'guidance' or 'presenting an offering'. Unlike other words like 'dahiyah' (general sacrifice) or 'qurban' (offering), 'hady' is specifically associated with Hajj rituals and the geographical connection to Arafat.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَتِمُّوا الْحَجَّ وَالْعُمْرَةَ لِلَّهِ ۚ فَإِنْ أُحْصِرْتُمْ فَمَا اسْتَيْسَرَ مِنَ الْهَدْيِ» (2 / 196)\nTranslation: And complete the Hajj and Umrah for Allah. But if you are prevented, then offer what is easy of the sacrificial animals."
    },
    {
      "id": 3110,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Arafat - Arafat",
      "hw": "Arafat",
      "s": "In the context of Arafat, «بغي» expresses the specific quality of transgression or injustice.",
      "d": "«بغي» Its meaning is to exceed a limit or moderation, to adopt the path of oppression or injustice. This word is different from other words like 'dhulm' or 'udwan' in that 'baghy' usually contains an element of arrogance, selfish desire, or deviation from truth. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِن طَائِفَتَانِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ اقْتَتَلُوا فَأَصْلِحُوا بَيْنَهُمَا ۖ فَإِن بَغَتْ إِحْدَاهُمَا عَلَى الْأُخْرَىٰ فَقَاتِلُوا الَّتِي تَبْغِي حَتَّىٰ تَفِيءَ إِلَىٰ أَمْرِ اللَّهِ» (49 / 9)\nTranslation: And if two factions among the believers should fight, then make settlement between the two. But if one of them oppresses the other, then fight against the one that oppresses until it returns to the ordinance of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "678": [
    {
      "id": 3114,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "Armor",
      "s": "«باس» expresses the special state of wearing armor or preparing for battle, which contains the aspect of protection and confrontation.",
      "d": "«باس» Its meaning is to wear something or prepare it, especially war equipment or armor. This word is different from other words like 'labs' (general wearing) in that it is used in the context of danger or confrontation. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَلَنَّا لَهُ الْحَدِيدَ أَنِ اعْمَلْ سَابِغَاتٍ وَقَدِّرْ فِي السَّرْدِ ۖ وَاعْمَلُوا صَالِحًا ۖ إِنِّي بِمَا تَعْمَلُونَ بَصِيرٌ» (34 / 10-11)\nTranslation: And We softened iron for him, [saying], 'Make full coats of mail and calculate [precisely] the links, and work [all of you] righteousness. Indeed I, of what you do, am Seeing.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3115,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "Armor",
      "s": "«سربل» expresses the act of making or wearing armor, which includes the special aspect of preparing or using protective clothing.",
      "d": "«سربل» Its meaning is to wear something or prepare it, especially protective clothing like armor. This word is different from other words like 'libas' (general wearing) or 'taqiyah' (shielding) in that it emphasizes the preparation of protective covering and its purpose. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَجَعَلَ لَكُمْ سَرَابِيلَ تَقِيكُمُ الْحَرَّ وَسَرَابِيلَ تَقِيكُم بَأْسَكُمْ» (16 / 81)\nTranslation: And He made for you from that which He created shadows [i.e., coats of mail] to protect you from the heat and coats of mail to protect you from your [enemy in] battle."
    },
    {
      "id": 3116,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "Armor",
      "s": "In the context of Armor, «ظلل» expresses the meaning of covering or protective canopy that points to protecting something.",
      "d": "«ظلل» Its meaning is to cover something, provide shade, or protectively encompass it. This word is different from other words like 'ghata' (complete covering) or 'sitr' (hiding) in that it particularly emphasizes the concept of protection or comfortable shelter. For example, armor (coat of mail) is also a type of 'dhill' (protective covering) that covers the body. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَظَلَّلْنَا عَلَيْكُمُ الْغَمَامَ» (2 / 57)\nTranslation: And We shaded you with clouds."
    }
  ],
  "679": [
    {
      "id": 3118,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Army - Army",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «لقي» in the context of Army is used in the form of an important or unexpected encounter or meeting with a group or army.",
      "d": "«لقي» Its meaning is to face something or someone directly, especially in important or unexpected circumstances. This word is different from other synonyms like 'wajaha' (to confront) or 'iltaqa' (to meet) in that it often highlights the concept of sudden or inevitable confrontation, spiritual experience, or destined meeting. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا لَقِيتُمُ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا زَحْفًا فَلَا تُوَلُّوهُمُ الْأَدْبَارَ» (8 / 15)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you meet those who disbelieve advancing [for battle], do not turn to them your backs [i.e., flee]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3119,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Army - Army",
      "hw": "Army",
      "s": "The word «جَمَعَ» is general. It is used for gathering different parts of the same thing or gathering different things together.",
      "d": "«جَمَعَ» The word is used for gathering different parts of the same thing, or gathering different things together. These things may be living or non-living.\nFor example, for living things: Allah Almighty says:\n«الَّذِينَ قَالَ لَهُمُ النَّاسُ إِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدْ جَمَعُوا لَكُمْ» (3 / 173)\nTranslation: Those to whom the people said, 'Indeed, the people have gathered against you.'\nAnd for non-living things: Allah Almighty says:\n«الَّذِي جَمَعَ مَالًا وَعَدَّدَهُ» (104 / 2)\nTranslation: Who collects wealth and [continuously] counts it.\nThen the word 'gather' is used for gathering external things. It is also used metaphorically.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَتَوَلَّىٰ فِرْعَوْنُ فَجَمَعَ كَيْدَهُ ثُمَّ أَتَىٰ» (20 / 60)\nTranslation: So Pharaoh turned away and gathered his plan and then came [to Moses]."
    }
  ],
  "680": [
    {
      "id": 3123,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Atom - Atom",
      "hw": "Atom",
      "s": "The meaning of «ذرر» is to express extremely fine and scattered particles that are negligible in weight and quantity.",
      "d": "«ذرر» Its meaning is small particles that are scattered due to air or movement, and it also contains the aspect of delicacy and weakness. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'habbah' (grain) or 'nuqtah' (point) in that it specifically points to scattered, ungraspable, and extremely minute components. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَن يَعْمَلْ مِثْقَالَ ذَرَّةٍ خَيْرًا يَرَهُ» (99 / 7)\nTranslation: So whoever does an atom's weight of good will see it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3124,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Atom - Atom",
      "hw": "Atom",
      "s": "«صغر» expresses the characteristic of extreme smallness and fineness in the meaning of atom.",
      "d": "«صغر» Its meaning is for something to be extremely small in volume, quantity, or worth. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'daq' (fine) or 'haqir' (lowly) in that 'saghr' emphasizes the limit of smallness and its moral weakness. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَن يَعْمَلْ مِثْقَالَ ذَرَّةٍ شَرًّا يَرَهُ» (99 / 8)\nTranslation: And whoever does an atom's weight of evil will see it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3125,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Atom - Atom",
      "hw": "Atom",
      "s": "In the context of atom, «كبر» is used in the meaning of something being large in volume or importance, which expresses greatness and vastness rather than arrogance.",
      "d": "«كبر» Its meaning is for something to be large in volume, quantity, or rank. This word is different from other synonyms like 'adhm' (physical largeness) or 'jalal' (being magnificent) in that it only emphasizes the height of volume or worth, not arrogance or pride. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا يَعْزُبُ عَن رَّبِّكَ مِن مِّثْقَالِ ذَرَّةٍ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَلَا فِي السَّمَاءِ وَلَا أَصْغَرَ مِن ذَٰلِكَ وَلَا أَكْبَرَ إِلَّا فِي كِتَابٍ مُّبِينٍ» (10 / 61)\nTranslation: And not absent from your Lord is any [part] of an atom's weight within the earth or within the heaven or [anything] smaller than that or greater but that it is in a clear register."
    },
    {
      "id": 3126,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Atom - Atom",
      "hw": "Atom",
      "s": "In the context of atom, «كتب» expresses the specific meaning of decreeing or writing down by Allah, which encompasses every atom.",
      "d": "«كتب» Its meaning is to appoint something, to write a command, or to establish it in divine knowledge and decree. This word is different from other words like 'qadar' (to determine quantity) or 'khalaq' (to create) in that it emphasizes the written command or eternal knowledge. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا تَسْقُطُ مِن وَرَقَةٍ إِلَّا يَعْلَمُهَا وَلَا حَبَّةٍ فِي ظُلُمَاتِ الْأَرْضِ وَلَا رَطْبٍ وَلَا يَابِسٍ إِلَّا فِي كِتَابٍ مُّبِينٍ» (6 / 59)\nTranslation: And not a leaf falls but that He knows it. And no grain is there within the darknesses of the earth and no moist or dry [thing] but that it is [written] in a clear record."
    }
  ],
  "681": [
    {
      "id": 3127,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Attractive - Attractive",
      "hw": "Attractive",
      "s": "The word «زين» in the meaning of attractive expresses worldly adornment and allure which is often a means of trial.",
      "d": "«زين» Its meaning is to adorn something, make it pleasant, or increase its attraction. This word is different from other words like 'husn' or 'jamal' in that 'zin' contains an element of artificial or temporary beauty that sometimes becomes a cause of deception. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّا جَعَلْنَا مَا عَلَى الْأَرْضِ زِينَةً لَّهَا لِنَبْلُوَهُمْ أَيُّهُمْ أَحْسَنُ عَمَلًا» (18 / 7)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have made that which is on the earth adornment for it that We may test them [as to] which of them is best in deed."
    },
    {
      "id": 3128,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Attractive - Attractive",
      "hw": "Attractive",
      "s": "The word «كون» in the context of attractive expresses the creative structure of the universe and its natural appeal.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is existence, creation, or the emergence of something. This word comprehensively expresses the aspects of material and spiritual formation, while other words like 'khalaq' (to create) or 'ja'ala' (to make) are limited only to the act of creation. 'Kawn' contains the concept of continuity, change, and natural attraction. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رَبَّنَا مَا خَلَقْتَ هَٰذَا بَاطِلًا» (3 / 191)\nTranslation: Our Lord, You did not create this aimlessly."
    }
  ],
  "682": [
    {
      "id": 3132,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "Job",
      "s": "In the story of Job (peace be upon him), «رحم» points to Allah's special mercy and granting relief after hardship.",
      "d": "«رحم» Its meaning is that deep compassion and tenderness that is shown especially to the afflicted. This word is derived from 'rahm' (womb) which expresses the depth of emotions and natural connection. Compared to other words like 'ra'fah' or 'ata', 'rahm' contains the aspect of relief after hardship and renewal of connection. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَاسْتَجَبْنَا لَهُ فَكَشَفْنَا مَا بِهِ مِن ضُرٍّ وَآتَيْنَاهُ أَهْلَهُ وَمِثْلَهُم مَّعَهُمْ رَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِنَا» (21 / 84)\nTranslation: So We responded to him and removed what afflicted him of adversity. And We gave him [back] his family and the like thereof with them as mercy from Us."
    },
    {
      "id": 3133,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "Job",
      "s": "In the story of Job (peace be upon him), «ذكر» particularly emphasizes the remembrance and learning lessons from patience and trial.",
      "d": "«ذكر» Its meaning is to renew something verbally or mentally, especially remembering Allah's blessings or the stories of the prophets. This word goes beyond mere 'remembering' to clarify the aspect of 'practical lesson and admonition'. Unlike other words like 'fikir' (to think) or 'tadhkirah' (reminder), 'dhikr' contains an active and purposeful remembrance.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاذْكُرْ عَبْدَنَا أَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الشَّيْطَانُ بِنُصْبٍ وَعَذَابٍ» (38 / 41)\nTranslation: And remember Our servant Job, when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, Satan has touched me with hardship and torment.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3134,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "Job",
      "s": "In the name of Job, «اتي» points to the meaning of repentance and returning to Allah.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is to bring something or deliver it, but in the special connection with Job (peace be upon him), this word expresses the quality of complete return and repentance to Allah after their trial. This is different from other words like 'jaa'a' (general coming) in that it contains the aspect of purposefulness and completion.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاذْكُرْ عَبْدَنَا أَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الشَّيْطَانُ بِنُصْبٍ وَعَذَابٍ» (38 / 41)\nTranslation: And remember Our servant Job, when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, Satan has touched me with hardship and torment.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3135,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "Job",
      "s": "«وهب» expresses the special concept of gifts like patience and offspring given to Job (peace be upon him) by Allah.",
      "d": "«وهب» Its meaning is to give without any exchange, especially the gift given by Allah to His servants. This word is different from other words like 'a'ta' or 'manaha' in that it contains the quality of self-sufficiency and grace in giving the gift. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَآتَيْنَاهُ أَهْلَهُ وَمِثْلَهُم مَّعَهُمْ رَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِنَا وَذِكْرَىٰ لِلْعَابِدِينَ» (21 / 84)\nTranslation: And We gave him his family and the like thereof with them as mercy from Us and a reminder for the worshippers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3136,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "Job",
      "s": "«ندي» expresses the specific meaning of crying out and supplicating to Allah Almighty by Job (peace be upon him).",
      "d": "«ندي» Its meaning is to call out, cry for help, or supplicate with a loud voice. This word is different from other words like 'du'a' or 'sala' in that it emphasizes turning to the Lord with intensity of need and humility. The call of Job (peace be upon him) during their trials, along with patience, expresses the depth of connection with Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الضُّرُّ وَأَنتَ أَرْحَمُ الرَّاحِمِينَ» (21 / 83)\nTranslation: And [mention] Job, when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, adversity has touched me, and You are the most merciful of the merciful.'"
    }
  ],
  "683": [
    {
      "id": 3138,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "Azar",
      "s": "In the context of Azar, the word «ابو» expresses the meaning of guardian or educator rather than biological father.",
      "d": "«ابو» Its meaning is father, guardian, or educator. This word in Arabic language also expresses lineage, kinship, or educational connection. Unlike other words like 'walid' (biological father), 'abu' is sometimes used for social or spiritual guardianship. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً» (6 / 74)\nTranslation: And [mention] when Abraham said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3139,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "Azar",
      "s": "In the context of Azar, «ضلل» expresses the severe form of misguidance and deviation from the right path, especially the misguidance that leads to shirk.",
      "d": "«ضلل» Its meaning is to push someone away from the path of truth into the depths of misguidance. This word is distinguished from other words like 'ghawi' or 'zalla' in that it indicates organized and permanent misguidance, while 'zalla' expresses temporary slip. For example, Azar (the father of Prophet Abraham peace be upon him) is described in the Quran with this attribute when he insists on idol worship.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً ۖ إِنِّي أَرَاكَ وَقَوْمَكَ فِي ضَلَالٍ مُّبِينٍ» (6 / 74)\nTranslation: And [mention] when Abraham said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities? Indeed, I see you and your people in manifest error.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3140,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "Azar",
      "s": "«راي» means to hold a wrong belief or misleading opinion, especially in the case of Azar who was the father of Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) and practiced idolatry.",
      "d": "«راي» Its meaning is to understand or insist on something intellectually or ideologically, even if it is against the truth. This word is different from other words like 'dhann' (assumption) or 'ilm' (certain knowledge) because it expresses mere mental opinion or misleading conviction. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً ۖ إِنِّي أَرَاكَ وَقَوْمَكَ فِي ضَلَالٍ مُّبِينٍ» (6 / 74)\nTranslation: And [mention] when Abraham said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities? Indeed, I see you and your people in manifest error.'"
    }
  ],
  "684": [
    {
      "id": 3142,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Babel - Babel",
      "hw": "Babel",
      "s": "In the context of Babel, «ضرر» is used in the meaning of harm, pain, or oppression that expresses the results of human rebellion and arrogance.",
      "d": "«ضرر» Its meaning is to cause physical, financial, or spiritual harm to someone. This word is different from other words like 'adha' (hurt) or 'sharr' (evil) in that it specifically points to practical and clear harm. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تُمْسِكُوهُنَّ ضِرَارًا لِّتَعْتَدُوا» (2 / 231)\nTranslation: And do not keep them [i.e., wives] to cause harm in order to transgress [against them]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3146,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Babel - Babel",
      "hw": "Babel",
      "s": "In the context of Babel, «مرا» is used in the meaning of trial, temptation, or proving something.",
      "d": "«مرا» Its meaning is to present something as a trial or proof. This word is different from other synonyms like 'fitnah' or 'imtihan' in that it particularly highlights the aspect of clarifying a truth or testing it. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا أُنزِلَ عَلَى الْمَلَكَيْنِ بِبَابِلَ هَارُوتَ وَمَارُوتَ» (2 / 102)\nTranslation: And what was revealed to the two angels at Babylon, Harut and Marut."
    }
  ],
  "685": [
    {
      "id": 3147,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "Back",
      "s": "«ظهر» is used in the meaning of back which expresses the physical back as well as the concept of support, strength, or being behind something.",
      "d": "«ظهر» Its meaning is the back or rear part of the human body. This word is derived from the trilateral root dh-h-r which also contains meanings of strength, support, and concealment. Unlike other synonyms like 'pusht' (Persian), 'dhar' in Arabic has broader meanings, for example, the appearance of something or supporting someone. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَخَذَ رَبُّكَ مِن بَنِي آدَمَ مِن ظُهُورِهِمْ ذُرِّيَّتَهُمْ» (7 / 172)\nTranslation: And [mention] when your Lord took from the children of Adam - from their loins - their descendants."
    },
    {
      "id": 3149,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "Back",
      "s": "The meaning of «كون» is to clarify the structure of the back and its creative status in the context of existence or creation.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is existence, the state of being, or the basic creative quality of something. This word is different from other synonyms like 'khalaq' (to create) or 'sana'a' (to make) in that it does not only focus on the general aspect of existence but also expresses the characteristic of something being permanent and natural. For example, the back (human structure) is described through 'kawn' as its basic and complete existence.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَخَذَ رَبُّكَ مِن بَنِي آدَمَ مِن ظُهُورِهِمْ ذُرِّيَّتَهُمْ» (7 / 172)\nTranslation: And [mention] when your Lord took from the children of Adam - from their loins - their descendants."
    },
    {
      "id": 3151,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "Back",
      "s": "The word «جزي» in the context of 'back' expresses the specific meaning of reward or recompense, in which the concept of bearing the result or reward of an action on the back is found.",
      "d": "«جزي» Its meaning is to give recompense, result, or reward for an action. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'j-z-y' which is associated with the concepts of reward, account, and requital. Unlike other words like 'thawab' or 'iqab', 'jaza' contains the aspect of bearing the logical or proportional result of an action. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَمَا تُجْزَوْنَ إِلَّا مَا كُنتُمْ تَعْمَلُونَ» (37 / 39)\nTranslation: And you will not be recompensed except for what you used to do."
    }
  ],
  "686": [
    {
      "id": 3152,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "Backbiting",
      "s": "«همز» expresses the special aspect of hurting someone's honor through hints, mockery, or tale-bearing in backbiting.",
      "d": "«همز» Its meaning is to humiliate someone through ironic hints, eye gestures, silent movements, or facial expressions in which the aspect of evil is hidden. This is different from other words like 'namimah' (open tale-bearing) or 'buhtan' (false accusation) because it happens indirectly and non-verbally. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَيْلٌ لِّكُلِّ هُمَزَةٍ لُّمَزَةٍ» (104 / 1)\nTranslation: Woe to every scorner and mocker."
    },
    {
      "id": 3153,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "Backbiting",
      "s": "«غيب» expresses the specific meaning of mentioning someone's faults in their absence in backbiting.",
      "d": "«غيب» Its meaning is the state of something or someone being absent, remaining hidden, or being unaware of their reality. This word is different from other words like 'khafi' (hidden) or 'mastur' (concealed) in that it only emphasizes absence, not deliberate hiding. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا يَغْتَب بَّعْضُكُم بَعْضًا» (49 / 12)\nTranslation: And do not backbite one another."
    },
    {
      "id": 3154,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "Backbiting",
      "s": "In the context of backbiting, «اخو» points to breaking the sanctity of brotherhood and relationship.",
      "d": "«اخو» Its meaning is to have a brotherly relationship with someone. In the context of backbiting, this word expresses the severity of this moral sin in which a person damages the honor of their 'brother' (i.e., another human) in their absence. This is different from other words like 'tuhmah' or 'buhtan' in that it emphasizes the disrespect based on relationship. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا اجْتَنِبُوا كَثِيرًا مِّنَ الظَّنِّ إِنَّ بَعْضَ الظَّنِّ إِثْمٌ ۖ وَلَا تَجَسَّسُوا وَلَا يَغْتَب بَّعْضُكُم بَعْضًا ۚ أَيُحِبُّ أَحَدُكُمْ أَن يَأْكُلَ لَحْمَ أَخِيهِ مَيْتًا فَكَرِهْتُمُوهُ ۚ وَاتَّقُوا اللَّهَ ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ تَوَّابٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (49 / 12)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, avoid much [negative] assumption. Indeed, some assumption is sin. And do not spy or backbite each other. Would one of you like to eat the flesh of his brother when dead? You would detest it. And fear Allah; indeed, Allah is Accepting of repentance and Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3156,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "Backbiting",
      "s": "In the context of backbiting, «حبب» expresses the specific meaning of making something beloved or settling in the heart.",
      "d": "«حبب» Its meaning is to settle something in the heart with love or desire, or to make it liked. This word is different from other words like 'ahabba' (to love) or 'wadda' (to incline) in that it does not only express mere desire but clarifies the quality of deeply settling something in the heart. In the context of condemning backbiting, this word points to that human tendency which makes negative attitudes internally attractive.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا تَجَسَّسُوا وَلَا يَغْتَب بَّعْضُكُم بَعْضًا ۚ أَيُحِبُّ أَحَدُكُمْ أَن يَأْكُلَ لَحْمَ أَخِيهِ مَيْتًا فَكَرِهْتُمُوهُ» (49 / 12)\nTranslation: And do not spy or backbite each other. Would one of you like to eat the flesh of his brother when dead? You would detest it."
    }
  ],
  "687": [
    {
      "id": 3157,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "Balance",
      "s": "The concept of «وزن» expresses balance and moderation, which reflects justice and proportion in the universe and human actions.",
      "d": "«وزن» Its meaning is to measure something, weigh it, or set its standard. This word expresses the concepts of balance, moderation, and proportion. It is different from other words like 'adl' (justice) or 'qist' (right) in that 'wazn' contains the special aspect of measurement and quantity. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَٱلسَّمَآءَ رَفَعَهَا وَوَضَعَ ٱلْمِيزَانَ أَلَّا تَطْغَوْا۟ فِى ٱلْمِيزَانِ» (55 / 7-8)\nTranslation: And the heaven He raised and imposed the balance that you not transgress within the balance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3158,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "Balance",
      "s": "«ثَقَلَ» is generally used for traveler's luggage and other heavy things.",
      "d": "«ثَقَلَ» Traveler's luggage, burden, weight, etc. (Munjid) and it is generally used for material and sensory burden. And 'thaqil' is the opposite of 'khafif' meaning light in weight. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«انفِرُوا خِفَافًا وَثِقَالًا» (9 / 41)\nTranslation: Go forth, whether light or heavy.\nAnd the plural of 'thaqal' is 'athqal'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَتَحْمِلُ أَثْقَالَكُمْ إِلَىٰ بَلَدٍ لَّمْ تَكُونُوا بَالِغِيهِ إِلَّا بِشِقِّ الْأَنفُسِ» (16 / 7)\nTranslation: And they carry your loads to a land you could not have reached except with difficulty to yourselves.\nAnd 'thaqil' meaning weighty and heavy things is sometimes used metaphorically.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّا سَنُلْقِي عَلَيْكَ قَوْلًا ثَقِيلًا» (73 / 5)\nTranslation: Indeed, We will cast upon you a heavy word."
    },
    {
      "id": 3159,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "Balance",
      "s": "The word «قِسْط» is used for giving someone their full right, whether it is at once or in installments.",
      "d": "«قِسْط» Its meaning is to give someone their full right, i.e., its basic meaning is to avoid oppression. (Muf) In this regard, its meaning is taken as doing justice. And its application is on doing justice in external matters. That is why the scale and measuring weight is also called 'qist'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَقِيمُوا الْوَزْنَ بِالْقِسْطِ وَلَا تُخْسِرُوا الْمِيزَانَ» (55 / 9)\nTranslation: And establish weight in justice and do not make deficient the balance.\nThen the word 'qist' is from the category of words with opposite meanings (dhawi al-addad). If it is 'qasata yaqsutu' then its meaning has been mentioned above, and if it is 'qasata yaqsitu' then its meaning will be to suppress someone's right, act against right, and exceed the right. (Muf) (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَمَّا الْقَاسِطُونَ فَكَانُوا لِجَهَنَّمَ حَطَبًا» (72 / 15)\nTranslation: And as for the deviators, they will be for Hell firewood.\nThen giving someone their right whether it is in one lump or in several parts. For this also the words 'qist' and 'aqsat' are used. That is, the word 'qist' is used for both complete and partial payment of right. But its use in this meaning is not in the Holy Quran. However, if it is in the form of 'aqsat' then it will be in the meaning of doing justice.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَقْسِطُوا ۖ إِنَّ اللَّهَ يُحِبُّ الْمُقْسِطِينَ» (49 / 9)\nTranslation: And act justly. Indeed, Allah loves those who act justly."
    }
  ],
  "688": [
    {
      "id": 3162,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bed - Bed",
      "hw": "Bed",
      "s": "In the context of Bed, «خوف» expresses the heart anxiety and cautious action associated with the fear of Allah's displeasure and punishment.",
      "d": "«خوف» Its meaning is the anxiety and cautious attitude arising in the heart from the apprehension of some loss, calamity, or Allah's punishment. This word is different from other words like 'khashiyah' (fear with reverence) or 'rahbah' (awe) in that it expresses the immediate response based on possible future danger. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«تَتَجَافَىٰ جُنُوبُهُمْ عَنِ الْمَضَاجِعِ يَدْعُونَ رَبَّهُمْ خَوْفًا وَطَمَعًا» (32 / 16)\nTranslation: Their sides part [i.e., they arise] from [their] beds; they supplicate their Lord in fear and aspiration."
    },
    {
      "id": 3164,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bed - Bed",
      "hw": "Bed",
      "s": "In the meaning of Bed, «جفو» particularly shows the making and preparation of the bed.",
      "d": "«جفو» According to Urdu, the basic meaning of bed is which is produced in Arabic language through the root jafw (jafa). This word is used anywhere for bed, but this basic meaning shows how the bed is prepared, and what is hidden beneath it. Just as a bed is prepared, in the same way a person is prepared with their actions at their relevant place. When the bed is prepared, it means that a place is prepared to give someone comfort. The meaning of 'jafw' is to keep someone at their place with their preparation. Its comparison is with other words like 'bed' or 'table', where the meaning of 'bed' is only a specific place, but in 'jafw' the meaning of preparation of the relevant place is included. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي الْأُمَمِ مِن رَّسُولٍ إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِ لِيُبَيِّنَ لَهُمْ وَلِيَتَّقُوا فَمَن تَابَ مِن قَبْلِ أَن يَأْتِيَهُمُ الْعَذَابُ فَقَدْ أَنْجَا اللَّهُ مَنْ أَنْجَا مِنْهُمْ وَمَن لَّمْ يَتُبْ فَقَدْ أَخَذَهُمُ الْعَذَابُ وَهُمْ فِي الْبِطَانَةِ مَخْلُوفِينَ»\n\nTranslation: And We certainly sent into every nation a messenger, [saying], 'Worship Allah and avoid Taghut.' And among them were those whom Allah guided, and among them were those upon whom error was [deservedly] decreed."
    }
  ],
  "689": [
    {
      "id": 3167,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "Bedouin",
      "s": "«عرب» expresses the Bedouin Arabs who live a desert life and highlights their cultural and linguistic characteristics.",
      "d": "«عرب» Its meaning is those people who live in the desert regions of the Arab region and their language, civilization, and traditions are purely Arab. This word is different from urban Arabs (Hadari) who are settled in cities. The center of Bedouin Arabs' life is the desert, nomadism, and tribal system. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«الْأَعْرَابُ أَشَدُّ كُفْرًا وَنِفَاقًا» (9 / 97)\nTranslation: The bedouins are stronger in disbelief and hypocrisy."
    },
    {
      "id": 3168,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "Bedouin",
      "s": "In the context of Bedouin, «كون» points to something coming into existence or acquiring a special state.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is existence, creation, or the emergence of something. This word comprehensively expresses the aspects of material and spiritual formation, while other words like 'khalaq' (to create) or 'ja'ala' (to make) are limited only to the act of creation. 'Kawn' contains the concept of continuity, change, and natural state. In the context of Bedouin, this word expresses their natural and original state of existence. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قَالَتِ الْأَعْرَابُ آمَنَّا ۖ قُل لَّمْ تُؤْمِنُوا وَلَٰكِن قُولُوا أَسْلَمْنَا» (49 / 14)\nTranslation: The bedouins say, 'We have believed.' Say, 'You have not [yet] believed; but say [instead], 'We have submitted.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3170,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "Bedouin",
      "s": "In the context of Bedouin, «رحم» expresses the vast meaning of mercy and compassion that extends beyond family relationships to encompass all creatures.",
      "d": "«رحم» Its meaning is that deep love, compassion, and mercy that is part of human nature or Allah's attribute of Rahmaniyat. This word is distinguished from other synonyms like 'shafaqah' or 'mehrabani' in that it not only covers emotional attachment but also practical help and cooperation. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَلَّفَ بَيْنَ قُلُوبِهِمْ ۚ لَوْ أَنفَقْتَ مَا فِي الْأَرْضِ جَمِيعًا مَّا أَلَّفْتَ بَيْنَ قُلُوبِهِمْ وَلَٰكِنَّ اللَّهَ أَلَّفَ بَيْنَهُمْ ۚ إِنَّهُ عَزِيزٌ حَكِيمٌ» (8 / 63)\nTranslation: And He brought together their hearts. If you had spent all that is in the earth, you could not have brought their hearts together; but Allah brought them together. Indeed, He is Exalted in Might and Wise."
    }
  ],
  "690": [],
  "691": [
    {
      "id": 3178,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Belly - Belly",
      "hw": "Belly",
      "s": "«اكل» refers to the act of eating to fill the belly, which unlike other words only emphasizes the physical consumption of food.",
      "d": "«اكل» Its meaning is that act of eating which is related to satisfying the belly and fulfilling physical needs. This word is different from other words like 'ta'am' (food) or 'shurb' (drinking) in that it only highlights the material aspect of eating and its connection with the belly. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الرُّسُلُ كُلُوا مِنَ الطَّيِّبَاتِ وَاعْمَلُوا صَالِحًا» (23 / 51)\nTranslation: O messengers, eat from the good foods and work righteousness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3179,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Belly - Belly",
      "hw": "Belly",
      "s": "The word «نور» in the context of 'belly' is a symbol of spiritual light and guidance that illuminates the human inner being.",
      "d": "«نور» Its meaning is that divine light that illuminates the apparent and inner being. This word is derived from the trilateral root n-w-r and is different from other words like 'diya' (intense light) or 'siraj' (lamp) in that it particularly expresses guidance, purity, and spiritual radiance. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اللَّهُ نُورُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (24 / 35)\nTranslation: Allah is the Light of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3181,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Belly - Belly",
      "hw": "Belly",
      "s": "The word «ثمن» in the Holy Quran is used in the meaning of the price or exchange of something, which in the context of belly points to some material benefit or worldly greed.",
      "d": "«ثمن» Its meaning is the compensation, price, or exchange of something. This word clarifies the aspect of material benefit, trade, or worldly greed. Unlike other words like 'qimah' or 'naf', 'thaman' contains a negative meaning, especially when it describes the meager benefit taken in exchange for deviation from Allah's path. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَشَرَوْهُ بِثَمَنٍ بَخْسٍ دَرَاهِمَ مَعْدُودَةٍ» (12 / 20)\nTranslation: And they sold him for a reduced price, a few dirhams."
    }
  ],
  "692": [
    {
      "id": 3182,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Will - Will",
      "hw": "Will",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «وصي» expresses the delegation and continuity of entrusting someone with responsibility or advice.",
      "d": "«وصي» Its meaning is to transfer a command, responsibility, or advice with continuity and trust to someone. This word is different from other words like 'ahd' or 'amanah' in that there is a strong spiritual or legal connection between the testator and the recipient. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمْ إِذَا حَضَرَ أَحَدَكُمُ الْمَوْتُ إِن تَرَكَ خَيْرًا الْوَصِيَّةُ لِلْوَالِدَيْنِ وَالْأَقْرَبِينَ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ» (2 / 180)\nTranslation: Prescribed for you when death approaches [any] one of you if he leaves wealth [is that he should make] a will for the parents and near relatives according to what is acceptable."
    },
    {
      "id": 3183,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Will - Will",
      "hw": "Will",
      "s": "In the context of Will, «ترك» expresses the characteristic of leaving something behind or bequeathing as an inheritance.",
      "d": "«ترك» Its meaning is to leave something behind, keep it as inheritance, or entrust responsibility. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'a'ta' (to give) or 'amr' (to command) in that it clearly points to the action or wealth that remains after death. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمْ إِذَا حَضَرَ أَحَدَكُمُ الْمَوْتُ إِن تَرَكَ خَيْرًا الْوَصِيَّةُ لِلْوَالِدَيْنِ وَالْأَقْرَبِينَ» (2 / 180)\nTranslation: Prescribed for you when death approaches [any] one of you if he leaves wealth [is that he should make] a will for the parents and near relatives."
    },
    {
      "id": 3186,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Will - Will",
      "hw": "Will",
      "s": "«قَرَّبَ» means to make someone close by granting rank.",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» Meaning to be near. And to do an action that becomes a means of nearness in rank. And 'qurban' is that offering through which rank and status is sought.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ اتْلُ عَلَيْهِمْ نَبَا ابْنَيْ آدَمَ بِالْحَقِّ إِذْ قَرَّبَا قُرْبَانًا» (5 / 27)\nTranslation: And recite to them the story of Adam's two sons, in truth, when they both offered a sacrifice.\nAnd in another place Allah Almighty says:\n«وَالسَّابِقُونَ السَّابِقُونَ أُولَٰئِكَ الْمُقَرَّبُونَ» (56 / 10-11)\nTranslation: And the forerunners, the forerunners - those are the ones brought near [to Allah]."
    }
  ],
  "693": [
    {
      "id": 3187,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Gospel - Gospel",
      "hw": "Gospel",
      "s": "The word «كتب» in the context of 'Gospel' points to the guidance decreed or written by Allah.",
      "d": "«كتب» Its meaning is to command something, to appoint it, or to enforce it in written form. This word is distinguished from other words like 'kataba' (general writing) in that it expresses the adherence and stability of a divine or legal command. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَقَفَّيْنَا بِعِيسَى ابْنِ مَرْيَمَ وَآتَيْنَاهُ الْإِنجِيلَ وَجَعَلْنَا فِي قُلُوبِ الَّذِينَ اتَّبَعُوهُ رَأْفَةً وَرَحْمَةً» (57 / 27)\nTranslation: And We sent following their footsteps Jesus, the son of Mary, confirming that which came before him in the Torah; and We gave him the Gospel, in which was guidance and light."
    },
    {
      "id": 3188,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Gospel - Gospel",
      "hw": "Gospel",
      "s": "In the context of Gospel, «كثر» expresses the abundance and spread of teachings.",
      "d": "«كثر» Its meaning is to increase the number, quantity, or effect of something. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'zada' (to increase) or 'nama' (to grow) in that it not only covers increase and decrease but also includes the aspect of diversity and expansiveness. In the context of the Gospel, this points to the comprehensive and all-encompassing spread of its teachings. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاذْكُر رَّبَّكَ كَثِيرًا وَسَبِّحْ بِالْعَشِيِّ وَالْإِبْكَارِ» (3 / 41)\nTranslation: And remember your Lord much and exalt [Him with praise] in the evening and the morning."
    },
    {
      "id": 3189,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Gospel - Gospel",
      "hw": "Gospel",
      "s": "«اهل» refers to those people who are followers of the Gospel or included among the People of the Book.",
      "d": "«اهل» Its meaning is a group that has a special connection, ownership, or relationship with something. This word is different from other words like 'qawm' or 'ashab' in that it expresses spiritual, intellectual, or creedal attachment more deeply. For example, in the Holy Quran, the People of the Gospel are urged to act upon their revealed book.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلْيَحْكُمْ أَهْلُ الْإِنجِيلِ بِمَا أَنزَلَ اللَّهُ فِيهِ» (5 / 47)\nTranslation: And let the People of the Gospel judge by what Allah has revealed therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 3191,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Gospel - Gospel",
      "hw": "Gospel",
      "s": "In the context of Gospel, «بغض» expresses the deep feeling of hatred and enmity in hearts that was created by Allah's command in those who deviated from its teachings.",
      "d": "«بغض» Its meaning is the presence of deep hatred or malice in the heart, which expresses the feeling of enmity more deeply and permanently than other words like 'kurh' (dislike) or 'adawah' (enmity). This word clarifies the psychological and emotional quality. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَطِيعُوا اللَّهَ وَرَسُولَهُ وَلَا تَنَازَعُوا فَتَفْشَلُوا وَتَذْهَبَ رِيحُكُمْ ۖ وَاصْبِرُوا ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ مَعَ الصَّابِرِينَ» (8 / 46)\nTranslation: And obey Allah and His Messenger, and do not dispute and [thus] lose courage and [then] your strength would depart; and be patient. Indeed, Allah is with the patient."
    }
  ],
  "694": [
    {
      "id": 3192,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "Biology",
      "s": "In the context of Biology, «موه» points to the basic element or substance that is necessary for the formation and survival of life.",
      "d": "«موه» Its meaning is the basic substance or fundamental part of something, especially that which is given naturally or divinely. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'm-w-h' which points to a soft and fluid substance. Unlike other synonyms like 'ma' (water), 'mawh' contains the aspect of creative or biological power. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ مِنَ الْمَاءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَهُ نَسَبًا وَصِهْرًا» (25 / 54)\nTranslation: And it is He who has created from water a human being and made him [a relative by] lineage and marriage."
    },
    {
      "id": 3193,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "Biology",
      "s": "In the context of Biology, «كون» expresses something coming into existence, its formation, and evolutionary process.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is to come into existence, to become, or to transform into some state. This word expresses not only the general process of creation but also the dynamic aspect of evolution and change. Unlike other words like 'khalaq' (to create), 'kawn' includes the continuity or gradual process of something coming into existence. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَن يَقُولَ لَهُ كُن فَيَكُونُ» (36 / 82)\nTranslation: His command is only when He intends a thing that He says to it, 'Be,' and it is."
    },
    {
      "id": 3194,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "Biology",
      "s": "In the context of Biology, «كلل» expresses the meaning of comprehensive or complete coverage of something, such as a comprehensive analysis of biological systems.",
      "d": "«كلل» Its meaning is to encompass something, to include it completely, or to be comprehensive from every aspect. This word is different from other synonyms like 'shamal' (to include) or 'damm' (to join) in that it emphasizes generality and complete coverage. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَدَانِيَةً عَلَيْهِمْ ظِلَالُهَا وَذُلِّلَتْ قُطُوفُهَا تَذْلِيلًا» (76 / 14)\nTranslation: And near above them are its shades, and its [fruit] to be picked will be lowered in compliance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3195,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "Biology",
      "s": "The concept of «شيا» in the context of biology points to bringing something into existence or its creation, especially under Allah's will and wisdom.",
      "d": "«شيا» Its meaning is to intend something, to want it, or to give it existence. This word is different from other words like 'khalaq' (to create) in that it particularly emphasizes will and volition, while 'khalaq' describes the process of creation in general. For example, in the Holy Quran, Allah's will and creation is mentioned in these words:\n«إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَن يَقُولَ لَهُ كُن فَيَكُونُ» (36 / 82)\nTranslation: His command is only when He intends a thing that He says to it, 'Be,' and it is."
    }
  ],
  "695": [
    {
      "id": 3197,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "Birds",
      "s": "«طير» refers to the general form of birds, but in the Quran it sometimes also points to divine signs or destiny.",
      "d": "«طير» Its meaning is the collective concept of flying animals which includes all birds. This word is derived from the Arabic root 't-y-r' (flight) which expresses the concept of movement and circulation in the air. Unlike other words like 'ta'ir' (single bird) or 'usfur' (sparrow), 'tayr' has general and sometimes symbolic meanings, especially in the Quran as signs of divine power.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَرْسَلَ عَلَيْهِمْ طَيْرًا أَبَابِيلَ» (105 / 3)\nTranslation: And He sent against them birds in flocks."
    },
    {
      "id": 3198,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "Birds",
      "s": "The word «كلل» in the context of birds expresses the characteristic of including each one separately and completely.",
      "d": "«كلل» Its linguistic root is 'k-l-l' which gives the meaning of encompassing something, covering it, or including it completely. This word is different from other synonyms like 'jamee' (all) in that it gives individual attention to each individual or part while covering them collectively. For example, in the Quran during the mention of birds, this word is used to highlight their unique identity and the comprehensiveness of their actions.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«أَلَمْ تَرَ أَنَّ اللَّهَ يُسَبِّحُ لَهُ مَن فِي السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ وَالطَّيْرُ صَافَّاتٍ ۖ كُلٌّ قَدْ عَلِمَ صَلَاتَهُ وَتَسْبِيحَهُ» (24 / 41)\nTranslation: Do you not see that Allah is exalted by whomever is within the heavens and the earth and [by] the birds with wings spread [in flight]? Each [of them] has known his [means of] prayer and exalting [Him]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3199,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "Birds",
      "s": "The word «راي» in the Holy Quran is used to describe the special quality of their flight and movement regarding birds.",
      "d": "«راي» Its meaning is to see something moving or to turn attention toward it. This word is different from other words like 'tayr' (flying bird) in that the aspect of observation and attention is dominant in 'ra'y'. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«أَوَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ فَوْقَهُمْ صَافَّاتٍ وَيَقْبِضْنَ» (67 / 19)\nTranslation: Do they not see the birds above them with wings outspread and [sometimes] folded in?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3200,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "Birds",
      "s": "«كون» expresses the special process of birds' creation and their coming into existence, which is a sign of Allah's perfect power.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is to come into existence or for something to appear in a particular state. This word is different from other words like 'khalaq' (to create) or 'ja'ala' (to make) in that it emphasizes the continuity of a thing's existence and its natural quality. In the context of birds, this highlights the delicacy of their creation, their ability to fly, and Allah's wisdom in their life system.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ مُسَخَّرَاتٍ فِي جَوِّ السَّمَاءِ مَا يُمْسِكُهُنَّ إِلَّا اللَّهُ» (16 / 79)\nTranslation: Do they not see the birds controlled in the atmosphere of the sky? None holds them up except Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3201,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "Birds",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «اتي» points to birds coming quickly or being brought swiftly.",
      "d": "«اتي» Its meaning is for something to come or be brought, especially quickly and swiftly. This word is different from other words like 'jaa'a' (to come) in that it expresses movement with purposefulness and subjugation. For example, in the Quran in the mention of birds, this word is used to describe the quality of their immediate gathering by Allah's command.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَخُذْ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنَ الطَّيْرِ فَصُرْهُنَّ إِلَيْكَ ثُمَّ اجْعَلْ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنْهُنَّ جُزْءًا ثُمَّ ادْعُهُنَّ يَأْتِينَكَ سَعْيًا» (2 / 260)\nTranslation: Then take four birds and train them to yourself; then [after slaughtering them] put on each hill a portion of them; then call them - they will come [flying] to you in haste."
    }
  ],
  "696": [
    {
      "id": 3202,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "Blame",
      "s": "The meaning of «لوم» is to gently admonish someone for their fault or shortcoming, in which the aspect of reform is found.",
      "d": "«لوم» Its meaning is to reproach someone by stating their mistake or shortcoming in gentle words. This is different from other words like 'tawbikh' or 'itab' in that it contains an element of gentleness and sympathy, not harsh condemnation. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَا أُقْسِمُ بِالنَّفْسِ اللَّوَّامَةِ» (75 / 2)\nTranslation: And I swear by the reproaching soul [to the certainty of resurrection]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3204,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "Blame",
      "s": "The word «كون» in the context of 'blame' expresses the continuity and persistence of an action or state that becomes a cause of blame.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is existence, proof, or expressing the continuity of some state. This word is different from other words (like 'fi'l' or 'sara') in that it emphasizes the quality of something being or remaining, not just its occurrence. In the Holy Quran, this word is often used to point to the permanence of human actions or attributes, which become a cause of blame. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَضُرِبَتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الذِّلَّةُ وَالْمَسْكَنَةُ وَبَاءُوا بِغَضَبٍ مِّنَ اللَّهِ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِأَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَكْفُرُونَ بِآيَاتِ اللَّهِ وَيَقْتُلُونَ النَّبِيِّينَ بِغَيْرِ الْحَقِّ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِمَا عَصَوْا وَّكَانُوا يَعْتَدُونَ» (2 / 61)\nTranslation: And they were covered with humiliation and misery and pulled upon themselves anger from Allah. That was because they [repeatedly] disbelieved in the signs of Allah and killed the prophets without right. That was because they disobeyed and [habitually] transgressed."
    }
  ],
  "697": [
    {
      "id": 3208,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Blood money - Blood money",
      "hw": "Blood money",
      "s": "In the context of Blood money, «حرر» points to the quantity of blood money being determined and associated with the status of a free person.",
      "d": "«حرر» Its meaning is freedom or to exempt something from restrictions. In the context of blood money, this word clarifies the characteristic of the determined blood money for a free human, which is different from slaves or other ranks of individuals. For example, in the Holy Quran, the distinction of blood money between free and slave is connected to this root. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمُ الْقِصَاصُ فِي الْقَتْلَى الْحُرُّ بِالْحُرِّ وَالْعَبْدُ بِالْعَبْدِ» (2 / 178)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, prescribed for you is legal retribution for those murdered - the free for the free, the slave for the slave."
    }
  ],
  "698": [
    {
      "id": 3213,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bone - Bone",
      "hw": "Bone",
      "s": "«كون» expresses the state of existence of bones or the special aspect of transformation in them.",
      "d": "«كون» Its meaning is to come into existence or to transform into a particular state. This word is different from other words like 'khalaq' (to create) or 'ja'ala' (to make) in that it basically expresses the process of something coming into existence or changing state, not just its external structure. For example, in the context of bones, 'kawn' points to their composite existence or the stage of their formation.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَقَالُوا أَإِذَا كُنَّا عِظَامًا وَرُفَاتًا أَإِنَّا لَمَبْعُوثُونَ خَلْقًا جَدِيدًا» (17 / 49)\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we are bones and crumbled particles, will we [truly] be resurrected [in] a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3215,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bone - Bone",
      "hw": "Bone",
      "s": "In the context of Bone, «موت» expresses the decomposability of the human body after death and the special quality of being revived again by Allah's power.",
      "d": "«موت» Its meaning is the end of life and the separation of body and soul. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'm-w-t' which expresses the general state of death of any living being, but its connection with bones emphasizes the lifeless structure of the dead human body and the miracle of its revival again. Other words like 'wafat' or 'rahlat' only contain the aspect of death, while 'mawt' includes a deep concept of physical transformations. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ قَالَ مَن يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ» (36 / 78)\nTranslation: And he presents for Us an example and forgets his [own] creation. He says, 'Who will give life to bones while they are disintegrated?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3216,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bone - Bone",
      "hw": "Bone",
      "s": "«ترب» points to the original substance of bones, i.e., dust and soil, which expresses the initial state of human creation.",
      "d": "«ترب» Its meaning is dust, soil, or particle of earth. This word points to the initial substance of human creation, which also includes the formation of bones. It is different from other words like 'adhm' (bone) in that 'turb' emphasizes the basic structure (soil) of creation, while 'adhm' describes the complete form of bone. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ ۖ قَالَ مَن يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ» (36 / 78)\nTranslation: And he presents for Us an example and forgets his [own] creation. He says, 'Who will give life to bones while they are disintegrated?'"
    }
  ],
  "699": [
    {
      "id": 3217,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "Books",
      "s": "The word «كتب» in the Quran is used for revealed books and sacred scriptures that are written by Allah and their preservation is their characteristic.",
      "d": "«كتب» Its meaning is to write, to appoint, or to establish a command. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'qara'a' (to read) or 'khatta' (to draw/write) in that the aspect of destiny, permanent law, or divine revelation is dominant in 'kataba'. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فِيهَا كُتُبٌ قَيِّمَةٌ» (98 / 3)\nTranslation: In which are correct writings."
    },
    {
      "id": 3218,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "Books",
      "s": "The meaning of «اتي» regarding books expresses the revelation of divine revelation or heavenly scriptures.",
      "d": "«اتي» The literal meaning of the Arabic word is 'to come' or 'to bring', but in Quranic terminology it is particularly used for the descent of revelation, commands, or heavenly books. This word is different from other synonymous words like 'nazala' (to descend) in that 'ati' contains the concept of wisdom, completion, and arrival. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَلَمَّا جَاءَهُمْ كِتَابٌ مِّنْ عِندِ اللَّهِ مُصَدِّقٌ لِّمَا مَعَهُمْ» (2 / 89)\nTranslation: And when there came to them a Book from Allah confirming that which was with them."
    }
  ],
  "700": [
    {
      "id": 3223,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "Botany",
      "s": "In the context of Botany, «موه» expresses the characteristic of life and growth granted to plants by Allah.",
      "d": "«موه» Its meaning is to give something as a gift or with special ability. This word is distinguished from other words like 'i'ta' or 'khalaq' in that it emphasizes natural and divine bestowal. In botany, this points to granting water and life to the earth. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَنزَلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً بِقَدَرٍ فَأَسْكَنَّاهُ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَإِنَّا عَلَىٰ ذَهَابٍ بِهِ لَقَادِرُونَ» (23 / 18)\nTranslation: And We have sent down rain from the sky in a measured amount and settled it in the earth. And indeed, We are Able to take it away."
    },
    {
      "id": 3224,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "Botany",
      "s": "In the context of Botany, «ليل» expresses the specific role of night time in plant growth and biological processes.",
      "d": "«ليل» Its meaning is the time of night, which is derived from the Arabic word 'layl' (l-y-l). This word expresses not only the period of darkness but also the specific division of time and biological rhythm (circadian rhythm). It is different from other synonyms like 'dhalam' (darkness) in that 'layl' includes the concept of time limitation and natural period. In botany, it is deeply connected with plant metabolic processes during night (such as respiration) and activities like flower opening.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ» (36 / 37)\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night. We remove from it [the light of] day, so they are [left] in darkness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3225,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "Botany",
      "s": "In the context of Botany, «غشو» expresses the characteristic of grass or greenery covering the earth.",
      "d": "«غشو» Its meaning is for something to cover or overshadow another thing. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'gh-sh-w' which expresses the concept of any kind of veil, hiding, or encompassing. In botany, this expresses the density of grass or greenery spread over the earth, such as the growth of crops or wild plants. It is different from other words like 'nabat' (to grow) or 'zar' (to sow) in that the aspect of spread and covering is dominant in 'ghashw'.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَنبَتْنَا فِيهَا مِن كُلِّ زَوْجٍ بَهِيجٍ» (22 / 5)\nTranslation: And We have caused to grow within it [the earth] from every beautiful kind [of plant]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3226,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "Botany",
      "s": "The word «نهر» in the context of Botany expresses the fundamental role of water sources and nurturing plant life.",
      "d": "«نهر» Its meaning is a flowing water source or river that irrigates the land and causes the growth of plants. This word is different from other words like 'bahr' (sea) or 'wadi' (valley) in that it is particularly associated with the flow of water and fertility. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَبَشِّرِ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ أَنَّ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتٍ تَجْرِي مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ» (2 / 25)\nTranslation: And give good tidings to those who believe and do righteous deeds that they will have gardens [in Paradise] beneath which rivers flow."
    }
  ],
  "701": [
    {
      "id": 3227,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bowing - Bowing",
      "hw": "Bowing",
      "s": "The specific Quranic meaning of «ركع» expresses the worship quality of bowing in prayer.",
      "d": "«ركع» Its meaning is to bow in prayer where the knees are placed on hands and the back is kept straight. This is different from general bowing (like 'hana' or 'inhana') which only expresses physical movement, while 'ruku' includes the intention of worship and the prescribed method. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَقِيمُوا الصَّلَاةَ وَآتُوا الزَّكَاةَ وَارْكَعُوا مَعَ الرَّاكِعِينَ» (2 / 43)\nTranslation: And establish prayer and give zakah and bow with those who bow [in prayer and obedience]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3228,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bowing - Bowing",
      "hw": "Bowing",
      "s": "The meaning of «سجد» expresses the special quality of bowing down or prostrating in worship which is deeply connected to the spiritual aspect of bowing.",
      "d": "«سجد» Its meaning is to place the forehead on the ground with humility and express complete submission before Allah. This word is derived from the trilateral root 's-j-d' which is distinguished from other words like 'ruku' (bowing the waist) in that the extreme form of physical and spiritual humility is found in prostration. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا ارْكَعُوا وَاسْجُدُوا وَاعْبُدُوا رَبَّكُمْ» (22 / 77)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, bow and prostrate and worship your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 3229,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bowing - Bowing",
      "hw": "Bowing",
      "s": "The meaning of «صلو» is to worship Allah with humility and attention in the performance of prayer, which reflects a spiritual connection higher than mere external movements.",
      "d": "«صلو» Its meaning is supplication, mercy, or establishing a connection. This word is the root of 'salah' which encompasses the entire system of worship, which includes heart concentration, tongue remembrance, and physical worship. Unlike other words like 'du'a' (general supplication) or 'ibadah' (pure servitude), 'salaw' particularly describes the quality of prayer in which the servant establishes a deep spiritual connection with their Lord. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَأَقِيمُوا الصَّلَاةَ وَآتُوا الزَّكَاةَ وَارْكَعُوا مَعَ الرَّاكِعِينَ» (2 / 43)\nTranslation: And establish prayer and give zakah and bow with those who bow [in prayer and obedience]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3230,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bowing - Bowing",
      "hw": "Bowing",
      "s": "In the context of Bowing, «طهر» expresses the quality of purity and cleanliness, which includes both material and spiritual cleanliness.",
      "d": "«طهر» Its meaning is to purify something from impurity, filth, or contamination. This word encompasses both physical purity and inner cleanliness. Unlike other words like 'nazaf' (only external cleanliness) or 'zaka' (growth purity), 'tahr' contains deep comprehensiveness. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَثِيَابَكَ فَطَهِّرْ» (74 / 4)\nTranslation: And your clothing purify."
    },
    {
      "id": 3231,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bowing - Bowing",
      "hw": "Bowing",
      "s": "In the context of Bowing, «طوف» expresses its rotation and circulation which indicates the movement of its strings.",
      "d": "«طوف» The Urdu word 'kaman' has its original root 'tawaf' which basically gives the meaning of a circle, rotation, or circulation. When the word 'kaman' is used, the process of rotation and circulation of its strings is associated with it. The translation of this does not use other synonymous words like 'spread' or 'rotate'. 'Tawaf' is the descriptive term that expresses the rotation of the bow's strings. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَإِذَا طَوَّفَتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الْمَلَائِكَةُ»\nTranslation: And when the angels circled around them."
    }
  ],
  "702": [
    {
      "id": 3233,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bracelet - Bracelet",
      "hw": "Bracelet",
      "s": "In the context of Bracelet, «ذهب» expresses the precious metal of gold which is used in jewelry.",
      "d": "«ذهب» Its meaning is pure gold metal which is considered a symbol of brilliance, value, and delicacy. This word is distinguished from other metals like silver (fiddah) or copper (nuhas) in that it particularly points to a precious and strong element. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يُحَلَّوْنَ فِيهَا مِنْ أَسَاوِرَ مِن ذَهَبٍ» (18 / 31)\nTranslation: They will be adorned therein with bracelets of gold."
    },
    {
      "id": 3234,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bracelet - Bracelet",
      "hw": "Bracelet",
      "s": "«حلي» is a word that expresses bracelet or jewelry which is used for body adornment and decoration.",
      "d": "«حلي» Its meaning is jewelry or adornment that is worn on the body for beauty and decoration. This word is derived from the root 'h-l-y' which includes the concepts of adornment, beautification, and ornamentation. Unlike other words like 'zinah' (general decoration) or 'libas' (clothing), 'hily' particularly expresses wearable jewelry. For example, in the Holy Quran:\n«يُحَلَّوْنَ فِيهَا مِنْ أَسَاوِرَ مِن فِضَّةٍ» (76 / 21)\nTranslation: They will be adorned therein with bracelets of silver."
    }
  ],
  "703": [
    {
      "id": 3235,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bracelet - Bracelet",
      "hw": "Bracelet",
      "s": "The word «جنن» means to cover or encompass, which reflects the aspect of hiding or protecting inherent in the meaning of 'bracelet'.",
      "d": "«جنن» Its meaning is to cover, conceal, or surround something. This word differs from other synonymous words like 'غطی' (to cover) or 'حفظ' (to protect) in that it particularly emphasizes the concept of completely surrounding or protecting something by concealing it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَنَّ عَلَيْهِ اللَّيْلُ» (6 / 76) Translation: Then when the night covered him. In this verse, the use of 'جَنَّ' refers to the night's dark veil covering, which points to a protected and complete enclosure like the encompassing nature of a 'bracelet'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3237,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "Brass",
      "s": "The word «مهل» refers to molten brass or copper in liquid or viscous form, derived from its original meaning of 'delay' or 'thick substance'.",
      "d": "«مهل» Its meaning is to describe a thick, liquid, or molten state of metal. This word emphasizes the fluid characteristic of metals, while other synonyms like 'نُحاس' (copper) refer to the general state. For example, in the Holy Quran: «آتُونِي زُبَرَ الْحَدِيدِ ۖ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا سَاوَىٰ بَيْنَ الصَّدَفَيْنِ قَالَ انفُخُوا ۖ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا جَعَلَهُ نَارًا قَالَ آتُونِي أُفْرِغْ عَلَيْهِ قِطْرًا» (18 / 96) Translation: Bring me sheets of iron until when he had leveled them between the two cliff sides, he said, 'Blow,' until when he had made it into fire, he said, 'Bring me molten copper to pour over it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3238,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "Brass",
      "s": "The word «نور» in the context of brass highlights the moral aspect of light, brightness, and radiance, reflecting both its external and internal qualities.",
      "d": "«نور» Its meaning is light, brightness, or radiance that dispels darkness. This word is used both for physical light and spiritual guidance and illumination. Unlike other words like «ضیاء» (intense light) or «سراج» (lamp), «نور» conveys the concept of soft, spreading light. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اللَّهُ نُورُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (24 / 35) Translation: Allah is the Light of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3240,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "Brass",
      "s": "The linguistic nuance of «حقق» in the context of brass relates to firmly establishing or verifying something with truth or evidence.",
      "d": "«حقق» Its meaning is to firmly establish or prove something based on facts, evidence, or logic, or to give it a final form. It differs from other words like «أكد» (to emphasize) or «ثبت» (to prove) in that it is not limited to mere verification but emphasizes practically establishing the truth. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَلْبِسُوا الْحَقَّ بِالْبَاطِلِ وَتَكْتُمُوا الْحَقَّ وَأَنتُمْ تَعْلَمُونَ» (2 / 42) Translation: And do not mix the truth with falsehood or conceal the truth while you know."
    }
  ],
  "704": [
    {
      "id": 3242,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bread - Bread",
      "hw": "Bread",
      "s": "The word «اكل» in the context of bread describes the comprehensive process of obtaining, consuming, and enjoying food.",
      "d": "«اكل» Its meaning is to eat, consume, or ingest something through the mouth into the body. This word differs from other words like «طعام» (food) or «شرب» (drinking) in that it focuses specifically on the act of eating, not the nature of the food or drinking. For example, in the Holy Quran, the use of «اكل» refers not only to physical nourishment but also conveys spiritual or moral effects. For example, in the Holy Quran: «یَأْكُلْنَ مَا یَخْطُفْنَ» (12 / 37) Translation: (Those women) will eat whatever they snatch."
    },
    {
      "id": 3246,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bread - Bread",
      "hw": "Bread",
      "s": "The word «فوق» in the context of bread conveys the concept of elevation, superiority, and abundance of sustenance.",
      "d": "«فوق» Its meaning is elevation, superiority, or the state of being above something. This word differs from other synonyms like «على» (on) in that it denotes not only positional elevation but also moral superiority, increase, or dominance. In the Holy Quran, this word is used for both material and spiritual elevations. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَأَنزَلْنَا عَلَى الَّذِينَ ظَلَمُوا رِجْزًا مِّنَ السَّمَاءِ بِمَا كَانُوا يَفْسُقُونَ» (2 البقرة / 59) Translation: And We sent down upon those who wronged a punishment from the sky because they were defiantly disobedient."
    }
  ],
  "705": [
    {
      "id": 3247,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "Bribe",
      "s": "The meaning of «اكل» is to consume wealth through unlawful means, which in the case of bribery symbolizes usurping the rights of others.",
      "d": "«اكل» Its meaning is to swallow or devour something. This word is used not only for physical eating but also for financial exploitation, unlawful benefit, and destruction of rights. In the context of bribery, it points to the reprehensible act of consuming others' wealth through false means, while other words like 'اخذ' (taking) or 'استفادہ' (benefiting) do not carry this negative connotation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَأْكُلُوا أَمْوَالَكُم بَيْنَكُم بِالْبَاطِلِ» (2 / 188) Translation: And do not consume one another's wealth unjustly."
    },
    {
      "id": 3250,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "Bribe",
      "s": "When referring to the social aspect of human beings (i.e., social interaction), the word «اِنْس» and its derivatives are used; when referring to the historical aspect, 'Adam' and 'Children of Adam' are used; and when referring to the natural and instinctive aspect, the word 'Bashar' is used.",
      "d": "«اِنْس» Its plural is «اُنَاس». It refers to a group or community of humans who differ from one another due to tribe, family, or other reasons. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (60 / 2) Translation: Each group knew its drinking place. And (اَنَاسِیَّ) refers to a very large group of humans. For example, Allah the Almighty says: «خَلَقۡنَاۤ اَنۡعَامًا وَّ اَنَاسِیَّ  کَثِیۡرًا» (49 / 25) Translation: We have created cattle and many humans."
    },
    {
      "id": 3251,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "Bribe",
      "s": "The word «حكم» in the context of bribery points to the act of corrupting the ability to govern or make decisions.",
      "d": "«حكم» Its meaning is to command, judge, or use authority in a just manner. This word differs from other words like 'قضاء' (judgment) in that 'حكم' includes the concept of governance and system sustainability, while bribery corrupts it unlawfully. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَمَن لَّمْ يَحْكُم بِمَا أَنزَلَ اللَّهُ فَأُولَٰئِكَ هُمُ الْكَافِرُونَ» (5 / 44) Translation: And whoever does not judge by what Allah has revealed - then it is those who are the disbelievers."
    }
  ],
  "706": [
    {
      "id": 3252,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "Silk",
      "s": "The word «جنن» in the context of silk points to its delicacy and ability to cover, reflecting the fineness of its structure.",
      "d": "«جنن» Its meaning is to cover or conceal. This word describes the characteristics of silk due to its softness and smoothness, which covers the body and distinguishes it from other materials. While other words like 'حریر' only describe the material structure of silk, 'جنن' highlights its practical and symbolic qualities. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا بَنِي آدَمَ قَدْ أَنزَلْنَا عَلَيْكُمْ لِبَاسًا يُوَارِي سَوْآتِكُمْ وَرِيشًا» (7 / 26) Translation: O children of Adam! We have sent down to you clothing that conceals your shame and (becomes) adornment for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3253,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "Silk",
      "s": "The word «وكا» in the context of silk points to its delicacy and the binding or wrapping aspect.",
      "d": "«وكا» Its meaning is to tie, fasten, or wrap tightly. This word differs from other words like 'ربط' or 'عقد' in that it particularly conveys the concept of joining something delicate or subtle in a secure manner, like silk threads. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَكَاءَ الْفَجْرِ» (2 / 187) Translation: And perceive the binding of the dawn (i.e., its white streak). Here, 'وكاء' compares the spread of dawn's light to a soft and organized binding like silk."
    },
    {
      "id": 3256,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "Silk",
      "s": "The word «ثوب» in the context of silk refers to a fine and valuable type of cloth or garment.",
      "d": "«ثوب» Its meaning is cloth or garment, which in Arabic encompasses any type of clothing. This word is distinguished from other synonyms like «لباس» or «رداء» in that it particularly emphasizes the structure, nature, or quality of the cloth's preparation. In the case of silk, «ثوب» refers to soft, shiny, and high-quality fabric. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَثِيَابَكَ فَطَهِّرْ» (74 / 4) Translation: And purify your garments. In this verse, «ثوب» refers to general clothing, but in the context of valuable fabrics like silk, this word highlights the concept of delicacy and purity."
    }
  ],
  "707": [
    {
      "id": 3257,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "Burial",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «وري» in the context of burial points to concealing or covering something.",
      "d": "«وري» Its meaning is to completely hide something or bury it in the earth to make it disappear from sight. This word differs from other words like 'دفن' in that it emphasizes the aspect of concealment and protection rather than just placing. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا بَنِي آدَمَ قَدْ أَنزَلْنَا عَلَيْكُمْ لِبَاسًا يُوَارِي سَوْآتِكُمْ» (7 / 26) Translation: O children of Adam! We have sent down to you clothing that conceals your shame. In this verse, the use of 'يُوَارِي' refers to physical covering, which is semantically aligned with the concept of concealment in burial."
    },
    {
      "id": 3258,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "Burial",
      "s": "In the context of burial, «اخو» carries the special significance that burying a deceased person is the responsibility of their brother or close relative.",
      "d": "«اخو» Its meaning is that this word fundamentally refers to a brother or close relative, while in the context of burial it points to the familial or fraternal responsibility. Other words like 'دفن' (burying in earth) only describe the act of burial, but 'اخو' highlights the depth of relationship and social aspect in it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَبَعَثَ اللَّهُ غُرَابًا يَبْحَثُ فِي الْأَرْضِ لِيُرِيَهُ كَيْفَ يُوَارِي سَوْءَةَ أَخِيهِ» (5 / 31) Translation: Then Allah sent a crow searching in the earth to show him how to hide the disgrace of his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 3259,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "Burial",
      "s": "The concept of «مثل» in the context of burial relates to displaying a body as an exemplary punishment or lesson.",
      "d": "«مثل» Its meaning is to make something an example or lesson. Lexically, this word is derived from 'مثیل' which contains the aspect of resemblance or display. In the context of burial, it points to that punishment in which a criminal's body is buried after public display, which differs from other words like 'دفن' (merely hiding in earth). For example, in the Holy Quran: إِنَّمَا جَزَاءُ الَّذِينَ يُحَارِبُونَ اللَّهَ وَرَسُولَهُ وَيَسْعَوْنَ فِي الْأَرْضِ فَسَادًا أَنْ يُقَتَّلُوا أَوْ يُصَلَّبُوا... (۵:۳۳) Translation: Indeed, the recompense of those who wage war against Allah and His Messenger and strive upon earth spreading corruption is none but that they be killed or crucified... (5:33)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3261,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "Burial",
      "s": "In the context of burial, «سوا» describes the characteristic of leveling the earth over the deceased in the grave and completely covering them.",
      "d": "«سوا» Its meaning is to make something correct, level, or give it complete form. Lexically, this word is derived from 'تسویہ' (leveling) which in the burial process points to leveling the grave's earth and covering the deceased with respect. Unlike other words like 'دفن' (burying in earth), 'سوا' emphasizes the aspect of completion and care. For example, in the Holy Quran: «ثُمَّ سَوَّاهُ وَنَفَخَ فِيهِ مِن رُّوحِهِ» (32 / 9) Translation: Then He proportioned him and breathed into him from His spirit. Although this verse refers to human creation, the use of 'سوا' clarifies the concept of making something complete and balanced, which also highlights its significance in the burial process."
    }
  ],
  "708": [
    {
      "id": 3262,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Constellations",
      "hw": "Constellations",
      "s": "The word «برج» refers to heavenly towers or clusters of stars that are prominent due to their grandeur and stability.",
      "d": "«برج» Its meaning is lofty buildings or heavenly signs that possess strength and magnificent structure. This word comes from the trilateral root 'ب ر ج' which contains the concept of emerging, becoming prominent, or protecting. Unlike other words like 'قصر' (palace) or 'صرح' (tall building), 'بروج' is typically used for heavenly or astronomical structures. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ جَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (15 / 16) Translation: And We have placed within the heaven great stars and have beautified it for the observers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3263,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Constellations",
      "hw": "Constellations",
      "s": "In the context of constellations, «زين» is used in the specific meaning of adorning the heavens with stars or bestowing beauty upon astronomical structures.",
      "d": "«زين» Its meaning is to make something beautiful, decorate it, or enhance its attractiveness. This word differs from other synonyms like «حسن» or «جمال» in that it denotes additional adornment upon something, not inherent beauty. In Quranic usage, this word appears to highlight cosmic grandeur and Allah's craftsmanship. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ جَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (15 / 16) Translation: And We have placed within the heaven great stars and have beautified it for the observers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3264,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Constellations",
      "hw": "Constellations",
      "s": "The word «نَظَرَ» is generally used for looking or casting a glance.",
      "d": "«نَظَرَ» To look, to see, so that something may become visible, whether that thing is visible or not. This word is used in both ways. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ  اِذَا مَاۤ  اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ  نَّظَرَ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (9/127) Translation: And whenever a Surah is revealed, they look at one another. In another place, Allah the Almighty says: «فَانۡظُرِیۡنَ مَاذَا تَاۡمُرِیۡنَ» (27/33) Translation: So consider what you will command. However, the use of 'نظر' is generally related to seeing with the eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3265,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Constellations",
      "hw": "Constellations",
      "s": "In the context of constellations, «نور» is a symbol of heavenly light and divine radiance that reflects the grandeur of the cosmic system.",
      "d": "«نور» Its meaning is the light that dispels apparent and hidden darkness, whether it be physical or spiritual. This word is distinguished from other words like 'ضیا' or 'سراج' in that it particularly encompasses purity, guidance, and divine manifestations. The connection of 'نور' with constellations (heavenly towers or clusters of stars) reflects the brightness of celestial bodies and their representation of the universe's order. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَجَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (25 / 61) Translation: And We have placed within the heaven great stars and have beautified it for the observers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3266,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Constellations",
      "hw": "Constellations",
      "s": "In the context of constellations, the concept of «برك» is to manifest Allah's greatness and blessing, which indicates the stability, permanence, and increase of blessing in something.",
      "d": "«برك» Its meaning is to make something firm, stable, and blessed. This word differs from other words like 'خلق' or 'جعل' in that it includes not only existence but also blessing, expansion, and permanence within it. For example, in the Holy Quran, Allah Almighty has described the constellations (clusters of stars or great structures) in the heavens as a sign of His power and blessing. For example, in the Holy Quran: «تَبَارَكَ الَّذِي جَعَلَ فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا» (25 / 61) Translation: Blessed is He who has placed in the sky great stars."
    }
  ],
  "709": [
    {
      "id": 3267,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Romans - Romans",
      "hw": "Romans",
      "s": "«غَلَبَ» means to gain dominance through physical strength.",
      "d": "«غَلَبَ» contains the concept of power, force, and intensity (م ل), meaning to gain superiority and dominance through physical strength. To conquer. And the defeated (مغلوب) is one who is forcibly compelled through physical strength and power. For example, in the Holy Quran: «کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» (2/249) Translation: How often has a small company overcome a large company by permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3269,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Romans - Romans",
      "hw": "Romans",
      "s": "«دنو» describes the closeness of victory after the defeat of the Romans and proximity in terms of time.",
      "d": "«دنو» Its meaning is for something to be near in terms of time or place. This word comes from the root دِنْوَتْ (closeness) and differs from other words like «قرب» or «جوار» in that «دنو» particularly contains the concept of immediate or intense proximity. For example, in the Holy Quran: «غُلِبَتِ الرُّومُ * فِي أَدْنَى الْأَرْضِ وَهُم مِّن بَعْدِ غَلَبِهِمْ سَيَغْلِبُونَ» (30 / 2-3) Translation: The Romans have been defeated * In the nearest land. But they, after their defeat, will overcome."
    }
  ],
  "710": [
    {
      "id": 3272,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Happy",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "The word «خوش» means the feeling of happiness and joy that arises from Allah's pleasure and grace.",
      "d": "«خوش» Its Arabic root (خ-ش-و) originally expresses happiness, joy, and gladness. Its terminological meaning arises when a person feels happiness and comfort through Allah's pleasure, grace, and worship. Compared to other related words, this particularly expresses the happiness that arises from Allah's grace and pleasure. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً» (البقرة / 30) Translation: And when your Lord said to the angels, 'Indeed, I will make upon the earth a successive authority.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3273,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Joyful",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "The original meaning of «شاد» is that which brings comfort to the human heart, and then its meaning expands to tranquility and ease.",
      "d": "«شاد» Its original root is ش-د-د which in Urdu gives the meaning of 'happiness' and 'comfort'. Its literal meaning is 'happy' which makes the human heart feel good. It has several synonyms such as: tranquility, ease, gladness, security, joy, delight, pleasure, comfort, and ease. But the difference between «شاد» and «خوش» is that in «شاد» there is a specific and strong feeling of happiness from the emotional side that gives special comfort to the heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (الحج / ۴۰) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith and put not in our hearts resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3274,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Delighted",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "The word «مسرور» describes a deep and tranquil quality of happiness that is felt from the depths of the heart.",
      "d": "«مسرور» Its meaning is the happiness that is a satisfying joy arising in the heart upon attaining a particular cause or blessing. This word is derived from the Arabic root «سَرَّ» (to be happy) which differs from other words like «فرح» (great joy) or «بَشِش» (outward happiness) because it emphasizes inner tranquility and lasting joy. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَوَقَاهُمُ اللَّهُ شَرَّ ذَٰلِكَ الْيَوْمِ وَلَقَّاهُمْ نَضْرَةً وَسُرُورًا» (76 / 11) Translation: So Allah will protect them from the evil of that Day and give them radiance and happiness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3275,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Rejoicing",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "The word «فرحاں» expresses a temporary or excessive quality of happiness that is often associated with pride or arrogance.",
      "d": "«فرحاں» Its meaning is to take pride in something or express temporary joy based on فَرَح (happiness). This word differs from other happiness words (like سعید or مسرور) in that its element of happiness is temporary, superficial, or sometimes arrogant. For example, in the Holy Quran: «كُلُّ حِزْبٍۭ بِمَا لَدَيْهِمْ فَرِحُونَ» (30 / 32) Translation: Every party rejoicing in what it has."
    },
    {
      "id": 3276,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Cheerful",
      "hw": "Happy",
      "s": "«خرم» is that quality of happiness in which a deep element of freshness and vibrancy is found.",
      "d": "«خرم» Its meaning is joyful happiness, a state filled with vibrancy and freshness. This word is distinguished from other synonyms like 'فرح' or 'سرور' in that it particularly expresses the natural freshness, lushness, and inner energy of something. For example, it is used in describing the abundance of blessings or the lushness of a garden. For example, in the Holy Quran: «مَّثَلُ ٱلَّذِينَ يُنفِقُونَ أَمْوَٰلَهُمُ ٱبْتِغَآءَ مَرْضَاتِ ٱللَّهِ وَتَثْبِيتًۭا مِّنْ أَنفُسِهِمْ كَمَثَلِ جَنَّةٍۭ بِرَبْوَةٍ أَصَابَهَا وَابِلٌۭ فَـَٔاتَتْ أُكُلَهَا ضِعْفَيْنِ» (2 / 265) Translation: The example of those who spend their wealth seeking Allah's pleasure and assurance from themselves is like a garden on high ground which is hit by a downpour so it yields its fruits in double."
    }
  ],
  "711": [
    {
      "id": 3277,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Sadness - Sadness",
      "hw": "Sadness",
      "s": "«غَمّ» is used in all these meanings: grief, sorrow, anxiety, pain, and regret.",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «غَمَّ» is to cover and conceal. «غُمّٰی» means dust and darkness, and «غَمَام» means clouds that cover the sun's light. And «غم» means anxiety. Pain, distress (مف ۔ منجد). For example, in the Holy Quran: «ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» (3/154) Translation: Then Allah sent down upon you, after grief, security, a drowsiness covering a party of you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3278,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Sadness - Sorrow",
      "hw": "Sadness",
      "s": "«اندوہ» describes a deep and permanent form of sadness that envelops the heart.",
      "d": "«اندوہ» Its meaning is deep and long-lasting sorrow that engulfs the heart, expressing an internal quality. This word is derived from the Arabic root «غ-م-م», whose basic concept is 'to cover' or 'to engulf'. Unlike other synonyms like «حُزن» (temporary grief) or «كرب» (painful anxiety), «اندوہ» emphasizes the intensity and permanence of sadness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَأَثَابَكُمْ غُمًّا بِغَمٍّ» (3 / 153) Translation: Then He repaid you with grief upon grief."
    },
    {
      "id": 3279,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Sadness - Regret",
      "hw": "Sadness",
      "s": "In the context of sadness, «ملال» expresses the deep feeling of regret and sorrow over something not happening or being lost.",
      "d": "«ملال» Its meaning is the pain and remorse arising in the heart due to some loss, deprivation, or regret, that qualitative feeling which settles into deep sorrow when not consoled. This word differs from general grief (حزن) in that it contains the element of despair and painful thinking about the past. For example, in the Holy Quran: «رُبَمَا يَوَدُّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا لَوْ كَانُوا مُسْلِمِينَ» (15 / 2) Translation: Perhaps those who disbelieve will wish that they had been Muslims. Here, through 'يَوَدُّ' (to wish), the painful regret of the disbelievers is expressed which is compatible with the concept of 'ملال'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3280,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Sadness - Distress",
      "hw": "Sadness",
      "s": "«رنج» is connected with the feeling of weakness, complexity, and despair that opens the heart like a crowd.",
      "d": "«رنج» Its original root is connected with the feeling of weakness, complexity, and despair. These words express more emotional and human characteristics. Compared to this, «غم» mentions the state of feeling which particularly comes through the human mind. «رنج» is a special type of feeling that is present in the human heart at all times. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ لَيَكُونَنَّ فِي تَرَدُّدٍ مِنْهُمْ» (۳۹/۲۶) Translation: And those who came after them will be in doubt among them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3281,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Sadness - Alas",
      "hw": "Sadness",
      "s": "In the expression of sadness, «افسوس» particularly expresses the painful state of failure, loss, and heartache.",
      "d": "«افسوس» Its meaning is failure, loss, corruption, and the heart's painful state that has grown in the human heart. These words differ from each other in that «غم» is generally a state of feeling, while «افسوس» particularly expresses heartache due to failure or corruption. Its origin in Arabic is افسوس (أَفْسُوس) which is a word that expresses a deep state of feeling. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَفْسُوسَ عَلَى الْقَوْمِ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِذَا مَرُّوا بِهِمْ وَلَمْ يَجِدُوا فِيهِمْ مِنْ أَهْلِهِمْ أَحَدًا» (الأنفال / ۲۷) Translation: Alas for the believing people when they passed by them and did not find any of their family among them."
    }
  ],
  "712": [
    {
      "id": 3282,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Anger",
      "hw": "Anger",
      "s": "The word «غصہ» means when a person considers himself great and ignores others, and also ignores his own reality.",
      "d": "«غصہ» Its Arabic root is غ-ص-ہ, which originally means to make a small thing big. Its literal meaning is 'to magnify' or 'to consider great'. This word expresses a big thought present in the human mind that leads him to ignore others and consider himself great. Its synonym is «تعصب» or «غرور», but the special meaning of «غصہ» is that a person considers himself great and ignores other people, and also ignores his reality. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ\nإِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ وَمَلَأِهِۦ فَقَالُوآ إِنَّا نَحْنُ كَانَ الْمُؤْتَمِرُونَ\nقَالَ يَا فِرْعَوْنُ إِنِّي لَكَ الْمُنْذِرُ الْمُبِينُ\nلَقَدْ جَاءَكَ الْحَقُّ مِنْ رَّبِّكَ فَأَمَّا يَكُونَ لَكَ أَنْ تَكُونَ فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ\nفَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا يَغْصُو فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ\nوَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا يَغْصُو فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ\nفَلَوْلَا أَنْ يَكُونَ فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ» (طه 20:13-20) Translation: It has been said that Moses was sent with Our signs and clear authority to Pharaoh and his chiefs. They said that we understand that we must do this. It was said to Pharaoh that I am your warner and clear authority. Yes, the declaration of truth has come to you from your Lord, but if you consider yourself great and ignore other people, then this is a misguidance. Similarly, when he becomes angry and ignores other people, the result is that he also ignores his reality."
    },
    {
      "id": 3283,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Wrath",
      "hw": "Anger",
      "s": "«غَضَبٌ» When a person becomes furious with anger and descends to take revenge, whether small or big, its connection is not with one's own self but with the self of another.",
      "d": "«غَضَبٌ» According to Sahib al-Fiqh al-Lughah, this word is general which is spoken for every type of anger. (ف ل 169) But this definition does not seem correct. The definition of anger that the Messenger of Allah ﷺ gave is as follows: «اِتَّقُوْا مِنْ الْغَضَبِ فَاِنَّہٗ جُمْرَۃٌ تُوْقَدُ فِیْ قَلْبِ ابْنِ اٰدَمَ اَلَمْ تَرَوْا اِلَی انْتِفَاخِ اَوْدَاجِہٖ وَجُمْرَۃِ عَیْنَیْہِ» Translation: Guard against anger, for it is an ember that burns in the heart of the son of Adam. Do you not see the swelling of his neck veins and the redness of his eyes? And it is clear that this quality occurs when anger overcomes a person and he descends to take revenge. And Ibn al-Faris has defined it as «اَشَدّْ السَّخَط» meaning extreme anger (م ل). And the author of Munjid has written the meaning of «غَضِبَ» as holding malice, being angry (Munjid) and as «اِرَادَۃُ الضَّرْر لِلْمَغْضُوْبِ عَلَیْہِ» (wanting harm for the one who is angered). And «غَضْب» always comes upon another, meaning it can be from the small upon the big and from the big upon the small (فق ل 106). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یَّحۡلِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ غَضَبِیۡ فَقَدۡ ہَوٰی» (20/81) Translation: And whoever My wrath descends upon has perished."
    },
    {
      "id": 3284,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Domination",
      "hw": "Anger",
      "s": "The word «قہر» means a specific, pointed, and merciless emotion of anger that leads the heart to burst.",
      "d": "«قہر» Its meaning is a specific, pointed, and merciless emotion of anger that leads the heart to burst. This is with the spine of words, which causes the human heart to burst and open others from the other side. There is a difference between قہر and غصہ; anger is generally with feeling, while قہر is an additional pressure and a kind of cruelty. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ الَّذِينَ أَتَوْا مِن قَبْلِكَ لِيَقُولَنَّ الَّذِينَ أَحْسَنُوا وَالَّذِينَ قَدْ أَخْلَفُوا مِنْهُمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ لَمْ يَكُنْ بِهِمْ عَلِيمًا» (الأنعام / 150) Translation: And when Allah took the covenant of those who came before you, those who did good and those who had broken from among them would say that Allah was not knowing of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3285,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Fury",
      "hw": "Anger",
      "s": "The word «طیش» means a specific point of anger that expresses irregularity, discouragement, and heart corruption.",
      "d": "«طیش» In the Urdu language, it means anger, irritation, and irregularity. Its Arabic origin is طیش which originally expresses irritation, heart corruption, and irregularity of feeling. Compared to this, «غضب» is generally a quick and immediate shower of feeling, while «طیش» appears in the form of a continuous, unorganized, and heart-corrupting feeling. «طیش» contains the meaning of feeling's will, discouragement, and heart corruption that makes human feelings irregular and wrong. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَسَّكَ اللَّهُ الْقَلْبَ فَلَا مُفَرِّضٍ لَّهُ وَإِذَا مَسَّكَ الْغَضَبَ فَلَا مُعَلِّقٍ لَّهُ» (الأنعام 6/103) Translation: And when Allah touches the heart, there is no one secure from it, and when anger touches it, there is no one suspended from it."
    }
  ],
  "713": [
    {
      "id": 3286,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Love",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "The word «محبت» means a feeling created by Allah that fills the heart and draws a person toward their Creator.",
      "d": "«محبت» Its Arabic root consists of the letters (م), (ح), and (ب), which originally express an intense attraction or emotion. This word shows the feeling of approaching something, which comes at the level of the heart. Compared to this, «عشق» has a more general and passionate meaning, while «حب» expresses the feeling of connecting the matters of the human heart. «محبت» is particularly directed toward Allah, which helps generate feelings in the heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُ كَنِيْٓءٌ وَّلَا وَلَدٌ وَّلَمْ يَكُن مَّعَهُ شَرِيكٌ فَلِيَّهُ الْحُبُّ وَلَهُ الْمَلَكُ وَهُوَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (الطلاق: ۳) Translation: And He has no partner, nor does He have a son, and there is no associate with Him. To Him belongs love and sovereignty, and He is over all things competent."
    },
    {
      "id": 3287,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Passionate Love",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "«عشق» is a special manifestation of love that expresses the human and divine relationship.",
      "d": "«عشق» In Urdu, it is a special form of love that expresses the human and divine relationship. Its Arabic origin is عَشَق which starts with the letter Ain (ع) and means 'a small piece of heart' or 'to be helpless'. Its literal meaning is 'to see' or 'to love'. The meaning of عشق is that a person loves their companion or Allah immensely, with another feeling that is extraordinary and specific. Its English synonym is belovedness or feeling, but the feeling of عشق is special that brings a person's dreams to the forefront. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُهُمْ وَلَنَحْنُهُمْ وَإِلَيْهِ يَرْجِعُ الْأُمُورُ» (العنكبوت، ۲۹: ۶۵) Translation: And those who strive for Us - We will surely guide them to Our ways. And indeed, Allah is with the doers of good."
    },
    {
      "id": 3288,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Affection",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "«الفت» is the original meaning of love that expresses the special feeling and connection that arises in the human heart.",
      "d": "«الفت» Its original root is in the letters alif-ta-ya which originally expresses many qualities arising in the human heart, such as passionate love, feeling, and connection. This word shows a special type of love that arises at a specific level within the heart, which expresses a special feeling with others and human connection. Compared to this, «حب» generally means passionate love, while «وداد» expresses simple connection and feeling. «الفت» particularly contains the feeling of human heart's love that expresses the special connection arising between the human mind and heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَّ الْقُوَّةِ إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ رَبَّنَا وَلَكَ الْحَمْدُ أَنْتَ وَلِيُّنَا فِي الدُّنْيَا وَالْآخِرَةِ وَلَكَ الْحَمْدُ» (آل عمران / 195) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith and put not in our hearts resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3289,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Affection",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "The word «پیار» particularly means the immense belovedness and feeling that arises in a person's heart, which is the most valued aspect of humanity and does not ignore the heart-filled soul.",
      "d": "«پیار» In Urdu, this word is derived from Arabic words «پیار» which originally expresses 'heart's burning' or 'connection of hearts'. Its meaning is to love someone very much, to care for their heart, and to understand their condition. Compared to this, «محبت» has a more general meaning, while «پیار» particularly expresses heart's burning, belovedness, and heart's tenderness. «پیار» is a word that does not ignore the state of the heart, but rather expresses it in a better way. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُ لَهُمْ مُّلْكُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالأَرْضِ فَإِنَّمَا يَجْزَوْنَ مَا كَانُوا يَعْمَلُونَ» (الأنعام / ١٢٧) Translation: And those who strive for Us - We will surely give them possession of the heavens and the earth, for they will only be recompensed for what they used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 3290,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Desire",
      "hw": "Love",
      "s": "The word «چاہت» means the feeling of love and the desire to see one's companion that comes from the human heart.",
      "d": "«چاہت» In Urdu lexicon, it is the original synonym of love, which is derived from the Arabic language \"چاہت\" (desire) which originally expresses the heart's desire and encouragement. This word shows the human's best and extraordinary desire that accompanies the heart. Compared to this, \"محبت\" is a general expression which is the feeling of liking someone, while \"چاہت\" is a feeling of connection that comes from the heart. This word expresses human's desire, which is the desire to see another person. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحُكْمِ مِنَ اللَّهِ فَلَمْ يَجِدْ مِنْهُمْ أَحَدًا لَمْ يَكُونَ مُتَّبِعًا لِلْمَنْ هُوَ أَعْلَمُ بِالْمُعْتَقِدِينَ» (النساء/ ۱۶۷) Translation: And the one who brought the judgment from Allah - none of them found anyone who was not following the one who is most knowing of the believers."
    }
  ],
  "714": [
    {
      "id": 3291,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Hatred",
      "hw": "Hatred",
      "s": "The word «نفرت» means to feel intense aversion or disgust toward something that creates deep repulsion in heart and mind.",
      "d": "«نفرت» Its meaning is a natural or acquired feeling of disgust, aversion, or repulsion toward a thing, action, or state, which is contrary to human nature or rational thinking. This word is derived from the Arabic trilateral root 'ن-ف-ر' whose basic meanings are 'to turn one's back' or 'to move away'. It differs from other words like 'کُره' (dislike) or 'بُغض' (deep hatred of the heart) in that 'نفرت' emphasizes the aspect of complete physical or psychological deviation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «كَأَنَّهُمْ حُمُرٌ مُّسْتَنفِرَةٌ» (74 / 50) Translation: As if they were donkeys fleeing. In this verse, 'مُسْتَنفِرَةٌ' (those who flee in aversion) refers to those who flee from the reminder of truth as donkeys flee from a predator at the sight of a beast, which presents a practical image of the concept of 'نفرت'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3292,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Enmity",
      "hw": "Hatred",
      "s": "«عداوت» is that deep form of hostility and opposition that creates hatred in hearts.",
      "d": "«عداوت» Its meaning is enmity, opposition, and emotional tension with someone that settles in hearts and becomes a cause of permanent hatred. This word is derived from the Arabic trilateral root 'ع-د-و' which denotes the concept of enmity, competition, and conflict. Unlike other synonyms like 'بغض' (temporary dislike) or 'کینہ' (personal grudge), enmity emphasizes the aspect of systematic opposition and collective hostility. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَتَّخِذُوا عَدُوِّي وَعَدُوَّكُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ» (60 / 1) Translation: O you who have believed, do not take My enemy and your enemy as allies."
    },
    {
      "id": 3293,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Aversion",
      "hw": "Hatred",
      "s": "The concept of «کراہت» expresses the quality of dislike or reluctantly accepting, which is somewhat different from intense hatred arising from the depths of the heart.",
      "d": "«کراہت» Its meaning is for nature to feel burdened by something or to accept it unwillingly. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'ك ر ه', which describes an action done with compulsion or unwillingness. It differs from other synonyms like 'بغض' (heartfelt enmity) or 'شدتِ انکار' in that 'کراہت' often includes the aspect of practical compulsion or enduring something disliked under religious command. For example, in the Holy Quran: «كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمُ الْقِتَالُ وَهُوَ كُرْهٌ لَّكُمْ» (2 / 216) Translation: Fighting has been enjoined upon you while it is hateful to you. Here 'کُرْہ' refers to compliance with Allah's command despite the heart's dissatisfaction, which clarifies both the psychological and legal layers of this word."
    },
    {
      "id": 3294,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Malice",
      "hw": "Hatred",
      "s": "The concept of «بغض» is a deep feeling of hatred and enmity in the heart that is often based on hostility or oppression.",
      "d": "«بغض» Its meaning is firm hatred or malice in the heart that manifests in actions and behaviors. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'ب-غ-ض' which points to something breaking or ending, like the breaking of a heart's relationship. Compared to other words like 'كراهية' (dislike), 'بغض' expresses more intensity, depth, and lasting enmity. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَدُّوا۟ لَوْ تَكْفُرُونَ كَمَا كَفَرُوا۟ فَتَكُونُونَ سَوَآءًۭ ۖ فَلَا تَتَّخِذُوا۟ مِنْهُمْ أَوْلِيَآءَ حَتَّىٰ يُهَاجِرُوا۟ فِى سَبِيلِ ٱللَّهِ» (3 / 118) Translation: They wish you would disbelieve as they disbelieved so you would be alike. So do not take from among them allies until they emigrate for the cause of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "715": [
    {
      "id": 3295,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Fear",
      "hw": "Fear",
      "s": "In the context of the Quran, «خوف» expresses apprehension, dread, or anxiety that is usually about Allah's displeasure or punishment, which includes the aspect of caution and piety.",
      "d": "«خوف» Its meaning is the anxiety or fear arising in the heart from the apprehension of some loss, harm, or undesirable outcome. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'خ و ف' which describes a mental state in view of some danger. It differs from other words like 'خشية' (fear of greatness and reverence) or 'رهبة' (awe) in that 'خوف' emphasizes the feeling of immediate or potential danger. For example, in the Holy Quran: «إِنَّمَا ذَٰلِكُمُ الشَّيْطَانُ يُخَوِّفُ أَوْلِيَاءَهُ فَلَا تَخَافُوهُمْ وَخَافُونِ إِن كُنتُم مُّؤْمِنِينَ» (3 / 175) Translation: It is only Satan that suggests to you the fear of his allies. So fear them not, but fear Me, if you are believers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3296,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Dread",
      "hw": "Fear",
      "s": "In the context of fear, «ڈر» expresses a cautious attitude with the concern of avoiding Allah's displeasure and punishment.",
      "d": "«ڈر» Its meaning is a quality arising in the heart in view of an unpleasant outcome that compels a person to caution. The Arabic word 'خوف' has the root 'خ-و-ف' which differs from other words like 'خشية' (faithful respect) or 'رهبة' (awe) because it particularly emphasizes the awareness of consequences and the sense of responsibility. For example, in the Holy Quran: «إِنَّمَا ذَٰلِكُمُ الشَّيْطَانُ يُخَوِّفُ أَوْلِيَاءَهُ فَلَا تَخَافُوهُمْ وَخَافُونِ إِن كُنتُم مُّؤْمِنِينَ» (3 / 175) Translation: It is only Satan that suggests to you the fear of his allies. So fear them not, but fear Me, if you are believers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3297,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Terror",
      "hw": "Fear",
      "s": "«دہشت» describes an intense and sudden quality of fear that arises in the heart due to some danger or frightening scene.",
      "d": "«دہشت» Its meaning is a state of unexpected or intense fear that creates trembling and anxiety in the heart. This word, along with Persian 'دہشت', is distinguished from Arabic words like 'رعب' or 'خشیۃ' which express more general or permanent fear. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أُولَـٰئِكَ الَّذِينَ لَعَنَهُمُ اللَّـهُ فَأَصَمَّهُمْ وَأَعْمَىٰ أَبْصَارَهُمْ» (47 / 23) Translation: Those are the ones that Allah has cursed, so He made them deaf and blinded their vision. In this verse, the concept of the quality of 'دہشت' is related to the intense fear of Allah's wrath that is placed in the hearts of disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3298,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Apprehension",
      "hw": "Fear",
      "s": "«ہراس» [The special meaning of fear that also includes religious events, which protects a person's faith and religion]",
      "d": "«ہراس» Its meaning is a feeling of fear upon the human heart that motivates them to protect their religion and faith. This fear is related to a doctrine or teaching, which a person feels through their actions in the presence of Allah. This differs from the translation of words like «خائف» or «ڈر» in that it is generally a feeling of fear against human decision. For example, in the Holy Quran: «الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ صَالِحًا فَأُولَٰئِكَ يُحَبُّونَ اللَّهَ وَيُحَبُّونَهُ مُحَبَّةً كَثِيرَةً» (البقرة ۲/۱۶۵) Translation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day and do righteousness - those will be loved by Allah and will love Him with a great love."
    }
  ],
  "716": [
    {
      "id": 3299,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Hope",
      "hw": "Hope",
      "s": "The concept of «امید» expresses the peaceful desire for positive future outcomes with complete trust in Allah and expectation of His mercy.",
      "d": "«امید» Its meaning is to expect a better future or positive outcome, which is based on faith and trust. This word is derived from the Arabic word 'أَمَد' (duration/time), which points to the continuity of time and toward the future. Unlike other synonyms like 'توقع' (waiting for something) or 'آس' (heart's support), 'امید' includes the aspect of deep trust in Allah's mercy and waiting with patience. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَمَن يَقْنَتَ مِنكُنَّ لِلَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَتَعْمَلْ صَالِحًا نُّؤْتِهَا أَجْرَهَا مَرَّتَيْنِ وَأَعْتَدْنَا لَهَا رِزْقًا كَرِيمًا» (33/31) Translation: And whoever of you devoutly obeys Allah and His Messenger and does righteousness - We will give her her reward twice; and We have prepared for her a noble provision."
    },
    {
      "id": 3301,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Expectation",
      "hw": "Hope",
      "s": "The original meaning of «توقع» is hope that also includes the heart's thought.",
      "d": "«توقع» Its meaning is hope, thought, expectation, and the state of waiting for the future through the heart's thought, which also includes the heart's thought. Its original roots are تَوَقَّع (expectation) which means to hope with thought, and to wait for a particular thing. Its synonym is «امید» but «توقع» has a special additional meaning that it is hope with thought, and it is with the thought of another person or thing. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُوْنَ» (الانعام / ٩٣) Translation: And those who strive for Us - We will surely guide them to Our ways."
    },
    {
      "id": 3302,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Expectancy",
      "hw": "Hope",
      "s": "The original meaning of «رجاء» is hope that plans human's desire and another's help.",
      "d": "«رجاء» Its meaning is human's desire, hope, explanation, connection, and pointing to oneself with another's help. These words are: رَجَاءٌ (rajaa), رَجُوٌّ (rajuu) and رَجِیٌّ (rajiyy). Its original root is ر-ج-اء. The meaning of رجاء is human's desire, hope, and pointing to oneself with another's help. Besides, there is a specific term that plans human's desire and another's help. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَأْخِرْنِي فِي الْمُحْتَجَّاتِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ» (البقرة / 134) Translation: And do not delay me among the needy of the believers."
    }
  ],
  "717": [
    {
      "id": 3303,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Despair",
      "hw": "Despair",
      "s": "The word «مایوسی» means a state when something has not been received from Allah, and one does not understand oneself; when a person does not receive mercy or blessings from Allah, then the feeling of despair arises.",
      "d": "«مایوسی» Its original literal ownership is related to terms that originally point to \"مایوس\" (desperate), which is a type that is related to our freedom and trade. Its basic terminological meaning is: a state when a person fails to understand themselves after seeing the results of their actions or due to the absence of mercy or blessings received from Allah. Besides, compared to other words, despair expresses the feeling of the absence of blessings received from Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ يَا قَوْمِ إِنَّكُمْ ظَلَمْتُمْ أَنْفُسَكُمْ بِاتِّخَاذِكُمُ الْعِجْلَ فَتُوبُوا إِلَىٰ بَارِئِكُمْ فَاقْتُلُوا أَنفُسَكُمْ فَأَسْلَمُوا وَهُوَ أَحْسَنُ لَكُمْ» (الأنعام/۱۴۷) Translation: And when Moses said to his people, 'O my people, indeed you have wronged yourselves by your taking of the calf [for worship]. So repent to your Creator and kill yourselves. That is best for [all of] you in the sight of your Creator.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3304,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Hopelessness",
      "hw": "Despair",
      "s": "The word «ناامیدی» means the feeling of discouragement from Allah when a person looks at the results of their actions with hopelessness.",
      "d": "«ناامیدی» Its Arabic root is نا-امیدی, where نا- is a negative prefix and is related to امیدی which means hope. These words are compared with each other along with مایوسی. Despair is a feeling when a person looks at the results of their efforts with hopelessness. Its difference from other words is like «ہیں» (hopelessness) or «خیال» (insecurity). «ناامیدی» is a special feeling that is the feeling of discouragement from Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ أَعْدَاءِ اللَّهِ مِنْ وَاقِعٍ» (الأنفال 8/57) Translation: And they would not have found for themselves against Allah any protector."
    },
    {
      "id": 3305,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Despondency",
      "hw": "Despair",
      "s": "The original meaning of «قنوطیت» is despair that troubles the human heart with hopelessness and failure.",
      "d": "«قنوطیت» Its meaning is the state of human's heart's hopelessness, failure, and despair that drives them away from their actions. This word is derived from the word «قنوط» which originally points to hopelessness and failure. Compared to this, it is used together with «کُسْف» or «خَسَرَانِی», but «قنوطیت» is particularly the state of heart's hopelessness after human's pain and affliction. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِینٍ» (طه / 43) Translation: And We had certainly sent Moses with Our signs and a clear authority."
    }
  ],
  "718": [
    {
      "id": 3306,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Wonder - Wonder",
      "hw": "Wonder",
      "s": "The word «حیرت» means that when something gives us a feeling of unexpectedness and helplessness from our side, it explains that.",
      "d": "«حیرت» Its original root word is ح-ی-ر-ت which expresses a special feeling in Urdu. This word is the feeling of our helplessness and wonder before something that also comes to us before our belongings. This meaning is related to our helplessness, wonder, and feeling of failure before something. Compared to this, «تعجب» means only feeling, but «حیرت» means feeling along with helplessness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَى الَّذِي أَخَذَ قَوْلَكُمْ وَجَعَلَ مِنْهُمْ أَزْوَاجًا وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ مِنْ أَزْوَاجِهِمْ مِنْ بَعْدِ ذَلِكَ أَبَوَانِ مَنْ كَانَ لَهُمْ فِي الْقَوْلِ مِنْ حِلْمٍ وَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا تَصَدَّقَ الْمَوْعِظَةَ مِنْهُمْ وَمَنْ قَالَ لَهُمْ أَنْ لَيْسَ لَكُمْ مِنْ أَبَوَيْكُمْ مِنْ بَعْدِ ذَلِكَ أَبَوَانِ مِنْ حِلْمٍ وَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا تَصَدَّقَ الْمَوْعِظَةَ مِنْهُمْ» (النساء/١٥٩) Translation: Have you not seen the one who took your statement and made from them spouses, and there were not for them after that parents? Who was for them in the statement of patience? And when he gave the admonition from them, and who said to them that there are not for you from your parents after that parents of patience? And when he gave the admonition from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3307,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Wonder - Amazement",
      "hw": "Wonder",
      "s": "The word «تعجب» means to express the heart very much toward something that is strange and extraordinary.",
      "d": "The word «تعجب» is derived from Arabic «تعجب» which originally is the feeling of the heart when seeing something that its special expression should be made. This word is a very strong feeling of the heart about something, which is strange and extraordinary. Compared to this, «حیرت» generally means the feeling that something is very great. The meaning of «تعجب» is that there is a very strong feeling of the heart toward the thing, which is very strange and extraordinary. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ ادْعُوا رَبَّكُمْ وَلْيَمْسَطْ لَكُمْ رِزْقَهُ» (الأعراف، ۱۴۳) Translation: And when Moses said to his people, 'Call upon your Lord and He will provide for you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3308,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Wonder - Astonishment",
      "hw": "Wonder",
      "s": "The word «استعجاب» means the feeling of wonder and amazement with Allah's great power and the increasing visible punishability of creation when facing something that exceeds the norm.",
      "d": "The original literal origin of «استعجاب» is استعجاب, which in Urdu gives the meaning of wonder, amazement, and educational feeling arising upon facing Allah's power. By its grace, upon seeing something there is wonder and the feeling that how was such work done from its side. Its equivalent concept in Urdu is wonder but «استعجاب» means wonder with Allah's power and order. This concept is best expressed in a specific verse of the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا رَآهُمْ قَالَ الْمُؤْمِنُونَ لَمَّا أَدْرَكَهُمْ: أَسْتَعِيبٌ وَلَمَّا أَدْرَكَهُمْ: أَسْتَعِيبٌ وَلَمَّا أَدْرَكَهُمْ: أَسْتَعِيبٌ وَلَمَّا أَدْرَكَهُمْ: أَسْتَعِيبٌ» (سورہ طارق / آیت ۱۰) Translation: When the believers saw them, they said: 'We realized that we have to face this.'"
    }
  ],
  "719": [
    {
      "id": 3309,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Shame",
      "hw": "Shame",
      "s": "The word «شرم» means to worry oneself about one's disobedience and sins and to have the feeling of heart beating because of that.",
      "d": "«شرم» Its Arabic root is شرم (ش ر م) which originally is the manifestation of feeling in the human heart when they think about their disobedience or sin that others may feel sorry because of it. This word is a special feeling of human moral connection, which is a feeling of crossing a boundary. Its meaning is a type of feeling that prevents a person from sinning, and it differs from words like «خجلی» or «دیوانگی». For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ إِذَا مَآ أَنْفَقُوا لَمْ يُسْرِفُوا وَلَمْ يَقْتُرُوا وَكَانُوا بَيْنَ ذَٰلِكَ رَاسِخِينَ» (النور / ۳۷) Translation: And those who, when they spend, do so not excessively or sparingly but are ever, between that, justly balanced."
    },
    {
      "id": 3310,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Modesty",
      "hw": "Shame",
      "s": "«حیا» is a human and religious feeling that is given by Allah and prevents a person from inactivity and inappropriate actions.",
      "d": "The original root word of «حیا» is «حیا» (ح-ی-ا) which expresses human and religious feeling. This word is originally a feeling arising in the human heart that prevents them from inactivity and inappropriate actions. Compared to this, the meaning of «خجل» is a feeling in a person's life that prevents them from actions that are wrong in their sight. «حیا» is the representative of human's religious and human feeling that helps them fulfill the laws given by Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَأْمُرُونَ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ وَيَنْهَوْنَ عَنِ الْمُنكَرِ وَيُقِيمُونَ الصَّلَاةَ وَيُؤْتُونَ الزَّكَاةَ وَهُمْ يَخْشَوْنَ رَبَّهُمْ مِّنْ غَيْرِ مَا يَرَوْنَهُ وَهُمْ يُقِيمُونَ الْحَدِيثَ» (البقرۃ ۲/۴۵) Translation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong and establish prayer and give zakah, and they fear their Lord without seeing Him, and they maintain the conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 3311,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Regret",
      "hw": "Shame",
      "s": "The original meaning of «ندامت» is shame that shows human's goodness and beauty when they protect themselves from exposure and wrong actions.",
      "d": "«ندامت» Its meaning is the feeling of human's goodness and beauty that prevents them from their sins and wrong actions. This word, wherever anyone has the feeling that they have human goodness and moral virtues, and they want to protect their beauty and humanity from themselves. Its meaning is that we preserve our goodness, and we also show our beauty related to our actions. Its comparison is with other words like «خجل» or «بے خجلی» which is not only because of human feeling but with it there is a much more special feeling of human goodness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَكُونُوا الَّذِينَ يُؤْلِينَ أَنْفُسَهُمْ وَيَحْسَدُونَ النَّاسَ عَلَىٰ مَا آتَاهُمُ اللَّهُ مِنْ فَضْلِهِ» (سورة عمران، آیت 173) Translation: And do not be those who expose themselves and envy people for what Allah has given them of His bounty."
    }
  ],
  "720": [
    {
      "id": 3313,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Pride - Arrogance",
      "hw": "Pride",
      "s": "The word «غرور» means to consider oneself very important and give less power to others which harms a person.",
      "d": "«غرور» Its meaning is to consider oneself very important and give less power to others which harms a person. Its original root is گرور which is a synonym of 'فخر' in Urdu. Its literal origin also matches with 'فخر' in Urdu words. Besides غرور, other meanings include 'فخر', 'بڑا', 'خودپسندی' and 'اعتماد' but the meaning of غرور is to consider oneself very important which results in giving less power to others. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَفْرَحْ وَلَا تَغْرُورْ بِاللَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا» (النساء / 43) Translation: And do not rejoice and do not be arrogant toward those who disbelieved."
    },
    {
      "id": 3314,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Pride - Boasting",
      "hw": "Pride",
      "s": "The word «تفاخر» means to consider oneself higher than others and try to show one's blessings and power to others.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of «تفاخر» is (تفاخر) which is an Urdu word that tries to show one's power, quality, or blessings to others. Its lexical meaning is: to consider oneself high, to show one's belongings to others, and to try to differentiate one's example from others. It differs from «فخر» which is to truly understand one's blessings and feel one's right, and «تکبر» which is to consider oneself high against Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا فَخْرٌ وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا فَخْرٌ» (الأنعام/147) Translation: There was not for them in that except pride, only the feeling of their own pride."
    }
  ],
  "721": [
    {
      "id": 3315,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Patience",
      "hw": "Patience",
      "s": "«صَبْر» means to endure when calamities and difficulties befall.",
      "d": "«صَبْر» means to endure upon any harm or shock reaching and not expressing restlessness, impatience, and weeping. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَصَبَرُوۡا عَلٰی مَا کُذِّبُوۡا وَ اُوۡذُوۡا حَتّٰۤی اَتٰہُمۡ  نَصۡرُنَا» (6/34) Translation: So those prophets endured upon what they were denied and harmed until Our help came to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3316,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Endurance",
      "hw": "Patience",
      "s": "In the concept of patience, «تحمل» highlights the special quality of the ability to bear burdens and endure hardship.",
      "d": "«تحمل» Its meaning is to consciously take on any harm, responsibility, or difficulty and endure it with steadfastness. This word comes from the root 'ح-م-ل' whose basic concept is 'to lift' or 'to load'. Compared to other words like 'صبْر' (endurance) or 'ثبات' (steadfastness), تحمل emphasizes the aspect of active consent and choice of burden. For example, in the Holy Quran: «رَبَّنَا وَلَا تُحَمِّلْنَا مَا لَا طَاقَةَ لَنَا بِهِ» (البقرہ 2/286) Translation: Our Lord, and lay not upon us that which we have no ability to bear."
    },
    {
      "id": 3317,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Forbearance",
      "hw": "Patience",
      "s": "In the context of patience, «برداشت» expresses the characteristic of facing difficulties with tranquility and perseverance.",
      "d": "«برداشت» Its meaning is to endure any harm or trial with courage and restraint without complaint. This word comes from the root 'برد' (coolness) which points to keeping emotions cool in the process of patience. Unlike other words like 'تحمل' (to endure), 'برداشت' includes firmness in action along with accepting the calamity. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاسْتَعِينُوا بِالصَّبْرِ وَالصَّلَاةِ» (2 / 153) Translation: And seek help through patience and prayer."
    }
  ],
  "722": [
    {
      "id": 3318,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Mistake - Mistake",
      "hw": "Mistake",
      "s": "«غلطی» refers to an error that occurs in the form of forgetfulness, slip, or deviation from the path in some work, which is usually unintentional or due to negligence.",
      "d": "«غلطی» Its meaning is to exceed the truth due to unintentional or careless behavior in some work. Lexically, it is derived from the Arabic trilateral root 'غ ل ط' which contains the concept of 'misguidance', 'straying', or 'twisting facts'. This word differs from 'خطأ' (unintentional mistake) in that 'غلطی' mostly includes the aspect of conscious negligence or ignoring evidence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَمَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا إِذْ جَاءَهُمُ الْهُدَىٰ إِلَّا أَن قَالُوا أَبَعَثَ اللَّهُ بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا» (18/55) Translation: And nothing prevented the people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, 'Has Allah sent a human messenger?' (Here there is a reference to wrong reasoning based on 'مَّغَالِطَةً')."
    },
    {
      "id": 3320,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Mistake - Slip",
      "hw": "Mistake",
      "s": "The word «لغزش» means the expression of mistake that happens unintentionally or unknowingly.",
      "d": "«لغزش» Its meaning is the expression of mistake that happens unintentionally or unknowingly. Its Arabic root is that which guides everything, and its meaning is \"against guidance\". These words are also: \"غلطی\", \"افسوس\", \"خطا\". The original meaning of لغزش is to be against guidance, while the meaning of غلطی is to be away from correct. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَقُولُوا لِمَنْ يَمُوتُ فِي مَلْكِهِ أَنَّهُ مَوْتٌ إِلَّا أَنْ تَقُولُوا لَهُ لَعَلَّ اللَّهَ لِيَجْعَلَ لَكُمْ خَيْرًا فِي مَلَكِهِ وَلَعَلَّهُ يَمُوتُ فِي مَلْكِهِ وَأَنْتُمْ تَعْمَلُونَ» (سورة النمل، آیت 84) Translation: Do not say about one who dies in his kingdom that he is dead, but say to him that perhaps Allah may make good for you in his kingdom, and perhaps he will die in his kingdom while you are working."
    }
  ],
  "723": [
    {
      "id": 3321,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Regret",
      "hw": "Regret",
      "s": "«افسوس» is an expression of grief or remorse that shows intense sorrow over an inevitable loss or missed opportunity.",
      "d": "«افسوس» means intense grief or remorse that arises in the heart over an irreparable loss, failure, or lost opportunity. This word entered Arabic from Persian and its close synonym in Quranic Arabic is «حَسْرَة» (ح س ر) which expresses the same emotion. «افسوس» differs from general remorse («نَدم») because it focuses on irreversible past loss rather than future expectations. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا حَسْرَةً عَلَى الْعِبَادِ» (36/30) Translation: O regret upon the servants! (for how they ignored the truth)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3322,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Sensitivity",
      "hw": "Regret",
      "s": "«حسرت» expresses the intensity of regret, lasting remorse, and the feeling that comes after an opportunity has passed.",
      "d": "«حسرت» means a deep feeling of intense remorse over an irreparable loss, lost opportunity, or past actions. This word is derived from the Arabic root «ح-س-ر» which denotes 'loss' or 'deficiency'. Unlike other synonyms like 'ندامت' or 'غم', حسرت includes anxiety about the future and the irreversible nature of past moments. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَقُولُ يَا لَيْتَنِي قَدَّمْتُ لِحَيَاتِي» (89/24) Translation: He will say, 'O I wish I had sent ahead for my life.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3323,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Sorrow",
      "hw": "Regret",
      "s": "«ملال» describes a deep and lasting quality of regret related to the feeling of remorse over failure or past actions.",
      "d": "«ملال» means intense regret or remorse resulting from an action that affects the heart deeply. This word differs from general regret (like حزن or غم) because it expresses recurring remorse and spiritual fatigue that comes to mind repeatedly. Its lexical root is 'م ل ل' which denotes repetition or weariness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «رُّبَمَا يَوَدُّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا لَوْ كَانُوا مُسْلِمِينَ» (15/2) Translation: Perhaps those who disbelieved will wish that they had been Muslims."
    }
  ],
  "724": [
    {
      "id": 3324,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Happiness",
      "hw": "Happiness",
      "s": "«خوشی» in the Quran refers to heart's joy, tranquility, and gratitude for Allah's blessings that transcends temporary worldly pleasures.",
      "d": "«خوشی» means inner peace, positive emotions, and the feeling that arises from recognizing divine gifts. In Arabic, its close synonyms like 'فرح' (temporary happiness/pride) and 'سرور' (heart's contentment) distinguish this word in the context of spiritual purity and lasting tranquility. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلْ بِفَضْلِ اللَّهِ وَبِرَحْمَتِهِ فَبِذَٰلِكَ فَلْيَفْرَحُوا هُوَ خَيْرٌ مِّمَّا يَجْمَعُونَ» (10/58) Translation: Say, 'In the bounty of Allah and in His mercy - in that let them rejoice; it is better than what they accumulate.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3325,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Joy",
      "hw": "Happiness",
      "s": "«مسرت» refers to deep inner happiness and heart's joy that is lasting and pure.",
      "d": "«مسرت» means deep and hidden happiness felt in the heart. This word is based on 'س ر ر' which denotes inner contentment and pure joy. Unlike other words like 'فرح' which express temporary or outward happiness, 'مسرت' has depth and permanence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَوَقَاهُمُ اللَّهُ شَرَّ ذَٰلِكَ الْيَوْمِ وَلَقَّاهُمْ نَضْرَةً وَسُرُورًا» (76/11) Translation: So Allah will protect them from the evil of that Day and will give them radiance and happiness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3326,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Gladness",
      "hw": "Happiness",
      "s": "«شادمانی» is the original meaning of happiness that expresses the heart's prosperity and comfort.",
      "d": "«شادمانی» has an Arabic root similar to the heart's prosperity, comfort, and joy. This word together with others gives the meaning of happiness. When a person feels happiness in their heart, they are شادمان. Its synonyms include words like فرح, سرور, بہتری, and مسرت. But «شادمانی» specifically means the heart's prosperity and comfort that shows the state of the heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (الحجرات/13) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith and put not in our hearts any resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.'"
    }
  ],
  "725": [
    {
      "id": 3327,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Pain - Pain",
      "hw": "Pain",
      "s": "«دکھ» means to express, to show, and to present in a great way, especially used for expressing feelings.",
      "d": "«دکھ» has an Arabic root د-ك-ه which originally means 'to express' and 'to present'. These words are originally used for expressing feelings, conditions, or showing something. Its synonyms include seeing, appearing, and looking, but «دکھ» is especially used for expressing feelings. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَإِنَّا لَهُمْ مُحْتَجَّةٌ» (الأنبياء 21:45) Translation: And We had certainly sent Moses with Our signs and indeed We are, for them, arguing."
    },
    {
      "id": 3328,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Pain - Grief",
      "hw": "Pain",
      "s": "«غَمّ» is used in the meanings of sorrow, grief, anxiety, pain, and regret.",
      "d": "«غَمَّ» basic meaning is to cover and to hide. «غُمّٰی» means dust and darkness, and «غَمَام» means clouds that cover the sun's light. And «غم» means anxiety, pain, and distress (منجد). For example, in the Holy Quran: «ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» (3/154) Translation: Then Allah sent down upon you, after grief, security [in the form of] drowsiness overcoming a group of you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3329,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Pain - Distress",
      "hw": "Pain",
      "s": "«رنج» is the original meaning of pain that has a powerful effect on the human heart and mind.",
      "d": "«رنج» means to create great pain and distress in someone's heart and mind, which distances a person from themselves. This works not only in words but also inside the mind and heart. It is a specific type of pain and distress that is created deeply in someone's mind and heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّىٰ تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَقَدْ كَانَ فِي أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ مِن قَبْلِهَا حَبٌّ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّىٰ تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ» (البقرة/207) Translation: And those who disbelieved from the People of the Scripture and the polytheists were not to be parted [from misbelief] until there came to them clear evidence."
    }
  ],
  "726": [
    {
      "id": 3330,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Anxiety - Anxiety",
      "hw": "Anxiety",
      "s": "«بےچینی» shows the meaning of doing something without care and without enthusiasm, away from the original concept.",
      "d": "«بےچینی» in Urdu means doing something without care, without enthusiasm, and without attention. Its Arabic root word بیچینی originally is a word for doing something without attention. Its original meaning is doing something without activity, without enthusiasm, and without care. This differs from restlessness in that بےچینی means without attention and without enthusiasm, while other words like 'بے دلی' or 'بے احساس' mean without feeling. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَوْلَا دَعَوَتُهُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُم مِّنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (البقرة/217) Translation: And if not for their supplication, you would have been among the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 3331,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Anxiety - Disturbance",
      "hw": "Anxiety",
      "s": "«اضطراب» means anxiety where something standing and moving is not easy, like a clock's hand spreading in the sun.",
      "d": "«اضطراب» original lexical meaning is that something standing and moving is not easy, like a clock's hand spreading in the sun. Its root in Urdu terminology is 'اُضْطِرَاب' which means to stand something up or spread it in the sun. Compared to this, 'بےچینی' means that something standing and moving is not easy. Its meaning is that something standing and moving is not easy. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ وَرَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (آل عمران/194) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith and put not in our hearts any resentment toward the believers. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3332,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Anxiety - Restlessness",
      "hw": "Anxiety",
      "s": "«بےقراری» means living in an unknown and unprotected place, which expresses the concept of anxiety.",
      "d": "«بےقراری» Arabic origin is بے-قراری which means living in an unknown, unprotected, and uncertain place. This word originally indicates all kinds of despair and instability, which clarifies the human state in relation to anxiety. Compared to this, 'بےچینی' means placing something in an unknown and unprotected place, which is the descriptive meaning of restlessness. Its synonym is 'بےثباتی' or 'بےرویائی', but 'بےقراری' specifically means placing something in an unknown place which is a quality of anxiety. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا أَنزِلْ لَنَا مِن فَوْقِنَا ظَهْرًا مِّن سَاقِطٍ وَرَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِكَ وَلِيَكُونَ لَنَا آمِنًا مِّن لَّدُنْهُ وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَعْلَمُونَ» (البقرة 2:247) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, send down to us from heaven a table spread [with food] and mercy from You, and make it safe for us from You, even though they were knowing.'"
    }
  ],
  "727": [
    {
      "id": 3333,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Tranquility - Tranquility",
      "hw": "Tranquility",
      "s": "«اطمینان» means firm and stable confidence obtained from Allah that gives peace to the heart and does not leave again.",
      "d": "«اطمینان» Arabic root word is اطمنان which is related to the meanings of 'faith' and 'trust', and based on this there is a concept of natural and honest quality of confidence. Its meaning is that a person's heart makes itself better, and with it there is a feeling of faith and love. Its synonym is 'ایمان' but in اطمنان there is additional confidence and a feeling of heart's comfort along with faith. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِهِ وَيَتَوَكَّلُونَ فِي أَمْرِهِمْ وَلَا يَرْتَابُونَ» (البقرة/59) Translation: And those who came after them believe in it and rely upon it in their affairs and do not doubt."
    },
    {
      "id": 3334,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Tranquility - Peace",
      "hw": "Tranquility",
      "s": "«سکون» is the original meaning of tranquility that expresses the heart's comfort and ease when one presents themselves before Allah and their duties.",
      "d": "«سکون» means the heart's connection and comfort, which also makes a person feel approaching their God. This is a new state in the form of words that is the means of the heart's tranquility. It expresses a person's heart's tranquility when they present their actions and duties. Compared to this, 'امین' and 'اعتماد' also have similar meanings but in 'سکون' the expression of the heart's comfort is more clear. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (البقرة 2/286) Translation: And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3335,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Tranquility - Consolation",
      "hw": "Tranquility",
      "s": "«تسلی» is the original meaning of tranquility that expresses faith and comfort obtained from the Lord in the human heart.",
      "d": "«تسلی» original root word is «تَسَلَّى» which expresses the state that gives a feeling of comfort and ease in the human heart. This word expresses faith, certainty, and confidence obtained from the Lord in the human heart. This is a specific type of tranquility that not only expresses the feeling like the heart's beating but also expresses the strengthening of faith and the state of being near Allah. Compared to this, 'امان' means general tranquility, 'ال信任' means only trust, and 'طمینان' means the feeling of comfort along with confidence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِينَا لَنَهْدِيَنَّهُمْ سُبُلَنَا» (العنکبوت 69) Translation: And those who strive for Us - We will surely guide them to Our ways."
    }
  ],
  "728": [
    {
      "id": 3336,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Flattery - Flattery",
      "hw": "Flattery",
      "s": "«خوشامد» means that which goes beyond happiness and comfort, and because of it a person feels happiness.",
      "d": "«خوشامد» original root is related to happiness, comfort, and support, which naturally gives a person happiness and comfort. Its word meaning is 'happiness' or 'comfort' that is the best and gives more happiness. Compared to this, 'خوشی' (خوش) only shows general happiness, while 'خوشامد' shows such happiness that is specifically better, which goes beyond many happinesses. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَسَّكُمُ الضُّرُّ فِي الْبَحْرِ ضَلَّ مَن تَدْعُونَ إِلَّا إِيَّاهُ» (الإسراء/67) Translation: And when adversity touches you at sea, lost are all those you invoke except Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3337,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Flattery - Flattery",
      "hw": "Flattery",
      "s": "«چاپلوسی» is a special point of flattery that shows a person's best behavior and encouragement.",
      "d": "«چاپلوسی» means that a person's heart and soul becomes happy, and their behavior and encouragement also becomes better, when they flatter someone. This word compared to others is a special point of flattery that shows a person's best behavior and encouragement. This word is also used in the Quran when a person flatters someone, they do so with all their heart's happiness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا جَاءُوا عَلَيْكُمْ قَالُوا سَلَامًا» (2/25) Translation: And when they come to you, they say, 'Peace.'"
    }
  ],
  "729": [
    {
      "id": 3339,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Knowledge - Knowledge",
      "hw": "Knowledge",
      "s": "«دانش» is the special quality of reading, understanding, and knowledge that gives a person the ability to understand and use information.",
      "d": "«دانش» means reading, understanding, and is the special quality of knowledge that gives a person the ability to understand and use information. Its original radical word is 'د-ن-ش' which means reading and understanding repeatedly. Compared to this, 'علم' generally looks at information or recognition, while 'دانش' is information that gives a person the ability to understand and use it. 'علم' is a general term, while 'دانش' is a specific term that shows a person's education, understanding, and performance. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّهُ يَعْلَمُ مَا تَحْمِلُ كُلُّ أُنثَىٰ وَمَا تَغِيضُ الْأَرْحَامُ وَمَا تَزْدَادُ ۖ وَكُلُّ شَيْءٍ عِندَهُ بِمِقْدَارٍ» (الرعد/8) Translation: Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs lose [prematurely] or exceed. And everything with Him is by due measure."
    },
    {
      "id": 3340,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Knowledge - Awareness",
      "hw": "Knowledge",
      "s": "«آگہی» means the ability to know and the collection of education that specifically expresses divine wisdom and the Prophet's teaching.",
      "d": "«آگہی» root word is 'آگہی' which originally means wisdom, knowledge, and education. These words are used in somewhat different meanings but 'آگہی' is especially used in the meaning of knowing something, understanding it, and obtaining its related knowledge. Its meaning is wisdom determined by Allah, and obtaining that wisdom. Compared to other words, 'آگہی' specifically means obtaining wisdom and its educational use which is given by Allah. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ يَعْلَمُ مَا فِي السَّمَاءِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (البقرة/29) Translation: Do you not know that Allah knows what is in the heaven and earth?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3341,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Knowledge - Recognition",
      "hw": "Knowledge",
      "s": "«معرفت» is a special type of knowledge that expresses detailed information about previously known things.",
      "d": "«معرفت» is a special type of knowledge that expresses detailed information about previously known things. Its Arabic root is معرفت which originally has the meaning of 'to know' and 'to recognize'. Its meaning is that a person has knowledge which they store in their mind and can also tell it to other people. This differs from knowing knowledge and information knowledge, because معرفت means knowing that thing along with expressing it clearly. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يَصْنَعُونَ» (آل عمران/75) Translation: And Allah is most knowing of what they do."
    }
  ],
  "730": [
    {
      "id": 3342,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect - Intellect",
      "hw": "Intellect",
      "s": "«عَقْل» is that intellect which protects from harm and makes arrangements to choose beneficial things.",
      "d": "«عَقَلَ» means to be understanding. To be capable of feeling error (منجد) and «عَقَلَ» means to stop and prevent. And «عِقَال» is the hobble with which a camel's leg is tied (مف). Thus the work of intellect is to distinguish between its benefit and harm, to make arrangements to avoid harmful things (فق۔ل 65) and to be ready at all times for beneficial things and accepting knowledge. Then to think (مف). For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ قَالُوۡا لَوۡ كُنَّا نَسْمَعُ اَوۡ نَعْقِلُ مَا كُنَّا فِيۡۤ اَصْحٰبِ السَّعِيۡرِ» (67/10) Translation: And they will say, 'If we had been listening or reasoning, we would not be among the companions of the Blaze.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3343,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect - Wisdom",
      "hw": "Intellect",
      "s": "«خرد» is called human mental ability and comprehension capability that Allah has given to humans so they may understand truth and make reform.",
      "d": "«خرد» original root is خرد, which originally looks at the ability to understand everything and make correct decisions. This word connects with words like 'عقل', 'فکر', 'تفکر', and 'ہوش'. But instead of 'عقل', the use of 'خرد' generally limits human mental capability and the ability to understand truth through it. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمِ الْأَوَّلِينَ» (الحجر/10) Translation: And We had certainly sent [messengers] before you among the sects of the former peoples."
    },
    {
      "id": 3344,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect - Understanding",
      "hw": "Intellect",
      "s": "«فہم» means mental understanding and the knowledge of wisdom that gives a person feeling related to Allah's guidance.",
      "d": "«فہم» has an Arabic root فہم (فَهْم) which in Urdu means 'to understand' and 'to comprehend'. These words are very important and more specific, while the meaning of عقل is generally as mental power. Terms related to عقل mean for example the power of understanding, the ability to understand, and forming theory. The meaning of عقل is human mental power which gives them the ability to understand and comprehend, while the meaning of فہم is the ability to understand which is especially a part of human mental power. For example, in the Holy Quran: «الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ لَهُمْ أَجْرٌ غَيْرُ مَمْنُونٍ» (الانشقاق/25) Translation: Those who have believed and done righteous deeds - for them is a reward uninterrupted."
    }
  ],
  "731": [
    {
      "id": 3345,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Thought - Thought",
      "hw": "Thought",
      "s": "«سوچ» means mental thinking, reflection, and analysis that is given by Allah.",
      "d": "«سوچ» Arabic root is سوچ (س-و-چ) which expresses thinking, reflection, analysis, and mental process. Its verbal synonyms are گھنٹا, فکر, تفکر, تحلیل, and تذکرہ, but 'سوچ' is especially a manifestation of vision and thinking given by Allah. Its explanation happens like multiple words that think about Allah and turn themselves toward Allah while thinking. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَفَلَا يَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (3/190) Translation: Do they not reflect upon the creation of the heavens and earth?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3346,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Thought - Thinking",
      "hw": "Thought",
      "s": "«فکر» is the original meaning of thought that is the process of reflecting and feeling through the mind.",
      "d": "«فکر» Arabic root word is ف-ک-ر which expresses reflection, thought, and mental process. This word differs from other synonyms of thought like 'تامل' or 'الٹا' because in فکر the element of mental reflection and analysis is more clear. This word expresses the operation of human mind which is the process of thinking, understanding, and comprehending. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلْ إِنَّمَا أَعِظُكُم بِوَاحِدَةٍ ۖ أَن تَقُومُوا لِلَّهِ مَثْنَىٰٰ وَفُرَادَىٰ ثُمَّ تَتَفَكَّرُوا» (سبأ/46) Translation: Say, 'I only advise you of one [thing] - that you stand for Allah, [in pairs] or individually, and then give thought.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3347,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Thought - Idea",
      "hw": "Thought",
      "s": "«خیال» is a special method of thought that is based on the mind's concepts and thoughts.",
      "d": "«خیال» means the mind's concepts, thoughts, and the process of thinking that is created in human mind. This expresses not with words but the internal process of the mind. Besides its synonym words like 'فکر' and 'تجربہ', خیال especially expresses human mental concepts. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَفَلَا يَتَدَبَّرُونَ الْقُرْآنَ ۚ وَلَوْ كَانَ مِنْ عِندِ غَيْرِ اللَّهِ لَوَجَدُوا فِيهِ اخْتِلَافًا كَثِيرًا» (النساء/82) Translation: Do they not then reflect upon the Quran? If it had been from [any] other than Allah, they would have found within it much contradiction."
    }
  ],
  "732": [
    {
      "id": 3348,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Memory - Memory",
      "hw": "Memory",
      "s": "«یاد» means to keep in mind and its connection is again with performance and remembrance.",
      "d": "«یاد» Arabic origin is یَادَ (یاد) which is related like a number, and its meaning is to keep in mind, to remember, and its difference with other words is that 'یاد' is a human mind's capability that keeps a thing as remembrance and with related performance, while other words like 'ذکر' or 'تذکرہ' generally point to indicating something. Proven is: 'یاد کرو گا تو ہو گا' (البقرۃ 2/286) Translation: When you have kept it in your memory, its effect will be there."
    },
    {
      "id": 3349,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Memory - Memorization",
      "hw": "Memory",
      "s": "«حافظہ» means to remember, to keep as storage, and to protect it.",
      "d": "«حافظہ» means to remember, to protect, and such storage that is preserved. Its original verbal root is from 'حفظ' which says to remember, to protect, and to save. The specificity of memory in this meaning is that it is not only remembering but also protecting it with restraint. Compared to other words, 'یاد' is generally remembering, while in 'حافظہ' the meaning of memory's protection and storage is included. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَوَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَيْفَ يُبْدِئُ اللَّهُ الْخَلْقَ ثُمَّ يُعِيدُهُ ۚ إِنَّ ذَٰلِكَ عَلَى اللَّهِ يَسِيرٌ» (العنکبوت/19) Translation: Have they not considered how Allah begins creation and then repeats it? Indeed that, for Allah, is easy."
    },
    {
      "id": 3350,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Memory - Remembrance",
      "hw": "Memory",
      "s": "«تذکر» means to remember, especially things that have come from Allah and mentioning them which helps a person.",
      "d": "«تذکر» Arabic root is تذکر, which originally means to remember, to mention, and to understand and present things that have come from Allah. This word for remembering is especially used for Allah's commands and remembering His words. Compared to this, 'یاد' generally says remembering, while 'تذکر' especially says mentioning and its remembrance. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ أَنْجَيْنَا مُوسَىٰ وَأَهْلَهُ مِنَ الْعَذَابِ الْأَلِيمِ» (الشعراء/28) Translation: And [mention] when We saved Moses and his people from the painful punishment."
    }
  ],
  "733": [
    {
      "id": 3352,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Conversation",
      "hw": "Speech",
      "s": "«گفتگو» means conversation, learning talk, dialogue that happens with understanding.",
      "d": "«گفتگو» Arabic origin is گفتگو, which shows the act of speaking and hearing. This word is related to conversation, dialogue, learning talk, and understanding. Compared to this, 'بات' means general talk, but 'گفتگو' means a conceptual or intellectual talk that happens with understanding and learning. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً» (البقرة/30) Translation: And [mention] when your Lord said to the angels, 'Indeed, I will make upon the earth a successive authority.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3353,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Speech",
      "hw": "Speech",
      "s": "«کلام» is the meaning of speech that is transmitted through text and speech.",
      "d": "«کلام» original root is کلمہ which is related to speech, talk, and text. These words are the name of both word and talk, while other synonyms like 'قول' or 'بیان' only mention the expression of talk. 'کلام' is originally the meaning of speech which is the state of talk. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ اللَّهُ يَا عِيسَى ابْنَ مَرْيَمَ أَأَنتَ قُلْتَ لِلنَّاسِ اتَّخِذُونِي وَأُمِّيَ إِلَٰهَيْنِ مِن دُونِ اللَّهِ» (المائدة/116) Translation: And [mention] when Allah will say, 'O Jesus, Son of Mary, did you say to the people, \"Take me and my mother as deities besides Allah\"?'"
    }
  ],
  "734": [
    {
      "id": 3355,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Discussion",
      "hw": "Debate",
      "s": "«مباحثہ» means to debate, to discuss with opposition on a topic which is done to defend a theory or argument.",
      "d": "«مباحثہ» Arabic radical root is مابحثہ (مبح) which is related to the meanings of discussion, debate, and argument. These words are different in some types: to debate, to give reason, to discuss, and to debate with opposition on a topic. مباحثہ is a specific type of debate that happens with reasons and arguments. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَمَا آتَاكُمُ الرَّسُولُ فَخُذُوهُ وَمَا نَهَاكُمْ عَنْهُ فَانتَهُوا» (الحشر/7) Translation: And whatever the Messenger has given you - take; and what he has forbidden you - refrain from."
    },
    {
      "id": 3356,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Debate",
      "hw": "Debate",
      "s": "«مناظرہ» gives the meaning of debate which assists about alternative opinion on a topic.",
      "d": "«مناظرہ» means to reconcile different viewpoints on a topic, to debate according to alternative opinion, and to clarify one's opinion. Its literal meaning is 'to see' or 'to see viewpoints' which indicates debating on a specific topic. Compared to this, it differs from 'جدل' and 'جدل' because in 'مناظرہ' there is only debate of alternative opinion on one topic, while in 'جدل' opposition or quarrel can also be included. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَادَلُوا فِي آيَاتِ اللَّهِ بِغَيْرِ سُلْطَانٍ أَتَاهُمْ كَبُرَ مَقْتًا عِندَ اللَّهِ وَعِندَ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا» (غافر/35) Translation: Those who dispute concerning the signs of Allah without authority having come to them - great is hatred [of them] in the sight of Allah and in the sight of those who have believed."
    }
  ],
  "735": [
    {
      "id": 3357,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Decision - Decision",
      "hw": "Decision",
      "s": "«فیصلہ» means decision, judgment, and giving order that comes out under a person's mental understanding in a special state.",
      "d": "«فیصلہ» Arabic root word is فَيْصَلٌ which originally means organizing small things. Its literal meaning is 'to do something' or 'to close'. This word differs from other words like 'حکم' or 'قرارت' because فیصلہ especially expresses an order or decision that comes out under a human mental understanding. In the Holy Quran: «رَبَّنَا افْتَحْ بَيْنَنَا وَبَيْنَ قَوْمِنَا بِالْحَقِّ وَأَنتَ خَيْرُ الْفَاتِحِينَ» (الأعراف/89) Translation: Our Lord, decide between us and our people in truth, and You are the best of those who give decision."
    },
    {
      "id": 3358,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Decision - Judgment",
      "hw": "Decision",
      "s": "«حَکَمَ» is a decision by which one is prevented from excess and arrangements are made to correct it.",
      "d": "«حَکَمَ» means «مَنَعَ عَنِ الظُّلْم» (م۔ل) a decision in which oppression and excess is prevented. And means «مَنَعَ عَنِ الْخَصُومَۃ» (فق ل 156) meaning order to prevent from dispute. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ دَاوٗدَ وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ» (21/78) Translation: And [mention] David and Solomon - when they judged concerning the field."
    },
    {
      "id": 3359,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Decision - Decision",
      "hw": "Decision",
      "s": "«قضیہ» means legal order or religious decision that is given for solving issues.",
      "d": "«قضیہ» Arabic origin is which means giving legal or religious order for solving related issues. This word together with others gives the meaning of decision which is done for solving the original issue. Its meaning is a special order or decision that is given for solving an issue. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقَضَىٰ رَبُّكَ أَلَّا تَعْبُدُوا إِلَّا إِيَّاهُ» (الإسراء/23) Translation: And your Lord has decreed that you not worship except Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3360,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Decision - Verdict",
      "hw": "Decision",
      "s": "«فَتَحَ» is a decision by which distinction is made between truth and falsehood and complexity is removed and no party remains in doubt.",
      "d": "«فَتَحَ» means to remove bondage and complexity from something (مف). Its opposite is «اِغْلَاق» meaning imprisonment and bondage (م۔ل) and «فَتَحَ» means to give victory and to decide. Such a decision that distinction is made between truth and falsehood and complexity is removed and no party remains in doubt or suspicion. For example, in the Holy Quran: «رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (7/89) Translation: Our Lord, decide between us and our people in truth."
    }
  ],
  "736": [
    {
      "id": 3361,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Consultation",
      "hw": "Consultation",
      "s": "«مشورہ» means to consult with politics and wisdom which is based on human wisdom and the need for education.",
      "d": "«مشورہ» Arabic origin is (م-ش-و-ر) which is a specific word related to wisdom, consultation, and human education. Its meaning is to consult with politics and wisdom, which is based on human wisdom and the need for education. Compared to this, other synonym words like 'مکالمہ' or 'تشریح' have different meanings, which only means conversation or explanation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَشَاوِرْهُمْ فِي الْأَمْرِ» (آل عمران/159) Translation: And consult them in the matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 3362,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Opinion",
      "hw": "Consultation",
      "s": "«رائے» means opinion, thought, and the original meaning of consultation is to understand a related person's thoughts and viewpoints on a related issue.",
      "d": "«رائے» Arabic origin is رائے (رَآيَة) which is originally related to 'seeing' and 'thinking'. Its meaning is to understand a person's viewpoints, thoughts, and information on an issue. Its synonym is 'مشورہ' but the special meaning of 'رائے' is the feeling of a related person's own seeing, understanding, and thinking. Compared to 'مشورہ', 'رائے' especially shows a person's special thoughts. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَأَمْرُهُمْ شُورَىٰ بَيْنَهُمْ» (الشورى/38) Translation: And whose affair is [determined by] consultation among themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 3363,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Advice",
      "hw": "Consultation",
      "s": "«صلاح» means to consult with truth, justice, and fairness which is necessary for solving related issues.",
      "d": "«صلاح» original meaning is truth, justice, and fairness. These words are the qualities of truth and justice created in a person's heart which are important for a person to understand and make correct decisions. Compared to this, 'مشاورہ' is only talking, while in 'صلاح' a person's quality of justice and truth is also included. This word is a person's quality of justice and truth which is also shown in the process of consultation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَبِمَا رَحْمَةٍ مِّنَ اللَّهِ لِنتَ لَهُمْ ۖ وَلَوْ كُنتَ فَظًّا غَلِيظَ الْقَلْبِ لَانفَضُّوا مِنْ حَوْلِكَ» (آل عمران/159) Translation: So by mercy from Allah, [O Muhammad], you were lenient with them. And if you had been rude [in speech] and harsh in heart, they would have disbanded from about you."
    }
  ],
  "737": [
    {
      "id": 3364,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Question",
      "hw": "Question",
      "s": "«سوال» means that which is asked originally and truly, which points toward information or wisdom.",
      "d": "«سوال» Arabic root word is سوال which originally means to ask something in an elevated way, meaning to ask originally and clearly, to ask for understanding. Its meaning is such a question that is asked for understanding something and for explanation about it. This differs from words which only mean asking questions, but in this there is also the effect of understanding reality. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاسْأَلُوا أَهْلَ الذِّكْرِ إِن كُنتُمْ لَا تَعْلَمُونَ» (النحل/43) Translation: So ask the people of the message if you do not know."
    },
    {
      "id": 3365,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Inquiry",
      "hw": "Question",
      "s": "«پرسش» is a special type of question that can be best seen when a person is encouraged for the answer of their question.",
      "d": "«پرسش» means that a special question is created in a person's mind which they need to know, and encouragement is given to solve this question in the best way. This word is different from the meanings of several other questions like 'سوال' which is generally asking someone, 'استفسار' which is a subtle question, and 'تحلیل' which is a detailed research. These words do not all represent the same meaning. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَسْأَلُونَكَ عَنِ الْأَنفَالِ ۖ قُلِ الْأَنفَالُ لِلَّهِ وَالرَّسُولِ» (الأنفال/1) Translation: They ask you about the bounties [of war]. Say, 'The [decision concerning] bounties is for Allah and the Messenger.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3366,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Interrogation",
      "hw": "Question",
      "s": "«استفسار» is a special form of question that is done to clarify the original issue.",
      "d": "«استفسار» is a special form of question in Urdu which is used to clarify the original issue, obtain information, and obtain explanation about an issue. Its Arabic root word is استفسار which in Urdu gives the meaning of question. Its depth is that this question is done to clarify an issue, and its purpose is to know whether we have understood correctly. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاسْأَلْ بِهِ خَبِيرًا» (الفرقان/59) Translation: So ask about Him one well informed."
    }
  ],
  "738": [
    {
      "id": 3367,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Answer",
      "hw": "Answer",
      "s": "«جواب» means to answer a question, then to say something which is the related answer of the question.",
      "d": "«جواب» Arabic root is «جواب» which means to answer a question, then to say something which is the related answer of the question. Its synonyms are 'جواب دینا', 'پھر کچھ بات کہنا', 'جواب دینا'. But the special meaning of 'جواب' is that when someone answers a question, it should be related to the question. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالُوا سُبْحَانَكَ لَا عِلْمَ لَنَا إِلَّا مَا عَلَّمْتَنَا» (البقرة/32) Translation: They said, 'Exalted are You; we have no knowledge except what You have taught us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3368,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Rejection",
      "hw": "Answer",
      "s": "«ردّ» is to turn back something because of being unacceptable.",
      "d": "«ردّ» to turn back something because of being unacceptable. To return. To repel. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65) Translation: And when they opened their baggage, they found their merchandise had been returned to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3369,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Response",
      "hw": "Answer",
      "s": "«اَجَابَ» is to answer a question.",
      "d": "«اَجَابَ» its opposite is «سَاَلَ» and «سَاَلَ» means to ask a question, and to ask for something is also and to ask something is also. Similarly «اَجَابَ» meanings are also to answer a question. And if something is asked then to accept it or give it is also. Here the answer of a question is under discussion. For example, in the Holy Quran: «یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» (5/109) Translation: [Mention] the Day when Allah will assemble the messengers and say, 'What was the response you received?'"
    }
  ],
  "739": [
    {
      "id": 3370,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Clarification",
      "hw": "Clarification",
      "s": "«وضاحت» means detail and clear expression which clarifies Allah's actions and attributes.",
      "d": "«وضاحت» Arabic origin is (و-ض-ح) which means 'clarity' or 'clarification'. These words are related to each other, but clarification especially works to clarify something. Its meaning is to give a means to understand something in the best way. These words are different, like 'توضیح' which is used for understanding the concept, and 'وضوح' which is the original meaning of clarification. For example, in the Holy Quran: «الَّذِي أَنزَلَ الْكِتَابَ بِالْحَقِّ» (3/7) Translation: The One who sent down the Book in truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3371,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Explanation",
      "hw": "Clarification",
      "s": "«تشریح» is the meaning of clarification which clarifies the original subject and gives its detail.",
      "d": "«تشریح» Arabic origin is تشریح which is to clarify in detail. Its root is تشریح meaning to clarify in detail, while the difference from other words like 'شرح' or 'تبین' is that 'تشریح' is especially the word for detailed explanation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا تُتْلَىٰ عَلَيْهِمُ الْآيَاتُ» (الأنعام/95) Translation: And when the verses are recited to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3372,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Interpretation",
      "hw": "Clarification",
      "s": "«تفسیر» means clarification that is to express something in a clear way which shows the original meaning.",
      "d": "«تفسیر» means to express something in a clear way, which shows the original meaning, indication, and detail. Its synonym words like 'وضاحت', 'شرح', 'توضیح', 'شرح' and 'پیش کاری' but the special point of 'تفسیر' is that it includes the process of clarifying the original meaning. 'تفسیر' is used for the reader to gain benefit from the original subject. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَهْلَكْنَا مِن قَبْلِهِم مِّنَ الْقُرُونِ» (الأنعام/6) Translation: Have they not seen how many generations We destroyed before them?"
    }
  ],
  "740": [
    {
      "id": 3373,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Truth",
      "hw": "Truth",
      "s": "«سچ» special meaning is reality, truth, and something that is ultimately correct as opposed to falsehood.",
      "d": "«سچ» Arabic origin is (س-چ-ی) which expresses original reality, truth, and correctness. This word connects with possible words which give the meaning of 'truthfulness' or 'صدق'. This differs from other synonymous words like 'درست' or 'واقعی' because it is used as a social and philosophical concept which shows original truth. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا آمِنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ» (النساء/136) Translation: O you who have believed, believe in Allah and His Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 3374,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Truthfulness",
      "hw": "Truth",
      "s": "«صداقت» means the ability to present reality and truth which is a fundamental part of human moral and religious structure.",
      "d": "«صداقت» Arabic root word is ص-د-ق which originally expresses 'reality' and 'correctness'. This word shows a person's original reality, which is free from anxiety, disobedience, and corruption. Compared to this, the meaning of 'سچ' is generally that something is correct, but the meaning of 'صداقت' is to present reality and truth, which is a fundamental part of human moral structure. This expresses the health of human heart, human ethics, and religious structure. For example, in the Holy Quran: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَنفِقُوا مِن طَيِّبَاتِ مَا كَسَبْتُمْ» (البقرة/267) Translation: O you who have believed, spend from the good things which you have earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 3375,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Reality",
      "hw": "Truth",
      "s": "«حقیقت» expresses the original reality and correctness of truth which affects the servant's heart and tongue.",
      "d": "«حقیقت» Arabic root is 'ح ق ت' which expresses original reality, correctness, and goodness. This word is used as a specific and complete form of truth which includes original reality besides simple truth. Its synonyms include 'صِدْق' (صدق) and 'سَحْب' (سچ) but the meaning of 'حقیقت' is truth that shows original reality. For example, in the Holy Quran: «الْحَقُّ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَلَا تَكُونَنَّ مِنَ الْمُمْتَرِينَ» (آل عمران/60) Translation: The truth is from your Lord, so never be among the doubters."
    }
  ],
  "741": [
    {
      "id": 3376,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lie - Lie",
      "hw": "Lie",
      "s": "«جھوٹ» means speech that is not correct and does not correspond to reality, and expresses disobedience from truth.",
      "d": "«جھوٹ» Arabic origin starts from the letter (جھوٹ) which originally indicates a sign against correctness. Its literal meaning is 'not to be correct' or 'to be away from reality'. Compared to its synonym words like 'ضلال' or 'غلو', in 'جھوٹ' there is especially the quality of disobeying truth with human knowledge and will. The meaning of lie is that a person ignores reality and says a wrong thing, which works with their knowledge and will. For example, in the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يَكْتُمُونَ مَا أَنزَلَ اللَّهُ مِنَ الْكِتَابِ» (آل عمران/187) Translation: Indeed, those who conceal what Allah has sent down of the Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 3377,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lie - Falsehood",
      "hw": "Lie",
      "s": "«کِذْب» is a lie - speech against reality.",
      "d": "«کِذْب» means to deliberately give wrong news (منجد). Lack of harmony between heart and tongue (مطابقت) (مف) or to speak against reality. And its opposite is 'صِدْق'. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (3/78) Translation: And they speak falsehood about Allah while they know."
    },
    {
      "id": 3378,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lie - Falsehood",
      "hw": "Lie",
      "s": "«دروغ» is the original meaning of lie which is related to a series that shows irregular and wrong speech.",
      "d": "«دروغ» in Urdu is the original meaning of lie, which is to say something wrong against the original event. Its Arabic root is 'درغ' which is related to a series that shows irregular and wrong speech. This word is also possibly different from other cases of lie, while 'جھوٹ' generally expresses extreme despair according to human heart. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَقُولُوا لِمَا تَصِفُ أَلْسِنَتُكُمُ الْكَذِبَ هَٰذَا حَلَالٌ وَهَٰذَا حَرَامٌ» (النحل/116) Translation: And do not say about what your tongues describe of falsehood, 'This is lawful and this is unlawful.'"
    }
  ],
  "742": [],
  "743": [
    {
      "id": 3382,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Certainty - Certainty",
      "hw": "Certainty",
      "s": "«یقین» means the feeling of tranquility that arises from the heart's certainty which is established against the irregularity of knowledge and doubt.",
      "d": "«یقین» Arabic origin is (یقین) which is originally the feeling of heart's tranquility. Its literal meaning is 'to recognize' or 'to see' which is the feeling of seeing a broken news. The meaning of certainty is tranquility which is without doubt, while faith is tranquility with knowledge. Compared to certainty, the meaning of faith is tranquility which comes with wisdom and education. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَا إِنَّ أَوْلِيَاءَ اللَّهِ لَا خَوْفٌ عَلَيْهِمْ وَلَا هُمْ يَحْزَنُونَ» (يونس/62) Translation: Unquestionably, [for] the allies of Allah there will be no fear concerning them, nor will they grieve."
    },
    {
      "id": 3383,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Certainty - Confidence",
      "hw": "Certainty",
      "s": "«اعتماد» is the original meaning of certainty which is such a fixed and strong feeling in human heart that cannot be changed by others.",
      "d": "«اعتماد» means a hidden and strong feeling in human heart which in such a situation is expressed with certainty and faith. This word is different from several others, like 'ایمان' or 'صدق' which expresses faith, but 'اعتماد' is the original meaning of certainty which is inside the heart and has its faithful state. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَعَلَى اللَّهِ فَلْيَتَوَكَّلِ الْمُؤْمِنُونَ» (آل عمران/122) Translation: And upon Allah let the believers rely."
    }
  ],
  "744": [
    {
      "id": 3385,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News - News",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«خَبْر» is that news whose connection is with the listener's self and they can be affected by it.",
      "d": "«خَبْر» its plural is اخبار. It is a famous word. Such an event about which a person has no knowledge and they get information through someone else is news. Knowledge of surrounding conditions. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قَالَ لِأَهْلِهِ امْكُثُوا إِنِّي آنَسْتُ نَارًا لَعَلِّي آتِيكُم مِّنْهَا بِخَبَرٍ» (28/29) Translation: Moses said to his family, 'Stay here; indeed, I have perceived a fire. Perhaps I will bring you from there [some] information.' In another place Allah says: «قُل لَّا تَعْتَذِرُوا لَن نُّؤْمِنَ لَكُمْ قَدْ نَبَّأَنَا اللَّهُ مِنْ أَخْبَارِكُمْ» (9/94) Translation: Say, 'Make no excuse - never will we believe you. Allah has already informed us of your news.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News - Information",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«اطلاع» is the original meaning of news which is the process of conveying information to a person.",
      "d": "«اطلاع» means to give a person knowledge of something, to inform. Its Arabic root is اطلاع, which is the process of learning, informing, and giving news. Besides its synonym words like خبر, اخبار, and خبرداری, 'اطلاع' is especially the process of conveying information to a person. For example, in the Holy Quran: «عَالِمِ الْغَيْبِ فَلَا يُظْهِرُ عَلَىٰ غَيْبِهِ أَحَدًا» (الجن/26) Translation: [He is] Knower of the unseen, and He does not disclose His [knowledge of the] unseen to anyone."
    },
    {
      "id": 3387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News - Newsletter",
      "hw": "News",
      "s": "«خبرنامہ» means the announcement of news or giving information which gives a person knowledge that they bring change in their behavior.",
      "d": "«خبرنامہ» Arabic root is خبر (خ-ب-ر) which expresses the meanings of information, news, announcement, and informing. Its complete word form is خبرنامہ which is the process of conveying news. Compared to this, 'خبر' only means information or news, while 'خبرنامہ' is its process of communication or process of broadcasting. The meaning of 'خبرنامہ' is the announcement of news or giving information which gives a person knowledge that they bring change in their behavior. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِلَىٰ ثَمُودَ أَخَاهُمْ صَالِحًا قَالَ يَا قَوْمِ اعْبُدُوا اللَّهَ» (هود/61) Translation: And to Thamud [We sent] their brother Salih. He said, 'O my people, worship Allah.'"
    }
  ],
  "745": [
    {
      "id": 3388,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Information - Information",
      "hw": "Information",
      "s": "«معلومات» term's special meaning is to convey deliberately understood and available information in a topic-based manner.",
      "d": "«معلومات» Arabic origin is معلومات (مَعْلُومات) which indicates the quality of making known and making known information available. This word is distinguished from various terms like 'علم' which is generally a term for knowledge, 'خبر' which are very simple news, and 'عرف' which is mental understanding or comprehension. The special meaning of information is to deliberately understand information in a topic-based manner, to correctly understand incoming information, and to use them correctly. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَمَا يَعْزُبُ عَن رَّبِّكَ مِن مِّثْقَالِ ذَرَّةٍ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَلَا فِي السَّمَاءِ» (يونس/61) Translation: Not absent from your Lord is any [part] of an atom's weight within the earth or within the heaven."
    },
    {
      "id": 3389,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Information - Data",
      "hw": "Information",
      "s": "«ڈیٹا» is the original meaning of information which becomes known to a person through knowledge and understanding.",
      "d": "«ڈیٹا» means information that goes into a person's mind, which is related to knowledge, information, and wisdom. These words are used in different ways but the special meaning of 'ڈیٹا' is what becomes known to a person through understanding. This is not about speech but about information. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلْ هُوَ اللَّهُ أَحَدٌ» (الإخلاص/1) Translation: Say, 'He is Allah, [who is] One.'"
    }
  ],
  "746": [
    {
      "id": 3391,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Education",
      "hw": "Education",
      "s": "«تعلیم» means learning and teaching through help and support which gives a person the opportunity to learn with their original understanding.",
      "d": "«تعلیم» Arabic root is 'ع-ل-م' which originally means 'teaching' and 'education', which gives a person the opportunity to learn with their original understanding. Its meaning is that a person is given the opportunity to learn something, which gives them the opportunity to learn with their developed understanding. This concept is a specific type of education which gives a person the opportunity to learn their principles and moral values. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَعَلَّمَ آدَمَ الْأَسْمَاءَ كُلَّهَا» (البقرة/31) Translation: And He taught Adam the names - all of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3392,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Teaching",
      "hw": "Education",
      "s": "«تدریس» means the process of education, which is the process of giving knowledge to a person with the deception of teaching.",
      "d": "«تدریس» original root word is 'تدريس' which in Arabic language means 'the process of teaching someone' or 'to give knowledge to someone'. These words express the general concept of education, but 'تدریس' especially expresses the process of giving knowledge, the deception of learning that accompanies it, and the supervision of its principled and skilled organization. Compared to this, 'تعلیم' is generally an official or learning facility, while the meaning of 'تدریس' is the process of teaching. For example, in the Holy Quran: «كَمَا أَرْسَلْنَا فِيكُمْ رَسُولًا مِّنكُمْ يَتْلُو عَلَيْكُمْ آيَاتِنَا وَيُزَكِّيكُمْ وَيُعَلِّمُكُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَالْحِكْمَةَ» (البقرة/151) Translation: Just as We have sent among you a messenger from yourselves reciting to you Our verses and purifying you and teaching you the Book and wisdom."
    }
  ],
  "747": [
    {
      "id": 3394,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Learning - Learning",
      "hw": "Learning",
      "s": "«سیکھنا» means to understand and examine something with interest and enthusiasm.",
      "d": "«سیکھنا» original root word is سیکھنا which in Urdu means the process of understanding, examining, and comprehending. These words are different from each other, like 'جانتا ہوں' or 'جانا' which is generally knowledge of information, but in 'سیکھنا' there is the meaning of interest, detailed examination, and enthusiasm. These words have a specific difference from each other which is related to their respective work. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا قُرِئَ الْقُرْآنُ فَاسْتَمِعُوا لَهُ وَأَنصِتُوا لَعَلَّكُمْ تُرْحَمُونَ» (الأعراف/204) Translation: So when the Quran is recited, then listen to it and pay attention that you may receive mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 3395,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Learning - Acquiring Knowledge",
      "hw": "Learning",
      "s": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا» is the process of study and comprehension which according to the Holy Quran is necessary for giving a person faith and knowledge.",
      "d": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا» means to learn by recognizing something through understanding, which in the original meaning is the process of understanding and obtaining knowledge of the visible thing. Its Arabic origin is from 'تعلیم' which is the process of increasing. Compared to this, 'سیکھنا' is generally the process of learning while 'تعلیم حاصل کرنا' is to obtain something through understanding. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقُولُوا آمَنَّا بِاللَّهِ وَمَا أُنزِلَ إِلَيْنَا» (البقرة/136) Translation: And say, 'We have believed in Allah and what has been revealed to us.'"
    }
  ],
  "748": [
    {
      "id": 3396,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Understanding",
      "hw": "Understanding",
      "s": "«سمجھ» means to create and understand the concept, and through it to use wisdom and intellect.",
      "d": "«سمجھ» original root is س-م-جھ, which is the process of creating and understanding the concept. This is not only with words but to create and understand the concept through intellect, wisdom, and comprehension. This word is similar to other synonyms like 'فهم' or 'علم' but the special connection of 'سمجھ' is with intellectual understanding, comprehension, and wisdom. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَفَلَا يَتَدَبَّرُونَ الْقُرْآنَ أَمْ عَلَىٰ قُلُوبٍ أَقْفَالُهَا» (محمد/24) Translation: Do they not then reflect upon the Quran, or are there locks upon [their] hearts?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3397,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Comprehension",
      "hw": "Understanding",
      "s": "«ادراک» is a special level of understanding which shows great development and comprehension.",
      "d": "«ادراک» in Urdu is a special level of understanding which shows great development and comprehension. Its Arabic root word is ادراک which originally is seeing things and understanding them and understanding their development. This is a specific type of meaning in reference to words which is more than simple understanding. Compared to its synonym words like 'فہم' or 'ہوش', the meaning of 'ادراک' is to clearly understand things and see their reality. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ ذَرَأْنَا لِجَهَنَّمَ كَثِيرًا مِّنَ الْجِنِّ وَالْإِنسِ» (الأعراف/179) Translation: And We have certainly created for Hell many of the jinn and mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 3398,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Understanding",
      "hw": "Understanding",
      "s": "«فہم» means to understand by examining, to understand with wisdom, and to understand the meaning in a better way.",
      "d": "«فہم» Arabic root is فهم, which originally means 'to understand', 'to examine', and 'to recognize'. These words are different: 'سُمْع' (hearing sound), 'فَهْم' (understanding), and 'عِلْم' (knowing). The special meaning of 'فہم' is to understand something with original meaning, wisdom, and through understanding, not only hearing but understanding by examining. This is a detailed, and better way of understanding. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِن مِّنكُمْ إِلَّا وَارِدُهَا ۚ كَانَ عَلَىٰ رَبِّكَ حَتْمًا مَّقْضِيًّا» (مريم/71) Translation: And there is none of you except he will come to it. This is upon your Lord an inevitability decreed."
    }
  ],
  "749": [
    {
      "id": 3399,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Walking",
      "hw": "Walking",
      "s": "«چلنا» means to move, to deliberately move forward, and to proceed toward one's purpose.",
      "d": "«چلنا» Arabic root is چ-ل-ن-ا, which originally gives the meaning of movement, moving forward, and deliberately working. These words are used in different ways, for example there is a difference between 'چلنا' and 'جنا', where 'چلنا' indicates human and logical movement, while 'جنا' generally means walking with extreme speed or appearing on a specific occasion. 'چلنا' is a famous word for human and safe movement. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَامْشُوا فِي مَنَاكِبِهَا وَكُلُوا مِن رِّزْقِهِ» (الملك/15) Translation: So walk among its slopes and eat from His provision."
    },
    {
      "id": 3400,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Moving",
      "hw": "Walking",
      "s": "«حرکت کرنا» is the meaning of walking which happens when a human or animal moves from one place to another place.",
      "d": "«حرکت کرنا» means to move something or person from one place to another place, which is originally the state of walking for human or animal. These words are different: 'چلنا' is generally a means for human or animal walking, while 'حرکت کرنا' generally means the movement of a thing, which is also related to walking. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَوَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَىٰ مَا خَلَقَ اللَّهُ مِن شَيْءٍ يَتَفَيَّأُ ظِلَالُهُ» (النحل/48) Translation: Do they not see what things Allah has created whose shadows incline?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3401,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Departing",
      "hw": "Walking",
      "s": "«روانہ ہونا» means that something moves with constant speed, like walking feet.",
      "d": "«روانہ ہونا» word in Arabic is synonymous with روانہ ہونا, which originally means something moving constantly. This word does not indicate someone's inactivity or less movement but expresses their active movement. This word is different from other synonyms like 'چلنا' which generally looks at someone's feet movement, but the meaning of 'روانہ ہونا' is that something moves automatically, like water flowing. For example, in the Holy Quran: «مَّثَلُ الْجَنَّةِ الَّتِي وُعِدَ الْمُتَّقُونَ ۖ فِيهَا أَنْهَارٌ مِّن مَّاءٍ غَيْرِ آسِنٍ» (محمد/15) Translation: Is the description of Paradise, which the righteous are promised, wherein are rivers of water unaltered."
    }
  ],
  "750": [
    {
      "id": 3402,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Running - Running",
      "hw": "Running",
      "s": "«دوڑنا» means to walk quickly, to exit, and to spread untimely.",
      "d": "«دوڑنا» Arabic root (د-ر-ن) means to walk quickly, to roam, and to exit. These words give the meaning of something being sold or spread untimely or without knowledge. Its synonym words like 'پھیلانا' or 'بے وقت چلنا' are similar in meaning but in 'دوڑنا' there is especially a feeling of speed and haste. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاسْعَوْا إِلَىٰ ذِكْرِ اللَّهِ» (الجمعة/9) Translation: Then proceed to the remembrance of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3403,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Running - Fleeing",
      "hw": "Running",
      "s": "«بھاگنا» is the meaning of running which expresses the state of speed and escaping from danger.",
      "d": "«بھاگنا» in Urdu expresses running, quick movement, and the state of escaping from danger. Its Arabic origin is بھاگنا which is the process of walking with speed, escaping, and exiting from danger. It is possible with these words that its meaning is running, but it also includes the state of escaping. Its special meaning is to remove some danger or risk. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَفِرُّوا إِلَى اللَّهِ» (الذاريات/50) Translation: So flee to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3404,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Running - Walking Fast",
      "hw": "Running",
      "s": "«تیز چلنا» means to walk something in the best way and with more speed which is used in the meaning of running.",
      "d": "«تیز چلنا» Arabic origin is تیز چلنا which in the original meaning is to walk with the most speed. These words are different from each other, like 'ہوا' which is said to walk something well, but the meaning of 'تیز چلنا' is that walking which happens in the best way and with more speed. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاسْعَوْا إِلَىٰ مَغْفِرَةٍ مِّن رَّبِّكُمْ» (آل عمران/133) Translation: And hasten to forgiveness from your Lord."
    }
  ],
  "751": [
    {
      "id": 3405,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Coming - Coming",
      "hw": "Coming",
      "s": "«آنا» means that one gets the opportunity to see someone, while others do not see.",
      "d": "«آنا» Arabic root is and its meaning is to see, to appear, and to appear from home. These words are further elsewhere like 'نَظَر' or 'رَأَى', but the special meaning of 'آنا' is that someone is seen, and they see themselves too. This concept holds the collective meaning of coming before someone, appearing, and coming before oneself. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَتَىٰ أَمْرُ اللَّهِ فَلَا تَسْتَعْجِلُوهُ» (النحل/1) Translation: The command of Allah is coming, so be not impatient for it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3406,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Coming - Arriving",
      "hw": "Coming",
      "s": "«وارد ہونا» [to enter something or to come, which appears to come repeatedly or again]",
      "d": "«وارد ہونا» means to enter something, to come, or to be such that appears to come repeatedly or again. Its root is وارد ہونا which is the process of entering something. Its synonym words include 'آنا', 'آیا', 'پہنچنا' but 'وارد ہونا' especially means to enter something or to come repeatedly. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِن مِّنكُمْ إِلَّا وَارِدُهَا» (مريم/71) Translation: And there is none of you except he will come to it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3407,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Coming - Reaching",
      "hw": "Coming",
      "s": "«پہنچنا» means when something or person reaches their place, which expresses the original place or state.",
      "d": "«پہنچنا» original root is پہنچنا which originally means to leave, but its use is such that something or person reaches their theory or place. This term is different from others like the meaning of 'آنا' is that something or person reaches their place, while the meaning of 'آنا' refers to something or person reaching their place. This concept expresses the original place or state. For example, in the Holy Quran: «حَتَّىٰ إِذَا جَاءُوهَا فُتِحَتْ أَبْوَابُهَا» (الزمر/71) Translation: Until, when they reach it, its gates will be opened."
    }
  ],
  "752": [
    {
      "id": 3408,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Going - Going",
      "hw": "Going",
      "s": "«جانا» means to exist with the ability of life and soul, which is the meaning of original life.",
      "d": "«جانا» in Urdu gives the meaning of original life, which is related to the ability of life and soul. Its Arabic origin is (ج ن و) which gives the original meaning of life. Compared to this, the meaning of 'روانا' is the feeling of something or the talk coming to mind, while the meaning of 'پڑھنا' or 'سمجھنا' is to understand something. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَقْتُلُوا أَنفُسَكُمْ ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ كَانَ بِكُمْ رَحِيمًا» (النساء/29) Translation: And do not kill yourselves. Indeed, Allah is to you ever Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3409,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Going - Departing",
      "hw": "Going",
      "s": "«روانہ ہونا» emphasizes the point that one must go with something or continue their state with their activities, as in the Quran it is said that Allah commanded Muslims to go with His guidance.",
      "d": "«روانہ ہونا» means that expression of going with something is made, which is specific and constant. Its root is 'ر-ون-ہ' which originally means 'to walk', 'to move forward', 'journey of guidance'. Its meaning is to go toward something, to be with it, and to act under it. This word is especially used in Quranic terminology when someone is commanded to go with their guidance. For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَانطَلَقَا حَتَّىٰ إِذَا رَكِبَا فِي السَّفِينَةِ خَرَقَهَا» (الكهف/71) Translation: So they set out, until when they had embarked on the ship, he tore it open."
    }
  ],
  "753": [
    {
      "id": 3411,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Roaming - Roaming",
      "hw": "Roaming",
      "s": "«Roaming» means to completely circle around something or to tour it, such as touring the earth.",
      "d": "«Roaming» is an Arabic root word that originally means to completely circle around something, to tour it, or to see all its parts. This word gives the meaning of completely touring something, while other synonyms like «turning» or «roaming» only mean to circle one thing or to roam once. The special meaning of «Roaming» is to completely circle around something or to see all its parts. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِي أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ بِالْقَضِي وَالْمَقْضِي» (39/47) Translation: The One Who revealed the Book with judgment and decree, its meaning is to completely circle around everything, examine it, and see all its parts."
    },
    {
      "id": 3412,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Roaming - Circling",
      "hw": "Roaming",
      "s": "«Circling» means to move around something, change it, or look at it again until it leaves its original state.",
      "d": "«Circling» means to move around something, change it, or look at it again until it leaves its original state. This word means to roam around something, decrease, and do something with it so that it leaves its original state. This word is different from other words with meanings like «roaming» which is generally roaming, but «Circling» has the best concept that the meaning of circle is to change something, to be active, and to look at it again. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُتَّخِذِينَ» (Al-An'am 6/149) Translation: «And they have nothing in that except that they become takers.»"
    }
  ],
  "754": [
    {
      "id": 3413,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Fighting - Fighting",
      "hw": "Fighting",
      "s": "«Fighting» means to quarrel, to struggle, and to mention the act of warfare done by coming out from the station of friendship.",
      "d": "«Fighting» is an Urdu root word that in Urdu mentions the act of warfare done by coming out from the station of friendship against someone. Its original Arabic root word is fighting which originally mentions warfare and struggle. Its other meanings include quarreling over small matters, mentioning the act of warfare done by coming out from the station of friendship against someone. Its Urdu equivalent concept is 'to fight war' or 'to wage warfare'. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَقَطَّعُواْ فَتَفَشَّلَ الْمَوْدَّةُ مِنْكُمْ وَلَا تَقَارَبُواْ فَتَكُونُواْ مِنْهُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ بِالْعَدَاءِ وَالْحَرَبِ» (An-Nisa: 137) Translation: \"And do not come out from the station of friendship to wage warfare, do not wage warfare against other people who are not giving you permission for your warfare.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3414,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Fighting - Waging War",
      "hw": "Fighting",
      "s": "«Waging War» is another name for war which happens with a specific dangerous and large writing.",
      "d": "«Waging War» is another name for war which happens with a specific dangerous and large writing. Its root word is waging war which originally means a large writing, arrangement, and waging war with religious difference. Besides, the synonyms going with «Fighting» are like «cunning», «war», «exposure», «madness», and «warrior». Its special meaning is to wage war through small wars or interventions. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَلِكَ أَن يَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ فَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَلِكَ أَن يَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ» (Al-An'am / 63) Translation: When they are not believers in it, then they will not have the opportunity to be believers in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3415,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Fighting - Confronting",
      "hw": "Fighting",
      "s": "«Confronting» in this sense means to quarrel, to threaten, and to create danger.",
      "d": "«Confronting» means to quarrel, to threaten, and to create danger. Its Arabic root is Muqabilah (confrontation) which originally gives the meaning of confronting. Its relative meaning is to have two-way communication, while Fighting has more dangerous and military meanings than this. Fighting means to have a two-way quarrel which is specifically in the form of danger and attack. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تُلْقَىٰ فِي الْقَوْلِ مِنْ قَبْلِ أَنْ يُقَالَ لَكَ وَلَا تَرْكَ الْحَدِيثَ فَإِنَّهُ أَحَدُ الْمُقَادِمِينَ» (Al-An'am/ 150) Translation: Until someone has said something to you, do not leave someone's talk before, and its meaning is to quarrel and create danger."
    }
  ],
  "755": [
    {
      "id": 3416,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Giving - Giving",
      "hw": "Giving",
      "s": "«Giving» means to command the one who obeys the religion to obey the religion, that is, to give means with the guidance of religion.",
      "d": "«Giving» has an Arabic origin (D-N-A) which originally holds the meaning of commanding religion and giving means for obeying religion. The difference between these words is that \"Giving\" is to command religion, while \"Teaching\" is only to command obedience. Besides, it also has the meaning of \"commanding\" and \"ordering\". Example: In the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ فَإِذَا جَاءَهُمْ بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ قَالُوا هَذَا سِحْرٌ مُّبِينٌ» (An-Nisa: 159) Translation: «All previous Messengers were sent to the People of the Book, when clear proofs came to them, they said this is manifest magic.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3417,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Giving - Bestowing",
      "hw": "Giving",
      "s": "«Bestowing» means to give those points that are sent to humans through the Lord, such as expressing favor, mercy, and great blessings.",
      "d": "«Bestowing»'s original literal source is bestowing which originally means to give or send something. Its meaning is to give someone something they cannot obtain themselves. Its use is originally for giving blessings given by the Lord. In comparison, «Giving» is generally to give one's wealth or favor to someone, while «Bestowing» specifically holds the meaning of giving blessings and favors. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ سَبَقَتْ لَهُمْ مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ مِنْ قَبْلِهِمْ أَنْ يَكُونَ لَهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ إِلَّا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَأَنْ يَكُونُوا مُسْتَقِيمِينَ وَاللَّهُ يُحِبُّ الْمُسْتَقِيمِينَ» (Al-Imran / 38) Translation: \"And it is most secure for those who believed and before them the People of the Book could not make such a guardian except those who believe and who remain upright. Allah loves those who remain upright.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3418,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Giving - Providing",
      "hw": "Giving",
      "s": "«Providing» the meaning of giving is to give something to someone or fulfill their need as a master provides everything to his servant.",
      "d": "«Providing» means to give something to someone, fulfill their need, and provide everything for them. This word is an expression of giving something through someone or fulfilling their need, which is the original meaning of giving. Its synonym is «Giving», but «Providing» has a special importance that to give something to someone or fulfill their need, as a master provides everything to his servant. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا جَاءَكَ الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِآيَاتِنَا فَقُلْ أَسْلَمْتُمْ وَلَهُمُ الدِّينُ وَلِيَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ مَوْلَاهُمْ فِي الدِّينِ» (Al-An'am / 159) Translation: «When those who believe in Our verses come to you, then say: You have accepted Islam and for them the command of religion is the guardian of the Muslims.»"
    }
  ],
  "756": [
    {
      "id": 3419,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Taking - Taking",
      "hw": "Taking",
      "s": "«Taking» means to bring something to oneself, keep it with oneself, and become its owner.",
      "d": "«Taking» has an Arabic origin (L N A) which originally gives the meaning of grasping something, bringing it to oneself, and becoming its owner. This word is used in different ways: «Taking» specifically means to bring such things to oneself like wealth, love, or respect. In comparison, «Akhadh» means to bring something to oneself or obtain it, while «Iqtina» means to make something related to oneself or become its owner. Example: In the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ عِلْمٍ إِلَّا مَا اَخَذَتْهُ الْمَوْجُ مِنْهُ» (Surah An-Naml, verse 39) Translation: \"And they had no share of knowledge except what the wave took from it.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3420,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Taking - Obtaining",
      "hw": "Taking",
      "s": "«Obtaining» means to obtain something and bring it to oneself, while «Taking» is only to present something or bring it to oneself.",
      "d": "«Obtaining»'s Arabic origin is «Hasala» which originally holds the meaning of reaching something, obtaining it, and bringing it to oneself. This word is used with better composition anywhere, while «Taking» only holds the meaning of presenting something or bringing it to oneself. These two words are different from each other because «Obtaining» is an action that happens after obtaining something, while «Taking» is only to present something or bring it to oneself. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَسَّكُمُ الْقَلَبُ مِنَ الْحَزْنِ فَأَخَذَتْكُمُ الْمَوْتُ» (Al-An'am/128) Translation: When anxiety comes to your hearts due to the heart, then you are protected from death."
    },
    {
      "id": 3421,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Taking - Taking",
      "hw": "Taking",
      "s": "«Akhdha» means to take something, to take it into possession, to grasp it.",
      "d": "«Akhdha» means to take something, to take it into possession, to grasp it (Mufrad) and its usage is both sensory (i.e., things perceived through one of the five senses) and abstract. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ اِذۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ النَّبِیّٖنَ» (3/81) Translation: And when Allah took the covenant from the Prophets. At another place, Allah the Exalted says: «وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ  اَخَذَ الۡاَلۡوَاحَ» (7/154) Translation: And when Moses' anger subsided, he took up the tablets."
    }
  ],
  "757": [
    {
      "id": 3422,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Opening - Opening",
      "hw": "Opening",
      "s": "«Opening» means to bring something forward, correct it, and give the ability to understand it while it originally means to extract from context.",
      "d": "«Opening» in Urdu lexicons originally means to close something, such as opening a window or door. Its Arabic origin (K-H-L) originally holds the meaning of bringing something forward, correcting it, and giving the ability to understand it. This word holds a special kind of detail and correctness compared to other similar words. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَنزَلْنَا إِلَيْكُمْ كِتَابًا فِيْهِ ذِكْرُكُمْ أَيْنَمَا كُنْتُمْ تُحَرَّكُوْنَ فِيْهِ مُعَلَّقِيْنَ وَكَانَ الْعَذَابُ مُقَرَّبًا» (Al-An'am 6/153) Translation: «And We have sent down to you a Book in which is your remembrance, wherever you are moving in it, you are suspended in it, and the punishment is so near that you understand very well.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3423,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Opening - To Open Wide",
      "hw": "Opening",
      "s": "«To Open Wide» means to close or shut something, while «Opening» originally is in contrast to closing or shutting something.",
      "d": "«To Open Wide» and «Opening» both have an original literal root, meaning in Arabic «To Open Wide»'s root is which means «to close» or «to shut». Besides, «To Open Wide» means to bloom or open something, such as a flower closing or opening. Its contrast is «Opening» which originally means to open something or to open it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالْعَقِلِ الْمُحْتَجِدِ» (Surah An-Naml, verse 30) Translation: And open to examine and see the one who examines their mind."
    }
  ],
  "758": [
    {
      "id": 3424,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Closing - Closing",
      "hw": "Closing",
      "s": "«Closing» originally means to stop something, end it, and put an obstacle in its way.",
      "d": "«Closing»'s Arabic origin is \"Band\" which means to close something, stop it, and end it. These words are different from each other, such as \"Stopping\" (Rokna) or \"Ending\" (Khatam karna) which only means to end an action. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَى الَّذِي نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسْكُونٌ مِّنْ دُونِهِ فَتَقَبَّلَتْ دُعَاؤهُ وَأَصْبَحَ مِنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (Al-Anbiya / 90) Translation: Have you not seen the one who called to his Lord that I am afflicted without Him, so He accepted his supplication and he became among the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 3425,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Closing - Locking",
      "hw": "Closing",
      "s": "«Locking» shows the meaning of completely closing or sealing something such as closing a door or with a key.",
      "d": "«Locking» means to completely close something, seal it, or estimate it such as through a door or key. Its root word is «Qafl» which means to close, seal, and end. This word is different from other synonyms because it is specifically the act of sealing or closing something while other synonyms are to stop or suspend something. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِي فَتَحَ بَابَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَّةِ» (Surah Al-Hijr, verse 37) Translation: «And the One Who opened their door in the religion.»"
    }
  ],
  "759": [
    {
      "id": 3426,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Starting - Starting",
      "hw": "Starting",
      "s": "«Starting» means to begin a work or action, while starting means to begin a new work or action.",
      "d": "«Starting» means to begin a work or action, while starting means to begin a new work or action. Its Arabic root word is starting which originally means \"beginning\". Its other meanings are: to begin, to commence, and to start from. Its synonymous words include \"beginning\", \"commencing\", \"starting\", \"creating\", \"beginning\". Its contrasting word is \"ending\" or \"concluding\". For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ» (Al-Isra/104) Translation: «And We sent Moses with Our verses and clear authority.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3427,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Starting - Commencing",
      "hw": "Starting",
      "s": "«Commencing» holds the meaning of starting an original and pre-existing thing in a new form while «Starting» is generally a word for beginning a new action or operation.",
      "d": "«Commencing»'s Arabic origin (Aaghaz) means to start one thing from its origin, which is at a large level original. Its difference from other words is that \"Starting\" is generally a word for starting something new, while \"Commencing\" is a word for starting the original thing in its original form. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَرَّ بِهِمْ أَنْبِيَاءُ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ أَنْبِيَاءُ مُتَّصِلِينَ بِاللَّهِ وَمَعَهُمْ مُسْتَقِرُّونَ» (Al-Anbiya/ 13) Translation: At that time when Prophets came before them in the land, they are positive with Allah in the land and they hold their destiny with it."
    }
  ],
  "760": [
    {
      "id": 3428,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Ending - Ending",
      "hw": "Ending",
      "s": "«Ending» shows the meaning of completing and ending a work or action, such as organizing prayer or completing Quran recitation.",
      "d": "«Ending»'s Arabic root word is Kh-T-M which originally holds the meaning of completing a work and ending it. This word is different while «Completing» means to complete a work, and «Ending» means to complete a work and reach its final limit. In its verbal writing, it is said that to completely do a work and end it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلْ أَعُوذُ بِرَبِّ الْفَلَقِ مِن شَرِّ مَا خَلَقَ وَمِن شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ إِذَا وَقَبَ وَمِن شَرِّ النَّفَّاثَاتِ فِي الْعُقَدِ وَمِن شَرِّ حَاسِدٍ إِذَا حَسَدَ» (Al-Falaq 113) Translation: «Say: I seek refuge in the Lord of the dawn from the evil of what He created, and from the evil of darkness when it settles, and from the evil of those who blow on knots, and from the evil of an envier when he envies.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3429,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Ending - Concluding",
      "hw": "Ending",
      "s": "«Concluding» comes to the meaning of completely ending or completing a work or action.",
      "d": "«Concluding» means to completely end a work or action, complete it, or reach its extremity. Its root is related to \"Khatam\" which means \"complete\" or \"last\". Its synonymous words like \"ending\", \"completing\", \"to end\", \"to complete\", \"to end\", \"reaching extremity\", \"ending\" and \"to end\" exist but «Concluding»'s special meaning is to completely complete or end a work. Its use is for completely ending a work or action. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا اُوتِيَتْ أَمْوَالُكُمْ فَأَخْتَمَتْ لَكُمْ الْحُلُولُ وَكَانَ لَكُمْ فِيهَا بَرَاءَةٌ مِّنْهَا» (Surah Al-Baqarah 225) Translation: «And when your wealth is obtained by you, then the meaning of your wealth ending is established and in it is your innocence from it.»"
    }
  ],
  "761": [
    {
      "id": 3430,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Creating - Creating",
      "hw": "Creating",
      "s": "«Creating» [means to make something appear, to see it intentionally, or for its existence to come forward.]",
      "d": "«Creating» comes from original Arabic words which are related to «FAYD» (FAYD) which originally means to see something, to create it, or to express being present. Its original meaning is to recognize something, to come forward, or for its existence to become clear. In its other meanings, its use includes something becoming visible, and feeling caused by it. In comparison, «seeing» or «seeing» only expresses visual acceptance, but «Creating» also includes expression of feeling, mind, and existence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا رَآهُ مُحَرَّكًا لَّمْ يَعِدْ» (Al-Qasas / 28) Translation: \"And We sent Moses to Pharaoh with authority, but when he saw it moving, he did not understand.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3431,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Creating - Creating",
      "hw": "Creating",
      "s": "«Creating» in this sense is said to originally create existing living beings through the Lord, while «Creating» is generally to make something appear.",
      "d": "«TPLQ» means to originally create existing living beings through the Lord, which is the act of structuring original creatures. Its original terminological meaning is to create creatures or to create original creation, while «Creating» is generally to make something appear. Its terminological difference is that «TPLQ» is the act of structuring existing living beings through the Lord's power, while «Creating» is simply to make something appear. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا» (Al-Ankabut/30) Translation: \"We have created man from a drop of mixed sperm which We test, so We made him hearing, seeing.\""
    }
  ],
  "762": [
    {
      "id": 3432,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Becoming - Becoming",
      "hw": "Becoming",
      "s": "«Becoming» means the act of making which is originally done by the Lord and its meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will.",
      "d": "«Becoming» in Urdu language indicates a singular action which is done by the Lord. With its original root, its meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will. Its English synonym is \"to create\" or \"to make\". Its other synonym is \"creation\", but in \"Becoming\" the feeling of producing creatures through the Lord is present. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَأَنْبَتْنَا لَهُ حَسَنَةً وَإِنَّا إِلَيْهِ لَمُحْتَشِرُونَ» (Al-A'la 23) Translation: «We have created man from a drop of sperm, for him We have produced goodness for him, and We are gatherers to him.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3433,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Becoming - Taking Form",
      "hw": "Becoming",
      "s": "«Taking Form» means to give something a special shape, structure, and organization that expresses original existence.",
      "d": "«Taking Form» means to give something a special shape, structure, and organization that expresses original existence. This is talk of words that is to bring something into its original form. In comparison, «making» is generally to give something a new form, while «Taking Form» means to show the original form. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ» (Ash-Shu'ara 26/17) Translation: «And We sent Moses with Our verses and clear authority.»"
    }
  ],
  "763": [
    {
      "id": 3434,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Decreasing - Decreasing",
      "hw": "Decreasing",
      "s": "«Decreasing» means to reduce something or to become less, when the quantity or importance of something becomes less.",
      "d": "«Decreasing» is related to the Arabic origin (decreasing) which originally gives the meaning of reducing something or becoming less. Its meaning is that the quantity, importance, or power of something becomes less. It has similarity with synonymous words like 'becoming less' or 'reducing' but «Decreasing» specifically mentions the decrease in power or quantity of something. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَقَدْ أَخَذْنَا مَن فِي الْأَرْضِ مَوْسَىٰ وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَمْ يُؤَخِّرْنَهُمْ إِلَىٰ أَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّى» (Ash-Shu'ara 26:49) Translation: «And if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would have taken those on the earth from Moses, and if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would not have delayed them to an appointed term.» In this, the meaning of «Decreasing» is that if something becomes less or its quantity becomes less, then the effect of your wisdom occurs."
    },
    {
      "id": 3435,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Decreasing - Becoming Less",
      "hw": "Decreasing",
      "s": "«Becoming Less» in this sense is decreasing when something becomes less or deficiency occurs.",
      "d": "«Becoming Less» means that something becomes less, deficiency occurs, or some loss or deficiency is created. These words are used in different ways, but «Becoming Less» specifically shows the deficiency or loss of something. This word gives the meaning of deficiency which expresses the deficiency or weakness of a thing. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَرَّتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الْقَوْمُ الْمُؤْمِنُونَ فَقَالُوا لَهُمْ إِنَّكُمْ لَمَّا بَلَغْتُمْ مَّوْعِدَنَا وَأَنْتُمْ تَكْتُمُونَ» (An-Nisa / 105) Translation: When the believing people passed over them, they said to them: You have reached our appointed time but you conceal from us."
    }
  ],
  "764": [
    {
      "id": 3436,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increasing - Increasing",
      "hw": "Increasing",
      "s": "«Increasing» means that something increases in original quantity or production, such as wealth, progeny, or the spread of religious education.",
      "d": "«Increasing»'s original root is B-R-D, which originally means to increase the quantity or production of something. This word possibly gives the meaning of \"becoming more\" in comparison to \"becoming less\". Like its other words, this word is used specifically in the form of increase, growth, production, and spreading flower. In the Holy Quran, the meaning of increasing is originally presented in the form of religious education, faith, and reform. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ ظَلَمُوا مِنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذَ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَّهُمْ مِّنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذْ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ» (Surah An-Naml, verse 35) Translation: Such people's families will not have intercession and no admonition will be taken from them, so they will get what they thought. Those who increase after admonition, then they go astray."
    },
    {
      "id": 3437,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increasing - Increasing",
      "hw": "Increasing",
      "s": "«Increasing» in this sense means that something becomes more than original, such as increasing or progressing.",
      "d": "«Increasing»'s linguistic root is and its meaning is the progress, increase, or growth of something. These words are different in several ways: increasing (meaning to grow) in the form of everything's meaning is to increase, while the meaning of increasing is that something's more progress is happening. This term is generally used in reference to human progress, natural progress, and religious progress. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَأَحَدًا مِّنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَيَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَكَانُوا يَزْدَادُونَ فِي الْإِيمَانِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَكَانُوا يَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ» (Al-Baqarah 54) Translation: «We sent before you Messengers from the People of the Book, and one from the People of the Book, and they were settled with the believers in Madinah, and they were not fighting the believers in Madinah, and they were increasing in faith, and with the believers from the People of the Book and the believers from the People of the Book, they were settled with the believers in Madinah.»"
    }
  ],
  "765": [
    {
      "id": 3438,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Rising - Rising",
      "hw": "Rising",
      "s": "«Rising» means to bring the body upward or move it toward the chest, while it is different from other words in that this letter is also used in the form of working.",
      "d": "«Rising» means to bring the body upward or move it toward the chest, while it is different from other words in that this letter is also used in the form of working. Its original roots are AWTR (A) and TAHHAR (T) and NAHHAR (N) which is the act of bringing a body upward. This word is also used in the form of working such as when a person starts work or picks up and takes work. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنَ الْمُسْتَقْرِمِينَ مِنْهُمْ فَأَخَذَتْهُمُ الْحَزَنَةُ وَالْمَسَعَةُ وَكَانُوا فِي ذَلِكَ لَيَسْتَفْتِحُونَ» (Al-An'am / 6) Translation: At that time, none of them was picked up and taken on the day of sacrifice, so grief and calamity surrounded them and right there again their and others' sacrifice was picked up and taken."
    },
    {
      "id": 3439,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Rising - Becoming High",
      "hw": "Rising",
      "s": "«Becoming High» is the meaning of rising which is the act of bringing something up or elevating it.",
      "d": "«Becoming High» means to bring something up, to elevate it, or to move it upward to see it. This is different from words that only mention its extreme height, not general coming up. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا سَقَطَتْ سَاقِطَةٌ مِّنْهُمْ فَأَوْرَدَتْ فِي الْعَرْضِ فَأَخْرَجَتْهُ مِنَ الْعَرْضِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/17) Translation: When that falling thing falls from its side, then it enters it into its width and then takes it out from its width."
    }
  ],
  "766": [
    {
      "id": 3440,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Falling - Falling",
      "hw": "Falling",
      "s": "«Falling» means to spread something, increase it, and show it merged with the visible thing while its meaning is to spread the thing, increase it, and show it in its progressing or growing state.",
      "d": "«Falling»'s linguistic original root is with which in Urdu means 'falling' or 'falling'. Its Arabic origin is from 'falling' (gradation) which is to spread things, increase them, grow them, and show them merged with the visible thing. Its meaning occurs when something is increased or its progress happens. In its other meanings is to show the thing merged with the visible thing. This word is used when something is spread, increased, or its progress happens. It is proven that its meaning occurs when something is increased or its progress happens. Showing merged with it occurs when something is shown merged with the visible thing. Example: In the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا رَأَيْتَ الْعُدُوَّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ كَرَأْيَةِ الْعُدُوِّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ» (An-Nisa: 143) Translation: «When you see that the disbelievers are appearing merged with the Muslims, then its meaning is that they are seen that the disbelievers are being shown merged with the Muslims.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3441,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Falling - Falling Down",
      "hw": "Falling",
      "s": "«Falling Down» shows the meaning that something falls to the ground or downward by itself, while originally no compulsion or force is needed in it.",
      "d": "«Falling Down» means for something to fall downward from its original place, which happens by itself, without effort or without a specific cause. Its source is falling down which takes the thing downward from its original place. In comparison, other synonyms like 'falling' mean the work of bringing something down, but in «Falling Down» there is self-occurring movement. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا مَا أَنْزَلْنَا مِنْ آَيَةٍ فَإِنَّمَا يُسْرِفُ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ بِهَا وَيَقُولُونَ أَيُّهُمْ أَكْبَرُ مَوْلَىٰ لَهُ الْمَلَكُ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ» (Surah Al-Ma'idah, verse 57) Translation: When We revealed any verse, then among the believers that activity occurs that they express being more owner than each other, but We revealed their owner that he is the owner of the owner, and they fell that they have no right with the owner."
    }
  ],
  "767": [
    {
      "id": 3442,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Leaving - Leaving",
      "hw": "Leaving",
      "s": "«Leaving» means to leave something on its own, and to look away from it.",
      "d": "«Leaving»'s Arabic origin is \"Dhara'a\" which originally means to explain something, or to look away from it so that it is left. These words are different from each other: \"abandoning\" and \"leaving without account\" are different because in leaving the best feature is to look away from it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَوْلَا دَعْوَتُكُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُمْ مُّهْلِكِينَ» (Al-An'am / 148) Translation: If it were not for your invitation, then you people would have been destroyed."
    },
    {
      "id": 3443,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Leaving - Abandoning",
      "hw": "Leaving",
      "s": "«Abandoning» in this sense is leaving to keep something away from oneself and not to emphasize it, such as ignoring the Lord's command.",
      "d": "«Abandoning» means to keep something away from oneself, not to emphasize it, and to separate it from oneself. This word gives the choice to do or not do a work or action. Its original root word is TARAKUN (abandoning) which originally means to leave something, to be free from it, or not to emphasize it. Its synonymous words like «abandoning», «leaving», «abandoning», «making unique», «stopping», «closing» and «estimating» exist but «Abandoning»'s special meaning is to separate something from oneself, to end relation with it, and not to emphasize it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا أَعِدَّةً مِّنْ عَادٍ أَوْ مُتَّقِينَ لَكَانَ خَيْرًا لَّهُمْ وَأَحْسَنَ تَرْكًا» (Al-An'am / 6) Translation: If they had been prepared from Aad or as righteous, then thinking about it would have been better for them and leaving it would have been good."
    }
  ],
  "768": [
    {
      "id": 3444,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Catching - Catching",
      "hw": "Catching",
      "s": "«Catching» means to hold something manually by surrounding it or to enforce it on it such as holding from the chest.",
      "d": "«Catching»'s Arabic origin is catch (Qaf) meaning to hold manually by surrounding it, to hold from the chest, and its meaning is to close and hold something, such as to hold something manually by surrounding it or to enforce it on it. Its synonyms include «surrounding», «closing», «holding» but «Catching»'s special meaning is to hold something manually by surrounding it. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَأَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ» (Al-An'am: 127) Translation: In this, for them is only that they keep moving in the earth and keep moving in the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3445,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Catching - Grasping",
      "hw": "Catching",
      "s": "«Grasping» means to catch something by closing it or to enforce it on it as said in the Quran.",
      "d": "«Grasping»'s linguistic original root is from grasp (Qaf-Ra-Fa) which originally means to close something, to enforce it on it, and to keep it safe. This word exists with other meanings such as 'catching' or 'making available'. In grasping, originally the feeling is to enforce something and keep it safe. In the Holy Quran with the same meaning is: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَيَكُونُوا فَاسِقِينَ» (Al-An'am/148) Translation: «And in this, for them is only that they are turned in the earth and are transgressors.»"
    }
  ],
  "769": [
    {
      "id": 3446,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Human",
      "hw": "Human",
      "s": "«Human» means to understand the characteristics of humans intentionally, and to see their capacity for education and thought.",
      "d": "«Human»'s Arabic root is insan (ANSAN) which looks at the characteristics of humans. Its original meaning is \"a living being who understands intentionally\". During the explanation of the word human, we should warn about its various attributes, such as its mental power, education, thought, and human characteristics. Another word related to human is \"man\" (rajul) which only looks at men, and \"servant\" (abd) which looks at the faithful attribute of humans. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَنَجْعَلُهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا» (Surah Al-Isra, verse 67) Translation: «We have created man from a drop of mixed sperm which We test, and We make him hearing, seeing.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3447,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Bashr",
      "hw": "Human",
      "s": "«BASHAR» in common parlance is called human, although it is also used for the upper surface of human skin.",
      "d": "«BASHAR»'s basic meanings are for something to appear with its beauty and charm (M L) while the meanings of uns are only to appear. And «AL-BASHARAH» is called the upper surface of human skin. For example, in the Holy Quran: «لَوَّاحَۃٌ لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (29/74) Translation: The fire of Hell will scorch the skin and make it black. And its plural is «BASHARUN» and «ABSHARUN» and human is called bashr because its skin is very clean and clear compared to other animals from wool, hair and hairs etc. and appears clean (Muf). The word bashr is used for singular, plural, masculine, feminine all. However, if used for two humans then «BASHARAYN» will be said. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا» (47/23) Translation: Shall we believe in two men like ourselves? And the word bashr is used when it is intended to mention the physical and material aspect of humans, and their bodily structure, natural needs and weaknesses. As is clear from the verse mentioned above. And in contrast to bashr is the word «MALAK» (i.e., angel) which is pure from the material aspect, i.e., apparent bodily and natural needs. The disbelievers always had this objection that we should believe in a man like ourselves who is born and dies like us, eats, drinks, walks in markets and fulfills his needs like us. So what preference does he have over us that we should believe in him. Yes, if there were an angel, who was pure from these needs and necessities, then it would be something. In the following verses, Allah the Exalted has answered this same objection: «وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَلَکًا رَّسُوۡلًا» (94-95/17) Translation: And when guidance came to the people, nothing prevented them from believing except that they said: Has Allah sent a man as Messenger? Say: If there were angels walking peacefully on earth, We would have sent down to them an angel as Messenger from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 3448,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Man",
      "hw": "Human",
      "s": "«Man» expresses the original essence and presence on earth of humans as animals.",
      "d": "«Man» means to be present on earth, to be related to earth, and to indicate the fineness of the human species. This word shows the earthly and philosophical essence of humans while other synonyms like «Insan» and «BASHAR» are related to human attributes and moral characteristics. «Man» looks at humans in terms of original essence and nature. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً» (Al-Baqarah / 30) Translation: «And when your Lord said to the angels: I am going to make a vicegerent on earth.»"
    }
  ],
  "770": [
    {
      "id": 3449,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Friend",
      "hw": "Friend",
      "s": "«Friend» means a special relationship of the heart that sends humans toward their friendship.",
      "d": "«Friend»'s Arabic root is D-W-S-T which originally means \"to make each other better\" or \"to keep oneself with others in a better way\". This word holds the largest and original meaning of friendship, which expresses closeness of heart and human relations. Friendship means the state of companionship, friendship of heart, and special closeness of heart. Friend is compared to other words like \"m.friend\" or \"RIB'\" which express a general relationship or state of companionship. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِینَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ وَلَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ» (Al-An'am / 125) Translation: «And those who strive in Us, We will surely be among them and they will be among Us.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3450,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion",
      "hw": "Friend",
      "s": "«RAFIQ» sympathetic and soft-hearted friend.",
      "d": "«AR-RIFQ» means gentle behavior. Kind treatment and that thing from which help is taken. And «MIRFAQAH» means small pillow (Munjad) and «RAFIQ» means sympathetic companion, soft-hearted, one who agrees and stays close (M L). And the opposite of «RAFAQA» is «ANAF» meaning harshness and hard-heartedness (M L). For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» (4/69) Translation: Those people on the Day of Judgment will be with those on whom Allah has bestowed great favor. That is, the Prophets and the truthful and the martyrs and the righteous people. And the companionship of those people is very good."
    },
    {
      "id": 3451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion",
      "hw": "Friend",
      "s": "«Companion» means a friend who walks together, and becomes the cause of society.",
      "d": "«Companion»'s Arabic root is S-T-H-Y whose meaning is one who walks together, who is with someone. This word is the original meaning of friend who walks together, and companion means one who is with someone. This word is the original meaning of friend who walks together, and companion means one who is with someone. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عِندِهِ فَقَدْ جَاءَ الْمُحْتَجَىٰ» (Ash-Shu'ara 26:18) Translation: The one who came with the truth, its meaning is one who walks together, and companion means one who is with someone."
    }
  ],
  "771": [
    {
      "id": 3452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Enemy",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«Enemy» means one who stays away from friends and becomes a cause of danger and opposition to others.",
      "d": "«Enemy»'s Arabic root is D-Sh-M which does not only mean difficulty but expresses distance and opposition from friends according to others. This word is to oppose through human understanding against a person or group and to create cruelty and difficulty with them. In comparison, the meaning of «Aduw» and «MU'ARID» and «DIDD» is different. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ دَاعٍ إِلَّا أَن يَقُولُوا سُبْحَانَ رَبِّنَا إِنَّا كُنَّا ظَالِمِينَ» (Al-An'am/145) Translation: «And they had no prayer except that they would say: Glory be to our Lord, we have gone like the wrongdoers.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Opponent",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«Opponent» in the concept of enemy is said to such a person who opposes Allah's command and acts according to their desires.",
      "d": "«Opponent» means such a person who opposes Allah's command, acts contrary to their desires and extremity, and harms others without sacrifice and cruelty according to their nature. Its synonymous words include 'Adw', 'Khasim' and 'Shaytan' but in «Opponent» the special meaning of opposing Allah's command is included. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَن يَخْرُجُوا كُلَّهُمْ وَلَكِن يَخْرُجُ مِن كُلِّ قَوْمٍ مِّنْهُمْ مُسَارِيَةٌ لِّيَتَبَعُوا الْحَدِيثَ وَلَيْسَ بِهِمْ بَأْسٌ» (An-Nisa: 79) Translation: \"Muslims should not all go out together, but from every nation one or two individuals should be sent so that they understand the commands and laws and have conformity with them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Aduw",
      "hw": "Enemy",
      "s": "«ADUWW» meaning enemy.",
      "d": "«ADUWW» its plural is «A'DA»'. Such an enemy who is ill-wishing, spiteful. One who thinks of evil and harm and is happy on pain. And its opposite is «SIDDIQ» (F L 168). For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/22) Translation: Indeed, Satan is a clear enemy to you both (Adam and Eve). And «ADAWAH» means enmity and ill-will. And this is the first degree of enmity. (F L 169) And meaning to turn away from someone's help, its opposite is wilayah. (Fa Q L 106)"
    }
  ],
  "772": [
    {
      "id": 3455,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "King - King",
      "hw": "King",
      "s": "«King» means ruler, supreme owner of ownership, who is the ruler of kingdom through his ownership and power.",
      "d": "«King»'s Arabic origin (B-D-Sh-A) is which originally is the act of \"kingship\" which shows a royal ruler. Its meaning is that the person who protects his ownership and is the ruler of kingdom through his power. In comparison, the meaning of \"Malik\" and \"Sultan\" is also similar but «King»'s meaning is the supreme ruler of kingdom who is the ruler of kingdom through his power and ownership. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ فِرْعَوْنُ لِمَنْ أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ مِنْ بَعْدِهِ قَدْ جَاءَكُمْ رَسُولٌ مِّن لَدُنِّي بِالْحَقِّ فَأَكْفُوا بِهِ فَأَنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ» (Ta-Ha / 43) Translation: Pharaoh said to him: The book that was revealed after you, a path has come to you from me with truth, so stop it, because you have not asked for it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3457,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "King - Shah",
      "hw": "King",
      "s": "«Shah» is the representative of the king's rule and arsh kingdom which is established on Allah's permission.",
      "d": "«Shah» means one who is the owner of kingdom, who is the representative of arsh power and rule, who governs on Allah's permission. Its original root is shah (shah) which shows rule and kingdom. According to this word, it is different from other terms like «Malik» or «Sultan» because «Shah» specifically shows the ruler who governs on Allah's permission. For example, in the Holy Quran: «أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَخْرَجْنَا مِنَ الْأَرْضِ جُزْءًا مِّنْهَا وَأَنْبَتْنَاهُ فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ كَمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُنْبَتِيْهِ» (Al-An'am/ 14) Translation: Do they not see that We brought out from the earth a portion of it and made it grow, and when We made it grow, then We left it after growing?"
    }
  ],
  "773": [
    {
      "id": 3459,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Minister - Advisor",
      "hw": "Minister",
      "s": "«Advisor» besides minister means a person who brings news to the Sultan or ruler and along with that helps in government work.",
      "d": "«Advisor»'s Arabic origin (Root) is mushir which originally is a thing that understands something or such a thing that is made to understand. Besides, it also has the meaning of minister, who is a person working for the Sultan or ruler. These words are different terms, for example \"Minister\" is used as an important officer of royal government, while \"Advisor\" means a person who brings news, or such a thing that explains to someone. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُۥ سُلْطَانُهُۥ قَالَ لَهُۥ مُوسَىٰٓ إِنِّي عَبْدُ اللَّهِ الَّذِي آتَىٰ بِالْحَقِّ وَأَنَا مِنَ الْمُرْسَلِينَ» (Ta-Ha/23) Translation: Moses was sent to Pharaoh with authority, and when he saw the authority, he said: I am the servant of Allah who has come with truth and I am among the Messengers."
    }
  ],
  "774": [
    {
      "id": 3460,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Teacher - Teacher",
      "hw": "Teacher",
      "s": "«Teacher» means one who gives education of knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is scholar and instructor.",
      "d": "«Teacher»'s Arabic original root is with related knowledge's owner, and its meaning is teacher or instructor of knowledge and religion. This word is used especially for religious education among the words, while other words like «Mu'allim» or \"teaching\" are generally used for educational assistance. Its special target is religious sciences, prophethood, and moral education. For example: «Teacher» means one who gives education of knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is scholar and instructor. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيَّينَا وَأَرْسَلْنَاهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ وَأَنْزَلْنَا مَعَهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَزَنَّا فِيهِ الْمِيزَانَ» (Al-Hadid / 25) Translation: «We sent before you in nations before you Our Prophets, and We sent them with clear proofs, and We sent down with them the Book, and We established in it the balance.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3461,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Teacher - Mu'allim",
      "hw": "Teacher",
      "s": "«Mu'allim» means one who flies knowledge and wisdom, and teaches his students.",
      "d": "«Mu'allim»'s Arabic original singular letter is from «MA'LAM» which expresses the voice of knowledge and wisdom through «MA'LAMAH». Its literal meaning is \"one who represents wisdom\" or \"one who flies knowledge\". Its meaning is generally a person who represents wisdom and knowledge, who teaches others. In comparison, the meaning of \"Teacher\" and \"Mudarris\" is also similar, but \"Mu'allim»'s meaning is especially to be a representative of wisdom. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ يَا قَوْمِ إِنَّكُمْ أَظْلَمُ مِنَ الْأَرْضِ فَاسْتَغْفِرُوا رَبَّكُمْ ثُمَّ تُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ رَبَّكُمْ رَحِيمٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (7/54) Translation: \"And when Moses said to his people: O my people! You have done wrong like the earth, so seek forgiveness from your Lord, then turn to Him, indeed your Lord is Merciful, Merciful.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3462,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Teacher - Mudarris",
      "hw": "Teacher",
      "s": "«Mudarris» is the name of one who studies, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, the teacher who guides Muslims through his wisdom and knowledge in the Quran.",
      "d": "«Mudarris» means one who studies, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, the name of teacher. Its meaning in Urdu is teacher, mu'allim, and one who nurtures wisdom. In Arabic language, its original root is mudarris (D-R-S) which in Urdu is the act of reading, explaining, and giving wisdom. Its meaning is to nurture knowledge, and to teach knowledge. These words are different terms, but mudarris' meaning is generally to nurture knowledge. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ رَسُولًا مِّنْهُمْ يَتْلُو عَلَيْهِمْ آيَاتِنَا وَيُزَكِّيهِمْ وَيُعَلِّمُهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَالحِكْمَةَ» (2/129) Translation: «And when We sent among them a Messenger from them who recites to them Our verses, and purifies them, and teaches them the Book and wisdom.»"
    }
  ],
  "775": [
    {
      "id": 3463,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Student - Student",
      "hw": "Student",
      "s": "«Student» means one who seeks knowledge, especially a person related to religious sciences.",
      "d": "«Student»'s Arabic origin (TALAB) means 'to seek' or 'to turn toward success'. Its synonym is 'Tilmidh' or 'student' but the difference is that student is generally said to a person related to religious sciences who obtains memorization and education under religious tradition. About it in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا مِن دُونِ اللَّهِ وَلِيًّا أَهْلَ الْقُرْآنِ مُحَدَّثِينَ» (An-Nisa/ 163) Translation: «And it is of utmost importance that people related to religious sciences who accept as guardian other than Allah, they should not be considered as people related to their Quran and obtaining fresh education.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3464,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Student - Student",
      "hw": "Student",
      "s": "«Student» means a person who turns toward knowledge, who is also said to a student obtaining education in school or university.",
      "d": "«Student»'s Arabic original root is from «student» which originally means \"to walk behind someone\" or \"to walk behind one's teacher\". This word especially looks at the person walking behind the teacher who is under his education and lesson. In comparison, the meaning of \"Student\" is one who seeks to obtain some knowledge, but \"Student»'s meaning shows the person walking behind the teacher who is under his education. Proof: «وَمَنْ أَحْسَنُ قَوْلًا مِّنَ الَّذِي دَعَا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَعَمِلَ صَالِحًا وَدَعَا إِلَى الْمَعْرُوفِ وَنَهَى عَنِ الْمُنكَرِ وَكَانَ مِنَ الْمُسْتَقِرِّينَ» (34/15) Translation: «And which speech is more beautiful than one who calls to Allah, and does righteous deeds, and calls to righteousness, and forbids from evil, and is among those who remain under it?»"
    }
  ],
  "776": [
    {
      "id": 3465,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Nation - Nation",
      "hw": "Nation",
      "s": "«Nation» expresses a group, tribe, or community that is related to a common religion, language, and tradition.",
      "d": "«Nation»'s Arabic origin Q-W-M which originally means 'a group of people of the same type' or 'a group of people related to the same tradition'. This word is used to express a specific group or community that is related to a common religion, language, tradition, tribe, or country. In comparison, the meaning of 'nation' is 'group' or 'collection', while the meaning of 'tribe' or 'community' expresses a specific tribe or community. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَحْنُ أَرْسَلْنَا إِلَيْهِمْ رُسُلًا مِّنْهُمْ وَنَحْنُ أَعْرَضْنَا عَنْهُمْ وَأَخَذْنَا مِنْهُمُ الْمَوْتَى وَأَرْسَلْنَا عَلَيْهِمُ الْبَرَدَ وَالْمَلَائِكَةَ وَالْبَيِّنَاتِ فَكَانُوا لَهُمْ نَادِمِينَ» (Al-Anbiya 21:70) Translation: \"We sent before you in the livelihood of a nation greater than you also Our Messengers, before whom before you, We erased their hearts, and sent upon them death, ice, angels, and clear proofs, and they were apologizing to them again and again.\""
    }
  ],
  "777": [
    {
      "id": 3468,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Country - Homeland",
      "hw": "Country",
      "s": "«Homeland» in the concept of country expresses a specific area or nation that is a safe and nurturing place for humans.",
      "d": "«Homeland»'s literal root is watn which expresses homeland, area, and nation. These words are used in different ways: Watn (place), Area (region), and Nation (community). This word originally had two parts: «WATAN» means \"your special place\" which is a safe and related place for humans. In the concept of country, «Homeland» expresses a specific area or nation that is a safe and nurturing place for humans. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالْمَلَكُ يَوْمَئِذٍ بِأَيْدِي النَّاسِ» (Surah Ma'idah / Verse 52) Translation: \"And on that day the kingdom will be in the hands of the people.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3469,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Country - State",
      "hw": "Country",
      "s": "«State» is the original meaning of country which expresses political governance and national wisdom.",
      "d": "«State» means political governance, national wisdom, and national administration that is given by God. These words are different: Country (ownership), State (sultanate), Wilayah (governorship), and Sultan (authority) seem similar in meaning but «State» specifically means political governance and administrative system. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَّ اَلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (59/10) Translation: «And those who came after them say: Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not put in our hearts any resentment toward those who believed. Our Lord! Indeed You are Kind and Merciful.»"
    }
  ],
  "778": [
    {
      "id": 3470,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - City",
      "hw": "City",
      "s": "«City» means a place created for hospitality and tourism that is suitable for people to live.",
      "d": "«City»'s Arabic origin is shahr, which originally is a term for naming a place where people have the opportunity to live. Its literal meaning is \"to name a place\" and with its increasing number, its terminology changed which now means a place suitable for hospitality. Its synonym \"neighborhood\" or \"village\" is different, which is for less time, while \"City\" means a permanent residence place. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالْقُرْآنِ الْحَكِيمِ» (An-Naml/26) Translation: And the Wise Quran, which I have given to my city in such a way that it is easy for its people to understand."
    },
    {
      "id": 3471,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - Town",
      "hw": "City",
      "s": "«Town» means a city or place that is large, organized, and prosperous.",
      "d": "«Town» means a city or place that is large, organized, and prosperous. These words originally come from the root «N-G-R» which expresses city, place, or a prosperous and organized area. These words are also used in other meanings but the best meaning of this term is city or place. In comparison, «MADINAH» (M-D-Y-N-T) also means city but it indicates that it is a specific small type of city or place. «City» also means city but its meaning is the same which is similar to «Town». For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالْقَرْيَةَ الْعَادِيَةَ» (Al-Ankabut/29) Translation: \"And the village of Aad\""
    }
  ],
  "779": [
    {
      "id": 3473,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Village",
      "hw": "Village",
      "s": "«Village» means a large and compact learning vehicle that is especially used for learning other parts of the land.",
      "d": "«Village» means a large and compact learning vehicle that is especially used for learning other parts of the land. Its Arabic root word is village (Q) which means to learn a part of someone's house. This is one of the words that is originally a specific learning vehicle name that is used for learning other parts of the land. In comparison, «Village» means to learn a part of someone's house. In the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ» (Al-Ankabut/28) Translation: When they had no argument in their partners, and they had no argument in their partners."
    },
    {
      "id": 3474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Countryside",
      "hw": "Village",
      "s": "«Countryside» is the original meaning of village which is a specific reference for learning and agriculture.",
      "d": "«Countryside» means a specific part of land that is dedicated for agricultural work and homes, which is a specific reference for learning and agriculture. Its meaning in Urdu is village. If its root is explained, then village means a specific part of land that is dedicated for learning and agriculture. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيِّينَ وَجَعَلْنَا لَهُمْ زَوْجَةً وَذُرِّيَّةً وَمَا كَانَ لِنَبِيٍّ أَن يَأْخُذَ مِن قَبْلِهِ مِنْ عَطَاءٍ وَمَا كَانَ لَهُمْ مِّنْ عَطَاءٍ وَلَكِنَّ اللَّهَ أَعْطَىٰ بِعِلْمِهِ مَن يَشَاءُ وَاللَّهُ وَاسِعٌ عَلِيمٌ» (Al-Anbiya 21/74) Translation: \"We sent before you in nations before you Our Prophets, and We made for them wives and offspring, and it was not for a Prophet to take from before him any gift, and they had no gift, but Allah gives by His knowledge to whom He wills, and Allah is All-Encompassing, All-Knowing.\""
    }
  ],
  "780": [
    {
      "id": 3475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - House",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "«House» means where human soul gets peace and security environment, which is connected with Islamic ethics and religious principles.",
      "d": "«House»'s Arabic origin is from «BAIT» (Bayt) which originally means \"place\" or \"location\", but in Islamic language its meaning especially includes human and religious values. This word is different from other words like \"place\" or \"hotel\" because house means not only physical basis but also human relations, religious ethics, and faith environment. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (3/103) Translation: «And those who came after them say: Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - Home",
      "hw": "House",
      "s": "«Home» means house, which is a place of human rest and residence, and its special indication is in its context.",
      "d": "«Home»'s Arabic root is «Manazil» which originally means guidance and residence. This word shows a place of residence during human's journey, or a place of upbringing, or a space of religious and social organization. This word is different from other words like «Bayt» or «Dar» because «Home»'s specificity is in its human and social importance. «Bayt» is generally a physical space of place, while «Dar» is related to connection with related individuals. «Home»'s specificity is in its human and social organization capacity. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلِلَّذِينَ هَاجَوْا إِلَى الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ كَمَنْ هَاجَ فِي الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ» (Al-Baqarah/196) Translation: \"And those who migrate to the Sacred House from the people of the towns, like those who migrate in the Sacred House from the people of the towns.\""
    }
  ],
  "781": [
    {
      "id": 3478,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "People - People",
      "hw": "People",
      "s": "«People» especially expresses those people who are related to a place, religion, or branch's specificity and act accordingly.",
      "d": "«People»'s Arabic origin is Ahl (AHL) which originally means \"such people\" or \"family\" who are related to a specific thing or place. Its difference from other terms is that Ahl generally expresses those people who are related to a specific place or branch's specificity, while other terms like \"ULI AL-AMR\" or \"AL-MU'MINUN\" express specific places or faith's attribute. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَكُونُوا كَالَّذِينَ تَفَرَّقُوا وَكَانُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ أَحَادِيثَ الْأَهْلِ فِي الْمُلْكِ لَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ مَّعْرِفَةٌ» (Al-An'am/154) Translation: After that, those who became people of their countries and became related to their tribe's specificity, they had no knowledge."
    },
    {
      "id": 3479,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "People - Family",
      "hw": "People",
      "s": "«Family» is the meaning of Ahl which expresses individuals of a specific tribe or family who have a common connection with their companions.",
      "d": "«Family»'s Arabic origin is Khandan (KHADDAN) which originally expresses every tribe or family, who have a common connection with their companions. Its meaning is that Ahl Family means a specific tribe or family who have a common connection with their members. This concept is especially used in terms of a tribe or family compared to other synonyms, while other synonyms may express general relationships or social groups. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِینَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah/127) Translation: «And those who came after them said: «O my Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.»"
    }
  ],
  "782": [
    {
      "id": 3480,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Child",
      "hw": "Child",
      "s": "«Child» originally expresses child's specificity i.e., weakness, delicacy, and sensitivity.",
      "d": "«Child»'s Arabic root is Bachah which originally expresses weakness, delicacy, sensitivity, and flower-like pleasantness series. These words are related to child's meaning anywhere but «Child»'s special meaning is expression of weakness and delicacy. This word is especially used for those individuals who are weak, more sensitive, or delicate and not ready for very big work. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah/127) Translation: «And those who came after them say: O our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who have believed.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3481,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Infant",
      "hw": "Child",
      "s": "«INFANT» immature child.",
      "d": "«TAFILA» means to be soft and delicate and «TAFLAH» is called a woman with soft body. In this respect, as long as the child remains soft and delicate, he is «INFANT» (Mufrad). However, it refers to those children who have not yet reached puberty. And its plural is Atfal: For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاِذَا بَلَغَ الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24/59) Translation: And when your boys reach puberty, they should also seek permission as those before them (i.e., grown men) have been seeking permission. From this verse, it is clear that after puberty, the child exits the limit of infant and enters the limit of adult."
    },
    {
      "id": 3482,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Boy",
      "hw": "Child",
      "s": "«Boy» expresses the original meaning and original form of child which is understood according to the generation of production.",
      "d": "«Boy» means the sign of original generation of production, which in the Quran originally shows the child. Its residual roots are such that are originally produced humanly. Besides, its synonyms include \"child\", \"walad\" and \"dhakar\", but «Boy»'s special meaning is according to the original generation of production. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَتْ إِمْرَأَةُ عَامِرٍ لِّمَاكَ الْعَمِيَةُ لَوْلَا تَعَرَّفَتْ وَلَوْلَا تَرَكَتْ مَعَهُ فِي الْمَسْجِدِ فَأَخَذَتْ مِنْهُ حَمَلَةً فَكَانَتْ مِنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (Surah Al-Ankabut, Verse 24) Translation: When a worldly life helper woman saw her son prostrating, they said that if he did not see his son, he would see him, and if he did not prostrate with him, he would see him prostrating."
    }
  ],
  "783": [
    {
      "id": 3483,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Woman",
      "hw": "Woman",
      "s": "«Woman» is a special name of femininity, which expresses human ethics according to kindness, tradition, and religious principles.",
      "d": "«Woman»'s Arabic root word is A-W-R-T which originally expresses femininity's related characteristics. This word points to human body which expresses the state of child birth and education. In comparison, «Amah» or «Femininity» generally express human gender, while «Woman» especially expresses human ethics, kindness, and religious principles. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّذَٰلِكَ عَلَيْهِمْ حَرَجٌ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَيَتُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ غَفُورٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (8/14) Translation: For those who believed in Allah and His Messenger and turned to Him, there is no other intercession for them to turn to Allah, because Allah is Forgiving and Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3484,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Lady",
      "hw": "Woman",
      "s": "«Lady» is used as the best and more special attribute of woman which also comes from the perspective of wisdom, adab, and ethics.",
      "d": "«Lady»'s original literal root word is «KHATUN» which specifically describes a relative description in terms of woman, and its meaning is that \"as a lady is\" i.e., wise, adab-bearing, ethical, and also emerged from the perspective of pleasure. This word is related to woman's life, ethics, wisdom, and adab. Compared to other synonyms, it is especially used as a best and more special attribute, such as «Woman» generally decides woman, but «Lady» talks about its under-description and further high level. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عَدُوِّهِ فَهُوَ الْمُحْسِنُ وَالْمُحْسِنَةُ مِنْهُمَا» (An-Nisa: 12) Translation: Those who do works from their enemies on the side of truth that they are like ladies."
    },
    {
      "id": 3485,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Feminine",
      "hw": "Woman",
      "s": "«Feminine» expresses human's sexual characteristics in the original meaning of woman, which originally expresses the most kind and love attribute of human.",
      "d": "«Feminine» means the attribute that expresses human's sexual related characteristics, which originally expresses the attribute of human's great and more love-warrior and kind. Its original terminology is used to determine human's instincts and sexual characteristics, while other words like 'Zawj' or 'Mar'ah' especially express human's kindness and love attribute. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا هُوَ وَإِخْوَتَهُ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ وَمَلَئِهِۦ فَقَالُوا أَنَّا رَسُولُ رَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ» (Ta-Ha/43) Translation: When We sent him and his brothers to Pharaoh and his chiefs, they said: We are messengers of the Lord of the Worlds."
    }
  ],
  "784": [
    {
      "id": 3487,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Man",
      "hw": "Man",
      "s": "«Man» is the original structure of men who are servants of God and their specificity is expressed when they live life on God's command.",
      "d": "«Man» is the original structure of men who are servants of God and their specificity is expressed when they live life on God's command. Its root is originally from Adam who was created from God's name, and in comparison, «Man» generally includes human ethical and religious characteristics besides physical mean. «Man» means that it is the original structure of human attribute which is created by God. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا» (Surah Al-Hujurat/27) Translation: We created man from a drop of mixed nutfah, We test him, and We made him Hearing, Seeing."
    },
    {
      "id": 3488,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Man",
      "hw": "Man",
      "s": "«RAJULUN» its use is when the expression of bravery and manly power is intended.",
      "d": "«RAJULUN» (meaning man) is used when power, bravery, and manliness is intended to be expressed. «RAJULIYYAH» is a source meaning manly power. Manly power (Munjad). Its plural is «RIJALUN». And its feminine is «NISA» and «NISWAH». For example, in the Holy Quran: «اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (4/34) Translation: Men are guardians over women, because Allah has given preference to some over others."
    }
  ],
  "785": [
    {
      "id": 3489,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Poor",
      "hw": "Poor",
      "s": "«Poor» means one who is innocent, careless, and defenseless, as if unable to escape from needy situations.",
      "d": "«Poor»'s Arabic origin is Gh-R-B which originally means 'careless' or 'defenseless'. Its literal meaning is one who cannot escape from any of his big problems, defenseless, unaware, and without support. In comparison, «Miskin» and «Faqri» have similar meaning but in «Poor» there is a special kind of carelessness and failure expression. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالْغَرِيبِ فَیۡہِ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ لَہٗ نَقِیّ» (Surah At-Talaq, Verse 4) Translation: «And regarding the poor, whatever is in it, he has no supporter for it.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3490,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Needy",
      "hw": "Poor",
      "s": "«Needy» gives another bigger meaning in the meaning of poor which expresses the need for help.",
      "d": "«Needy» means a person who wants something and has need of it, who is related to help or facility. Its original radical returner is and he is a person who points to his importance. Its meaning shows a person who needs to obtain something. From this, the meaning of «Poor» is different, which does not only mean poverty but also has the meaning of his need for help. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ إِن مَّآ أَنفَقُوآ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُهَادِينَ وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحْتَاجِينَ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ لَا يُضِلُّ مَنْ هُوَ مُهَادٍ وَلَا مُحْتَاجٍ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ» (Al-Baqarah/179) Translation: And those who with their religious goodness not only do not need help, but do not need their work, then Allah does not forget those who need help and do not need their work."
    },
    {
      "id": 3491,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Destitute",
      "hw": "Poor",
      "s": "«Destitute» means poor and faqir who is deprived of wealth and possessions, and is a victim of lack of wealth.",
      "d": "«Destitute»'s Arabic origin is Muflis, which is the name of one deprived of wealth and possessions and poor. These words are different from each other: «Faqir» is generally the name of a poor person, while «Destitute» is especially the name of one deprived of wealth and possessions and a victim of lack. «Poor» is also the name of the same meaning but in «Destitute» there is more connection of financial lack and deprivation. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مَّالٌ وَلَا بَنُونَ» (Al-Baqarah 283) Translation: «And they had no wealth and no children.»"
    }
  ],
  "786": [
    {
      "id": 3492,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Rich - Rich",
      "hw": "Rich",
      "s": "«Rich» is called the national or public leader who rules over others.",
      "d": "«Rich»'s Arabic origin is Amir (AMEER) which originally means \"a person who increases something\" or \"to be big\". Its literal meaning is \"to increase something\" or \"to be the leader of something\". In comparison, «Khadim» is the head of official or administrative services, and «Malik» is the owner of the kingdom. In this respect, «Rich» originally calls the national or public leader who rules over others. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَن يَّتَّخِذُوا ءَابَاءهُمْ وَأَخْوَاهُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ فِي الْمَلَكِ» (At-Tawbah/107) Translation: \"Believers should not take their fathers and brothers as guardians in the kingdom.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3493,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Rich - Wealthy",
      "hw": "Rich",
      "s": "«Wealthy» is used as a helper and supporter of rich who is in the service of friends.",
      "d": "«Wealthy»'s original literal root word is from 'Dawlat' which means wealth, power, and administration. Its synonym is 'Mulk' or 'ruler' but 'Wealthy»'s special target is that he serves friendship and service for his friends. Its meaning is that he administers in terms of friendship and service for friends. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ لَهُمْ عَبْدُ اللَّهِ بْنُ أَبِي وَهْبٍ لِّقَوْمِهِمْ أَنْ تَعَظُّوا فَأَخَذَتْهُمُ الْعَذَابُ مِنْ غَدٍ إِلَى الْمَسَاءِ وَهُوَ دُولَتٌ مَّنْدٌ فِي أَهْلِهِمْ» (Surah An-Naml, Verse 46) Translation: «When Ubaidullah bin Abi Wahb invited his people to education, then punishment came upon them from next night to evening. And he was managing friendship among his people.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3494,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Rich - Affluent",
      "hw": "Rich",
      "s": "«Affluent» expresses the specificity of rich that he manages religious and social responsibilities beyond wealth and gifts.",
      "d": "«Affluent»'s meaning in Urdu is: Rich, big owner, investor, person who has reached high level in religious and economic terms. Its Arabic root is Th-R-W-T mend whose literal meaning is: Distinguished from wealth (distinguished), who has a lot of wealth. In comparison, it is related to «Malik» who has another specific support, and related to «Khadim» who tells about a person working for someone. Besides, it is related to «Khaliq» who expresses the state of creator. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَإِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ الَّذِينَ أَتَوْا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ لَكَيْنَ مَلَكَتْ أَنفُسَهُمْ فَأَنتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا بِمَوْلَاكُمْ شَرِيكِينَ» (3/186) Translation: «And when Allah took the covenant of those who came after them that they would make their souls owners, then you did not have partnership with your Lord.»"
    }
  ],
  "787": [
    {
      "id": 3495,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Worker - Worker",
      "hw": "Worker",
      "s": "«Worker» means one who works, a word used for official workers, a special writing used in the meaning of one who works.",
      "d": "«Worker»'s Arabic root is through workers who work. These words are used for workers and official workers. In comparison, other words like \"worker\" or \"agent\" have similar meaning but \"Worker»'s meaning is especially used for one who works officially or organizationally. Worker is used for official worker or one who works at home. Proof: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/286) Translation: «And those who came after them said, Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3496,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Worker - Laborer",
      "hw": "Worker",
      "s": "«Laborer» is called a person who works as a helper of worker who works for his work.",
      "d": "«Laborer» means one who works, worker, whatever work he does, his name is laborer. These words are originally a term of working, while \"Worker\" is a special type of laborer who comes to work for others. Its synonym is \"Kar\" which is called one who works. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ كَأَحَدٍ فِي الْعَرَضِ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْجَنَّةِ وَلَا مِنْ أَصْحَابِ النَّارِ» (Al-An'am/128) Translation: And they had no meeting with the people of Paradise or the people of Fire."
    }
  ],
  "788": [
    {
      "id": 3497,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Merchant - Merchant",
      "hw": "Merchant",
      "s": "«Merchant» means one who buys something and sells it, especially a person who works through financial and trade operations.",
      "d": "«Merchant»'s Arabic root word is Tajara (Tajr) which is originally the act of buying something and selling it. Its literal meaning is \"to sell something to another\". This word meets with different terms like «Matjar» (Tujjar), «Tujjar» (Tijarah), and «Tijarah» (Tijarah). Its original meaning is to buy something and sell it to another. Merchant means one who buys something and sells it, especially a person who works through financial and trade operations. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ يَتَّخِذُونَ مَوْلَىٰهُم مِّن دُونِ اللَّهِ أَرْبَابَ الْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ وَالْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ» (Al-An'am/108) Translation: Those who have taken their protector other than Allah, the lords of wealth and children."
    },
    {
      "id": 3498,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Merchant - Trader",
      "hw": "Merchant",
      "s": "«Trader» refers to a person who trades to obtain profit (benefit or gain), while «Merchant» refers to a general merchant or businessman.",
      "d": "«Trader»'s linguistic root comes from Arabic triad S-W-D (s-w-d) which means to trade, to benefit, or to earn profit. This word is derived from «Sod» (sod - profit/interest). In contrast, «Merchant»'s root is T-J-R (t-j-r) which means to travel and trade. The difference between both words is that «Trader» is more specific and indicates profit-oriented trade, while «Merchant» is a more general term. The word «Trader» has not come as an adjective or permanent noun in the Holy Quran, however, the word «Merchant» has come."
    }
  ],
  "789": [
    {
      "id": 3499,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Time",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«WAQT, MIQAT» fixed time or place.",
      "d": "«WAQT» is a well-known word (TIME) «AL-WAQT» means «ZAMANUN MA'LUMUN» (M.L) «WAQT» its plural is «AWQAT». And according to Imam Raghib, the last limit of fixed time for a work (Mufrad). For example, in the Holy Quran: «قُلۡ اِنَّمَا عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ ۚ لَا یُجَلِّیۡہَا لِوَقۡتِہَاۤ اِلَّا ہُوَ» (7/187) Translation: Say, its knowledge is only with my Lord. He alone will manifest it at its time. And «MIQAT» is a zarf noun from Waqt. It is used in both temporal and spatial forms. In the following verse, Miqat is used as a temporal zarf. For example, Allah Almighty says: «وَ وٰعَدۡنَا مُوۡسٰی ثَلٰثِیۡنَ لَیۡلَۃً وَّ اَتۡمَمۡنٰہَا بِعَشۡرٍ فَتَمَّ مِیۡقَاتُ رَبِّہٖۤ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ لَیۡلَۃً» (7/142) Translation: And We appointed for Moses thirty nights, and We completed them with ten, so the appointed time of his Lord was forty nights. And in the following verse, the word Miqat is used both temporally and spatially. That is, both time and place are fixed. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ لَمَّا جَآءَ مُوۡسٰی لِمِیۡقَاتِنَا وَ کَلَّمَہٗ رَبُّہٗ» (7/143) Translation: Then when Moses came to Our appointed time (at Mount Tur) and his Lord spoke to him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3500,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Era",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«Era» is used for a specific period or age which expresses the duration of a special period or time in the context of time.",
      "d": "«Era»'s verbal root is «Z-M-N-H» which expresses a specific period or age in the context of time. This word is different from «Zaman» (general time) and «Waqt» (a specific moment) in that «Era» mostly comes in the context of a long age or era, while «Waqt» is used for the concept of a specific point of time. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقَالُوا لَوْ كُنَّا سَمِعْنَا أَوْ عَقَلْنَا مَا كُنَّا فِي أَصْحَابِ السَّعِيرِ» (Surah Al-Mulk/67:10) Translation: And (the disbelievers) say: If we had listened or understood, we would not have been among the companions of the Blaze."
    },
    {
      "id": 3501,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Period",
      "hw": "Time",
      "s": "«Period» refers to a specific temporal period or age.",
      "d": "«Period» comes from the Arabic root «D-W-R» which expresses rotation, cycle, and duration of time. It is connected to «Time» in that period means a specific temporal age or duration. Its synonym words include «Era», «Age» and «Duration», but «Period»'s specificity is that it expresses the rotating aspect of time, i.e., a complete cycle or duration of time. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقَالَ الَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ وَالْإِيمَانَ لَقَدْ لَبِثْتُمْ فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ إِلَى يَوْمِ الْبَعْثِ فَهَذَا يَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ وَلَكِنَّكُمْ كُنْتُمْ لَا تَعْلَمُونَ» (Ar-Rum/56) Translation: And those who were given knowledge and faith said: You have remained in the Book of Allah until the Day of Resurrection, so this is the Day of Resurrection, but you did not know."
    }
  ],
  "790": [
    {
      "id": 3502,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Day",
      "hw": "Day",
      "s": "«Day» refers to the bright time that is spent in the presence of the sun, which in Arabic language is expressed by the word «Yawm».",
      "d": "Linguistically, «Day»'s basis is on Arabic radicaux «Y-W-M» (YAUMUN), whose meanings are «day» i.e., a collection of many days, time, and specific moments of time. In Urdu, «Day» entered through Persian language and it is the Urdu phonetic similarity of «Yawm». In the Holy Quran, its meaning is generally the day of the day or daily day, while in Arabic the word «Yawm» is more used. Its synonym words include «Roz» and «Nahar», however, «Day» especially expresses the time of spring and brightness. Its usage in the Holy Quran is very wide. For example: «وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَىٰ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا تَجَلَّىٰ» (Al-Lail/1-2) Translation: By the night when it covers, and by the day when it appears."
    },
    {
      "id": 3503,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Yawm",
      "hw": "Day",
      "s": "«YAWM» the collection of day and night i.e., 24 twenty-four hours.",
      "d": "«YAWM» meaning day. The time from sunset to the next day's sunset. The collection of Lail and Nahar's time is 24 hours. «YAWM»'s plural is «AYYAM». Time and era's calculation is done from «AYYAM». For example, in the Holy Quran: «فَمَن لَّمۡ یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ ثَلٰثَۃِ اَیَّامٍ فِی الۡحَجِّ وَ سَبۡعَۃٍ اِذَا رَجَعۡتُمۡ» (2/196) Translation: And whoever does not find (a sacrifice), then three days of fasting during Hajj and seven when you return. And this duration of «YAWM» is for humans. And its concept can only be done after the creation of sun and earth, otherwise at Allah's «YAWM»'s duration is a long period, whether this period is spread over millions of years according to our calculation. For example, Allah Almighty says: «قُلۡ اَئِنَّکُمۡ لَتَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ یَوۡمَیۡنِ» (41/9) Translation: Do you disbelieve in Him Who created the earth in two days? In the same way, when the mention of «YAWM» comes in the context of the creation of earth and heavens, it refers to a long period. For example, Allah Almighty says: «وَ اِنَّ یَوۡمًا عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ کَاَلۡفِ سَنَۃٍ مِّمَّا تَعُدُّوۡنَ» (22/47) Translation: And a day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you count. At another place, Allah Almighty says: «تَعۡرُجُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ اِلَیۡہِ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ کَانَ مِقۡدَارُہٗ خَمۡسِیۡنَ اَلۡفَ سَنَۃٍ» (70/4) Translation: To Him ascend the angels and the Spirit in a Day the measure of which is fifty thousand years. In the same way, Yawm ad-Din i.e., the Day of Recompense will also depend on a long period whose duration has been stated as fifty thousand years in the hadith."
    }
  ],
  "791": [
    {
      "id": 3504,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Night",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«Night» refers to the time that remains from sunset to dawn, and this is more general and used in daily language than Lail.",
      "d": "«Night»'s linguistic analysis: It is a basic noun in Arabic language which is used in the meaning of night. Its root «R-W-T» is derived which means to stop or to remain established. Night's opposition to day and its continuity is its basic characteristic. Its synonym words include «Lail» and «Zaleem». «Lail» is more eloquent and literary word which has come frequently in Quran and Hadith, while «Night» is more common in daily language and there is a feeling of comfort and ease in it. «Zaleem» is only used for dark night. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقُرْآنًا فَجْرًا إِنَّ قُرْآنَ الْفَجْرِ كَانَ مَشْهُودًا» (Al-Fajr/89:1-2) Translation: And the Quran at dawn. Indeed, the Quran at dawn is witnessed. (Another clear example): «وَجَعَلْنَا اللَّيْلَ وَالنَّهَارَ آيَتَيْنِ فَمَحَوْنَا آيَةَ اللَّيْلِ وَجَعَلْنَا آيَةَ النَّهَارِ مُبْصِرَةً» (Al-Isra/17:12) Translation: And We made the night and the day two signs. Then We erased the sign of the night and made the sign of the day illuminating."
    },
    {
      "id": 3505,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Shab",
      "hw": "Night",
      "s": "«Shab» refers to the time when the sun has set and darkness has spread.",
      "d": "«Shab» (Sh-B) is a basic root in Arabic language which is used for night and darkness. Its meaning is the whole time of night or the time of darkness. «Shab»'s plural is «Layal» or «Shuyub». Other words like «Lail» also come for night, but «Shab» mostly expresses the time when darkness is in its full intensity and it is people's sleeping time. This word has come in many places in the Holy Quran. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ» (Al-Fajr/89/4) Translation: By the night when it covers (the earth) with its darkness."
    }
  ],
  "792": [
    {
      "id": 3506,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Morning",
      "hw": "Morning",
      "s": "«Morning» refers to the time after Fajr when the daylight is fully apparent.",
      "d": "«Morning»'s original Arabic is Sabah which comes from the triliteral verb S-B-H. Its meaning is the time of morning (Sabah) and it is called the time after Fajr when the sun's light starts spreading on the sky. In its meaning, there is the thought of light's appearance and manifestation. Its meaning is that morning has happened. Morning and its synonym words' difference is that «Fajr» refers to the Fajr time when light starts, while «Morning» is the time after when the day becomes full. «Nama» is also called morning but it is mostly used in Arabic poetry. The word «Morning» has come in numerous places in the Holy Quran. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالصُّبْحِ إِذَا أَشْرَقَ» (Ash-Shams/1) Translation: And by the morning when it becomes bright."
    },
    {
      "id": 3507,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Dawn",
      "hw": "Morning",
      "s": "«Dawn» from its basic alphabetical form refers to the darkness before Fajr and the morning light that comes after, which is the origin of the word morning.",
      "d": "«Dawn»'s literal meaning is magic or spirit, however, in the context of morning, it refers to the time that is immediately after Fajr, i.e., early morning. It comes from root (S-H-R) which has several meanings, including magic (Sihr) and dawn (morning time). The difference from other words is that «Fajr» refers to the Fajr prayer time or the beginning of morning, while «Morning» in a broad sense is the whole morning time, and «Dawn» specifically refers to that delicate time which is the stage of transition from darkness to light. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّيْلِ وَمَا وَسَقَ وَالشَّمْسِ وَمَا غَسَقَ وَالْقَمَرِ إِذَا تَلَاهَا وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهَا وَالظِّلِّ وَمَا زَحَاهُ» (Ash-Shams/91) Translation: By the night and what it covers, and by the sun and what it illuminates, and by the moon when it follows it, and by the day when it reveals it, and by the shadow and what it disperses."
    }
  ],
  "793": [
    {
      "id": 3508,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Evening",
      "hw": "Evening",
      "s": "«Evening» refers to the evening time i.e., the time of sunset or the whole period of evening.",
      "d": "«Evening»'s linguistic root is from the Arabic source «Shama» which points to the evening time. This word «Evening» generally refers to the time after sunset. In contrast, «Lail» (night) and «Nahar» (day) refer to the whole day and whole night, while «Evening» specifically expresses the evening time. Geographically, «Evening» also refers to the region of Sham (Syria/Levant), however, in the Quranic context, it is mostly used for time. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّلَيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهُ» (Al-Asha'arah/90) Translation: By the night when it covers (the creation) and by the day when it illuminates (the creation) - in this verse, «Yaghsha» means to cover, i.e., the coming of evening."
    },
    {
      "id": 3509,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Maghrib",
      "hw": "Evening",
      "s": "«Maghrib» refers to the direction of Maghrib or the direction of sunset, and its connection to «Evening» is because it is located in the west of the Arabian Peninsula.",
      "d": "«Maghrib»'s Arabic root is Gh-R-B (gh-r-b) which means to set or to go to the west. In the Holy Quran, «Maghrib» refers to the place of sunset or the western direction. While «Sham» (Syria/Levant) is a place name which is located in the northwest of the Arabian Peninsula. In Arabic language, «Sham» was given this name because it is in the west (sunset direction) compared to the Arabian land. The difference between «Maghrib» and «Sham» is that «Maghrib» is used for an attribute and direction, while «Sham» is the name of a specific region. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِمَا أُنزِلَ إِلَيْكَ وَمَا أُنزِلَ مِن قَبْلِكَ وَبِالْآخِرَةِ هُمْ يُوقِنُونَ» (Al-Baqarah/4) Translation: And those who believe in what has been revealed to you and what was revealed before you, and they have certainty in the Hereafter."
    }
  ],
  "794": [
    {
      "id": 3510,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Today",
      "hw": "Today",
      "s": "«Today» in Urdu is called the time when we point to the current day.",
      "d": "«Today» is actually an Urdu/Hindi word which is derived from the Sanskrit word «Adya» (adya), which means «this day» or «current time». This word entered Urdu through Persian. In Arabic language, «Today» does not have meaning, but in Arabic, the semantic word for «Today» is «AL-YAWMU» (Al-Yawm) which expresses today's day. In Urdu, the word «Today» is very common in the context of time and its application is on the current or same day. Its synonyms or similar words include «Today's day» and «This time»."
    },
    {
      "id": 3511,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Amroz",
      "hw": "Today",
      "s": "«Amroz» is an Arabic language word which expresses today's day and is used in Persian-Urdu in the form of «Today».",
      "d": "«Amroz»'s linguistic root is from Arabic's Amroz which comes in the meaning of Yawm (day). In Urdu, «Today» is derived from Arabic through Persian. Its meaning is «this day» or «current day». The word «Amroz» is not used as «Today» in the Holy Quran, however, the words of Yawm (day) have come abundantly."
    }
  ],
  "795": [
    {
      "id": 3513,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Tomorrow - Tomorrow",
      "hw": "Tomorrow",
      "s": "«Farda» refers to the next day or tomorrow's time which expresses the reality of being separate and distinct from today.",
      "d": "«Farda»'s linguistic root is from Arabic triad F-R-D (f-r-d). The basic meanings of this root are \"to be separate, to be alone, or to be distinct\". The word «Fard» means \"one\" or \"alone\", and «Farda» is derived from it which expresses the next day as separate and distinct from today. Its synonym includes \"Ghadan\" (tomorrow) which is more used in the Quran. The difference between both words is that «Farda» comes more in formal and classical Arabic, while «Ghadan» is more common in Quran and Hadith. For example, in the Holy Quran: «سَأُرْهِقُهُمْ صَعُودًا» (Maryam/75) Translation: \"I will make them climb (on the Day of Tomorrow) a difficult ascent\". (Here, \"SA'UDAN\" means a hard climb or difficult path, which expresses the hardship of the Day of Resurrection.)"
    }
  ],
  "796": [
    {
      "id": 3514,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Forever - Forever",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«Forever» is actually a word derived from Persian language which means forever, however, in Arabic language, its meaning is eternity and permanence.",
      "d": "Analyzing «Forever» scientifically, it is necessary to explain that this word is actually from Persian language and its origin is from Persian 'Hameshah'. In Persian, 'Ham' means 'always' and 'Shah' means 'like', i.e., 'like always'. In Arabic language, 'ABADAN' (Abadan) and 'DA'IMAN' (Da'iman) are used for its meanings. In Urdu, the meaning of «Forever» is 'every time', 'forever', 'eternally'. Its synonym words include 'forever', 'from forever', 'for forever'. Since «Forever» is not an Arabic word, therefore, its Arabic text is not present in the Holy Quran. However, 'ABADAN' has come in the Holy Quran for eternity and permanence. For example, in the Holy Quran: «خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا» (Al-Kahf/108) Translation: They will remain in it forever (eternally)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3515,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Forever - Daiman",
      "hw": "Forever",
      "s": "«Daiman» is an Arabic language word which means permanently, without interruption, and forever, which is used in Urdu as a synonym for «Forever».",
      "d": "«Daiman»'s Arabic root is D-W-M (Dal, Waw, Mim) which gives the meaning of remaining permanent, continuing, and continuity. This word is derived from «Da'im» which is an adjective and its meaning is permanent, one who remains forever. In Urdu, «Forever» is its complete translation. The difference from other words like «Abadan» (never or forever) and «Sarmadan» (forever) is that «Daiman» is more eloquent and used in Quranic language. For example, in the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتُ الْفِرْدَوْسِ نُزُلًا (107) خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا لَا يَبْغُونَ عَنْهَا حِوَلًا (108)» (Al-Kahf/18) Translation: Indeed, those who believed and did righteous deeds, for them will be Gardens of Paradise as hospitality. They will remain in it forever, they will not desire from it any transfer."
    }
  ],
  "797": [
    {
      "id": 3516,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - Immediately",
      "hw": "Immediately",
      "s": "«Immediately» is a recent Arabic noun which is used in the meaning of immediate and without delay.",
      "d": "«Immediately»'s Linguistic basis is on the Arabic root «F-W-R». This root points to immediacy, speed, and primacy. Its source is «FAWRUN» which expresses immediacy or the same moment. Its synonym words include «Al'an», «Hala», «Ajilan» and «Sari'an», however, in «Immediately» there is especially more immediate and without interruption concept which is not found in other words. Its literal usage is not present in the Holy Quran, however, words expressing the concept of immediacy like «SARI'UN» and «HADHIRUN» etc. are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3517,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - Right away",
      "hw": "Immediately",
      "s": "«Right away» refers to doing a work immediately and as soon as possible without delay.",
      "d": "«Right away» comes from the Arabic root «F-W-R» which means speed and haste. It is derived from «Fawr» (speed). Its meanings are «Ajilan» i.e., quickly, «without delay» and «urgently». Its difference from other words is that in «Immediately» there is special consideration of immediacy and speed, while other words like «Sari'an» only express speed. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاسْتَعِينُوا بِالصَّبْرِ وَالصَّلَاةِ ۚ وَإِنَّهَا لَكَبِيرَةٌ إِلَّا عَلَى الْخَاشِعِينَ» (Al-Baqarah/45) Translation: And seek help through patience and prayer, and indeed, it is difficult except for the humble."
    }
  ],
  "798": [
    {
      "id": 3518,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Near",
      "hw": "Near",
      "s": "«Near» means to be close to something or time, whether in terms of distance or time.",
      "d": "«Near»'s verbal root is «Q-R-B» which expresses nearness and coming close. This word is abundantly used in Arabic language for proximity. In its meaning, there is also an element of «love» and «kindness», because being near actually expresses closeness (qinshu) i.e., closeness of heart. And «Near»'s synonyms include «Adna» (adna) and «Muqarib» (muqarib), but «Near»'s specificity is that it especially expresses closeness, while «Adna»'s tendency is more towards lesser. A clear example of «Near» in the Holy Quran is found in Allah Almighty's saying: «إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُجِيبٌ» (Surah Al-Fussilat/41:51) Translation: Indeed, your Lord is Near and He is the Acceptor of prayers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3519,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Close",
      "hw": "Near",
      "s": "«Near» comes from the Arabic root «Q-R-B» and its basic meaning is «close or near», which expresses the lack of distance.",
      "d": "«Close» is an Arabic word which is derived from the root «Q-R-B» (Qurb). The basic meaning of this root is «to be near» or «to be near something». Linguistically, this word expresses the lack of distance, but its metaphor is also abundantly found in the Quran. In its meaning, there are three basic aspects: first, to be close in terms of place, second, to be close in terms of time, and third, to be close in terms of relationship or connection. Furthermore, «Near»'s synonyms include «Adna» and «Sawda» etc., but «Near»'s specificity is that it does not only express the description of distance but also expresses the connection between Allah and the servant, as in the Hadith Qudsi that the servant is close to Me when he calls Me. For example, in the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُّجِيبٌ» (Fussilat/41:51) Translation: Indeed, your Lord is Close (near) and He is the Acceptor of prayers."
    }
  ],
  "799": [
    {
      "id": 3520,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Period - Period",
      "hw": "Period",
      "s": "«Period» refers to the duration of a specific time or age.",
      "d": "«Period»'s source is from the Arabic root «D-W-R» whose basic concept is rotation, cycle, and the series of time. This word comes in the meaning of «Period» (age, era) and its closest words include «Era» and «Time». However, «Period»'s specificity is that it expresses the continuity of time, i.e., the rotation from one age to another age, while «Era» tells about the beginning or end of a specific age. In the Holy Quran, the word «Period» is used in the meaning of time and era."
    }
  ],
  "800": [
    {
      "id": 3522,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - Above",
      "hw": "Above",
      "s": "«Above» is a Persian-origin word which is used in Urdu in the meaning of \"above/on height\", in Arabic language its meaning is \"Fawq\" or \"A'la\".",
      "d": "«Above» is actually a Persian word which has come in Urdu in the meaning of \"above/on height/ser-e-bala\". Its original source is Persian language, in Arabic language its synonymous words are \"Fawq\" (fawq) and \"A'la\" (a'la). In Urdu, the word \"Above\" is generally used for the description of place, while in Arabic, \"Fawq\" is more excellent and used in literature. In the Holy Quran, the Arabic word \"Fawq\" has come, in Urdu translation it is translated in the meaning of \"above/on\". For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ فِي سِتَّةِ أَيَّامٍ وَكَانَ عَرْشُهُ عَلَى الْمَاء» (Hud/11) Translation: And He is the One Who created the heavens and the earth in six days, and His Throne was upon the water. Here, the Arabic word \"ALA AL-MA\" (ALA) is translated in Urdu in the meaning of \"on/above\"."
    },
    {
      "id": 3523,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - Bala",
      "hw": "Above",
      "s": "«Bala» expresses the characteristic of height, high place, and being above.",
      "d": "«Bala» is used in Arabic language for height and high place. Its root is «B-L-W» which expresses reaching to height and high place. The word «Bala» in Arabic comes directly in the meaning of \"above\" or \"high\", while its synonym words include «Aali» and «Murtafi». However, «Bala»'s specificity is that it is mostly used in the expression of height in Arabic language. In Urdu, «Above» is a general term which is used for any height, while in Arabic, «Bala» comes more in the context of Allah Almighty's high place and greatness. For example, in the Holy Quran: «سَبِّحِ اسْمَ رَبِّكَ الْأَعْلَى» (Al-A'la/87) Translation: Glorify the name of your Lord, the Most High. In this verse, the word «Al-A'la» (A'la) expresses the highest place of Allah Almighty which is consistent with the concept of «Bala»."
    },
    {
      "id": 3524,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - Neeche",
      "hw": "Below",
      "s": "«Neeche» is actually a Persian word which is spoken in Urdu, in the Holy Quran its meaning has been expressed with Arabic words like «Asfal», «Taht» and with the concept of \"below\".",
      "d": "Linguistically, «Neeche» is originally a Persian word which is used in Urdu as «Neeche», however in Arabic language its synonymous words are «Asfal» (اسفل), «Taht» (تحت) and «Sufli» (سفلي). The Arabic word «Asfal» is derived from «Safal» which is the opposite of above and its root is S-F-L. «Taht» is derived from H-W-T which means below and underneath. Urdu's «Neeche» is the translation of these words and this concept is found in various verses in the Holy Quran. Difference from synonyms: «Asfal» is mostly used for being below in terms of place or degree, while «Taht» is generally applied for being under something. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَقِيلَ يَا أَرْضُ ابْلَعِي مَاءَكِ وَيَا سَمَاءُ أَقْلِعِي وَغِيضَ الْمَاءُ» (Hud/44) Translation: And it was said, O earth! Swallow your water, O sky! Stop, and the water was diminished (and contracted below the earth). Here is the description of water being below and contracting into the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3525,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - Zer",
      "hw": "Below",
      "s": "«Zer» means to be below or underneath something, that is, to be under something.",
      "d": "«Zer» is an Arabic word whose origin is Zer. This word is actually a noun which expresses being below or underneath something. In Arabic, it is applied when something is located below another thing or is under it. In contrast, «Fawq» expresses height and «Imam» expresses front. «Zer» has mostly come in the form of addition (idafa) in the Holy Quran. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يُوعُونَ» (Al-Bayyinah/1) Translation: And Allah knows best what they conceal (in their hearts)."
    }
  ],
  "802": [
    {
      "id": 3526,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - Andar",
      "hw": "Inside",
      "s": "«Andar» is a Persian word which is used in Urdu in the meanings of \"inside, interior, within\" and is not an Arabic language word.",
      "d": "«Andar» is actually derived from the Persian verb \"Andaridan\" which means \"to enter, to be inside\". This word is not of Arabic origin but has entered Urdu from Persian. In Arabic language, the synonyms of \"Andar\" include \"Dakhil\" (د-خ-ل), \"Fi\" and \"Bayn\". However, in Urdu language this word is very common and is frequently used in the meanings of \"ke andar\", \"androon\" and \"baatin\". This word is not found in any verse of the Holy Quran because the Quran was revealed in Arabic language."
    },
    {
      "id": 3527,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - Dakhil",
      "hw": "Inside",
      "s": "«Dakhil» is an Arabic word which means 'to enter inside or within', which is synonymous with Persian/Urdu's «Andar».",
      "d": "«Dakhil»'s original root in Arabic language is (D-KH-L) which expresses \"Dukhool\" meaning to enter. This word also comes in Arabic in the contrast of inner and outer, where «Dakhil» refers to the inner thing as opposed to outer. Urdu's «Andar» is derived from Persian language and its meaning is also \"androon\" or \"baatin\". Its other synonyms include «Fi», «Bayn» and «Zimn», but «Dakhil» is specifically used when expressing the state of entering into something or being inside it. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَمَن يَخْرُجْ مِن بَيْتِهِ مُهَاجِرًا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ ثُمَّ يُدْرِكْهُ الْمَوْتُ فَقَدْ وَقَعَ أَجْرُهُ عَلَى اللَّهِ» (An-Nisa/100) Translation: And whoever leaves his home emigrating to Allah and His Messenger, then death overtakes him, his reward is upon Allah. Here, in «Muhajiran» the root of «Dakhil» is implicit which describes entering from one place to another through migration."
    }
  ],
  "803": [
    {
      "id": 3528,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - Baahir",
      "hw": "Outside",
      "s": "«Baahir» means apparent, clear and manifest which describes the external or revealed aspect of something.",
      "d": "«Baahir» originates from the Arabic root B-H-R which indicates something being apparent, manifest and clear. This word is different from «Kharij» (external) and «Zahir» (apparent) because «Baahir» specifically describes the external aspect or state of being manifest of something, while «Kharij» merely expresses external and «Zahir» expresses being apparent. In the Holy Quran, words derived from this root have come. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ أَرۡسَلۡنَا مُوسىٰ بِـَٔايٰتِنَآ أَنۡ أَخۡرِجۡ قَوۡمَكَ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ إِلَى النُّورِ وَ ذَكِّرۡهُمۡ بِأَيَّامِ اللَّهِ ۚ إِنَّ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَأٓيٰتٍ لِّكُلِّ صَبّارٍ شَكُورٍ» (Ibrahim/5) Translation: Indeed, We sent Moses with Our signs, [saying], \"Bring out your people from darknesses into the light and remind them of the days of Allah.\" Indeed in that are signs for everyone patient and grateful. In this verse, the word «An-Noor» (light) is from the B-H-R root which describes being bright, clear and manifest."
    },
    {
      "id": 3529,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - Kharij",
      "hw": "Outside",
      "s": "The literal meaning of «Kharij» is 'to go out' or 'to exit' and it is the Arabic basis of 'Outside' which is the opposite of inside.",
      "d": "«Kharij」is an Arabic verb whose meaning is 'to go out', 'to exit' or 'to go towards outside'. It comes from the root 'KH-R-J' and its derivatives include 'Kharij' (active participle), 'Makhraj', 'Makharij' and 'Khurooj'. In Urdu, 'Baahir' is derived from this Arabic root. Its synonyms include 'Baroon' and 'Aziz' etc., but 'Kharij' specifically has the concept of 'exiting from something' or 'being outside a boundary', which distinguishes it from other words. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَإِذَا سَأَلْتُمُوهُنَّ مَتَاعًا فَاسْأَلُوهُنَّ مِن وَرَاءِ حِجَابٍ ذَٰلِكُمْ أَطْهَرُ لِقُلُوبِكُمْ وَقُلُوبِهِنَّ» (Al-Ahzab/53) Translation: And when you ask [his wives] for something, ask them from behind a partition. That is purer for your hearts and their hearts. Here, with 'Wara'a Hijab' (behind the curtain) the concept of 'Kharij' is implicit that one should speak from the outside."
    }
  ],
  "804": [
    {
      "id": 3530,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Yahan",
      "hw": "Here",
      "s": "«Yahan」is a demonstrative adverb which indicates a place near the speaker.",
      "d": "«Yahan」's linguistic root is from Arabic language's «Huna» (هنا) which is related to the system of demonstrative pronouns. In Urdu, «Yahan」is derived from Arabic and it is the combination of «Ye» (یہ) with the suffix «aan» which indicates spatial proximity. Its synonyms include «Wahan» (وہاں - there) and «Kahan» (کہاں - where). «Yahan」expresses the immediate vicinity of the speaker, while «Wahan」describes a distant place, and «Kahan」describes an interrogative or unknown location. In the Holy Quran, its Arabic equivalent «Huna」(huna) has come. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَكَذَٰلِكَ أَوۡحَيۡنَا إِلَيۡكَ رُوحًا مِّنۡ أَمۡرِنَاۚ مَاكُنتَ تَدۡرِي مَا الۡكِتَابُ وَلَا الۡإِيمَانُ وَلَٰكِن جَعَلۡنَاهُ نُورًا نَّهۡدِي بِهِۦ مَنۡ نَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِنَاۚ وَإِنَّكَ لَتَهۡدِي إِلَىٰ صِرَاطٍ مُّسۡتَقِيمٍ» (Ash-Shura/42:52) Translation: And thus We have revealed to you an inspiration from Our command. You did not know what is the Book or [what is] faith, but We have made it a light by which We guide whom We will of Our servants. And indeed, [O Muhammad], you guide to a straight path. Note: In the Quran, the Arabic word «Huna」(huna) has come which means «Yahan」in Urdu."
    },
    {
      "id": 3531,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Idhar",
      "hw": "Here",
      "s": "«Idhar」refers to pointing towards a place that is near the speaker.",
      "d": "«Idhar」's linguistic origin is from the Arabic suffix «A-DH-H-R」which is used for proximity and direction. It is different from «Huna」and «Hahna」because «Idhar」has a subtle undertone of movement or direction, while «Huna」is merely for static location. In Urdu, «Yahan」is actually derived from Arabic «Adhar」and its literal meaning is \"towards this side\" i.e., where the speaker is present. For example: In the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا بِآيَاتِنَا سَوْفَ نُدْخِلُهُمْ فِي نَارٍ مَاْ أُخْرِجُوا عَنْهَا وَسَاءَ مَثْوًى» (Maryam/72) Translation: Indeed, those who disbelieve in Our verses - We will drive them into a Fire. Every time their skins are roasted through We will replace them for them with other skins so they may taste the punishment. Indeed, Allah is ever Exalted in Might and Wise."
    }
  ],
  "805": [
    {
      "id": 3532,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - Wahan",
      "hw": "There",
      "s": "«Wahan」is an adverb which indicates a distant place.",
      "d": "«Wahan」is actually a word derived from Persian which has entered Urdu. Its basis is from the Persian word «Wah» (vah: وہ) which means \"that\" or \"those\", and «-aan」is a suffix which indicates a place. In Urdu, «Wahan」means \"there\" i.e., a place that is distant from both the speaker and the listener. In contrast, «Yahan」refers to a place that is near the speaker. «Kahan」comes in interrogative form for asking about a place. Since «Wahan」is a Persian word and the Holy Quran was revealed in Arabic language, this word is not present in the Quran, however in Urdu translations, where a verse mentions a distant place, the word «Wahan」is adopted."
    },
    {
      "id": 3533,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - Udhar",
      "hw": "There",
      "s": "«Udhar」is an Arabic language word which indicates direction and place, while «Wahan」is an Urdu word which indicates a distant place formed from the basis of \"Wah\".",
      "d": "«Udhar」's verbal root is from the Arabic original letters and it comes in the meanings of direction, side or towards that side. In Urdu, its meaning is «Yahan」or «Wahan」or \"towards that side\". Its difference from other synonyms is that «Udhar」has a sense of direction of movement, while «Wahan」merely indicates a distant place. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَإِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلَائِکَةِ ٱسۡجُدُوا۟ لِأٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوا۟ إِلَّاۤ إِبۡلِیسَ كَانَ مِنَ ٱلۡجِنِّ فَفَسَقَ عَنۡ أَمۡرِ رَبِّهِۦۗ أَفَتَتَّخِذُونَهُۥ وَذُرِّیَّتَهُۥ خُلَفَآءَ مِن دُونِی وَهُمۡ لَكُمۡ أَعۡدَآءُۚ بِئۡسَ لِلظَّالِمِینَ بَدَلࣰا» (Al-Kahf/50) Translation: And [mention] when We said to the angels, \"Prostrate to Adam,\" so they prostrated, except for Iblees. He was of the jinn and departed from the command of his Lord. Then will you take him and his descendants as allies other than Me while they are enemies to you? Wretched it is for the wrongdoers as an exchange. In this verse, the word «Khulafa» has come which is related to «Udhar」and its meaning is caliph or successor who takes someone's place."
    }
  ],
  "806": [
    {
      "id": 3534,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Everywhere - Har Jagah",
      "hw": "Everywhere",
      "s": "«Har Jagah」in Arabic language is a compound of «Har」(har) and «Jagah」(jagah) which is used for any place or location.",
      "d": "Analyzing the linguistic root of «Har Jagah」, it is a compound of two words: «Har」(har) which in Arabic is synonymous with «Kull」(kull - every/each), and «Jagah」(jagah) which in Arabic means «Makan」(makan - place/location). Its plural is «Amkinah」(amkinah). Its specificity is that it is absolute and comprehensive, meaning no place is left out. Its synonym includes «Har Taraf」or «Har Janib」, but «Har Jagah」is more explicit in earthly and spatial meaning. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَسِیقُوا۟ إِلَى ٱلَّذِیۡۤ أَحۡدَثَ فِی ٱلۡأَرۡضِ هَلۡ مِّن مَّحِیۡثٍ» (Surah Al-Mursalat/77:25-26) Translation: And they will be driven to the One who created something new in the earth \"everywhere\" (at every place). Is there any savior?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3535,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Everywhere - Har Maqam",
      "hw": "Everywhere",
      "s": "The literal meaning of «Har Maqam」is every place or position, which indicates a specific place or position.",
      "d": "«Maqam」's Linguistic_root is from W-Q-M (standing, place of standing) which in Arabic language expresses a specific place, position or status. Its difference from «Jagah」is that «Jagah」is a general Urdu-Persian word which describes any place, while «Maqam」in Arabic indicates a specific place, position or spiritual position which holds importance. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَلِلَّهِ الْمَشۡرِقُ وَالۡمَغۡرِبُۚ فَأَیۡنَمَا تُوَلُّوا۟ فَثَمَّ وَجۡهُ اللَّهِۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ وَاسِعٌ عَلِیمٌ» (Al-Baqarah/115) Translation: And to Allah belongs the east and the west. So wherever you [might] turn, there is the Face of Allah. Indeed, Allah is all-Encompassing and Knowing."
    }
  ],
  "807": [
    {
      "id": 3536,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Hurry - Jaldi",
      "hw": "Hurry",
      "s": "«Jaldi」refers to speed, haste or hastiness which originated from the Arabic root (J-L-D) and its basic meaning is from skin (leather), which has transitioned to haste and hurry.",
      "d": "The word «Jaldi」comes from the Arabic root J-L-D. From this root, several words emerge including «Jild」(skin), «Jaleed」(hard), and «Jaldi」(haste, speed). Verbally, the meaning of «Jaldi」is to perform a task as soon as possible without delay. Its synonyms include «Ijlat」, 「Taizi」, 「Sur'at」and 「Shitaab」. However, «Jaldi」has a specific connotation which also indicates undue haste or impatience, while «Taizi」is used merely for speed. An example of this word in the Holy Quran: For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَلَا تَسۡتَعۡجِلُوا۟ بِالۡقُرۡآنِ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ أَنۡ یُقۡضَیٰۤ إِلَیۡکَ وَحۡیُهُۥ» (Ta-Ha/114) Translation: And do not hasten with [recitation of] the Quran before its revelation is completed to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3537,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Hurry - Ijlat",
      "hw": "Hurry",
      "s": "«Ijlat」refers to doing work quickly, but it has a negative connotation of hastiness and acting without thinking.",
      "d": "In Arabic language, the alphabetical form of «Ijlat」is «A-J-L」. It is derived from the verb «Ajila」which means to perform a task quickly and without delay. However, it has a specific connotation that distinguishes it from other synonyms like «Sur'ah」(speed). 「Sur'ah」merely describes speed or swiftness, while «Ijlat」contains the color of hastiness, impatience and sometimes ignorant action. In Urdu, the word «Jaldi」is derived from Arabic and it reflects Ijlat. The field of use of this word in the Holy Quran is vast. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَقَالُوا لَن نُّؤْمِنَ لَكَ حَتَّى تَفجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الأَرضِ يَنبُوعًا أَو تَكُونَ لَكَ جَنَّةٌ مِّن نَّخِيلٍ وَعِنبٍ فَتُفَجِّرَ الأَهوارَ فِيهَا وَتَجۡعَلَ لَهُمۡ كُلَّ شَيۡءٍ مُّفَتَّرَضًا أَو تَقَعَ السَّمَاءُ كَمَا قلتَ عَلَينَا كُتُّابًا أۡو تَأۡتِيَ بِاللَّهِ وَالۡمَلَائِكَةِ قَبِيلًا أَو يَكُونَ لَكَ بَيۡتٌ مِّن زُخۡرُفٍ أَو تَرۡقَىٰ فِي السَّمَاءِ وَلَن نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِيِّكَ حَتَّى تُنَزِّلَ عَلَينا كِتَابًا نَّقرَؤُهُ قُلۡ سُبۡحَانَ رَبِّي هَلۡ كُنتُ إِلَّا بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا وَمَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ أَن يُؤۡمِنُوا إِذۡ جَاءَهُمُ الۡهُدَىٰ إِلَّا أَن قَالُوا أَبۡعَثَ اللَّهُ بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا قُلۡ لَوۡ كَانَ فِي الۡأَرۡضِ مَلَائِكَةٌ يَمۡشُونَ مُقۡتَدِينَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَيهِم مِّنَ السَّمَاءِ مَلَكًا رَّسُولًا» (Al-Isra/17) Translation: And they said, \"We will not believe you until you break open for us from the ground a spring. Or [until] you have a garden of palm trees and grapes and make rivers gush forth within them in force [and abundance]. Or you make the heaven fall upon us in fragments as you have claimed. Or you bring Allah and the angels before [us]. Or you have a house of gold. Or you ascend into the sky. And [even then], we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down to us a book we may read.\" Say, \"Exalted is my Lord! Was I ever but a human messenger?\" And what prevented the people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, \"Has Allah sent a human messenger?\" Say, \"If there were upon the earth angels walking securely, We would have sent down to them from the heaven an angel [as a] messenger.\""
    }
  ],
  "808": [
    {
      "id": 3538,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Dair",
      "hw": "Monastery",
      "s": "«Dair」refers to the residence of Christian monks, i.e., the home or monastery of Christian monks.",
      "d": "The original form of «Dair」is «DAYR」which comes from the Arabic root D-Y-R. This word is originally derived from «DAR」which means house or residence. The specificity of this word is that it is specifically used for the residence of Christian monks (presbyters). Its synonym instead of «Deir」is the word «Deir」which has come for a specific nation's religious place. It is different from «Biy'ah」(church) because «Biy'ah」is the place of worship of Christians while «Dair」is the residence of monks. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَكَأَيِّن مِّن قَرْيَةٍ عَتَتْ عَنْ أَمْرِ رَبِّهَا وَرُسُلِهِ فَحَاسَبْنَاهَا حِسَابًا شَدِيدًا وَعَذَّبْنَاهَا عَذَابًا نُّكْرًا ﴿٥٨﴾ كُلُوا مِمَّا رَزَقَكُمُ اللَّهُ وَلَا تَطْغَوْا فِيهِ وَاحْذَرُوا النَّارَ الَّتِي أُعِدَّتْ لِلْكَافِرِينَ» (Surah At-Tur 53/58) Translation: And how many a city was insolent toward the command of its Lord and His messengers, so We took it to severe account and punished it with a terrible punishment. Eat from what Allah has provided you and do not transgress therein. And fear the Fire which has been prepared for the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3539,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Takheer",
      "hw": "Monastery",
      "s": "«Takheer」refers to an action or event being delayed from its fixed time or being postponed in time determination.",
      "d": "In Arabic language, the original structure of «Takheer」is «A-KH-R」(alif-kha-ra) from which «Ta'kheer」(Ta'kheer) is made as a verb and «Mua'khir」(Mua'khir) is made as an active participle. This word describes the position where something falls behind its natural or fixed time. Its meaning is \"late\" or \"to be postponed\". Its synonyms include «Ta'akhkhar」(Ta'akhkhar) and «Ta'weez」(Ta'weez), but «Takheer」is mostly used for temporal delay, while «Ta'akhkhar」also includes the concept of falling behind. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَلَوْ يُعَجِّلُ اللَّهُ لِلنَّاسِ الشَّرَّ اسْتِعْجَالَهُمْ بِالْخَيْرِ لَقُضِيَ إِلَيْهِمْ أَجَلُهُمْ» (Yunus/10) Translation: And if Allah were to hasten for the people the evil [they invoke] as He hastens for them the good, their term would have been ended for them."
    }
  ],
  "809": [
    {
      "id": 3540,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Paani",
      "hw": "Water",
      "s": "«Paani」is a Persian-origin word which has entered Urdu, in the Holy Quran the Arabic word «Maa» (ماء) is used in its place.",
      "d": "The word «Paani」has actually come from Persian language to Urdu, it is not Arabic. In Arabic language, the words «Maa» (ماء, meem with alif with zabar) and «Mayah」are used for water. In the Holy Quran, only the Arabic word «Maa」has come for water. In Urdu, the meaning of «Paani」is a fluid, transparent substance that flows on earth and from which all living beings are nurtured. This word comes from Sanskrit's «Paaniya». For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَجَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡحَیۡوٰانَ مَآءً حَیًّا» (Al-Anbiya/30) Translation: And We made from it (water) living creatures."
    },
    {
      "id": 3541,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Aab",
      "hw": "Water",
      "s": "«Aab」in Arabic language means water and it is a symbol of life and purity in Quranic words.",
      "d": "«Aab」's Linguistic root is formed from the Arabic letters «Alif and Ba» and its basic meaning is water. In Urdu, «Paani」is actually derived from Sanskrit, while in Arabic «Aab」is used in compounds like Aab-e-Zamzam, Aab-e-Baran and Aab-e-Hayat. In the Holy Quran, the word «Aab」has come in the context of water's purity, life and Allah's blessings. For example: In the Holy Quran: «أَوَلَمْ يَرَ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا أَنَّ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ كَانَتَا رَتْقًا فَفَتَقْنَاهُمَا وَجَعَلْنَا مِنَ الْمَاءِ كُلَّ شَيْءٍ حَيٍّ أَفَلَا يُؤْمِنُونَ» (Al-Anbiya/30) Translation: Have those who disbelieved not considered that the heavens and the earth were a joined entity, and We separated them and made from water every living thing? Then will they not believe?"
    }
  ],
  "810": [
    {
      "id": 3542,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Aag",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«Aag」refers to that burning flame which is a symbol of Hell's punishment.",
      "d": "The word «Aag」is derived from Persian language which is also used in Arabic. In Arabic language, the words «Nar」, 「Jahim」and «Sa'ir」have come for fire. 「Nar」is the original Arabic word while «Aag」has entered from Persian. In the Holy Quran, fire has been described as a symbol of Hell's punishment and it is a sign of punishment for disbelievers and polytheists. For example: In the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ الْمُتَّقينَ في جَنّاتٍ وَعُيونٍ آخِذينَ ما آتاهُم رَبُّهُم» (Ad-Dahr/17) Translation: Indeed, the righteous will be among gardens and springs, taking what their Lord has given them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3543,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Aatish",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«Aatish」is an Arabic language word which is used for fire and its meaning is flame which is spoken for both worldly fire and divine punishment.",
      "d": "«Aatish」's verbal (linguistic) root is A-T-SH. It is an ancient Arabic word which describes flame and blazing fire. In Urdu 'Aag' and in Persian 'Aatish' have emerged from this root. Its meaning includes intensity and heat. The difference from other words like 'Nar' and 'Hareeq' is that 'Nar' is a general word for fire which is spoken for every type of fire, while 'Aatish' has the specific characteristic of flame and heat, and 'Hareeq' specifically describes fire that is kindled. For example: In the Holy Quran: «إِلَّا مَنْ أَتَى اللَّهَ بِقَلْبٍ سَلِيمٍ» (Ash-Shu'ara/89) Translation: 'Except he who comes to Allah with a sound heart.' Here, the word 'Salim' is from 'Salam' whose meanings are peace and health, and it indicates protecting the heart from the fitnah of fire (Aatish)."
    }
  ],
  "811": [
    {
      "id": 3544,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth - Zameen",
      "hw": "Earth",
      "s": "«Zameen」refers to that firm and spread out earth which Allah Almighty has created and made it a dwelling for living beings.",
      "d": "The word «Zameen」comes from the Arabic root Z-M-N. The original meaning of this root is 'to become firm' i.e., stable and solid. In the word earth, this concept is found that it is a spread out, stable and habitable surface. Its synonym words include 'Ard' (ard) which is also used in the meaning of earth or land, but the difference between the two is that 'Ard' is a general word which is used for both the expanse of earth and land, while 'Zameen' mostly refers to the physical surface of the earth i.e., the soil and earth's surface. In the Holy Quran, the word «Zameen」has often come together with Ard to describe both aspects of the earth. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالْأَرْضَ بَعْدَ ذَٰلِكَ دَحَاهَا» (Adh-Dhariyat/51) Translation: And the earth - after that He spread it."
    }
  ],
  "812": [
    {
      "id": 3546,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Aasman",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«Aasman」in Arabic language is related to height and elevation, and all the heavenly layers above the earth are called by this name.",
      "d": "«Aasman」's Linguistic root (root) is from the Arabic letters S-M-W (s-m-w) which gives the meaning of height and elevation. This word is the plural of «Sama» (sama') in Arabic and its meaning is sky, firmament, or that part above the earth which appears above our heads. Its difference from other words is that «Sama」directly indicates the tangible (perceptible) part of the sky, while «Jannah」(Jannah) is related to Allah's special reward and «Saqf」(saqf) merely comes in the meaning of roof or ceiling. In the Holy Quran, Allah Almighty has described «Aasman」as a sign of His power and might. For example: In the Holy Quran: «الَّذِي جَعَلَ لَكُمُ الْأَرْضَ فِرَاشًا وَالسَّمَاءَ بِنَاءً» (Al-An'am/164) Translation: It is He who made for you the earth a bed and the sky a ceiling."
    },
    {
      "id": 3547,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Falak",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«FALAK」refers to the orbits (paths) of planets in the sky.",
      "d": "The meaning of «FALAK」is generally taken as sky. But in reality, the orbits of planets in space or the paths of celestial bodies' movement are called Falak (M.R. - M.L. - Muf). For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَ هُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ وَ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (21/33) Translation: And it is He who created the night and the day and the sun and the moon; all [heavenly bodies] in an orbit are swimming. And the reason for calling these paths «FALAK」is that planets do not revolve in a complete circular shape in space, but under certain laws of motion they take an elliptical shape. Then due to their boat-like nature, they are called «FALAK」. Such a boat is called «FULK」in Arabic."
    }
  ],
  "813": [
    {
      "id": 3548,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Air - Hawa",
      "hw": "Air",
      "s": "«Hawa」refers to the speed of wind or the blowing of wind which is among the signs of Allah Almighty's power.",
      "d": "The word «Hawa」comes from the Arabic root H-W-Y (Hawa Yahwi) whose original meaning is the flowing or blowing of wind. These words are derived from «HAWA» (hawāʾ) and its meanings are wind, breeze, or waves of wind. In the Holy Quran, the word «Hawa」has often come as a sign of Allah Almighty's power and might. It is different from other words like «RIH」(rīḥ - strong gust of wind) and «ASIF」(āṣif - stormy wind). 「Hawa」is generally used for moderate wind while «RIH」is used for stronger wind. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُرْسِلُ الرِّيَاحَ بُشْرًا بَيْنَ يَدَيْ رَحْمَتِهِ» (Al-Furqan 25/48) Translation: And it is He who sends the winds as good tidings before His mercy."
    }
  ],
  "814": [
    {
      "id": 3550,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Pahar",
      "hw": "Mountain",
      "s": "«Pahar」refers to the earth's elevated and green or barren settlement which is called a high and stable earthly form in geological terms.",
      "d": "The word «Pahar」is actually not an original Arabic word but it is derived from Persian language and is used in Urdu. In Arabic language, the words «JABAL」(J-B-L) and «TUR」are used for mountain. In Arabic, «JABAL」refers to that large elevated land which is high from the earth's surface and has both considerable length and width. 「Pahar」in Urdu and Persian has come for the same meaning and it is a semantic synonym of Arabic «JABAL」but has a different lexical origin. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالطُّورِ» (At-Tur/1) Translation: By the Mount (i.e., the mountain upon which the word of Allah was revealed to Moses)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3551,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Koh",
      "hw": "Mountain",
      "s": "«Koh」refers to a hard and strong mountain which is a symbol of the earth's structural strength.",
      "d": "What is the meaning of «Koh»: In Arabic language, the root of «Koh」(K-W-H) comes from the meaning of hardness, stability and remaining firm. This word is used for mountain and its original meaning is a large and hard earthly element which remains standing. The word «Jabal」(jabal) is also used for mountain, but «Koh」has a special emphasis on hardness and stability. 「Koh」refers to those mountains which protect the earth from sinking and are signs of Allah's power."
    }
  ],
  "815": [
    {
      "id": 3552,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - Darya",
      "hw": "River",
      "s": "«Darya」refers to that wide water path which flows through the middle of the earth, used for both ocean and river.",
      "d": "The original language of «Darya」is Persian which has entered Arabic language. In Arabic language, the word «Bahr」is more commonly used for sea, but the word «Darya」is also found in Arabic and its meaning is big water, sea, or river. The difference is that «Bahr」comes from the Arabic verb (source) whose meaning is to become wide or spacious, while «Darya」is derived from Persian. In the Holy Quran, the word «Darya」has come in very few verses, mostly the word «Bahr」has come. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَهْوَ الَّذِي مَرَجَ الْبَحْرَيْنِ هَذَا عَذْبٌ فُورٌ وَهَذَا مِلْحٌ أُجَاجٌ» (Ar-Rahman/55) Translation: And it is He who has released [simultaneously] the two seas, one fresh and sweet and one salty and bitter. Note: In the Quran, the word «Bahr」has come more than «Darya», but the meaning of «Darya」is also sea or wide water."
    },
    {
      "id": 3553,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - Rud",
      "hw": "River",
      "s": "«Rud」refers to that flowing water which moves from one place to another.",
      "d": "The linguistic root «Rud」is of Arabic origin whose meaning is to flow or to be current. This root comes from R-W-D and it is related to flowing water. 「Rud」refers to a flowing water that continuously flows in one direction. In contrast, «NAHAR」(river) is used for more limited and artificial paths, while «AYR」(air) and «WADI」(valley) mean very large river and valley respectively. The specificity of «Rud」is that it expresses natural flow. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالْجِبَالَ أَرْسَاهَا» (An-Nazi'at/32) Translation: And the mountains - He has firmly established them. (Note: The word «Rud」has not come in the Quran in the form of river, however its origin «R-W-D」is connected which indicates flow and being current, and in Urdu «Darya」reflects this same concept that water flows from one place to another through a natural path.)"
    }
  ],
  "816": [
    {
      "id": 3554,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Barish",
      "hw": "Rain",
      "s": "«Barish」refers to water or rain descending from the sky which falls on earth in the form of many droplets.",
      "d": "According to linguistic analysis, «Barish」is derived from the Arabic root B-R-SH. The original meaning of this root is 'to scatter' or 'to spread', and «Barish」is its verbal noun (masdar) which describes the action of scattering rain water and falling on earth. In comparison to other words, where «Matar」(matr) and «Ghaith」(ghaith) are also used for rain, the specificity of «Barish」is that it specifically clarifies the descending of many droplets scattering, which distinguishes it from other synonymous words."
    },
    {
      "id": 3555,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Barsaat",
      "hw": "Rain",
      "s": "«Barsaat」refers to the rain of mercy descending from Allah Almighty from the sky which brings the earth to life.",
      "d": "«Barsaat」's root in Arabic language is «B-R-S-T」which is related to the concept of rain. This word is formed from «Bar」(i.e., to flow or fall) and the suffix «Sat», which indicates the continuity and abundance of rain. Its difference from other words like «Matar」(matr) and «Ghaith」(ghayth) is that «Barsaat」mostly describes the rain that comes in arid (desert regions) which is a sign of Allah's mercy. In the Holy Quran, Allah Almighty has described rain in the context of His blessings and mercy. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُنَزِّلُ الْغَيْثَ مِن بَعْدِ مَا قَنَطُوا» (Al-Kahf/28) Translation: And it is He who sends down the rain after they had despaired. Here, «Al-Ghaith」refers to the special mercy of Barsaat which Allah Almighty sends down upon His servants."
    }
  ],
  "817": [
    {
      "id": 3556,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud - Baadal",
      "hw": "Cloud",
      "s": "«Baadal」comes from the Arabic root B-D-L and its meaning is 'that which replaces' i.e., substitute or alternative.",
      "d": "«Baadal」's root is B-D-L (BADALA) which means 'to change' or 'to replace one thing with another'. These words are derived from 'badal' which is made from the source 'badalat'. Linguistically, «Baadal」is an active participle i.e., 'that which replaces'. Its synonyms include 'Mubdil', 'Badeel' and 'Mustabidl', but «Baadal」specifically describes that person or thing which takes the place of another or which is engaged in the act of changing. In the Quran, this root has often come in the context of Allah bringing one nation in place of another or changing commands. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَإِذۡ قَالَتۡ أُمَّتُہُمۡ رَبَّنَاۤ أَرۡسِلۡ فِیۡهِمۡ رَسُولࣰا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُواۡ عَلَیۡهِمۡۤ آیَاتِكَ وَیُعَلِّمُهُمُ ٱلۡكِتَٰبَ وَٱلۡحِكۡمَةَ وَیُزَكِّیۡهِمۡۚ إِنَّكَ أَنتَ ٱلۡعَزِیزُ ٱلۡحَكِیمُ» (Al-Baqarah/129) Translation: 'And when their nation said, \"O our Lord! Send among them a messenger from themselves who will recite to them Your verses and teach them the Book and Wisdom and purify them. Indeed, You are the Exalted in Might, the Wise.\"' Here, the root of 'YUZAKKI-HIM' is Z-K-W which means 'to purify'. However, the example of B-D-L root is found in numerous verses in the Quran where Allah Almighty has replaced one nation with another (baadal)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3557,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud - Sahab",
      "hw": "Cloud",
      "s": "«SAHAB」is commonly used for cloud in general parlance.",
      "d": "«SAHAB」means to drag and pull, its use for cloud is common (F - L 454). Every type of cloud is called «SAHAB」, however this word is applied to that cloud which the winds lift and spread across the sky. So this is the initial form of every cloud. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَاللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا» (35/9) Translation: And Allah is the One who sends the winds, and they stir up clouds."
    }
  ],
  "818": [
    {
      "id": 3558,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Tree - Darakht",
      "hw": "Tree",
      "s": "«Darakht」refers to that green plant which has branches and trunk, and it is synonymous with «Shajarah」in Arabic language.",
      "d": "«Darakht」is actually derived from Persian language which is used in Urdu, while in Arabic language its original word is «SHAJARAH」(SH-J-R). Its synonyms include «NABAT」(nabat) and «Ghirs」(ghirs), but «Shajarah」specifically is that tree which has branches and fruit, while «Nabat」is also used for general plants and «Ghirs」is related to planting. In the Holy Quran, in Urdu translation the word «Darakht」appears in verses which in the original Arabic text is in the meaning of «SHAJARAH」or «SHAJARIN». For example: In the Holy Quran: «الَّذِينَ يَذْكُرُونَ اللَّهَ قِيَامًا وَقُعُودًا وَعَلَى جُنُوبِهِمْ وَيَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ رَبَّنَا مَا خَلَقْتَ هَذَا بَاطِلًا سُبْحَانَكَ فَقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ» (Ali 'Imran/191) Translation: Who remember Allah while standing or sitting or [lying] on their sides and give thought to the creation of the heavens and the earth, [saying], \"Our Lord, You did not create this aimlessly; exalted are You [above such a thing]; then protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\" (In the context of this verse, the signs of Allah Almighty's power are mentioned which are also evident in the creation of trees and plants.)"
    }
  ],
  "819": [
    {
      "id": 3560,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower - Phool",
      "hw": "Flower",
      "s": "«Phool」is a Persian-Urdu word which does not exist as an original word in Arabic language, its Arabic equivalent is «ZAHRAH」(ZAHRA).",
      "d": "According to lexical analysis, the word «Phool」has entered Urdu from Persian language and is not an original Arabic word. In Arabic, the meanings of «Phool」are found in «ZAHRAH」(zahrah) and «WARQ」(waraq). The root of «Zahrah」is Z-H-R which means to shine and to bloom. In the Holy Quran, there is reference to this word where Allah Almighty has described examples of flowers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3561,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower - Gul",
      "hw": "Flower",
      "s": "«Gul」is a Persian language word which is used in the meaning of flower, however in Arabic language there are different meanings of this same root.",
      "d": "Linguistically, the Arabic root «J-L」(JALLA) refers to 'to appear', 'to be glorious' and 'honor and dignity'. In Persian language, the word «Gul」means 'flower' which is used in Urdu in the form of «Phool». In Arabic, the words «Zahrah」and «Ward」(which entered Arabic from Persian) come for flower. The specificity of this word is that it has entered Urdu from Persian language and it has no direct connection with Arabic root. For example: In the Holy Quran, the Persian word «WARD」has come in the meaning of flower: «وَالْوَرْدِ وَالْحُورِ» (Al-Ward/1) Translation: By the flowers and the Houris. (Here, «WARD」refers to heavenly flowers.)"
    }
  ],
  "820": [
    {
      "id": 3562,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf - Patta",
      "hw": "Leaf",
      "s": "«Patta」refers to the part of a tree which grows on its branches and its basic Arabic equivalent is «Waraq」.",
      "d": "The word «Patta」is actually derived from Persian language which is frequently used in Urdu. In Arabic language, its original word is «WARAQ」(waraq) from which «Waraqah」(waraqah) is made. This root (root) comes from W-R-Q whose meanings are 'skin' or 'peel' and this same root is also the root of «Qirtas」(QIRTAS - paper). Its synonyms include «Waraq」, 「Waraqah」, and «Ushb」(green leaf). The difference between «Patta」and «Waraq」is that «Waraq」is an original Arabic word while «Patta」is a Persian-Urdu word which is more commonly used in general conversation. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالَّتِي أَحْاطَتْ بِهِمْ أَوْ عَضَّهُمْ فِي الْغَابَاتِ» (Ibrahim/18) Translation: And that which surrounded them or bit them in the thick forests. Note: The word «Patta」is not explicitly found in the Quran, however the sources of «Waraq」and the word «Ushb」(green leaf) are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3563,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf - Waraq",
      "hw": "Leaf",
      "s": "«Waraq」refers to those leaves which grow on trees or those parts of paper on which writing is done.",
      "d": "In Arabic language, the initial meanings of «Waraq」are the leaf of a tree and that layer of paper which is very delicate and spread out. It comes from the root W-R-Q which indicates delicate layers and spreading. In Urdu, «Patta」is actually derived from Arabic-Persian «Waraqah」(warqah). Its synonyms include «Waraqah」(warqah - leaf), 「Safiyah」(safiyah - boat-like leaf), and «Sahifah」(sahifah - written paper). The difference is that «Waraq」is more general and comprehensive which includes both natural and artificial leaves, while «Sahifah」specifically comes for written paper."
    }
  ],
  "821": [
    {
      "id": 3564,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Seed - Beej",
      "hw": "Seed",
      "s": "The word «Beej」comes from the Arabic root B-Y-J and its meaning is 'egg'.",
      "d": "«Beej」is an Arabic noun which is derived from the root B-Y-J. Its basic meaning is 'egg', particularly the egg of a bird. This word is synonymous with 'Bayd' (bayd) and both are related to the root B-Y-D which means 'white'. The word 'Beej' was mostly used in ancient Arabic and 'Bayd' has come more frequently in the Holy Quran. For egg, 'BAYDATUN' (baydatun) also comes in Arabic. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالطَّیْرِ صَافَّاتٍ مَّا لَهُنَّ مِنْ فَرْعٍ وَمِمَّا یَكِیْلُونَ» (At-Tariq/19) Translation: And by the birds who set their wings in rows, there is no refuge for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3565,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Seed - Tukhm",
      "hw": "Seed",
      "s": "The word «Tukhm」in Arabic language comes in the meanings of seed, progeny and generation, offspring, and is used in the context of both plants and humans.",
      "d": "«Tukhm」comes from the Arabic root letters «T-KH-M」and its basic meaning is seed or seed-grain. This word comes in the meanings of seed of plants as well as progeny and generation of humans. Its Urdu synonym is «Beej」which is derived from Persian. The special thing about «Tukhm」is that in Arabic language it is used for both agriculture and lineage aspects, while «Beej」mostly comes for the seed of plants. For example: In the Holy Quran: «أَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ أَنَّ أَصۡحَـٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَالرَّقِیۡمِ کَانُواۡ مِنۡ ءَالَیۡتِنَا عَجَبًا أَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ أَصۡحَابَ بَقَرَۃٍ مَّا کَانَتۡ لَهُمۡ فِیۡهَا مِنۡ نَّسۡلٍ ذُکۡرًا فَإِمۡسَاکٌۭ بِمَعۡرُوفٍ أَوۡ تَشۡرِیۡدٌۭ بِظُلمٍۚ» (18/9) Translation: Do you think that the people of the Cave and the Inscription were among Our signs a wonder? Or were you among the companions of the cow who had no male offspring in it, so they restrained it with kindness or drove it away with injustice?"
    }
  ],
  "822": [
    {
      "id": 3566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil - Mitti",
      "hw": "Soil",
      "s": "«Mitti」refers to that soft and dust-like substance of the earth from which human creation took place.",
      "d": "«Mitti」is an Urdu language word which is actually derived from the Arabic word «Teen」(T-Y-N). Its meaning is clay or wet soil which is found on the earth's surface. In Urdu, it is generally called Mitti while in Arabic there are several words for it like «Teen」(clay), 「Turab」(soil), and «Ard」(earth). The difference is that «Mitti」specifically refers to soft and sticky soil which is the basic material of human creation, while «Turab」refers to general soil. In the Holy Quran, Allah Almighty has created humans from this same soil. For example: In the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ اللَّهَ يُحِبُّ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (Surah Al-Baqarah/195) Translation: Indeed, Allah loves the doers of good."
    },
    {
      "id": 3567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil - Khaak",
      "hw": "Soil",
      "s": "«Khaak」is an Arabic language word which in Urdu means «Mitti」i.e., soil, dust, dry earth.",
      "d": "«Khaak」's root is the Arabic triad KH-W-K. Its basic meaning is earth, soil, dust and dry soil. In Urdu, the origin of «Mitti」is from Sanskrit/Prakrit, but in Quranic translations «Khaak」is spoken and understood in the meanings of «Mitti». The difference is that Arabic «Khaak」refers to dust and dry soil scattered on the earth's surface, while Urdu «Mitti」generally includes both wet and hard soil. In the Quran, the word «Khaak」has also come in the context of earth and human creation. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَإِنَّ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لَحَافِظِینَ ۙ﴿۱۰﴾ کِرامًا کَاتِبِینَ ۙ﴿۱۱﴾ یَعۡلَمُونَ مَا تَفۡعَلُونَ» (Al-Infitar 82/10-12) Translation: And indeed, [appointed] over you are keepers, Noble and recording; They know whatever you do. (Here the word «Khaak」is not directly present but there are verses related to soil in the Quran). Another clear example: «وَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّقُولُ رَبَّنَاۤ اٰتۡنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا حَسَنَۃً وَّفِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ حَسَنَۃً وَّقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/201) Translation: And among them are those who say, \"Our Lord, give us in this world [that which is] good and in the Hereafter [that which is] good and protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\""
    }
  ],
  "823": [
    {
      "id": 3568,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Forest - Jangal",
      "hw": "Forest",
      "s": "«Jangal」refers to that area of heavy trees which is filled with wild plants, which is borrowed from Persian in Urdu.",
      "d": "The Lingua origin of «Jangal」is from Persian language and it is used in Urdu in the same way. Its original root in Arabic language is different from 「J-N-L」, in Arabic words related to 「Jinn」come for heavenly armies or jinn. In Urdu and Persian, 「Jangal」refers to that vast area where there is a density of trees and wild life inhabits. Its synonyms include 「Jangal, Jangalistan, Beshan, Jhari」, but 「Jangal」is the most appropriate and common word. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَكَمْ مِّن شَجَرَةٍ مُّمْبِدَةٍ» (Ar-Rahman/6) Translation: And how many a tree that is without leaves or fruit. (Note: The word 「Jangal」has not come explicitly in the Holy Quran, but Allah Almighty has described many types of trees (shajar) which indicate the trees of wild areas.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3569,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Forest - Ban",
      "hw": "Forest",
      "s": "「Ban」refers to the act of making and creating which in the context of forest expresses the natural settlement and construction of trees.",
      "d": "「Ban」is a basic Arabic root whose meanings are making, constructing, and producing offspring. This root comes in the form of 「Bani」(bani) in Arabic language which describes building houses or settlements. Jangal in Urdu has actually come from Sanskrit (Sanskrit: जंगल / Jhangal) and it has no connection with the Arabic root 「Ban」. However, conceptually 「Ban」can be connected to forest in this way that forest is Allah Almighty's constructed natural settlement where trees and plants are like His built structures. Its difference from other words like 「Ghabah」(غابة) which is used for forest in Arabic and its root is 「GH-B-W」is clear."
    }
  ],
  "824": [
    {
      "id": 3570,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Desert - Registan",
      "hw": "Desert",
      "s": "「Registan」refers to that land in which there is abundance of reg (gravel, sand), i.e., sandy and desert area.",
      "d": "「Registan」is actually a Persian-Urdu compound word which is formed from 「Reg」(gravel, sand) and 「Stan」(place, land). Its meaning is sandy land or desert. There is no exact equivalent word in Arabic language, however 「Sahra」(hard and barren land), 「Raml」(sand dune), and 「Falat」(desolate and remote land) are the closest words to it. In Urdu, the word 「Registan」is derived from Persian and it is applied to those areas where there is abundance of sand. In the Holy Quran, to express this concept, mostly the words 「Sahra」and 「Ard」have come."
    },
    {
      "id": 3571,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Desert - Sahra",
      "hw": "Desert",
      "s": "The literal meaning of 「Sahra」is waterless and barren, desert and desolate land which is used in Urdu in the form of 「Registan」.",
      "d": "「Sahra」is an Arabic word which comes in the meanings of waterless and barren, desert and desolate land. This word is derived from 「S-H-R」in Arabic and its original meaning is dry, barren and desolate land. In Urdu, this word has entered in the form of 「Registan」where 「Reg」(sand) is a Persian word and combined with 「Stan」(place of) gives the meaning of 「sandy place」. Its difference from other synonyms is that 「Sahra」specifically refers to sandy and dry desert areas, while 「Falat」(Falahah) generally means open and desolate area, and 「Barr」(Barr) also comes for land or country. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَضَرَبَ لَهُم مَّثَلًا وَذَكَرَ أَجَلًا» (Adh-Dhariyat/51) Translation: And He presented for them an example and mentioned a term. And another example: «كَأَنَّهُمۡ حُمُرٞ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَةٞ فَرَّتۡ مِّن قَسۡوَرَةِۭ» (Al-Ma'arij/70) Translation: As if they were donkeys fleeing. From a lion."
    }
  ],
  "825": [
    {
      "id": 3572,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sea - Samandar",
      "hw": "Sea",
      "s": "「Samandar」refers to a very large water reserve which surrounds most of the earth's surface.",
      "d": "「Samandar」's original Arabic language root is 「S-M-N-D」. In lexicon books, 「Samandar」is defined as that which is called very large water. Its literal meaning is the one that embraces or spread out water. Its meaning includes both vastness and depth. In contrast to other words, for example 「Bahr」which comes for sea, in 「Samandar」there is more sense of vastness and boundlessness. The word 「Samandar」in Arabic language is derived from 「Samandar」itself and is used in Urdu in the same way. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالہٗ أَنۢبَتَكُمۡ مِّنَ الۡأَرۡضِ نَبَاتًا ۙ-ثُمَّ يُعِيدُكُمۡ فِیۡهَا وَيُخۡرِجُكُمۡ إِخۡرَاجًا» (Nuh/71) Translation: And Allah has caused you to grow from the earth a growth. Then He will return you into it and extract you [another] extraction. And another example: «وَسَخَّرَ لَكُمُ الۡفُلۡكَ لِتَجۡرِیَ فِیۡہِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ وَالۡسُّفُنَ فِیۡ الۡبَحۡرِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ» (Ibrahim/32) Translation: And He has subjected for you the ships that they may sail through the sea by His command. Here, the word 「Samandar」describes the vastness of the entire sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 3573,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sea - Bahr",
      "hw": "Sea",
      "s": "「BAHR」is spoken for sea or river.",
      "d": "「BAHR」's plural is 「ABHUR」. The people of language also write the meaning of 「BAHR」as river or sea. But in today's time, 「BAHR」is called that large reserve of water which collects in a low-lying place and water from all sides keeps coming and joining it. If the water collected in a low-lying area is in small quantity, it is called a pond, and if it is in larger quantity, it is called a lake, and if it is in even larger quantity, it is called 「BUHAYRAH」i.e., small sea, and if it is in very large quantity, it is called 「BAHR」. In the Quran, the word 「BAHR」has been used for both 「BUHAYRAH」and 「BAHR」. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَاِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (2/50) Translation: And (O Children of Israel, remember that time also) when We parted the sea for you and saved you and drowned the people of Pharaoh. And historical research is that this 'Sea' was the Sea of Qulzum (Red Sea). The water collected in the sea is sometimes still. Sometimes winds create waves in it and keep it moving. Though this movement is not towards a low-lying area. Then, within the collected water of the sea, rivers of water also flow towards the low (slope) and sometimes two rivers also flow together. In which one is of hot water and the other is of cold water. Or one is of sweet water and the other is of bitter water. And they do not mix with each other. Although this is also against the property of water. And all this happens under the perfect power of Allah Almighty. Pointing towards this matter, Allah Almighty says: «مَرَجَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ لَّا یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (55/19,20) Translation: He has let loose the two seas, meeting together. Between them is a barrier which they do not transgress. In this verse, the word 「BAHR」has been used for river in the Quran. This is because such rivers flow only in the sea."
    }
  ],
  "826": [
    {
      "id": 3574,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sun - Suraj",
      "hw": "Sun",
      "s": "「Suraj」in Arabic language means 「Shams」and it represents the sun which is the source of light and life in the universe.",
      "d": "「Suraj」is actually a Persian and Urdu language word which is derived from the Arabic word 「Shams」(SH-M-S). Its original root (root) in Arabic language is 「SH-M-S」which gives the meaning of 'to shine' or 'to be bright'. In the Holy Quran, the expression 「Ash-Shams」(Al + Shams) is used for the sun. Other Arabic synonyms of the sun include 「Aftab」and 「Diya」, but 「Shams」specifically represents the celestial body of the sun while 「Diya」describes the general quality of light. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالشَّمْسُ تَجْرِي لِمُسْتَقَرٍّ لَّهَا ۚ ذَٰلِكَ تَقْدِيرُ الْعَزِيزِ الْعَلِيمِ» (Ya-Sin/38) Translation: And the sun runs [on course] toward its stopping point. That is the determination of the Exalted in Might, the Knowing."
    },
    {
      "id": 3575,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sun - Aftab",
      "hw": "Sun",
      "s": "「Aftab」refers to the sun's light or radiance which in Arabic language is used for light and brightness.",
      "d": "「Aftab」's linguistic root is A-T-B (Ayn-Ta-Ba) whose original meaning is to emerge, to appear or the spreading of light. This word describes the light and radiance of the sun rather than the complete body of the sun. In Arabic language, there are several words for the sun among which 「Shams」(SH-M-S) is the most famous which is called the star of the sun itself, while 「Aftab」indicates its light. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ» (Ya-Sin/37) Translation: And a sign for them is the night. We remove from it [the light of] day, so they are [left] in darkness. Here, the word 「Aftab」has not come specifically but in the Quran, the plural 「Aftab」refers to the sun's light which reaches the earth."
    }
  ],
  "827": [
    {
      "id": 3576,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Moon - Chand",
      "hw": "Moon",
      "s": "「Chand」refers to that celestial body which provides light at night and has various phases.",
      "d": "「Chand」is actually a Persian language word which is also used in Urdu. Its source is the Arabic word 「QAMAR」(qamar) which comes from the Arabic root Q-M-R (Qaf-Meem-Ra). The original meaning of this root is 'to become white' or 'to shine'. In Urdu, the word 「Chand」has come directly from Persian while in Arabic its equivalent is 「QAMAR」. The difference between 「Chand」and 「QAMAR」is that 「QAMAR」is an Arabic word which has been spoken in the Holy Quran, while 「Chand」is a Persian-Urdu word which is derived from Arabic. For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَالْقَمَرَ قَدَّرْنَاهُ مَنَازِلَ» (Ya-Sin/39) Translation: And the moon - We have determined for it phases."
    },
