      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Moon - Mah",
      "hw": "Moon",
      "s": "「Mah」in Arabic language is used in both the meanings of moon and month, which is connected to the determination of months according to the moon.",
      "d": "「Mah」's Arabic grammatical root is 「M-W-H」or 「M-Y-H」. This word comes in both meanings of moon and month, because in ancient Arabic tradition, months were divided according to the moon. In contrast, in Arabic, 「Qamar」is generally used for moon and 「Shahr」for month. In Urdu, 「Chand」is actually derived from Sanskrit's 「Chandar」, however the word 「Mah」is also used in Urdu in the meaning of month. For example: In the Holy Quran: «إِنَّ عِدَّةَ الشُّهُورِ عِندَ اللَّهِ اثْنَا عَشَرَ شَهْرًا فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ يَوْمَ خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ مِنْهَا أَرْبَعَةٌ حُرُمٌ» (At-Tawbah/36) Translation: Indeed, the number of months with Allah is twelve [lunar] months in the register of Allah [from] the day He created the heavens and the earth; of these, four are sacred."
    }
