      "s": "「Sitara」refers to those bright celestial bodies which shine in the sky and it comes from the Arabic original N-J-M.",
      "d": "According to linguistic analysis, the word Sitara comes from the Arabic trilateral simple root N-J-M (N-J-M). The original meaning of this root is 'to appear', 'to shine' and 'to emerge'. Sitara and 'Najm' are actually two different words of the same concept, however 'Najm' is more commonly used. The difference of Sitara from other words like 'Kawkab' is that 'Kawkab' is specifically said for bright and luminous stars, while 'Najm' or 'Sitara' is used for all types of celestial bodies."
